\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Part
Group Theory
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this document, we will go over the basics of group theory.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Basic Definitions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Throughout this section, let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be a nonempty set.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Definition of a Group
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A 
\begin_inset Formula $\textbf{binary operation}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\star$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is a function 
\begin_inset Formula $\star\colon X\times X\to X$
\end_inset

, which we denote by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(x,y)\mapsto x\star y.
\]

\end_inset

A set 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 equipped with a binary operation 
\begin_inset Formula $\star$
\end_inset

 is called a 
\series bold
magma
\series default
, and is denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,\star)$
\end_inset

.
 The pair 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,\star)$
\end_inset

 is called a 
\series bold
semigroup 
\series default
if the binary operation is 
\series bold
associative
\series default
; that is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(x\star y)\star z=x\star(y\star z)
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y,z\in X$
\end_inset

.
 The pair 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,\star)$
\end_inset

 is called a 
\series bold
monoid 
\series default
if 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,\star)$
\end_inset

 is a semigroup and there exists a 
\series bold
left 
\series default
and 
\series bold
right inverse
\series default
 
\series bold
element
\series default
; that is, there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $e,e'\in X$
\end_inset

 such that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
e\star x=x=x\star e'
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

.
 In fact, we automatically have 
\begin_inset Formula $e=e'$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
e' & =e\star e'\\
 & =e.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

For this reason, we say 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

 is the 
\series bold
identity element
\series default
.
 The pair 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,\star)$
\end_inset

 is called a 
\series bold
group 
\series default
if 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,\star)$
\end_inset

 and every element has a 
\series bold
left 
\series default
and 
\series bold
right
\series default
 
\series bold
inverse
\series default
; that is, for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

 there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $y,z\in X$
\end_inset

 such that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x\star z=e=y\star x.
\]

\end_inset

In fact, associativity automatically implies 
\begin_inset Formula $y=z$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
y & =y\star e\\
 & =y\star(x\star z)\\
 & =(y\star x)\star z\\
 & =e\star z\\
 & =z.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

For this reason, we say 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 has an 
\series bold
inverse element
\series default
, rather than a left and right inverse since they are the same element anyways,
 and we denote the inverse of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{-1}$
\end_inset

.
 The pair 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,\star)$
\end_inset

 is called an 
\series bold
abelian group 
\series default
if 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,\star)$
\end_inset

 is a group and the binary operation is 
\series bold
commutative
\series default
; that is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x\star y=y\star x
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in X$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We often denote a group by 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 where we view 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 as a set equipped with a binary operation.
 Arbitrary groups are usually denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

, and abelian groups are usually denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

.
 The binary operation for a group 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is usually denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $\cdot$
\end_inset

 rather than 
\begin_inset Formula $\star$
\end_inset

.
 To ease notation, if 
\begin_inset Formula $g,h\in G$
\end_inset

, then we often write 
\begin_inset Formula $gh$
\end_inset

 rather than 
\begin_inset Formula $g\cdot h$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Abelian Groups 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}^{\times}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Addition is a binary operation on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

, however negation is not a binary operation on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

.
 For example, 
\begin_inset Formula $1-5\notin\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

.
 The pair 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mathbb{N},+)$
\end_inset

 forms a semigroup with identity 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

.
 It is not quite a group yet, but we can make it into a group by 
\emph on
adjoining 
\emph default
inverse elements.
 When we do this, we obtain the group of integers under addition, denoted
 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

.
 Similarly, multiplication is a binary operation on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

, but division is not a binary operation on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

.
 The pair 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mathbb{Z},\cdot)$
\end_inset

 forms a semigroup with identity 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

.
 This semigroup is also not a group because we are again missing inverses
 as in the case of 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mathbb{N},+)$
\end_inset

.
 This time however, if we try to adjoin inverses to 
\emph on
all
\emph default
 elements in 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mathbb{Z},\cdot)$
\end_inset

, then we will run into a problem; namely adjoining an inverse to 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 will collapse the whole structure to the trivial group 
\begin_inset Formula $(\{1\},\cdot)$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
a & =1\cdot a\\
 & =(0^{-1}0)\cdot a\\
 & =0^{-1}(0\cdot a)\\
 & =0^{-1}0\\
 & =1.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

In order to avoid this, we adjoint inverses to all elements in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 
\emph on
except 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

.
 
\emph default
The pair 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mathbb{Q},\cdot)$
\end_inset

 is still not a group yet, but if we restrict multiplication to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}\backslash\{0\}\times\mathbb{Q}\backslash\{0\}$
\end_inset

, then we do get a group, denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}^{\times}$
\end_inset

.
 To see this, we just need to verify that restricting multiplication to
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}\backslash\{0\}\times\mathbb{Q}\backslash\{0\}$
\end_inset

 lands in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}\backslash\{0\}$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, assume for a contradiction that there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in\mathbb{Q}\backslash\{0\}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $ab=0$
\end_inset

.
 As 
\begin_inset Formula $a\neq0$
\end_inset

, we can multiply both sides by 
\begin_inset Formula $a^{-1}$
\end_inset

 to obtain 
\begin_inset Formula $b=0$
\end_inset

, which is a contradiction.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Define a binary operation 
\begin_inset Formula $\star$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

 by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a\star b=ab+3a+3b+6
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

.
 The binary operation is clearly abelian.
 It is also associative.
 Indeed, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
(a\star b)\star c & =(ab+3a+3b+6)c+3(ab+3a+3b+6)+3c+6\\
 & =abc+3ab+3ac+3bc+9a+9b+9c+24\\
 & =a(bc+3b+3c+6)+3a+3(bc+3b+3c+6)+6\\
 & =a\star(b\star c).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

There also exists an identity element; namely -
\begin_inset Formula $2\in\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

.
 To see this, we only need to check that 
\begin_inset Formula $-2$
\end_inset

 is a right inverse since the binary operation is abelian.
 For all 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
a\star-2 & =a(-2)+3a+3(-2)+6\\
 & =-2a+3a-6+6\\
 & =a.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
On the other hand, not every element in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

 has an inverse.
 Indeed, let 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

.
 To find the inverse of 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

, we solve for 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 in
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
ab+3a+3b+6=-2.
\]

\end_inset

We obtain
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a^{-1}=\frac{-3a-8}{a+3}.
\]

\end_inset

Thus every element in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}\backslash\{-3\}$
\end_inset

 has an inverse element, but 
\begin_inset Formula $-3$
\end_inset

 does not have an inverse element.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mathbb{Q},\star)$
\end_inset

 is a monoid, but not quite a group.
 However, if we restrict the binary operation 
\begin_inset Formula $\star$
\end_inset

 to the set 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}\backslash\{-3\}\times\mathbb{Q}\backslash\{-3\}$
\end_inset

, then we do get a group 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mathbb{Q}\backslash\{-3\},\star)$
\end_inset

.
 To see this, we just need to verify that 
\begin_inset Formula $\star$
\end_inset

 restricted to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}\backslash\{-3\}\times\mathbb{Q}\backslash\{-3\}$
\end_inset

 lands in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}\backslash\{-3\}$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, assume for a contradiction that 
\begin_inset Formula $a\star b=-3$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in\mathbb{Q}\backslash\{-3\}$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
0 & =a\star b+3\\
 & =ab+3a+3b+9\\
 & =(a+3)(b+3)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

implies either 
\begin_inset Formula $a+3=0$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $b+3=0$
\end_inset

.
 In either case, we obtain a contradiction.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Later on we will show that the group 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mathbb{Q}\backslash\{-3\},\star)$
\end_inset

 is in fact isomorphic (a term which we shall define later) to the group
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}^{\times}$
\end_inset

, with the isomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon\mathbb{Q}^{\times}\to(\mathbb{Q}\backslash\{-3\},\star)$
\end_inset

 defined by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varphi(a)=a-3
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in\mathbb{Q}^{\times}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Abelian Group 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mathcal{P}(X),\Delta)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The 
\series bold
power set 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}(X)$
\end_inset

, is the set of all subsets of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 The 
\series bold
symmetric difference 
\series default
of two subsets 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is defined by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A\Delta B=(A\cup B)\backslash(A\cap B).
\]

\end_inset

This gives rise to a binary operation 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\colon X\times X\to X$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The pair 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mathcal{P}(X),\Delta)$
\end_inset

 forms an abelian group.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The identity element for 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mathcal{P}(X),\Delta)$
\end_inset

 is clearly the empty set.
 Clearly 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta$
\end_inset

 is abelian.
 Let us show that it is also associative.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A,B,C\in\mathcal{P}(X)$
\end_inset

.
 Then we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
(A\Delta B)\Delta C & =((A\Delta B)\cup C)\cap((A\Delta B)\cap C)^{c}\\
 & =((A\Delta B)\cup C)\cap((A\Delta B)^{c}\cup C^{c})\\
 & =(((A\cup B)\cap(A\cap B)^{c})\cup C))\cap((A\cap B^{c})\cup(A^{c}\cap B))^{c}\cup C^{c})\\
 & =(A\cup B\cup C)\cap(A^{c}\cup B^{c}\cup C)\cap(((A\cap B^{c})^{c}\cap(A^{c}\cap B)^{c})\cup C^{c})\\
 & =(A\cup B\cup C)\cap(A^{c}\cup B^{c}\cup C)\cap((A^{c}\cup B)\cap(A\cup B^{c}))\cup C^{c})\\
 & =(A\cup B\cup C)\cap(A^{c}\cup B^{c}\cup C)\cap(A^{c}\cup B\cup C^{c})\cap(A\cup B^{c}\cup C^{c})\\
 & =(B\cup C\cup A)\cap(B^{c}\cup C^{c}\cup A)\cap(B^{c}\cup C\cup A^{c})\cap(B\cup C^{c}\cup A^{c})\\
 & =((B\cup C\cup A)\cap(B^{c}\cup C^{c}\cup A))\cap((B^{c}\cup C)\cap(B\cup C^{c}))\cup A^{c})\\
 & =((B\cup C\cup A)\cap(B^{c}\cup C^{c}\cup A))\cap(((B\cap C^{c})^{c}\cap(B^{c}\cap C)^{c})\cup A^{c})\\
 & =(((B\cup C)\cap(B\cap C)^{c})\cup A))\cap((B\cap C^{c})\cup(B^{c}\cap C))^{c}\cup A^{c})\\
 & =((B\Delta C)\cup A)\cap((B\Delta C)^{c}\cup A^{c})\\
 & =((B\Delta C)\cup A)\cap((B\Delta C)\cap A)^{c}\\
 & =(B\Delta C)\Delta A\\
 & =A\Delta(B\Delta C).
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Inverse elements also exist; every subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is its own inverse.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Matrix Groups
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In linear algebra, matrices get into row echelon form by elementary row
 operations:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Add a multilple of one row to another.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Multiply a row by a nonzero scalar.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Exchange two rows.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Elementary row operations on an 
\begin_inset Formula $m\times n$
\end_inset

 matrix can be expressed using left multiplication by an 
\begin_inset Formula $m\times m$
\end_inset

 matrix called an 
\series bold
elementary matrix
\series default
.
 These elementary matrices come in three flavors.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

First we have 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{ij}(a)=\exp(aE_{ij})=I_{n}+aE_{ij}$
\end_inset

.
 The effect of multiplying an 
\begin_inset Formula $m\times n$
\end_inset

 matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{ij}(\lambda)$
\end_inset

 on the left is an elementary row operation:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
e_{ij}(a)A=\begin{pmatrix}a_{11} & \cdots & a_{1n}\\
\vdots & \ddots & \vdots\\
a_{i1}+aa_{j1} & \cdots & a_{in}+aa_{jn}\\
\vdots & \ddots & \vdots\\
a_{m1} & \cdots & a_{mn}
\end{pmatrix},
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and the effect of multiplying 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{ij}(\lambda)$
\end_inset

 on the right is an elementary column operation:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Ae_{ij}(a)=\begin{pmatrix}a_{11} & \cdots & a_{1j}+aa_{1i} & \cdots & a_{1n}\\
\vdots & \ddots & \vdots & \ddots & \vdots\\
a_{m1} & \cdots & a_{mj}+aa_{mi} & \cdots & a_{mn}
\end{pmatrix}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These elementary matrices satisfy the following relations, called the 
\series bold
Steinberg relations
\series default
:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
e_{ij}(a)e_{ij}(b) & =e_{ij}(a+b);\\
e_{ij}(a)e_{jk}(b) & =e_{ik}(ab)e_{jk}(b)e_{ij}(a),\quad\mbox{for }i\neq k;\\
e_{ij}(a)e_{kl}(b) & =e_{kl}(b)e_{ij}(a),\quad\mbox{for }i\neq l\mbox{ and }j\neq k.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is useful to think of the second relation as, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

you can move 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{ij}(a)$
\end_inset

 from the left to the right of 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{jk}(b)$
\end_inset

 at the cost of multiplying by an element 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{ik}(ab)$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 A similar interpretation can be given for the other relations.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Next we have 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{i}(a)$
\end_inset

, which has entries 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 on the main diagonal except for a nonzero 
\begin_inset Formula $a\neq1$
\end_inset

 in the 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

th spot along the diagonal.
 The effect of multiplying an 
\begin_inset Formula $m\times n$
\end_inset

 matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{i}(a)$
\end_inset

 on the left is an elementary row operation: multiply the 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

th row by 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

.
 The effect of multiplying an 
\begin_inset Formula $m\times n$
\end_inset

 matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{i}(a)$
\end_inset

 on the right is an elementary column operation: multiply the 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

th column by 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

.
 These matrices together with the 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{ij}(a)$
\end_inset

's satisfy the following relations:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
d_{i}(a)d_{i}(b) & =d_{i}(ab);\\
d_{i}(a)d_{j}(b) & =d_{j}(b)d_{i}(a);\\
d_{i}(a)e_{ij}(b) & =e_{ij}(ab)d_{i}(a);\\
e_{ij}(b)d_{j}(a) & =d_{j}(a)e_{ij}(ab).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is useful to think of the third relation as 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

you can move 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{i}(a)$
\end_inset

 from the left to the right of 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{ij}(b)$
\end_inset

 at the cost of replacing 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{ij}(b)$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{ij}(ab)$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 A similar interpretation can be given for the other relations.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

The last type of elementary matrix to discuss is 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{ij}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $i\neq j$
\end_inset

, which is the matrix that has entry 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 in positions 
\begin_inset Formula $(i,j)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(j,i)$
\end_inset

 and also in every diagonal position except the 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

th and 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

th, and 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

's everywhere else.
 The effect of multiplying an 
\begin_inset Formula $m\times n$
\end_inset

 matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{ij}$
\end_inset

 on the left is an elementary row operation: swap the 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

th row and 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

th row.
 The effect of multiplying an 
\begin_inset Formula $m\times n$
\end_inset

 matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{ij}$
\end_inset

 on the right is an elementary column operation: swap the 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

th column and 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

th column.
 These matrices together with the 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{i}(a)'s$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{ij}(b)'s$
\end_inset

 satisfy the following relations
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
s_{ij}^{2} & =I;\\
s_{ij} & =s_{ji};\\
s_{ij}s_{jk}s_{ij} & =s_{jk}s_{ij}s_{jk};\\
s_{ij}s_{kl} & =s_{kl}s_{ij},\quad\mbox{for }i\neq k\ne j\mbox{ and }i\ne l\ne j;\\
s_{ij}e_{kl}(a) & =e_{\sigma(k)\sigma(l)}(a)s_{ij},\quad\sigma=(1,2);\\
s_{ij}d_{j}(a) & =d_{\sigma(j)}(a)s_{ij},\quad\sigma=(1,2);
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Addition and multilpication are commutative on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

, but negation and division are not commutative on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Matrix multiplication is an associative binary operation which is not commutati
ve: 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{12}(a)e_{23}(b)=e_{23}(a)e_{12}(b)e_{13}(ab)$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $G=\{f:\mathbb{R}\to\mathbb{R}\}$
\end_inset

.
 Composition 
\begin_inset Formula $\circ$
\end_inset

 of functions is an associative binary operation on 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 which is not commutative.
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Define 
\begin_inset Formula $\star$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $a\star b=\frac{a+b}{2}$
\end_inset

.
 This is clearly commutative, however it is not associative since:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(a\star b)\star c=\frac{\frac{a+b}{2}+c}{2}=\frac{a+b+2c}{4}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a\star(b\star c)=\frac{a+\frac{b+c}{2}}{2}=\frac{2a+b+c}{4}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 be a nonempty set and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\star$
\end_inset

 be a binary operation on 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

.
 An 
\begin_inset Formula $\textbf{identity element}$
\end_inset

 is an element 
\begin_inset Formula $e\in G$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $a\star e=e\star a=a$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in G$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Multiplication on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}\setminus\{0\}$
\end_inset

 has identity element 
\begin_inset Formula $e=1$
\end_inset

.
 Every 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 has an inverse, 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{a}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\star$
\end_inset

 be the binary operation 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}\setminus\{3\}$
\end_inset

 be given by 
\begin_inset Formula $a\star b=ab+3a+3b+6=(a+3)(b+3)-3$
\end_inset

.
 Let's verify that 
\begin_inset Formula $\star$
\end_inset

 really is a binary operation on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}\setminus\{3\}$
\end_inset

.
 For all 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in\mathbb{R}\setminus\{-3\}$
\end_inset

, we certainly have 
\begin_inset Formula $a\star b\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $a\star b=-3$
\end_inset

, then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(a+3)(b+3)-3=-3\quad\implies\quad(a+3)(b+3)=0\quad\implies\quad a=b=-3.
\]

\end_inset

Thus, it is a binary operation on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}\setminus\{-3\}$
\end_inset

.
 Does 
\begin_inset Formula $\star$
\end_inset

 have an identity element? Does there exist 
\begin_inset Formula $e\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $a\star e=e=e\star a$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

? In fact 
\begin_inset Formula $e=-2$
\end_inset

 works since 
\begin_inset Formula $a\star e=(a-3)(-2+3)-3=a$
\end_inset

.
 And since 
\begin_inset Formula $\star$
\end_inset

 is commutative, 
\begin_inset Formula $a\star e=e\star a$
\end_inset

.
 What about inverses? Given 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

, can we find a 
\begin_inset Formula $b\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $a\star b=-2$
\end_inset

? Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $a\star b=-2$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(a+3)(b+3)-3=-2\quad\implies\quad(a+3)(b+3)=1\quad\implies\quad(a+3)b=-3a-8\quad\implies\quad b=\frac{-3a-8}{a+3}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So each element except 
\begin_inset Formula $-3$
\end_inset

, has an inverse.
 We have just proved that 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mathbb{R}\setminus\{3\},\star)$
\end_inset

 is a group.
 Now we want to show that this group is actually isomorphic to 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mathbb{R}\setminus\{0\},\cdot\}$
\end_inset

.
 The isomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi:\mathbb{R}\setminus\{0\}\to\mathbb{R}\setminus\{3\}$
\end_inset

 will be given by 
\begin_inset Formula $a\mapsto a-3$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in\mathbb{R}\setminus\{0\}$
\end_inset

.
 We need to show 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(ab)=\varphi(a)\star\varphi(b)$
\end_inset

.
 The left side equals
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varphi(ab)=ab-3.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The right side equals
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varphi(a)\star\varphi(b)=(a-3)\star(b-3)=ab-3.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So this is a homomorphism.
 In fact, it is an isomorphism since 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is a bijection, with inverse 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi:\mathbb{R}\setminus\{3\}\to\mathbb{R}\setminus\{0\}$
\end_inset

 given by 
\begin_inset Formula $a\mapsto a+3$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in\mathbb{R}\setminus\{3\}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Group Homomorphisms
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $G'$
\end_inset

 be groups and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon G\to G'$
\end_inset

 be a function.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We say 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is a 
\series bold
homomorphism 
\series default
is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varphi(g_{1}g_{2})=\varphi(g_{1})\varphi(g_{2})
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1},g_{2}\in G$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We say 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is an 
\series bold
isomorphism 
\series default
if it is a bijection homomorphism.
 In this case, we say 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
isomorphic 
\series default
to 
\begin_inset Formula $G'$
\end_inset

, and we denote this by 
\begin_inset Formula $G\cong G'$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 In this document, if we write 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon G\to G'$
\end_inset

 be a homomorphism/isomorphism
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, then it is understood that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is a group homomorpism/isomorphism between groups 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $G'$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Inverse Map is also Homomorphism
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon G\to G'$
\end_inset

 be an isomorphism and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi\colon G'\to G$
\end_inset

 denote its inverse.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 is a homomorphism.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1}',g_{2}'\in G'$
\end_inset

.
 Then we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\psi(g_{1}'g_{2}') & =\psi(\varphi(\psi(g_{1}'))\varphi(\psi(g_{2}')))\\
 & =\psi(\varphi(\psi(g_{1}')\psi(g_{2}'))\\
 & =\psi(g_{1}')\psi(g_{2}').
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Group Homomorphisms Sends Identities to Identities and Inverses to Inverses
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $G'$
\end_inset

 be groups with identities 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $e'$
\end_inset

 respectively, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon G\to G$
\end_inset

 be a group homomorphism.
 Then
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 sends the identity to the identity: we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(e)=e'$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 sends inverses to inverses: we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(g^{-1})=\varphi(g)^{-1}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in G$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 1.
 Observe that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\varphi(e)=\varphi(ee)=\varphi(e)\varphi(e).\label{eq:cancelbothsidesidunn}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Now we multiply both sides of 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:cancelbothsidesidunn})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(e)^{-1}$
\end_inset

 to get the desired result.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
2.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in G$
\end_inset

.
 Then we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
e' & =\varphi(e)\\
 & =\varphi(gg^{-1})\\
 & =\varphi(g)\varphi(g^{-1}).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(g)^{-1}=\varphi(g^{-1})$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Determinant Homomorphism
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 be a field and let 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

.
 The determinant map 
\begin_inset Formula $\det\colon\mathrm{GL}_{n}(K)\to K^{\times}$
\end_inset

 is a homomorphism.
 Indeed, if 
\begin_inset Formula $A,B\in\mathrm{GL}_{n}(K)$
\end_inset

, then one learns from linear algebra that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\det(AB)=\det(A)\det(B).
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Isomorphism from 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{\times}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The exponential map 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}\to\mathbb{R}^{\times}$
\end_inset

, given by 
\begin_inset Formula $x\mapsto e^{x}$
\end_inset

, is an isomorphism.
 Indeed, for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
e^{x+y}=e^{x}e^{y}.
\]

\end_inset

Furthemore, the exponential map is a bijection, with the logarithm map 
\begin_inset Formula $\log\colon\mathbb{R}^{\times}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 being its inverse.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Automorphisms
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(G,\cdot)$
\end_inset

 be a group.
 An 
\series bold
automorphism
\series default
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is an isomorphism from 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

.
 Notation:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mbox{Aut}(G)=\{\varphi:G\to G\mid\varphi\mbox{ is an isomorphism}\}
\]

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mbox{Aut}(G),\cdot)$
\end_inset

 is a group.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 It suffices to show 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{Aut}(G)\leq S_{G}$
\end_inset

.
 We have an identity 
\begin_inset Formula $1_{G}\in\mbox{Aut}(G)$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma,\tau\in\mbox{Aut}(G)$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma\tau$
\end_inset

 is bijective and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sigma\tau(ab)=\sigma(\tau(ab))=\sigma(\tau(a)\tau(b))=\sigma(\tau(a))\sigma(\tau(b))=\sigma\tau(a)\sigma\tau(b).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma\tau$
\end_inset

 is an automorphism.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\in\mbox{Aut}(G)$
\end_inset

, then since 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is bijective, there exists an inverse funciton 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi^{-1}$
\end_inset

.
 Now we show 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi^{-1}\in\mbox{Aut}(G)$
\end_inset

: For all 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in G$
\end_inset

, there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in G$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(x)=a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(y)=b$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varphi^{-1}(ab)=\varphi^{-1}(\varphi(x)\varphi(y))=\varphi^{-1}(\varphi(xy))=xy=\varphi^{-1}(a)\varphi^{-1}(b).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The set of 
\series bold
inner automorphisms 
\series default
is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mbox{Inn}(G)=\{\sigma_{g}:G\to G,\,\sigma_{g}(x)=gxg^{-1}\mid g\in G\}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{Inn}(G)\leq\mbox{Aut}(G)$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $1_{G}=\sigma_{1}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 is the identity of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $1_{G}\in\mbox{Inn}(G)$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{g},\sigma_{h}\in\mbox{Inn}(G)$
\end_inset

.
 Then for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in G$
\end_inset

 we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\sigma_{g}\sigma_{h}(x) & =g\sigma_{h}(x)g^{-1}\\
 & =ghxh^{-1}g^{-1}\\
 & =\sigma_{gh}(x).
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So we have closure under the group operation.
 Lastly, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{g}\in\mbox{Inn}(G)$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{g}^{-1}=\sigma_{g^{-1}}$
\end_inset

 since for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in G$
\end_inset

 we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\sigma_{g}\sigma_{g^{-1}}(x) & =g\sigma_{g^{-1}}(x)g^{-1}\\
 & =gg^{-1}xgg^{-1}\\
 & =x.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 be a group and let 
\begin_inset Formula $H\trianglelefteq G$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 acts on 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 by conjugation by 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{g}(h)=g\cdot h=ghg^{-1}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in G$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $h\in H$
\end_inset

.
 The permutation representatoin is 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi:G\to\mbox{Aut}(H)$
\end_inset

, given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(g)=\sigma_{g}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{Ker}\varphi=C_{G}(H)$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, 
\begin_inset Formula $G/C_{G}(H)\cong\varphi(G)\leq\mbox{Aut}(H).$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $G=\langle g\rangle$
\end_inset

 be a cyclic group of order 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{Aut}(G)\cong\mathbb{Z}_{m}^{\times}$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Every automorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi:G\to G$
\end_inset

 is completely determined by where it maps the generator.
 If
\begin_inset Formula $\psi(g)=g^{a}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 must be relatively prime to 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 is surjective.
 Thus for each 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in\{1,2,\dots,m\}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 is relatively prime to 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

, we have an automorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{a}(g)=g^{a}$
\end_inset

.
 This assignment 
\begin_inset Formula $a\mapsto\psi_{a}$
\end_inset

 is in fact an isomorphism from 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}_{m}^{\times}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{Aut}(G)$
\end_inset

.
 We have just shown that the map is bijective.
 Given two automorphisms 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{a}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{b}$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $(\psi_{a}\circ\psi_{b})(g)=\psi_{a}(g^{b})=g^{ab}$
\end_inset

.
 So this map is a homomorphism too.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 be a finite group of order 
\begin_inset Formula $45$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $H\trianglelefteq G$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 is cyclic and 
\begin_inset Formula $|H|=9$
\end_inset

.
 We will show 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 must be abelian.
 By the previous proposition, 
\begin_inset Formula $|\mbox{Aut}(H)|=6$
\end_inset

.
 The permutation representation is a homomoprhism 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi:G\to\mbox{Aut}(H)$
\end_inset

 given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(g)=\sigma_{g}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{g}$
\end_inset

 is the conjugation map.
 We know that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{Ker}\varphi=C_{G}(H)$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $G/C_{G}(H)\cong\varphi(G)\leq\mbox{Aut}(H)$
\end_inset

, which implies 
\begin_inset Formula $|G/C_{G}(H)|$
\end_inset

 divides 
\begin_inset Formula $|\mbox{Aut}(H)|=6$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $|H|=3^{2}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 is abelian, which implies 
\begin_inset Formula $H\leq C_{G}(H)\leq G$
\end_inset

 which implies 
\begin_inset Formula $9$
\end_inset

 divides 
\begin_inset Formula $|C_{G}(H)|$
\end_inset

 which divides 
\begin_inset Formula $45$
\end_inset

.
 This implies 
\begin_inset Formula $|C_{G}(H)|\in\{9,45\}$
\end_inset

.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $|G/C_{G}(H)|\in\{1,5\}$
\end_inset

, but since 
\begin_inset Formula $|G/C_{G}(H)|$
\end_inset

 divides 
\begin_inset Formula $6$
\end_inset

, we must have 
\begin_inset Formula $|G/C_{G}(H)|=1$
\end_inset

.
 Now 
\begin_inset Formula $G/C_{G}(H)$
\end_inset

 is cyclic and 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{G}(H)$
\end_inset

 is abelian, this implies 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is abelian.
  
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Characteristic Subgroups
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A subgroup 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
characteristic
\series default
 if 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma(H)=H$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma\in\mbox{Aut}(G)$
\end_inset

.
 Notation: 
\begin_inset Formula $H\mbox{ char }G$
\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\{1\}\mbox{ char }G$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 char 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 In 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mathbb{Z},+)$
\end_inset

 any subgroup 
\begin_inset Formula $m\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 is characteristic.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Find the characteristic subgroups of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}_{2}\times\mathbb{Z}_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 The only characteristic subgroups are 
\begin_inset Formula $\{(0,0)\}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}_{2}\times\mathbb{Z}_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 To show this, we just need to find an autormorphism which does not fix
 any other subgroup.
 For example, the subgroup 
\begin_inset Formula $\{(0,0),(1,0)\}$
\end_inset

 is not fixed by the automorphism which maps 
\begin_inset Formula $(1,0)$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $(0,1)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(1,1)$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $(1,1)$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Properties of Characteristic Subgroups)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 is a characteristic subgroup of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 then it is normal in 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 is the unique subgroup of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 of a given order 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 is characteristic in 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is a characteristic subgroup of 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 is normal in 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is normal in 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $(1):$
\end_inset

 For every 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in G$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{g}$
\end_inset

 is an inner automorphism.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 is a characteristic subgroup of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

, it must be fixed by 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{g}$
\end_inset

.
 This means 
\begin_inset Formula $gHg^{-1}=H$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $(2):$
\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma\in\mbox{Aut}(G)$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma(H)\leq G$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 is a bijective map, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma(H)$
\end_inset

 will have the same size as 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

.
 This implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma(H)=H$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $(3):$
\end_inset

 For all 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in G$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{g}\in\mbox{Aut}(H)$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $H\trianglelefteq G$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is characteristic in 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{g}(K)=K$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Subgroups
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 be a group and let 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 be a nonempty subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

.
 We say 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 is a 
\series bold
subgroup 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

, denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $H\leq G$
\end_inset

, if 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 forms a group under the group operation.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Thus if 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 is a subgroup of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in H$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $ab\in H$
\end_inset

.
 Similarly, 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in H$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $a^{-1}\in H$
\end_inset

.
 Note that these two conditions (toegether with the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 is nonempty) implies 
\begin_inset Formula $e\in H$
\end_inset

.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 necessarily share the same identity.
 In fact, to see that 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 is a subgroup of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

, we just need to check that 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in H$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $ab^{-1}\in H$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, in this case, 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in H$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $e=aa^{-1}\in H$
\end_inset

.
 Also 
\begin_inset Formula $e,a\in H$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $a^{-1}=ea^{-1}\in H$
\end_inset

.
 Finally, 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in H$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b^{-1}\in H$
\end_inset

 which implies 
\begin_inset Formula $ab=a(b^{-1})^{-1}\in H$
\end_inset

.
 Let's use this test in the following example
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $G=\mathrm{GL}_{2}(\mathbb{R})$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $H=\left\{ \left(\begin{smallmatrix}a & 0\\
0 & a
\end{smallmatrix}\right)\mid a\in\mathbb{R}^{\times}\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 Clearly 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 is nonempty, so to see that 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 is a subgroup of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

, we just need to check that 
\begin_inset Formula $A,B\in H$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $AB^{-1}\in H$
\end_inset

.
 So given 
\begin_inset Formula $A=\left(\begin{smallmatrix}a & 0\\
0 & a
\end{smallmatrix}\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B=\left(\begin{smallmatrix}b & 0\\
0 & b
\end{smallmatrix}\right)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

, we compute
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
AB^{-1} & =\begin{pmatrix}a & 0\\
0 & a
\end{pmatrix}\begin{pmatrix}b & 0\\
0 & b
\end{pmatrix}^{-1}\\
 & =\begin{pmatrix}a & 0\\
0 & a
\end{pmatrix}\begin{pmatrix}b^{-1} & 0\\
0 & b^{-1}
\end{pmatrix}\\
 & =\begin{pmatrix}ab^{-1} & 0\\
0 & ab^{-1}
\end{pmatrix}\\
 & \in H.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 is a subgroup of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 be subgroups of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $H\cap K$
\end_inset

 is a subgroup of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 First note that 
\begin_inset Formula $e\in H\cap K$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $H\cap K$
\end_inset

 is nonempty.
 Now let 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in H\cap K$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in H$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in K$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $ab^{-1}\in H$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $ab^{-1}\in K$
\end_inset

.
 This implies 
\begin_inset Formula $ab^{-1}\in H\cap K$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $H\cap K$
\end_inset

 is a subgroup of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Kernels, Centralizers, and Normalizers
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(G,\cdot)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(G',\star)$
\end_inset

 be two groups and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi:G\to G'$
\end_inset

 be a homomorphism.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\textbf{ker}\varphi=\{a\in G\mid\varphi(a)=e\}
\]

\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(G,\cdot)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(G',\star)$
\end_inset

 be two groups and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi:G\to G'$
\end_inset

 be a homomorphism.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\textbf{im}\varphi=\{\varphi(a)\mid a\in G\}
\]

\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(G,\cdot)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(G,\star)$
\end_inset

 be two groups and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi:G\to G'$
\end_inset

 be a homomorphism.
 Then ker
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\leq G$
\end_inset

 and im
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\leq G'$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $e\in$
\end_inset

ker
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(e)=e$
\end_inset

, so ker
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is nonempty.
 Given 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in$
\end_inset

ker
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(ab^{-1})=\varphi(a)\varphi(b)^{-1}=e$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $ab^{-1}\in$
\end_inset

ker
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

.
 This proves ker
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\leq G$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $e\in$
\end_inset

im
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(e)=e$
\end_inset

, so im
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is nonempty.
 Given 
\begin_inset Formula $a',b'\in$
\end_inset

im
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

, there exists an 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in G$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(a)=a'$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(b)=b'$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(ab^{-1})=\varphi(a)\varphi(b)^{-1}=a'b'^{-1}$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $a'b'^{-1}\in$
\end_inset

im
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $m\in\mathbb{Z}^{+}$
\end_inset

 be fixed.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi:\mathbb{Z}\to\mathbb{Z}/(m)$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(a)=\bar{\pi}$
\end_inset

, is a group homomorphism: 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(a+b)=\overline{a+b}=\bar{a}+\bar{b}=\pi(a)+\pi(b)$
\end_inset

.
 Notice that ker
\begin_inset Formula $\pi=m\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 and im
\begin_inset Formula $\pi=\mathbb{Z}/(m)$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(G,\cdot)$
\end_inset

 be a group and let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 be a nonempty subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

.
 Then the 
\begin_inset Formula $\textbf{centralizer}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
C_{G}(A)=\{g\in G\mid ga=ag\quad\forall a\in A\}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{G}(A)\leq G$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $e\in C_{G}(A)$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $ea=ae$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in A$
\end_inset

.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{G}(A)$
\end_inset

 is nonempty.
 Given 
\begin_inset Formula $g,h\in C_{G}(A)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $gh^{-1}a=gah^{-1}=agh^{-1}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in A$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $gh^{-1}\in C_{G}(A)$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Consider 
\begin_inset Formula $(S_{3},\cdot)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $A=\{(1,2)\}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{S_{3}}(A)=\{1,(1,2)\}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 be an abelian group and 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 be a subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{G}(A)=G$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The 
\begin_inset Formula $\textbf{center}$
\end_inset

 of a group 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $Z(G)=\{g\in\mid ga=ag\mbox{ , }\forall a\in G\}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $Z(G)=C_{G}(G)$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $Z(G)\leq G$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Obviously 
\begin_inset Formula $e\in Z(G)$
\end_inset

 so 
\begin_inset Formula $Z(G)$
\end_inset

 is nonempty.
 Given 
\begin_inset Formula $g,h\in Z(G)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $gh^{-1}\in Z(G)$
\end_inset

 since
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\ell gh^{-1}=g\ell h^{-1}=gh^{-1}\ell\qquad\forall\ell\in G
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Z(G)=\bigcap_{\emptyset\neq A\subseteq G}C_{G}(A)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $Z(S_{3})=\{1\}$
\end_inset

.
 We have 
\begin_inset Formula $Z(S_{3})\subseteq C_{S_{3}}((1,2))\cap C_{S_{3}}((1,3))=\{1\}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 be a group and let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 be a nonempty subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

.
 Then for each 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in G$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
gAg^{-1}=\{gag^{-1}\mid a\in A\}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The 
\begin_inset Formula $\textbf{normalizer}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
N_{G}(A)=\{g\in G\mid gAg^{-1}=A\}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 be a group and let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 be a nonempty subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{G}(A)\leq G$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Obviously 
\begin_inset Formula $e\in N_{G}(A)$
\end_inset

 so 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{G}(A)$
\end_inset

 is nonempty.
 Given 
\begin_inset Formula $g,h\in N_{G}(A)$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
gh^{-1}A=gAh^{-1}=Agh^{-1}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $H\leq G$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $H\leq N_{G}(H)$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A,B\subseteq S_{3}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $A=\{1,(1,2)\}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B=\{1,(1,2,3),(1,3,2)\}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{S_{3}}(A)=\{1,(1,2)\}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{S_{3}}(B)=S_{3}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Quotient Groups and Homomorphisms
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Normal Subgroups
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 be a group and let 
\begin_inset Formula $H\leq G$
\end_inset

.
 Consider the relation 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a\sim b\quad\mbox{if}\quad a^{-1}b\in H
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

 is an equivalence relation: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

 is reflexive: 
\begin_inset Formula $a^{-1}a=e\in H\implies a\sim a,\forall a\in G.$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

 is symmetric: If 
\begin_inset Formula $a^{-1}b\in H$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $b^{-1}a=\left(a^{-1}b\right)^{-1}\in H$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 is closed under inverses.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $a\sim b$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $b\sim a$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

 is transitive: Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $a\sim b$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b\sim c$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $a^{-1}b\in H$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b^{-1}c\in H$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $a^{-1}c=\left(a^{-1}b\right)\left(b^{-1}c\right)\in H$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 is closed under products.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $a\sim c$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The equivalence class of 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in G$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\{b\in G\mid a^{-1}b\in H\}=\{ah\mid h\in H\}=aH
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $aH$
\end_inset

 is called the 
\series bold
left coset of H in G containing a
\series default
.
 We have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
aH=bH\quad\mbox{if and only if}\quad a\sim b
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\series bold
right coset of H in G containing a
\series default
 is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Ha=\{ha\mid h\in H\}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A subgroup 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
normal in G
\series default
 if 
\begin_inset Formula $aH=Ha$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in G$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 is normal in 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

, we write 
\begin_inset Formula $H\trianglelefteq G$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\{e\}\trianglelefteq G$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $G\trianglelefteq G$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is abelian then any subgroup 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 is normal in 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $H\leq G$
\end_inset

.
 Any left 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

-coset in 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 has a bijection with 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, when 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 is finite, the cosets of 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 all have the same size as 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Pick a left coset, say 
\begin_inset Formula $gH$
\end_inset

.
 We can pass from 
\begin_inset Formula $gH$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 by left multiplication by 
\begin_inset Formula $g^{-1}:$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $g^{-1}(gh)=h\in H$
\end_inset

.
 Conversely, we can pass from 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $gH$
\end_inset

 by left multiplication by 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

.
 These functions from 
\begin_inset Formula $gH$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 and vice versa are inverses to each other, showing 
\begin_inset Formula $gH$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 are in bijection with each other.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $H\leq G$
\end_inset

.
 The 
\series bold
index 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is the number of left cosets of 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

.
 This number, which is a positive integer or 
\begin_inset Formula $\infty$
\end_inset

, is denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $[G:H]$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The number of left cosets of 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is equal to the number of right cosets of 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

.
 A bijection from is given by the inverse map:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
aH\mapsto Ha^{-1}
\]

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $H\leq G$
\end_inset

.
 The following statements are equivalent
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $H\trianglelefteq G$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $gHg^{-1}=H$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in G$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $gHg^{-1}=\{ghg^{-1}\mid h\in H\}$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $N_{G}(H)=G$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $gHg^{-1}\subseteq H$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in G$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $(1\implies2):$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $H\trianglelefteq G$
\end_inset

 means 
\begin_inset Formula $gH=Hg$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in G$
\end_inset

.
 Multiply both sides by 
\begin_inset Formula $g^{-1}$
\end_inset

 (a bijection) to get 
\begin_inset Formula $gHg^{-1}=Hgg^{-1}=H$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $(2\implies3):$
\end_inset

 Recall 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{G}(H)=\{g\in G\mid gHg^{-1}=H\}$
\end_inset

.
 By assumption, 
\begin_inset Formula $gHg^{-1}=H$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in G$
\end_inset

, therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{G}(H)=G$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $(3\implies4):$
\end_inset

 By assumption 
\begin_inset Formula $gHg^{-1}=H$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in G$
\end_inset

, therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $gHg^{-1}\subseteq H$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $(4\implies1):$
\end_inset

 We need to show 
\begin_inset Formula $gHg^{-1}\supseteq H$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in G$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $h\in H$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $g^{-1}hg\in H$
\end_inset

 by assumption.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $h=gg^{-1}hgg^{-1}\in gHg^{-1}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We show 
\begin_inset Formula $SL_{2}(\mathbb{R})\trianglelefteq GL_{2}(\mathbb{R})$
\end_inset

.
 It suffices to check 
\begin_inset Formula $MAM^{-1}\subseteq SL_{2}(\mathbb{R})$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $M\in GL_{2}(\mathbb{R})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $A\in SL_{2}(\mathbb{R})$
\end_inset

.
 Given any such 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\det(MAM^{-1})=\det(M)\det(A)\det(M^{-1})=\det(M)\det(M^{-1})=\det(I)=1
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $MAM^{-1}\in SL_{2}(\mathbb{R})$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Quotient Group
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $H\leq G$
\end_inset

.
 Define multiplication on the left cosets by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(aH)(bH)=abH
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Check that this is well-defined iff 
\begin_inset Formula $H\trianglelefteq G$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 be a group and let 
\begin_inset Formula $H\leq G$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
G/H=\{gH\mid g\in G\}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Define multiplication on 
\begin_inset Formula $G/H$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(aH)(bH)=abH
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Multiplication of left cosets is well defined if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $H\trianglelefteq G$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Choose different coset representatives 
\begin_inset Formula $a'$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b'$
\end_inset

.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $b'=bh_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a'=ah_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(a'H)(b'H)=(ah_{2}H)(bh_{1}H)=aHbH=abH'H
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $H'=H$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $b\in G$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 is normal.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
HK=\{hk\mid h\in H,\,k\in K\}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $H\trianglelefteq G$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $G/H=\{gH\mid g\in G\}$
\end_inset

 is a group with multiplication 
\begin_inset Formula $\cdot$
\end_inset

 being 
\begin_inset Formula $(aH)(bH)=abH$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in G$
\end_inset

.
 We say 
\begin_inset Formula $G/H$
\end_inset

 is the quotient group 
\begin_inset Formula $G\mod H$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Binary Operation: For all 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in G$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $abH$
\end_inset

 is a left coset of 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $\cdot$
\end_inset

 is a binary operation defined on the set of left cosets of 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Associativity: For all, 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b,c\in G$
\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula $((aH)(bH))(cH)=(abH)(cH)=((ab)cH)=(a(bc)H)=(aH)(bcH)=(aH)((bH)(cH))$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Identity: For all 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in G$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $(aH)(eH)=aeH=aH=eaH=(eH)(aH)$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Inverse: For all 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in G$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $(aH)(a^{-1}H)=aa^{-1}H=eH=H=eH=a^{-1}aH=(a^{-1}H)(aH)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $K=\langle(1,2,3)\rangle\trianglelefteq S_{3}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $(1,2)K=\{(1,2),(2,3),(1,3)\}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $(2,3)K=\{(2,3),(1,3),(1,2)\}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $(1,3)K=\{(1,3),(1,2),(2,3)\}$
\end_inset

.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $(1,2)K=(2,3)K=(1,3)K$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $()K=(1,2,3)K=(3,2,1)K$
\end_inset

.
 So there are two elements in 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{3}/K$
\end_inset

, and they are represented by 
\begin_inset Formula $\{()K,(1,2)K\}$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi:S_{3}/K\to\mathbb{Z}_{2}$
\end_inset

 be given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(()K)=\bar{0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi((1,2)K)=\bar{1}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is an isomorphism.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is abelian then 
\begin_inset Formula $G/H$
\end_inset

 is abelian: 
\begin_inset Formula $(aH)(bH)=abH=baH=(bH)(aH)$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is cyclic then 
\begin_inset Formula $G/H$
\end_inset

 is cyclic: Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $G=\langle a\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $bH=a^{n}H=(aH)^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $G/H=\langle aH\rangle$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
What does it mean to say 
\begin_inset Formula $G/H$
\end_inset

 is abelian.
 It means for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in G$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $ab=\varphi(a,b)ba$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(a,b)\in H$
\end_inset

.
 So we have a function 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi:G\times G\to H$
\end_inset

.
 What can we say about this function 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

? First of all, 
\begin_inset Formula $ab=ba$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(a,b)=e$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in G$
\end_inset

.
 Next 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
ab=\varphi(a,b)ba=\varphi(a,b)\varphi(b,a)ab
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
tells us 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(a,b)=\varphi(b,a)^{-1}$
\end_inset

.
 Next, associativity tells us
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varphi(a,b)\varphi(b,ac)acb=\varphi(a,b)bac=abc=a\varphi(b,c)cb=\varphi(a,\varphi(b,c))\varphi(b,c)acb\qquad\forall a,b,c\in G
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
a\varphi(b,c)a^{-1}=\varphi(a,\varphi(b,c))\varphi(b,c)=\varphi(a,b)\varphi(b,ac)\qquad\forall a,b,c\in G\label{eq:ass}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
And finally, the identity element 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

 tells us
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a\varphi(e,a)=ae\varphi(e,a)=ea=a=ae=ea\varphi(a,e)=a\varphi(a,e)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\varphi(a,e)=\varphi(e,a)=e\qquad\forall a\in G\label{eq:id}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given 
\begin_inset Formula $b,c\in G$
\end_inset

, suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $bc=cb$
\end_inset

 or in other words 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(b,c)=e$
\end_inset

.
 Then using 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:ass})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:id})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 we get 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
e=\varphi(a,b)\varphi(b,ac)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
What we've been calling 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 actually goes by a better name.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Given 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in G$
\end_inset

, the 
\series bold
commutator 
\series default

\begin_inset Formula $[a,b]$
\end_inset


\series bold
 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
[a,b]=aba^{-1}b^{-1}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Check that 
\begin_inset Formula $ab=[a,b]ba$
\end_inset

 so what we've been calling 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(a,b)$
\end_inset

 can also be thought of as 
\begin_inset Formula $[a,b]$
\end_inset

.
 Next, what does it mean to say 
\begin_inset Formula $G/H$
\end_inset

 is cyclic? It means for every 
\begin_inset Formula $b\in G$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $b=a^{\psi(b)}\varphi(b)$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(b)\in H$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi(b)\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

.
 Now suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 is abelian.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a^{\psi(b)+\psi(c)}\varphi(b)\varphi(c)=a^{\psi(b)}\varphi(b)a^{\psi(c)}\varphi(c)=bc=a^{\psi(bc)}\varphi(bc)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $G/Z(G)$
\end_inset

 is cyclic, then 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is abelian.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A subgroup 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is normal in 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 is the kernel of a group homomorphism.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $H\trianglelefteq G$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $G/H=\{aH\mid a\in G\}$
\end_inset

 is a group.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi:G\to G/H$
\end_inset

 be given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(a)=aH$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

 is a homomorphism: 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(ab)=abH=(aH)(bH)=\pi(a)\pi(b)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in G$
\end_inset

.
 And 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{Ker}\pi=\{a\in G\mid\pi(a)=H\}=\{a\in G\mid aH=H\}=H$
\end_inset

.
 Conversely, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi:G\to G'$
\end_inset

 be a homomorphism.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $a\mbox{Ker}\varphi a^{-1}\subset\mbox{Ker}\varphi$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varphi(axa^{-1})=\varphi(a)\varphi(x)\varphi(a^{-1})=\varphi(a)\varphi(a^{-1})=1\qquad\forall x\in\mbox{Ker}\varphi
\]

\end_inset

We also have 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{Ker}\varphi\subset a\mbox{Ker}\varphi a^{-1}$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $x=a(a^{-1}xa)a^{-1}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mbox{Ker}\varphi$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\det:(GL_{n}(\mathbb{R}),\cdot)\to(\mathbb{R}\setminus\{0\},\cdot)$
\end_inset

 is a homomorphism with 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{Ker}\det=SL_{n}(\mathbb{R})$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $SL_{n}(\mathbb{R})$
\end_inset

 is a normal subgroup in 
\begin_inset Formula $GL_{n}(\mathbb{R})$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Cyclic Groups and Subgroups
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 be a group with identity 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in G$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
H=\{a^{m}\mid m\in\mathbb{Z}\}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
is a subgroup of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 is the 
\begin_inset Formula $\textbf{cyclic subgroup}$
\end_inset

 generated by 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

.
 Notation: 
\begin_inset Formula $H=\langle a\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 is nonempty since 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in H$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $b,c\in H$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $b=a^{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $c=a^{j}$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $i,j\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $bc^{-1}=\left(a^{i}\right)\left(a^{j}\right)^{-1}=a^{i-j}\in H$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 In 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle3\rangle=\{3\cdot m\mid m\in\mathbb{Z}\}=3\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 In 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}/10\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle\bar{2}\rangle=\{\bar{2},\bar{4},\bar{6},\bar{8},\bar{0}\}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 In 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{3}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle(1,2,3)\rangle=\{(1,2,3),(1,3,2),1\}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A group 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\textbf{cyclic}$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $G=\langle a\rangle$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in G$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 is cyclic since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}=\langle1\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}/m\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 is cyclic since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}/m\mathbb{Z}=\langle\bar{1}\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{3}$
\end_inset

 is not cyclic.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

 is not cyclic: To obtain a contradiction, suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle\frac{a}{b}\rangle=\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

.
 Then for any prime 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{p}\in\langle\frac{a}{b}\rangle\implies\frac{1}{p}=n\frac{a}{b}$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $b=pma\implies p\mid b$
\end_inset

 for any prime 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 which is a contradiction.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $H=\langle a\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $|H|=\mbox{ord}a$
\end_inset

.
 More precisely: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{ord}a=m<\infty$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $H=\{e,a,a^{2},\dots,a^{n-1}\}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{ord}a=\infty$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $a^{k}\neq a^{\ell}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $k,\ell\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $k\neq\ell$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $H=\langle a\rangle$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{ord}a=m<\infty$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{ord}(a^{k})=\frac{m}{\mbox{gcd}(m,k)}$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $m=\mbox{ord}(a)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $d=\mbox{gcd}(m,k)$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $m=dm'$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $k=dk'$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{gcd}(m',k')=1$
\end_inset

.
 We need to prove that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{ord}(a^{k})=\frac{m}{d}=m'$
\end_inset

.
 We have 
\begin_inset Formula $(a^{k})^{m'}=a^{km'}=a^{\frac{km}{d}}=a^{k'm}=(a^{m})^{k'}=e^{k'}=e$
\end_inset

.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{ord}(a^{k})\mid m'$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{ord}(a^{k})=t$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $(a^{k})^{t}=e\implies a^{kt}=e\implies m\mid kt\implies dm'\mid dk't\implies m'\mid k't\implies m'\mid t$
\end_inset

.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $m'\mid\mbox{ord}(a^{k})$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 In 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}/m\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{ord}(\bar{k})=\frac{m}{\mbox{gcd}(m,k)}$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{cor}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $H=\langle a\rangle$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{ord}a=m<\infty$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle a^{k}\rangle=H$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{gcd}(m,k)=1$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{cor}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{ex}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Find the number of generators of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}/625\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{ex}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Answer: 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(625)=\varphi(5^{4})=5^{4}-5^{3}=500$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Any two cyclic groups having the same order are isomorphic.
 More specifically:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle x\rangle$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle y\rangle$
\end_inset

 both have order 
\begin_inset Formula $m<\infty$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi:\langle x\rangle\to\langle y\rangle$
\end_inset

 given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(x^{k})=y^{k}$
\end_inset

 is an isomorphism.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle x\rangle$
\end_inset

 is an infinite cycle group, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi:\mathbb{Z}\to\langle x\rangle$
\end_inset

 given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi(k)=x^{k}$
\end_inset

 is an isomorphism.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Every subgroup of a cyclic group 
\begin_inset Formula $H=\langle x\rangle$
\end_inset

 is still cyclic.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $K\leq H$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $K=\{e\}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $K=\langle e\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $K\neq\{e\}$
\end_inset

, then there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{a}\in K\setminus\{e\}$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is a group, we can assume 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $P=\{b\in\mathbb{N}\mid x^{b}\in K\}\neq\emptyset$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $d=\min P$
\end_inset

.
 We will show 
\begin_inset Formula $K=\langle x^{d}\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 We have 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle x^{d}\rangle\subseteq K$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{nd}\in K$
\end_inset

.
 For the reverse inclusion, let 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in K$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $K\leq\langle x\rangle$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $y=x^{\ell}$
\end_inset

, for some integer 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell$
\end_inset

.
 Now 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\ell=gd+r\qquad\mbox{with }0\le r\le d-1
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So 
\begin_inset Formula $y=x^{dg+r}=x^{dg}x^{r}$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $r\neq0$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{r}=x^{-dg}y\in K$
\end_inset

, which is a contradiction since 
\begin_inset Formula $d=\min P$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{cor}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 be a cyclic group of order 
\begin_inset Formula $m<\infty$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $d\mid m$
\end_inset

, then there exists a unique subgroup of 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 of order 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{cor}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $H=\langle x\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 We first prove existence.
 Recall 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mbox{ord}(x^{a})=\frac{\mbox{ord}(x)}{\mbox{gcd}(\mbox{ord}(x),a)}=\frac{m}{\mbox{gcd}(m,a)}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $d\mid m\implies m=dk$
\end_inset

 and so
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
|\langle x^{k}\rangle|=\mbox{ord}(x^{k})=\frac{m}{\mbox{gcd}(m,k)}=\frac{m}{k}=d
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we prove uniqueness.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $L\leq H$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $|L|=d$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $L\leq H$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $L=\langle x^{t}\rangle$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
|L|=|\langle x^{t}\rangle|=\mbox{ord}(x^{t})=\frac{m}{\mbox{gcd}(m,t)}=d=\frac{m}{k}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{gcd}(m,t)=k$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $k\mid t$
\end_inset

 which implies 
\begin_inset Formula $t=ku$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{t}=x^{ku}\in\langle x^{k}\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle x^{t}\rangle=L\subseteq\langle x^{k}\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $|L|=\langle x^{k}\rangle$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $L\subseteq\langle x^{k}\rangle$
\end_inset

, we must have 
\begin_inset Formula $L=\langle x^{k}\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The number of subgroups of a cyclic group of order 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 is equal to the number of divisors of 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{ex}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Find all the subgroups of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}/12\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

, giving a generator for each.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{ex}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The number of subgroups of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}/12\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 is equal to the number of divisors of 
\begin_inset Formula $12=2^{2}\cdot3$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $m=p_{1}^{e_{1}}\cdots p_{k}^{e_{k}}$
\end_inset

, then the number of divisors of 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $(e_{1}+1)\cdots(e_{k}+1)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Subgroups generated by Subsets
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 be a group.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 be a nonempty subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

.
 The subgroup of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 
\series bold
generated by 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 
\series default
is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\langle A\rangle=\bigcap_{A\subseteq K\leq G}K
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 be a group.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 be a nonempty subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\bar{A}=\{a_{1}^{e_{1}}\cdots a_{m}^{e_{m}}\mid m\in\mathbb{N},\,a_{i}\in A,\,e_{i}=\pm1,\,1\leq i\leq m\}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{A}=\langle A\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 First we note that 
\begin_inset Formula $A\subseteq\bar{A}$
\end_inset

 since for any 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in A$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $a=a^{1}\in\bar{A}$
\end_inset

.
 Next we check that 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{A}$
\end_inset

 is a subgroup of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{A}$
\end_inset

 is nonempty since 
\begin_inset Formula $A\subseteq\bar{A}$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $a=a_{1}^{e_{1}}\cdots a_{m}^{e_{m}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b=b_{1}^{f_{1}}\cdots b_{m}^{f_{m}}$
\end_inset

 be two elements in 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{A}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $b^{-1}=b_{m}^{-f_{m}}\cdots b_{1}^{-f_{1}}\in\bar{A}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $ab=a_{1}^{e_{1}}\cdots a_{m}^{e_{m}}\cdot b_{m}^{-f_{m}}\cdots b_{1}^{-f_{1}}\in\bar{A}$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle A\rangle$
\end_inset

 is the smallest subgroup of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 which contains 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle A\rangle\subseteq\bar{A}$
\end_inset

.
 For the reverse inclusion, suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $a=a_{1}^{e_{1}}\cdots a_{m}^{e_{m}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $A\subseteq K\leq G$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in K$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is a subgroup of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 which contains 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{A}\subseteq\langle A\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is abelian, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle A\rangle=\{a_{1}^{e_{1}}\cdots a_{m}^{e_{m}}\mid m\in\mathbb{N},\,a_{i}\in A,\,e_{i}\in\mathbb{Z},\,1\leq i\leq m\}$
\end_inset

.
 Notice in this case the exponents can be any integer.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 In 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula $\langle a,b\rangle=\{ma+kb\mid m,k\in\mathbb{Z}\}$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 is cyclic, 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle a,b\rangle=\langle d\rangle$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $d\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

.
 In fact 
\begin_inset Formula $d=\gcd(a,b)$
\end_inset

.
 Proof: Since 
\begin_inset Formula $d\mid a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $d\mid b$
\end_inset

, we must have 
\begin_inset Formula $da'=a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $db'=b$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $a',b'\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

.
 Then for all 
\begin_inset Formula $m,k\in\mathbb{Z},$
\end_inset

 we have
\begin_inset Formula $ma+kb=ma'd+kb'd=(ma'+kb')d\in\langle d\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle a,b\rangle\subseteq\langle d\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 For the reverse inclusion, note that 
\begin_inset Formula $d=ax+by$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

, therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle d\rangle=\langle ax+by\rangle\subseteq\langle a,b\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 In 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{m}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\langle A\rangle=S_{m}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $A=\{(1,2),(1,3),\dots,(1,m)\}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\langle B\rangle=S_{m}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $B=\{(1,2),(2,3),\dots,(m-1,m)\}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\langle C\rangle=S_{m}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $C=\{(1,2),(1,2,\dots,m)\}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To prove 
\begin_inset Formula $(1)$
\end_inset

, we first note that any 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma\in S_{m}$
\end_inset

 is a product of transpositions.
 So it suffices to show that any transposition 
\begin_inset Formula $(i,j)\in\langle A\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $(i,j)=(1,i)(1,j)(1,i)$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $(i,j)\in\langle A\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 To prove 
\begin_inset Formula $(2)$
\end_inset

, it suffices to show any transposition 
\begin_inset Formula $(i,j)\in\langle B\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 Without loss of generality, assume 
\begin_inset Formula $i<j$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $(i,j)=(j-1,j)\cdots(i+1,i+2)(i,i+1)(i+1,i+2)\cdots(j-1,j)$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $(i,j)\in\langle B\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 To prove 
\begin_inset Formula $(3)$
\end_inset

, note that 
\begin_inset Formula $(1,2,\dots,m)^{k}(1,2)(m,m-1,\dots,1)^{k}=(k,k+1)$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $B\in\langle C\rangle$
\end_inset

 which implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle C\rangle=S_{m}$
\end_inset

.
  
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Order
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 be a group and let 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in G$
\end_inset

.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $\textbf{order}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 is the least natural number 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{Z}_{\geq1}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $g^{n}=e$
\end_inset

.
 If no such integer exists, we say 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 has infinite order.
 We sometimes denote the order of 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{ord}(g)$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The order of an element can also be thought of as the size of the cyclic
 group generated by 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 In the group 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

, every nonzero element has infinite order.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 In the group 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{C}^{\times}$
\end_inset

, there are infinitely many elements which have finite order.
 The elements in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{C}$
\end_inset

 which have finite order are called the 
\series bold
roots of unity
\series default
.
 The set of all roots of unity is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
T=\{e^{2\pi ir}\mid r\in\mathbb{Q}\}.
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is a finite group.
 Then every 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in G$
\end_inset

 has finite order.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Consider the set 
\begin_inset Formula $\{g^{n}\mid n\in\mathbb{Z}_{\geq1}\}$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is finite, we must have 
\begin_inset Formula $g^{m}=g$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $m\in\mathbb{Z}_{\geq1}$
\end_inset

.
 This implies 
\begin_inset Formula $g^{m-1}=1$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in G$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 be the order of 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $g^{n}=e$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $m\mid n$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 First note that 
\begin_inset Formula $m\leq n$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 is the least natural number which kills 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 is a Euclidean domain and 
\begin_inset Formula $m\leq n$
\end_inset

, there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $k\in\mathbb{Z}_{\geq1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq r<m$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $n=mk+r$
\end_inset

.
 Assume for a contradiction that 
\begin_inset Formula $r\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 Then we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
e & =g^{n}\\
 & =g^{mk+r}\\
 & =(g^{m})^{k}g^{r}\\
 & =g^{r}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

This contradicts the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 is least natural number which kills 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

.
 So we must have 
\begin_inset Formula $r=0$
\end_inset

 which implies 
\begin_inset Formula $m\mid n$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Order of a Product of Two Elements
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{propproductoftwoorders}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 be a group and let 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1},g_{2}\in G$
\end_inset

 with orders 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 respectively.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{2}$
\end_inset

 commute with one another and 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 is relatively prime to 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, then the order of 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1}g_{2}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $mn$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 be the order of 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1}g_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 First note that since 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{2}$
\end_inset

 commute with each other, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
(g_{1}g_{2})^{mn} & =g_{1}^{mn}g_{2}^{mn}\\
 & =(g_{1}^{m})^{n}(g_{2}^{n})^{m}\\
 & =e^{n}e^{m}\\
 & =e.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $k\mid mn$
\end_inset

.
 On the other hand, since 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 is the order of 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1}g_{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1}$
\end_inset

 commutes with 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{2}$
\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
e=g_{1}^{k}g_{2}^{k}.\label{eq:bothsidesorderof}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Raising both sides of 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:bothsidesorderof})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 to the 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

th power gives us 
\begin_inset Formula $e=g_{1}^{kn}$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $m\mid kn$
\end_inset

, and since 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 is relatively prime to 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, this implies 
\begin_inset Formula $m\mid k$
\end_inset

.
 A similar calculation shows 
\begin_inset Formula $n\mid k$
\end_inset

.
 Since both 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 divide 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

, we must have 
\begin_inset Formula $mn\mid k$
\end_inset

.
 So since 
\begin_inset Formula $k\mid mn$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $mn\mid k$
\end_inset

, we must have 
\begin_inset Formula $mn=k$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Note that we need 
\emph on
both 
\emph default

\begin_inset Formula $g_{1}$
\end_inset

 to commute with 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{2}$
\end_inset

 
\emph on
and 
\emph default

\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 to be relatively prime to 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 in order to conclude 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{propproductoftwoorders})
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 In one of these conditions do not hold, then the conclusion of 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{propproductoftwoorders})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 may not hold.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{2}$
\end_inset

 do not commute, then the result can fail.
 For example, in 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{3}$
\end_inset

, let 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1}=(13)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{2}=(12)$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1}g_{2}=(13)(12)=(123)$
\end_inset

 has order 
\begin_inset Formula $3$
\end_inset

, but 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{2}$
\end_inset

 both have order 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

.
 Even if 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{2}$
\end_inset

 commute, if their order is not relatively prime, the result can still fail.
 For example, in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}\slash12\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

, the order of 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{2}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $6$
\end_inset

 and the order of 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{6}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

.
 But the order of 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{2}+\overline{6}=\overline{8}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $3$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{2}$
\end_inset

 be elements in a group 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 with orders 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{2}$
\end_inset

 respectively.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1}$
\end_inset

 commutes with 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{ord}(g_{1}g_{2})=n_{1}n_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $(n_{1},n_{2})=1$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Assume for a contradiction that 
\begin_inset Formula $(n_{1},n_{2})\neq1$
\end_inset

.
 Denote 
\begin_inset Formula $k=(n_{1},n_{2})$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{1}/k$
\end_inset

 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{2}$
\end_inset

 have a nontrivial factor
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{ord}(g_{1}g_{2})=mn$
\end_inset

 and that is 
\begin_inset Formula $mn$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\backslash
label{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 be positive integers.
 Denote 
\begin_inset Formula $a=\gcd(m,n)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b=\mathrm{lcm}(m,n)$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
ab=mn.
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We will show 
\begin_inset Formula $a=mn/b$
\end_inset

.
 Observe that 
\begin_inset Formula $m\mid m(n/b)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $n\mid(m/b)n$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $a\mid mn/b$
\end_inset

.
 Conversely, observe that 
\begin_inset Formula $mn/a\mid m$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $(mn/a)(a/n)=m$
\end_inset

.
 Similarly, 
\begin_inset Formula $mn/a\mid n$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $(mn/a)(a/n)=n$
\end_inset

.
 It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $b\mid mn/a$
\end_inset

.
 In other words, 
\begin_inset Formula $mn/b\mid a$
\end_inset

.
 Since we have 
\begin_inset Formula $a\mid mn/b$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $mn/b\mid a$
\end_inset

, it follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $a=mn/b$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Basic Theorems
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Lagrange's Theorem
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 be a group and let 
\begin_inset Formula $H\leq G$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $|H|=|gH|$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in G$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The idea is that multiplying 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 on the left is an isomorphism since 
\begin_inset Formula $g^{-1}$
\end_inset

 exists.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Lagrange's Theorem) Let 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 be a finite group.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $H\leq G$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $|H|$
\end_inset

 divides 
\begin_inset Formula $|G|$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The set of left cosets of 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 form a partition of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 into equal sized parts.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $|G|=|H|[G:H]$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $H\trianglelefteq G$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $|G/H|=\frac{|G|}{|H|}=[G:H]$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{cor}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is a finite group then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{ord}a$
\end_inset

 divides 
\begin_inset Formula $|G|$
\end_inset

 for any 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in G$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{cor}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $H=\langle a\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $|H|=\mbox{ord}a$
\end_inset

 and by Lagrange's Theorem 
\begin_inset Formula $|H|$
\end_inset

 divides 
\begin_inset Formula $|G|$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{cor}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is a finite group with 
\begin_inset Formula $|G|=p$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is cyclic.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{cor}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Choose 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in G\setminus\{e\}$
\end_inset

.
 Then since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{ord}a$
\end_inset

 divides 
\begin_inset Formula $|G|=p$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{ord}a=p$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $G=\langle a\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Recall if 
\begin_inset Formula $G/Z(G)$
\end_inset

 is cyclic then 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is abelian (Proof: 
\begin_inset Formula $G/Z(G)$
\end_inset

 is cyclic means 
\begin_inset Formula $\exists g\in G$
\end_inset

 such that for all 
\begin_inset Formula $h,h'\in G$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $h=zg^{n}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $h'=z'g^{n'}$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $z,z'\in Z(G)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $n,n'\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $hh'=zg^{n}z'g^{n'}=zz'g^{n+n'}=zz'g^{n'+n}=z'g^{n'}zg^{n}=h'h$
\end_inset

).
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is a finite group of order 
\begin_inset Formula $pq$
\end_inset

 where both 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 are prime, then either 
\begin_inset Formula $Z(G)=\{e\}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is abelian.
 The possibilities for 
\begin_inset Formula $|G/Z(G)|$
\end_inset

 are 
\begin_inset Formula $1,p,q,$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $pq$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $|G/Z(G)|=1,p,$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $G/Z(G)$
\end_inset

 is cyclic which implies 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is abelian.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $|G/Z(G)|=pq$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $Z(G)=\{e\}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Cauchy's Theorem) Let 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 be a finite abelian group and let 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 be a prime.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $p\mid|G|$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 has an element of order 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We prove by induction on 
\begin_inset Formula $|G|$
\end_inset

.
 The base case is 
\begin_inset Formula $|G|=p$
\end_inset

.
 In this case, 
\begin_inset Formula $G=\langle a\rangle$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in G$
\end_inset

 and thus 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 has order 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 Now let 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in G\setminus\{e\}$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $p|\mbox{ord}x$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{ord}x=pm$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{ord}(x^{m})=p$
\end_inset

.
 So assume 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 does not divide 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{ord}x$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $N=\langle x\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $N\trianglelefteq G$
\end_inset

 because 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is abelian and 
\begin_inset Formula $|G|=|N||G/N|$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 divides 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 but does not divide 
\begin_inset Formula $|N|$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 divides 
\begin_inset Formula $|G/N|$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $p||G/N|$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $|G/N|<|G|$
\end_inset

, then by the induction hypothesis there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $yN\in G/N$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{ord}(yN)=p$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $(yN)^{p}=y^{p}N=N$
\end_inset

 and this implies 
\begin_inset Formula $y^{p}=n$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in N$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle y^{p}\rangle\subset\langle y\rangle$
\end_inset

 and the inclusion is strict, it follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{ord}(y^{p})=\frac{\mbox{ord}y}{\mbox{gcd}(\mbox{ord}y,p)}<\mbox{ord}(y)$
\end_inset

, which implies 
\begin_inset Formula $1<\mbox{gcd}(\mbox{ord}y,p)$
\end_inset

.
 It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{gcd}(\mbox{ord}y,p)=p$
\end_inset

.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $p|\mbox{ord}y$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Alternate Proof: This part doesn't require the induction part.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $G=\{g_{1},\dots,g_{n}\}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $m=\mbox{lcm}(\mbox{ord}g_{1},\dots,\mbox{ord}g_{n})$
\end_inset

.
 Assume no element in 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 has order 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 does not divide 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

.
 Construct homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varphi:\mathbb{Z}_{(m)}^{n}\mapsto G,\qquad(\overline{a_{1}},\dots,\overline{a_{n}})\mapsto g_{1}^{a_{1}}\cdots g_{n}^{a_{n}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This implies 
\begin_inset Formula $|\mbox{Ker}\varphi||G|=m^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $p\mid|G|$
\end_inset

, it must divide 
\begin_inset Formula $m^{n}$
\end_inset

, which implies it divides 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

, which is a contradiction.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The Isomorphism Theorems
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
First Isomorphism Theorem
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 be groups and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon G\to H$
\end_inset

 be a group homomorphism.
 Then
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The kernel of 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is a normal subgroup of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The image of 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is a subgroup of 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 and moreover we have the isomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $G\slash\ker\varphi\cong\mathrm{im}\,\varphi$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 1.
 First let us check 
\begin_inset Formula $\ker\varphi$
\end_inset

 is a subgroup of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

.
 It is nonempty since 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(e)=e$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $e\in\ker\varphi$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1},g_{2}\in\ker\varphi$
\end_inset

 .
 Then observe that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\varphi(g_{1}g_{2}^{-1}) & =\varphi(g_{1})\varphi(g_{2})^{-1}\\
 & =ee\\
 & =e
\end{align*}

\end_inset

implies 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1}g_{2}^{-1}\in\ker\varphi$
\end_inset

.
 It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\ker\varphi$
\end_inset

 is a subgroup of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Next, we check that 
\begin_inset Formula $\ker\varphi$
\end_inset

 is a normal subgroup of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in G$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\ker\varphi$
\end_inset

.
 Then observe that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\varphi(gxg^{-1}) & =\varphi(g)\varphi(x)\varphi(g)^{-1}\\
 & =\varphi(g)e\varphi(g)^{-1}\\
 & =\varphi(g)\varphi(g)^{-1}\\
 & =e
\end{align*}

\end_inset

implies 
\begin_inset Formula $gxg^{-1}\in\ker\varphi$
\end_inset

.
 It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\ker\varphi$
\end_inset

 is a normal subgroup of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
2.
 First let us check 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{im}\,\varphi$
\end_inset

 is a subgroup of 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

.
 It is nonempty since 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(e)=e$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $e\in\mathrm{im}\,\varphi$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(g_{1}),\varphi(g_{2})\in\mathrm{im}\,\varphi$
\end_inset

.
 Then observe that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\varphi(g_{1})\varphi(g_{2})^{-1} & =\varphi(g_{1}g_{2}^{-1})
\end{align*}

\end_inset

implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(g_{1})\varphi(g_{2})^{-1}\in\mathrm{im}\,\varphi$
\end_inset

.
 It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{im}\,\varphi$
\end_inset

 is a subgroup of 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Next, we define 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\varphi}\colon G\slash\ker\varphi\to\mathrm{im}\,\varphi$
\end_inset

 by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\overline{\varphi}(\overline{g})=\varphi(g)\label{eq:welldefinedgmodker}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{g}\in G\slash\ker\varphi$
\end_inset

.
 We need to check that 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:welldefinedgmodker})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is well-defined.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $gx$
\end_inset

 be another coset representative of 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{g}$
\end_inset

 (so 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(x)=e$
\end_inset

).
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\overline{\varphi}(\overline{gx}) & =\varphi(gx)\\
 & =\varphi(g)\varphi(x)\\
 & =\varphi(g)e\\
 & =\varphi(g)\\
 & =\overline{\varphi}(\overline{g}).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Thus 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:welldefinedgmodker})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is well-defined.
 Now we show 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\varphi}$
\end_inset

 gives us an isomorphism from 
\begin_inset Formula $G\slash\ker\varphi$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{im}\,\varphi$
\end_inset

.
 It is a group homomorphism since if 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1},g_{2}\in G$
\end_inset

, then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\overline{\varphi}(\overline{g}_{1}\overline{g}_{2}) & =\varphi(g_{1}g_{2})\\
 & =\varphi(g_{1})\varphi(g_{2})\\
 & =\overline{\varphi}(\overline{g}_{1})\overline{\varphi}(\overline{g}_{2}).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

It is also surjective since if 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(g)\in\mathrm{im}\,\varphi$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\varphi}(\overline{g})=\varphi(g)$
\end_inset

.
 Finally, it is injective since
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\overline{\varphi}(\overline{g})=e & \implies\varphi(g)=e\\
 & \implies g\in\ker\varphi\\
 & \implies\overline{g}=e.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\varphi}$
\end_inset

 is in fact a group isomorphism.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Second Isomorphism Theorem
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 be a group, let 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 be a subgroup of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 be a normal subgroup of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

.
 Then the following hold:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The product 
\begin_inset Formula $HN$
\end_inset

 is a subgroup of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The intersection 
\begin_inset Formula $H\cap N$
\end_inset

 is a normal subgroup of 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The quotient groups 
\begin_inset Formula $(HN)\slash N$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $H\slash(H\cap N)$
\end_inset

 are isomorphic.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 1.
 First note that 
\begin_inset Formula $HN$
\end_inset

 is nonempty since 
\begin_inset Formula $e=ee\in HN$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{1}n_{1},h_{2}n_{2}\in HN$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
(h_{1}n_{1})(h_{2}n_{2})^{-1} & =h_{1}n_{1}n_{2}^{-1}h_{2}^{-1}\\
 & =h_{1}(h_{2}^{-1}h_{2})n_{1}n_{2}^{-1}h_{2}^{-1}\\
 & =h_{1}h_{2}^{-1}(h_{2}n_{1}n_{2}^{-1}h_{2}^{-1})\\
 & \in HN.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $HN$
\end_inset

 is a subgroup of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
2.
 Let us check that it is a subgroup of 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 first.
 It is nonempty since 
\begin_inset Formula $e\in H\cap N$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in H\cap N$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $xy^{-1}\in H\cap N$
\end_inset

 also since both 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 are groups.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $H\cap N$
\end_inset

 is a subgroup of 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Now let us check that 
\begin_inset Formula $H\cap N$
\end_inset

 is a normal subgroup of 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in H\cap N$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $h\in H$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $hxh^{-1}\in N$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 is normal.
 Also 
\begin_inset Formula $hxh^{-1}\in H$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 is a group.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $hxh^{-1}\in H\cap N$
\end_inset

.
 It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $H\cap N$
\end_inset

 is a normal subgroup of 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
3.
 We shall define an isomorphism from 
\begin_inset Formula $H\slash(H\cap N)$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $(HN)\slash N$
\end_inset

.
 To simplify notation in what follows, we denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{h}$
\end_inset

 to be the coset in 
\begin_inset Formula $(HN)\slash N$
\end_inset

 represented by 
\begin_inset Formula $h\in H$
\end_inset

 and we denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $\underline{h}$
\end_inset

 to be the coset in 
\begin_inset Formula $H\slash(H\cap N)$
\end_inset

 represented by 
\begin_inset Formula $h\in H$
\end_inset

.
 Define a map 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon H\slash(H\cap N)\to(HN)\slash N$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\varphi(\underline{h})=\overline{h}\label{eq:welldefinedcoset2iso}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

for all cosets 
\begin_inset Formula $\underline{h}\in H\slash(H\cap N)$
\end_inset

.
 We need to check that 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:welldefinedcoset2iso})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is well-defined (that is, does not depend on the coset representative).
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $hx$
\end_inset

 is another coset representative of 
\begin_inset Formula $\underline{h}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in H\cap N$
\end_inset

.
 Then clearly 
\begin_inset Formula $hx$
\end_inset

 is another coset representative of 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{h}$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in N$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:welldefinedcoset2iso})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is well-defined.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

It is easy to see that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is a group homomorphism.
 It is also surjective since every coset in 
\begin_inset Formula $(HN)\slash N$
\end_inset

 can be represented by an element in 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 (since 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{hn}=\overline{h}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $h\in H$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in N$
\end_inset

).
 Finally, let us check that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is injective.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\underline{h}\in\ker\varphi$
\end_inset

 (so 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{h}=\overline{e})$
\end_inset

.
 This implies 
\begin_inset Formula $h\in N$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $h\in H$
\end_inset

 already, we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $h\in H\cap N$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\underline{h}=\underline{e}$
\end_inset

, which implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is injective.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is a group isomorphism, and we are done.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Here's something to watch out for: It is tempting to define 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi\colon(HN)\slash N\to H\slash(H\cap N)$
\end_inset

 by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\psi(\overline{h})=\underline{h}\label{eq:iswelldefined2iso}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

for all cosets 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{h}\in HN\slash N$
\end_inset

.
 While it is true that every coset in 
\begin_inset Formula $(HN)\slash N$
\end_inset

 can be represented by an 
\begin_inset Formula $h\in H$
\end_inset

, the definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:iswelldefined2iso})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 does not make it clear what 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 is doing to a general coset representative of 
\begin_inset Formula $(HN)\slash N$
\end_inset

.
 One should instead define 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\psi(\overline{hn})=\underline{h}\label{eq:welldefinedness2isocorr}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

for all cosets 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{hn}\in HN\slash N$
\end_inset

.
 The definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:welldefinedcoset2iso})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 makes it clear that we are chopping off the term which lies in 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

, unlike the definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:iswelldefined2iso})
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 When defining a map out of a quotient group, one should always describe
 how the map acts on a general coset representative, and then show that
 this map is well-defined by showing the map acts the same on another general
 coset representative which represents the same coset.
 Do not define a map out of a quotient group by describing how the map acts
 on a special coset representative! 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Third Isomorphism Theorem
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 ( The Third Isomorphism Theorem) Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(G,\cdot)$
\end_inset

 be a group.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $H,K\trianglelefteq G$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $H\leq K$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(G/H)/(K/H)\cong G/K
\]

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi:G/H\to G/K$
\end_inset

 be given by mapping 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(aH)=aK$
\end_inset

.
 To be sure this is well defined, suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $aH=bH$
\end_inset

.
 We want to show 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(aH)=\varphi(bH)$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $aK=bK$
\end_inset

 .
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $aH=bH$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $b=ah$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $h\in H\subset K$
\end_inset

.
 This implies 
\begin_inset Formula $b\in aK$
\end_inset

, and therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $bK=aK$
\end_inset

.
 Next we check this is a homomorphism.
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\varphi(aHbH) & =\varphi(abH)\\
 & =abK\\
 & =aKbK\\
 & =\varphi(aH)\varphi(bH)
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By the first isomorhpism theorem, 
\begin_inset Formula $(G/H)/\mbox{Ker}\varphi\cong\varphi(G/H)$
\end_inset

.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mbox{Ker}\varphi=\{aH\in G/H\mid aK=K\}=\{aH\in G/H\mid a\in K\}=K/H
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Also 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(G/H)=G/K$
\end_inset

 because for any 
\begin_inset Formula $aK\in G/K$
\end_inset

 we have 
\begin_inset Formula $aK=\varphi(aH)$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $H=8\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $K=4\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $H\trianglelefteq\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $K\trianglelefteq\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $8\mathbb{Z}\leq4\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

.
 By the third isomorphism theorem, 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mathbb{Z}/8\mathbb{Z})/(4\mathbb{Z}/8\mathbb{Z})\cong\mathbb{Z}/4\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(G,\cdot)$
\end_inset

 be a group and let 
\begin_inset Formula $H\trianglelefteq G$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $T\leq G/H$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $T=A/H$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $A\leq G$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $H\leq A$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $A/H\trianglelefteq G/H$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $A\trianglelefteq G$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $(1):$
\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A=\{a\in G\mid aH\in T\}$
\end_inset

.
 We need to check that 
\begin_inset Formula $A\leq G$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $H\leq A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $A/H=T$
\end_inset

.
 We have 
\begin_inset Formula $e\in A$
\end_inset

 because 
\begin_inset Formula $eH\in T$
\end_inset

.
 We have closure under multiplication because 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in A$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $aH,bH\in T$
\end_inset

, and since 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 is a group, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $abH=(aH)(bH)\in T$
\end_inset

 which implies 
\begin_inset Formula $ab\in A$
\end_inset

.
 Finally we check for inverses.
 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in A$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $aH\in T$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 is a group, 
\begin_inset Formula $aH$
\end_inset

 has an inverse, namely 
\begin_inset Formula $a^{-1}H$
\end_inset

.
 This implies 
\begin_inset Formula $a^{-1}\in A$
\end_inset

.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $A\leq G$
\end_inset

.
 Now if 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in H$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $xH=H\in T$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in A$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $H\subset A$
\end_inset

.
 Finally, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $A/H=\{aH\mid a\in A\}=T$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $(2):$
\end_inset

 First assume 
\begin_inset Formula $A/H\trianglelefteq G/H$
\end_inset

.
 We need to show for all 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in G$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $gAg^{-1}\subset A$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in G$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in A$
\end_inset

.
 We know 
\begin_inset Formula $gHaHg^{-1}H=gaHg^{-1}H=gag^{-1}H=a'H$
\end_inset

.
 some 
\begin_inset Formula $a'\in A$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $gAg^{-1}\subset A$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $A\trianglelefteq G$
\end_inset

.
 To prove the converse, assume 
\begin_inset Formula $A\trianglelefteq G$
\end_inset

.
 Then we want to show 
\begin_inset Formula $gH(A/H)(gH)^{-1}\subset A/H$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in G$
\end_inset

.
 So let 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in G$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in A$
\end_inset

.
 We know that 
\begin_inset Formula $gag^{-1}=a'$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $a'\in A$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $gHaH(gH)^{-1}=gag^{-1}H=a'H$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 All the subgroups of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}/10\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 are of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $A/10\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $10\mathbb{Z}\leq A\leq\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

.
 So any subgroup of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}/10\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 is of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $d\mathbb{Z}/10\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $d|10$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Cauchy's Theorem
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 be a finite group and 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 be a prime factor of 
\begin_inset Formula $|G|$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 contains an element of order 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 Equivalently, 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 contains a subgroup of size 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We will use induction on 
\begin_inset Formula $|G|$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $n=|G|$
\end_inset

.
 The base case is 
\begin_inset Formula $n=p$
\end_inset

.
 In this case, any nonidentity element has order 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 Now suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $n>p$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $p|n$
\end_inset

, and the theorem is true for all groups of order less than 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 and divisible by 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\hfill$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\textbf{Case 1}$
\end_inset

: G is abelian.
 Assume no element of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 has order 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 has order 
\begin_inset Formula $kp$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $k\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $g^{k}$
\end_inset

 has order 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, no element has order divisible by 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $G=\{g_{1},g_{2},\dots,g_{n}\}$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{i}$
\end_inset

 have order 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{i}$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{i}$
\end_inset

 is not divisible by 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 Set 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 to be the least common multiple of the 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{i}'s$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{i}^{m}=e$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq i\leq n$
\end_inset

, there exists a homomorphism of abelian groups 
\begin_inset Formula $f:(\mathbb{Z}/(m))^{n}\to G$
\end_inset

 given by 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\overline{a_{1}},\dots,\overline{a_{n}})=g_{1}^{a_{1}}\cdots g_{r}^{a_{r}}$
\end_inset

.
 It is obviously surjective (for example, 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\overline{1},\overline{0},\overline{0}\dots,\overline{0})=g_{1}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\overline{0},\overline{1},\overline{0}\dots,\overline{0})=g_{2}$
\end_inset

, etc...), and so there is a short exact sequence given by:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd}  1 
\backslash
arrow[r] & 
\backslash
ker f 
\backslash
arrow[r] & ( 
\backslash
mathbb{Z} / (m) )^n  
\backslash
arrow[r,"f"]  & G 
\backslash
arrow[r] & 1 
\backslash
end{tikzcd}
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We deduce from this short exact sequence the equation
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
|\ker f|\cdot|G|=m^{n}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 divides 
\begin_inset Formula $|G|$
\end_inset

, it divides 
\begin_inset Formula $m^{n}$
\end_inset

 too.
 But 
\begin_inset Formula $m^{n}$
\end_inset

 is not divisible by 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 is not divisible by 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, so we have reached a contradiction.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\textbf{Case 2}$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is nonabelian.
 If a proper subgroup 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 has order divisible by 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, then by induction there is an element of order 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

, which gives us an element of order 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

.
 Thus we may assume no proper subgroup of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 has order divisible by 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 We will show 
\begin_inset Formula $|Z(G)|$
\end_inset

 is divisible by 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, and hence 
\begin_inset Formula $Z(G)$
\end_inset

 can't be a proper subgroup of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

, and the proof reduces to the abelian case.
 For any proper subgroup 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $|G|=|H|\cdot[G:H]$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $|H|$
\end_inset

 is not divisible by 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $p|[G:H]$
\end_inset

 for every proper subgroup 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

.
 Let the conjugacy classes in 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 with size greater than 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 be represented by 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1},g_{2},\dots,g_{k}$
\end_inset

.
 The conjugacy classes of size 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 are the elements in 
\begin_inset Formula $Z(G)$
\end_inset

.
 Since the conjugacy classes are a partition of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

, counting 
\begin_inset Formula $|G|$
\end_inset

 by counting conjugacy classes implies
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
|G|=|Z(G)|+\sum_{i=1}^{k}[G:Z(g_{i})]
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $Z(g_{i})$
\end_inset

 is the centralizer of 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 Since the conjugacy class of each 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{i}$
\end_inset

 has size greater than 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $[G:Z(g_{i})]>1$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $Z(g_{i})\neq G$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $p|[G:Z(g_{i})]$
\end_inset

.
 The left side is divisible by 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 and each index in the sum on the right side is divisible by 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $|Z(G)|$
\end_inset

 is divisible by 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 Since proper subgroups of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 don't have order divisible by 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $Z(G)$
\end_inset

 has to be all of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

.
 That means 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is abelian, which is a contradiction.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Sylow Theorems
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 be a group such that 
\begin_inset Formula $|G|=p^{k}m$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is a prime and 
\begin_inset Formula $k,m\geq1$
\end_inset

.
 Cauchy's Theorem tells us that there exists a subgroup of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 whose order is 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 In fact, we can do much better than this.
 It turns out that there exists a subgroup of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 whose order is 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{i}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq i\leq k$
\end_inset

.
 This is part of the content of what the Sylow Theorems tells us.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

-Sylow Subgroups
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 be a group such that 
\begin_inset Formula $|G|=p^{k}m$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is a prime and 
\begin_inset Formula $k,m\geq1$
\end_inset

.
 Any subgroup of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 whose order is 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{k}$
\end_inset

 is called a 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

-
\begin_inset Formula $\textbf{Sylow subgroup}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

.
 A 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

-Sylow subgroup for some 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is called a 
\begin_inset Formula $\textbf{Sylow subgroup}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 In 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}/(12)$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $|\mathbb{Z}/(12)|=12=2^{2}\cdot3$
\end_inset

, the only 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

-Sylow subgroup is 
\begin_inset Formula $\{0,3,6,9\}=\langle3\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 The only 
\begin_inset Formula $3$
\end_inset

-Sylow subgroup is 
\begin_inset Formula $\{0,4,8\}=\langle4\rangle$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 In 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{4}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $|A_{4}|=12=2^{2}\cdot3$
\end_inset

.
 The only 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

-Sylow subgroup is 
\begin_inset Formula $V=\langle(12)(34),(14)(23)\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 There are four 
\begin_inset Formula $3$
\end_inset

-Sylow subgroups:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\langle(123)\rangle\quad\langle(124)\rangle\quad\langle(134)\rangle\quad\langle(234)\rangle
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $A_{4}$
\end_inset

 arises as the Galois group of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)=T^{4}+8T+12=(T-r_{1})(T-r_{2})(T-r_{3})(T-r_{4})$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

.
 Here's how we know this: The discriminant of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $-3^{3}\cdot8^{4}+4^{4}12^{3}=331776$
\end_inset

, which is a square, so the Galois group is contained in 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{4}$
\end_inset

.
 Here's how 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)$
\end_inset

 factors modulo different primes:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
f(T) & \equiv(T+1)(T^{3}+4T^{2}+T+2)\,\,\mathrm{mod}\,5\\
f(T) & \equiv(T^{2}+4T+7)(T^{2}+13T+9)\,\,\mathrm{mod}\,17
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From these factorizations, we know there is an element in the Galois group
 with cycle type 
\begin_inset Formula $(1,3)$
\end_inset

 (i.e.
 a 
\begin_inset Formula $3$
\end_inset

-cycle) and an element in the Galois group with cycle type 
\begin_inset Formula $(2,2)$
\end_inset

.
 We can also see from these factorizations that 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)$
\end_inset

 is irreducible over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

 (There's no degree 2 factor mod 5, and there's no degree 1 factor mod 17).
 Since there exists a 
\begin_inset Formula $3$
\end_inset

-cycle, we know the Galois group is divisible by 
\begin_inset Formula $3$
\end_inset

.
 Since we know 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)$
\end_inset

 has degree 
\begin_inset Formula $4$
\end_inset

 and is irreducible over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

, there is a sequence of field extensions 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd}  L 
\backslash

\backslash
 
\backslash
mathbb{Q} (r_1)  
\backslash
arrow[u,dash,"n"] 
\backslash

\backslash
 
\backslash
mathbb{Q} 
\backslash
arrow[u,dash,"4"] 
\backslash
end{tikzcd}
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Where 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 is the splitting field of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}(r_{1})$
\end_inset

 has degree 
\begin_inset Formula $4$
\end_inset

 Then as a field extension over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

.
 This information tells us that 
\begin_inset Formula $|Gal(L/\mathbb{Q})|=[L:\mathbb{Q}]=4n$
\end_inset

.
 Since the Galois group is divisible by 
\begin_inset Formula $3$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $4$
\end_inset

, and is contained in 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{4}$
\end_inset

, it must be isomorphic to 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{4}$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $|A_{4}|=12$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $[L:\mathbb{Q}(r_{1})]=12/4=3$
\end_inset

.
 So the set of all automorphisms of 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 that fix 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}(r_{1})$
\end_inset

 must be a subgroup of 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{4}$
\end_inset

 which has order 
\begin_inset Formula $3$
\end_inset

.
 This subgroup corresponds to one of the four 
\begin_inset Formula $3$
\end_inset

-sylow subgroups, in particular, it is 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle(234)\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 Of course, I arbitrarly decided to focus on the field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}(r_{1})$
\end_inset

, but I could have easily focused on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}(r_{2})$
\end_inset

 instead.
 But this is just a relabeling of indices, and relabeling indices is the
 same as conjugating in 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{4}$
\end_inset

, so the corresponding Galois group for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}(r_{2})$
\end_inset

 is given by conjugating 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle(234)\rangle$
\end_inset

 with an element in 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{4}$
\end_inset

 that sends 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

, like
\begin_inset Formula $(12)(34)$
\end_inset

.
 The cubic resolvent of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{3}-48T-64=(T-(r_{1}r_{2}+r_{3}r_{4}))(T-(r_{1}r_{3}+r_{2}r_{4}))(T-(r_{1}r_{4}+r_{2}r_{3}))$
\end_inset

.
 The cubic resolvent of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)$
\end_inset

 is irreducible since it is irreducible mod 
\begin_inset Formula $5$
\end_inset

.
 This means there is a sequence of field extensions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd}  L 
\backslash

\backslash
 
\backslash
mathbb{Q} (r_1 r_2 + r_3 r_4 )  
\backslash
arrow[u,dash,"n"] 
\backslash

\backslash
 
\backslash
mathbb{Q} 
\backslash
arrow[u,dash,"4"] 
\backslash
end{tikzcd}
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Again, we arbitrarily focused on the field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}(r_{1}r_{2}+r_{3}r_{4})$
\end_inset

, but notice this time that the subgroup which corresponds to this field
 extension is normal in 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{4}$
\end_inset

, thus we get the nonobvious fact that:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbb{Q}(r_{1}r_{2}+r_{3}r_{4})=\mathbb{Q}(r_{1}r_{3}+r_{2}r_{4})=\mathbb{Q}(r_{1}r_{4}+r_{2}r_{3})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Below is the lattice of subgroups of 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{4}$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd}  &&& 
\backslash
{ (1) 
\backslash
} 
\backslash

\backslash
 
\backslash
langle (12)(34) 
\backslash
rangle 
\backslash
arrow[urrr,dash] & 
\backslash
langle (13)(24) 
\backslash
rangle 
\backslash
arrow[urr,dash] &  
\backslash
langle (14)(23) 
\backslash
rangle 
\backslash
arrow[ur,dash] 
\backslash

\backslash
 & V 
\backslash
arrow[u,dash] 
\backslash
arrow[ul, dash] 
\backslash
arrow[ur,dash] & 
\backslash
langle (123) 
\backslash
rangle 
\backslash
arrow[uur,dash] & 
\backslash
langle (124) 
\backslash
rangle 
\backslash
arrow[uu,dash] & 
\backslash
langle (134) 
\backslash
rangle 
\backslash
arrow[uul,dash] & 
\backslash
langle (234) 
\backslash
rangle 
\backslash
arrow[uull,dash] 
\backslash

\backslash
 & A_4  
\backslash
arrow[u,dash] 
\backslash
arrow[ur, dash] 
\backslash
arrow[urr,dash] 
\backslash
arrow[urrr,dash] 
\backslash
arrow[urrrr,dash] 
\backslash
end{tikzcd}
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
And here is the corresponding lattice of fields:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd}  &&& 
\backslash
mathbb{Q} ( r_1 
\backslash
text{,} r_2 ) 
\backslash

\backslash
 
\backslash
mathbb{Q} ( r_1 + r_2 ) 
\backslash
arrow[urrr,dash] & 
\backslash
mathbb{Q} ( r_1 + r_3 ) 
\backslash
arrow[urr,dash] &  
\backslash
mathbb{Q} ( r_1 + r_4 ) 
\backslash
arrow[ur,dash] 
\backslash

\backslash
 & 
\backslash
mathbb{Q} ( r_1 r_2 + r_3 r_4) 
\backslash
arrow[u,dash] 
\backslash
arrow[ul, dash] 
\backslash
arrow[ur,dash] & 
\backslash
mathbb{Q} ( r_4 ) 
\backslash
arrow[uur,dash] & 
\backslash
mathbb{Q} ( r_3 ) 
\backslash
arrow[uu,dash] & 
\backslash
mathbb{Q} ( r_2 ) 
\backslash
arrow[uul,dash] & 
\backslash
mathbb{Q} ( r_1 ) 
\backslash
arrow[uull,dash] 
\backslash

\backslash
 & 
\backslash
mathbb{Q}  
\backslash
arrow[u,dash] 
\backslash
arrow[ur, dash] 
\backslash
arrow[urr,dash] 
\backslash
arrow[urrr,dash] 
\backslash
arrow[urrrr,dash] 
\backslash
end{tikzcd}
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 In 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{6}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $|D_{6}|=12=2^{2}\cdot3$
\end_inset

, there are three 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

-Sylow subgroups:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\{1,r^{3},s,r^{3}s\}=\langle r^{3},s\rangle,\quad\{1,r^{3},rs,r^{4}s\}=\langle r^{3},rs\rangle,\quad\{1,r^{3},r^{2}s,r^{5}s\}=\langle r^{3},r^{2}s\rangle
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The only 
\begin_inset Formula $3$
\end_inset

-Sylow subgroup in 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{6}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\{1,r^{2},r^{4}\}=\langle r^{2}\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 In 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{SL}_{2}(\mathbb{Z}\slash3)$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $|\mathrm{SL}_{2}(\mathbb{Z}/3)|=(3^{2}-1)(3^{2}-3)/2=2^{3}\cdot3$
\end_inset

, there is only one 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

-Sylow subgroup, whose elements are listed below:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Tabular
<lyxtabular version="3" rows="3" columns="4">
<features tabularvalignment="middle">
<column alignment="center" valignment="top">
