\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Statement and Proof of Sylow Theorems
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Before we state and prove the Sylow Theorems, we begin with a very important
 theorem called the fixed-point congruence.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 be a finite 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

-group acting on a finite set 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
|X|=\sum_{i=1}^{t}|\mbox{Orb}_{x_{i}}|.
\]

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $|\mbox{Orb}_{x_{i}}|=[G:\mbox{Stab}_{x_{i}}]$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $|G|$
\end_inset

 is a power of 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $|\mbox{Orb}_{x_{i}}|\equiv0$
\end_inset

 mod 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 unless 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{Stab}_{x_{i}}=G$
\end_inset

, in which case 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{Orb}_{x_{i}}$
\end_inset

 has length 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}$
\end_inset

 is a fixed point.
 Thus, when we reduce both sides of the equation above modulo 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, all terms on the right side vanish except for a contribution of 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 for each fixed point.
 That implies
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
|X|\equiv\mbox{\#\{fixed points\} mod }p
\]

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we state the first Sylow theorem.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Sylow I).
 A finite group 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 has a 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

-Sylow subgroup for every prime 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 and any 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

-subgroup of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 lies in a 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

-Sylow subgroup of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{k}$
\end_inset

 be the highest power of 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $|G|$
\end_inset

.
 We can assume 
\begin_inset Formula $k\geq1$
\end_inset

, since the result is obvious if 
\begin_inset Formula $k=0$
\end_inset

, hence 
\begin_inset Formula $p||G|$
\end_inset

.
 We will prove that there is a subgroup of order 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{i}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq i\leq k$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $|H|=p^{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $i<k$
\end_inset

, we will show there is a 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

-subgroup 
\begin_inset Formula $H'\supset H$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $[H':H]=p$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $|H'|=p^{i+1}$
\end_inset

.
 Then, starting with 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 as the trivial subgroup, we can repeat this process with 
\begin_inset Formula $H'$
\end_inset

 in place of 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 to create a rising tower of subgroups
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\{e\}=H_{0}\subset H_{1}\subset H_{2}\subset\cdots
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $|H_{i}|=p^{i}$
\end_inset

, and after 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 steps we reach 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{k}$
\end_inset

, which is a 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

-Sylow subgroup of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

.
 Consider the left multiplication action of 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 on the left cosets 
\begin_inset Formula $G/H$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
h\cdot\overline{g}=\overline{hg}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is an action of a finite 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

-group 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 on the set 
\begin_inset Formula $G/H$
\end_inset

, and so by the fixed-point congruence for actions of nontrivial 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

-groups
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
|G/H|\equiv|\mbox{Fix}_{H}(G/H)|\mbox{ mod }p\label{eq:1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
What does it mean for a coset 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{g}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $G/H$
\end_inset

 to be a fixed point by the group 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 under left multiplication? For all 
\begin_inset Formula $h\in H$
\end_inset

, we need 
\begin_inset Formula $hg=gh'$
\end_inset

, for some 
\begin_inset Formula $h'\in H$
\end_inset

.
 This happens if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in N(H)$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mbox{Fix}_{H}(G/H)=\{\overline{g}\mid g\in N(H)\}=N(H)/H.
\]

\end_inset

 So (
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
ref{eq:1}
\end_layout

\end_inset

) becomes
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
[G:H]\equiv[N(H):H]\mbox{ mod }p\label{eq:2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Because 
\begin_inset Formula $H\vartriangleleft N(H)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $N(H)/H$
\end_inset

 is a group.
 When 
\begin_inset Formula $|H|=p^{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $i<k$
\end_inset

, the index 
\begin_inset Formula $[G:H]$
\end_inset

 is divisible by 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, so the congruence 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
ref{eq:2}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $[N(H):H]$
\end_inset

 is divisible by 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $N(H)/H$
\end_inset

 is a group with order divisible by 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $N(H)/H$
\end_inset

 has a subgroup of order 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 by Cauchy's theorem.
 All subgroups of the quotient group 
\begin_inset Formula $N(H)/H$
\end_inset

 have the form 
\begin_inset Formula $H'/H$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $H'$
\end_inset

 is a subgroup between 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $N(H)$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore a subgroup of order 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $N(H)/H$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $H'/H$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $[H':H]=p$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $|H'|=p|H|=p^{i+1}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Sylow II).
 For each prime 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, the 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

-Sylow subgroups of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 are conjugate.
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Pick two 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

-Sylow subgroups 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

.
 We want to show they are conjugate.
 Consider the action of 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $G/P$
\end_inset

 by left multiplication:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
q\cdot\overline{g}=\overline{qg}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A fixed point 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{g}$
\end_inset

 under this action means 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{qg}=\bar{g}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $q\in Q$
\end_inset

.
 This implies for each 
\begin_inset Formula $q\in Q$
\end_inset

 there is a 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{q}\in P$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $qg=gp_{q}$
\end_inset

, or in other words, 
\begin_inset Formula $q=gp_{q}g^{-1}$
\end_inset

.
 This implies 
\begin_inset Formula $Q\subset gPg^{-1}$
\end_inset

, which further implies 
\begin_inset Formula $Q=gPg^{-1}$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $gPg^{-1}$
\end_inset

 have the same size.
 So a fixed point under this action corresponds with an element 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 which conjugates 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

.
 So we just need to show that there exists a fixed point in 
\begin_inset Formula $G/P$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 is a finite 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

-group, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
|G/P|\equiv|\mbox{Fix}_{Q}(G/P)|\mbox{ mod }p
\]

\end_inset

The left side is nonzero modulo 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

-Sylow subgroup: If 
\begin_inset Formula $|G|=p^{k}m$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $|P|=p^{k}$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $|G/P|=m$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $|\mbox{Fix}_{Q}(G/P)|$
\end_inset

 can't be 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

, so there is a fixed point in 
\begin_inset Formula $G/P$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 conjugates 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

, then so too does 
\begin_inset Formula $gh$
\end_inset

, for any 
\begin_inset Formula $h\in N(P)$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
ghPh^{-1}g^{-1}=gPg^{-1}=Q
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It's natural to wonder if the number of 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

-Sylow subgroups of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 equals 
\begin_inset Formula $[G:N(P)]$
\end_inset

.
 This is indeed true, but before we tackle that, we prove the third Sylow
 theorem.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Sylow III).
 For each prime 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, let 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{p}$
\end_inset

 be the number of 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

-Sylow subgroups of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

.
 Write 
\begin_inset Formula $|G|=p^{k}m$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 doesn't divide 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
n_{p}\equiv1\mbox{ mod }p\qquad\mbox{and}\qquad n_{p}|m.
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We will prove 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{p}\equiv1$
\end_inset

 mod 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 and then 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{p}|m$
\end_inset

.
 To show 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{p}\equiv1$
\end_inset

 mod 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, consider the action of 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 on the set 
\begin_inset Formula $Syl_{p}(G)$
\end_inset

 by conjugation
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P\cdot Q=PQP^{-1}.
\]

\end_inset

The size of 
\begin_inset Formula $Syl_{p}(G)$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{p}$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 is a finite 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

-group
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
n_{p}\equiv|\mbox{Fix}_{P}(Syl_{p}(G)|\mbox{ mod }p
\]

\end_inset

Fixed points for 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 acting by conjugation on 
\begin_inset Formula $Syl_{p}(G)$
\end_inset

 are 
\begin_inset Formula $Q\in Syl_{p}(G)$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $gQg^{-1}=Q$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in P$
\end_inset

.
 One choice for 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

.
 For any such 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $P\subset N_{G}(Q)$
\end_inset

.
 Also 
\begin_inset Formula $Q\subset N_{G}(Q)$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 are 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

-Sylow subgroups in 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{G}(Q)$
\end_inset

.
 Applying Sylow II to the group 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{G}(Q)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 are conjugate in 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{G}(Q)$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $Q\vartriangleleft N_{G}(Q)$
\end_inset

, the only subgroup of 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{G}(Q)$
\end_inset

 conjugate to 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $P=Q$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 is the only fixed point when 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 acts on 
\begin_inset Formula $Syl_{p}(G)$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{p}\equiv1$
\end_inset

 mod 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 To show 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{p}|m$
\end_inset

, consider the action of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 by conjugation on 
\begin_inset Formula $Syl_{p}(G)$
\end_inset

.
 Since the 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

-Sylow subgroups are conjugate to each other, there is one orbit.
 A set on which a group acts with one orbit has size dividing the size of
 the group, so 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{p}||G|.$
\end_inset

 From 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{p}\equiv1$
\end_inset

 mod 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, the number 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{p}$
\end_inset

 is relatively prime to 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{p}|m$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Sylow III*).
 For each prime 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, let 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{p}$
\end_inset

 be the number of 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

-Sylow subgroups of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{p}=[G:N_{G}(P)]$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 is any 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

-Sylow subgroup.
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 be a 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

-Sylow subgroup of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 act on 
\begin_inset Formula $Syl_{p}(G)$
\end_inset

 by conjugation.
 By the orbit-stabilizer formula,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
n_{p}=[G:\mbox{Stab}_{\{P\}}]=[G:N_{G}(P)].
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Sylow Applications
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 For a prime 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, any element of 
\begin_inset Formula $GL_{2}(\mathbb{Z}/(p))$
\end_inset

 with order 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is conjugate to a strictly upper-triangular matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{12}(a)$
\end_inset

.
 The number of 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

-Sylow subgroups is 
\begin_inset Formula $p+1$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The size of 
\begin_inset Formula $GL_{2}(\mathbb{Z}/(p))$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $(p^{2}-1)(p^{2}-p)=p(p-1)(p^{2}-1)$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore a 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

-Sylow subgroup has size 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 The matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{12}(1)$
\end_inset

 has order 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, so it generates a 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

-Sylow subgroup 
\begin_inset Formula $P=\{e_{12}(*)\}$
\end_inset

.
 Since all 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

-Sylow subgroups are conjugate, any matrix with order 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is conjugate to some power 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{12}(1)$
\end_inset

.
 The number of 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

-Sylow subgroups is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
n_{p}=[GL_{2}(\mathbb{Z}/(p)):N(P)]
\]

\end_inset

 by Sylow III*.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\begin{smallmatrix}a & b\\
c & d
\end{smallmatrix}\right)$
\end_inset

 to lie in 
\begin_inset Formula $N(P)$
\end_inset

 means it conjugates 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{12}(1)$
\end_inset

 to some power 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{12}(*)$
\end_inset

.
 Since
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{pmatrix}a & b\\
c & d
\end{pmatrix}\begin{pmatrix}1 & 1\\
0 & 1
\end{pmatrix}\begin{pmatrix}a & b\\
c & d
\end{pmatrix}^{-1}=\frac{1}{\Delta}\begin{pmatrix}1-ac & a^{2}\\
-c^{2} & 1+ac
\end{pmatrix}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta=ad-bc\neq0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\begin{smallmatrix}a & b\\
c & d
\end{smallmatrix}\right)\in N(P)$
\end_inset

 precisely when 
\begin_inset Formula $c=0.$
\end_inset

 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $N(P)=\{\left(\begin{smallmatrix}* & *\\
0 & *
\end{smallmatrix}\right)\}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $GL_{2}(\mathbb{Z}/(p))$
\end_inset

.
 The size of 
\begin_inset Formula $N(P)$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $(p-1)^{2}p$
\end_inset

, thus 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
n_{p}=[GL_{2}(\mathbb{Z}/(p)):N(P)]=p+1
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{cor}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The number of elements of order 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $GL_{2}(\mathbb{Z}/(p))$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{2}-1$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{cor}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Each 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

-Sylow subgroup has 
\begin_inset Formula $p-1$
\end_inset

 elements of order 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 Different 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

-Sylow subgroups intersect trivially, so the number of elements of order
 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $(p-1)n_{p}=p^{2}-1$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 There is a unique 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

-Sylow subgroup of 
\begin_inset Formula $Aff(\mathbb{Z}/(p^{2}))$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $Aff(\mathbb{Z}/(p^{2}))$
\end_inset

 has size 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{2}\varphi(p^{2})=p^{3}(p-1)$
\end_inset

, so a 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

-Sylow subgroup has order 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{3}$
\end_inset

.
 Letting 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{p}$
\end_inset

 be the number of 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

-Sylow subgroups, Sylow III says 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{p}|(p-1)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{p}\equiv1\mod p$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{p}=1$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 For any prime 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $Heis(\mathbb{Z}/(p))$
\end_inset

 is the unique 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

-Sylow subgroup of the group of invertible upper-triangular matrices
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{pmatrix}d_{1} & a & b\\
0 & d_{2} & c\\
0 & 0 & d_{3}
\end{pmatrix}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
in 
\begin_inset Formula $GL_{3}(\mathbb{Z}/(3))$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 This matrix group, call it 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

, has size 
\begin_inset Formula $(p-1)^{3}p^{3}$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $Heis(\mathbb{Z}/(p))$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

-Sylow subgroup of 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

.
 Sylow III tells us 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{p}|(p-1)^{3}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{p}\equiv1\mod p$
\end_inset

, but it does not follow from this that 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{p}$
\end_inset

 must be 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

.
 Let's prove 
\begin_inset Formula $Heis(\mathbb{Z}/(p))\vartriangleleft U$
\end_inset

 by showing it is in the kernel of a map out of 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

: Project a matrix in 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 to the 
\begin_inset Formula $3$
\end_inset

-fold product 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mathbb{Z}/(p))^{\times}\times(\mathbb{Z}/(p))^{\times}\times(\mathbb{Z}/(p))^{\times}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{pmatrix}d_{1} & a & b\\
0 & d_{2} & c\\
0 & 0 & d_{3}
\end{pmatrix}\mapsto(d_{1},d_{2},d_{3})
\]

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The kernel of this map is 
\begin_inset Formula $Heis(\mathbb{Z}/(p))$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Cayley's Theorem
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Cayley's Theorem) Let 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 be a finite group of order 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is isomorphic to a subgroup of 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We write 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{G}$
\end_inset

 for the group of all permutations of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 as a set.
 We have 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{G}\cong S_{n}$
\end_inset

, so we just need to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is isomorphic to a subgroup of 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{G}$
\end_inset

.
 Define a map 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi\colon G\to S_{G}$
\end_inset

, denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi\mapsto\pi_{g}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{g}\colon G\to G$
\end_inset

 is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\pi_{g}(x)=gx
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in G$
\end_inset

.
 We claim that 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

 is an injective group homomorphism.
 Indeed, first let us show that it is a group homomorphism.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1},g_{2}\in G$
\end_inset

.
 Then observe that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\pi_{g_{1}g_{2}}(x) & =g_{1}g_{2}x\\
 & =\pi_{g_{1}}(g_{2}x)\\
 & =\pi_{g_{1}}\pi_{g_{2}}(x)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in G$
\end_inset

.
 It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{g_{1}g_{2}}=\pi_{g_{1}}\pi_{g_{2}}$
\end_inset

, and hence 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

 is a group homomorphism.
 Now let us show that it is injective.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in\ker\pi$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $gx=x$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in G$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, 
\begin_inset Formula $g^{2}=g$
\end_inset

.
 Multiplying both sides by 
\begin_inset Formula $g^{-1}$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $g=1$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\ker\pi=\{1\}$
\end_inset

, which implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

 is injective.
 Finally, by the first isomorphism theorem for groups, we find that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{im}\,\pi$
\end_inset

 is a subgroup of 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{G}$
\end_inset

, and moreover, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{im}\,\pi\cong G\slash\ker\pi\cong G.
\]

\end_inset

It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is isomorphic to a subgroup of 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{G}$
\end_inset

 which implies 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is isomorphic to a subgroup of 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Composition Series and the Hlder program
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A group 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is said to be 
\series bold
simple
\series default
 if 
\begin_inset Formula $|G|>1$
\end_inset

 and if its only normal subgroups are 
\begin_inset Formula $\{e\}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 itself.
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 be a prime.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}/p\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 is simple.
 By lagrange's theorem, the order of any subgroup of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}/p\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 must divide 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 So we only have two options for subgroups of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}/p\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula $\{e\}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}/p\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

The Hlder program innitiated the classification all finite simple groups,
 which was accomplished in the 1980s.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 There are 
\begin_inset Formula $18$
\end_inset

 families of finite simples groups, and 
\begin_inset Formula $26$
\end_inset

 sporadic finite simple groups.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\mathbb{Z}_{p}\mid p\,\mbox{prime}\}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\mbox{PSL}_{m}(\mathbb{F}_{p})\mid m\geq2\}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 In a group 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 a sequence of subgroups 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
1=H_{0}\leq H_{1}\leq\cdots\leq H_{r}=G
\]

\end_inset

is called a 
\series bold
composition series
\series default
 if 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{i}\trianglelefteq H_{i+1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{i+1}/H_{i}$
\end_inset

 is simple for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in\{0,\dots,r-1\}$
\end_inset

.
 The groups 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{i+1}/H_{i}$
\end_inset

 are called the 
\series bold
composition factors
\series default
.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A composition series for 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{3}$
\end_inset

 is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
1\trianglelefteq\langle(1,2,3)\rangle\trianglelefteq S_{3},
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
with composition factors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}_{3}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A composition series for 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{4}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\{(1)\}\trianglelefteq U\trianglelefteq V\trianglelefteq A_{4}\trianglelefteq S_{4},
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $V=\{(1),(1,2)(3,4),(1,3)(2,4),(1,4)(2,3)\}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $U=\{(1),(1,2)(3,4)\}$
\end_inset

, and three factors being 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{2}$
\end_inset

 and one factor being 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{3}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 be a finite group.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 has a composition series 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
1=H_{0}\leq H_{1}\leq\cdots\leq H_{r}=G,
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and the composition factors are unique up to isomorphism, i.e.
 if 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
1=G_{0}\leq G_{1}\leq\cdots\leq G_{s}=G
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
is another composition series of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $r=s$
\end_inset

 and there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi\in S_{r}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{i+1}/G_{i}\cong H_{\pi(i)+1}/H_{\pi(i)}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We can always construct a normal series of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 be the length of the longest such sequence.
 We need to check that this is a composition series (i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{i+1}/H_{i}$
\end_inset

 is simple for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

).
 Suppose not: there is a some 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{i+1}/H_{i}$
\end_inset

 is not simple.
 Then there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $N\trianglelefteq H_{i+1}/H_{i}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $N\neq H_{i}/H_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $N\neq H_{i+1}/H_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 But then 
\begin_inset Formula $N=A/H_{i}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{i}\trianglelefteq A\trianglelefteq H_{i+1}$
\end_inset

.
 So we have a sequence of subgroups of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
1=H_{0}\leq H_{1}\leq\cdots\leq H_{i}\leq A\leq H_{i+1}\cdots\leq H_{r}=G.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
which is a contradiction because this has length 
\begin_inset Formula $r+1$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Lemma: Let 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 be a finite group.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $M\trianglelefteq G$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $N\trianglelefteq G$
\end_inset

, with 
\begin_inset Formula $M\neq N$
\end_inset

 and both 
\begin_inset Formula $G/M$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $G/N$
\end_inset

 are simple groups, then 
\begin_inset Formula $G/M\cong N/M\cap N$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $G/N\cong M/M\cap N$
\end_inset

.
 Now we prove the second part of the theorem using induction on 
\begin_inset Formula $|G|$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $|G|=1$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $G=\{1\}$
\end_inset

.
 Assume the statement is true for all groups of order less than 
\begin_inset Formula $|G|$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $M=G_{s-1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $N=H_{r-1}$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $M=N$
\end_inset

, then use the induction hypothesis to show 
\begin_inset Formula $r-1=s-1$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $(H_{1}/H_{0},\cdots,H_{r-1}/H_{r-2})\sim(G_{1}/G_{0},\cdots,G_{s-1}/G_{s-2})$
\end_inset

 .
 So assume 
\begin_inset Formula $M\neq N$
\end_inset

, then use the lemma.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $K=M\cap N$
\end_inset

.
 Consider a composition series for 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
1=K_{0}\leq K_{1}\leq\cdots\leq K_{t-1}\leq K_{t}=K
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Composition series for 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
1=G_{0}\leq G_{1}\leq\cdots\leq G_{s-3}\leq G_{s-2}\leq M
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
1=K_{0}\leq K_{1}\leq\cdots\leq K_{t-1}\leq K\leq M
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So 
\begin_inset Formula $(G_{1}/G_{0},\cdots,G_{s-2}/G_{s-3},M/G_{s-2})\sim(K_{1}/K_{0},\cdots,K/K_{t-1},M/K)$
\end_inset

 and 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Serre
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 be a group.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
A 
\series bold
filtration 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is a finite sequence of subgroups 
\begin_inset Formula $(G_{i})_{0\leq i\leq n}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 such that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
G_{0}=G\supset G_{1}\supset\cdots\supset G_{n}=1\label{eq:filtration}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

with 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{i+1}$
\end_inset

 normal in 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{i}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $0\le i\le n-1$
\end_inset

.
 Given a filtration 
\begin_inset Formula $(G_{i})_{0\leq i\leq n}$
\end_inset

, the successive quotients 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{i}\slash G_{i+1}$
\end_inset

 are denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{gr}_{i}(G)$
\end_inset

.
 The sequence of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{gr}_{i}(G)$
\end_inset

 is denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{gr}(G)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
A filtration 
\begin_inset Formula $(G_{i})_{0\leq i\leq n}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is called a 
\series bold
Joran-Hlder filtration
\series default
 (or a 
\series bold
Joran-Hlder series
\series default
 or a 
\series bold
composition series
\series default
) if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{gr}_{i}(G)$
\end_inset

 is simple all 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq i<n$
\end_inset

.
 The number 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is called the 
\series bold
length 
\series default
of the filtration.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 be a field.
 A filtration for the group 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{Aff}(F)$
\end_inset

 is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mbox{Aff}(F)\trianglerighteq\{e_{12}(*)\}\trianglerighteq\{1\},
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
with factors isomorphic to 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $F^{\times}$
\end_inset

.
 Compare this with the following sequence of field extensions:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd}[row sep=large] 
\backslash
mathbb{Q}( 
\backslash
sqrt[5]{2} , 
\backslash
zeta _5 ) 
\backslash
arrow[d,dash, "
\backslash
mathbb{F}_5 "] 
\backslash
arrow[d,dash,bend right=60, "  e_{12} ( * )  ", swap ] 
\backslash
arrow[dd,dash,bend left=60, , "
\backslash
text{Aff}(
\backslash
mathbb{F}_5 )"] 
\backslash

\backslash
 
\backslash
mathbb{Q} ( 
\backslash
zeta _5 ) 
\backslash
arrow[d,dash,"
\backslash
mathbb{F}_5 ^{
\backslash
times}"] 
\backslash

\backslash
 
\backslash
mathbb{Q} 
\backslash
end{tikzcd}
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A composition series for 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{4}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
S_{4}\trianglerighteq A_{4}\trianglerighteq V\trianglerighteq U\trianglerighteq\{(1)\},
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $V=\{(1),(1,2)(3,4),(1,3)(2,4),(1,4)(2,3)\}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $U=\{(1),(1,2)(3,4)\}$
\end_inset

, with three factors being 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{2}$
\end_inset

 and one factor being 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{3}$
\end_inset

.
 Compare this with the following sequence of field extensions:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd}[row sep=large] 
\backslash
mathbb{Q}( r_1 ) 
\backslash
arrow[d,dash, " C_2 "] 
\backslash
arrow[d,dash,bend right=30, " U ", swap ] 
\backslash
arrow[dd,dash,bend left=60, "V"] 
\backslash
arrow[ddd,dash,bend right=60,"A_4 ",swap] 
\backslash
arrow[dddd,dash,bend left=60, "S_4 "] 
\backslash

\backslash
 
\backslash
mathbb{Q}(r_1 + r_2 ) 
\backslash
arrow[d,dash," C_2 "] 
\backslash

\backslash
 
\backslash
mathbb{Q}(r_1 r_2  + r_3 r_4 ) 
\backslash
arrow[d,dash," C_3 "] 
\backslash

\backslash
 
\backslash
mathbb{Q} (
\backslash
prod _{i<j} (r_i - r_j )) 
\backslash
arrow[d,dash," C_2 "] 
\backslash

\backslash
 
\backslash
mathbb{Q} 
\backslash
end{tikzcd}
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{1},r_{2},r_{3}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{4}$
\end_inset

 are roots of the polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=x^{4}-x-1$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A composition series for 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{4}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
D_{4}\trianglerighteq\langle r^{2},s\rangle\trianglerighteq\langle s\rangle\trianglerighteq\langle1\rangle,
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
with all three factors being 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Every Finite Group has a Jordan-Hlder Filtration
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A group need not have a Jordan-Hlder filtration.
 Indeed, consider the group of integers 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

.
 It turns out that however, that finite groups always have Jordan-Hlder
 filtrations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 be a finite group.
 Then there exists a Jordan-Hlder filtration of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $G=1$
\end_inset

, take the trivial Jordan-Hlder filtration with 
\begin_inset Formula $n=0$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:filtration})
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is simple, take 
\begin_inset Formula $n=1$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:filtration})
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is neither 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 nor simple.
 Use induction on the order of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 be a normal subgroup of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 , distinct from 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

, and of maximal order.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $G\slash N$
\end_inset

 is simple.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $|N|<|G|$
\end_inset

, we apply the induction hypothesis to 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 and we obtain a Jordan-Hlder filtration 
\begin_inset Formula $(N_{i})_{0\leq i\leq n}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $(G_{i})_{0\leq i\leq n+1}$
\end_inset

 is a Jordan-Hlder filtration for 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{0}=G$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{i}=N_{i-1}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq i\leq n+1$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Uniqueness of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{gr}_{i}(G)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Jordan-Hlder).
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(G_{i})_{0\leq i\leq n}$
\end_inset

 be a Jordan-Hlder filtration of a group 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

.
 Then the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{gr}_{i}(G)$
\end_inset

 do not depend on the choice of filtration, up to the permutation of the
 indices.
 In particular, the length of the filtration is independent of the filtration.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

The length of the filtration is called the 
\series bold
length
\series default
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

, and is denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell(G)$
\end_inset

; when 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 has no Jordan-Hlder filtration, we write 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell(G)=\infty$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 be a simple group, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $n(G,(G_{i}),S)$
\end_inset

 be the number of 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{j}/G_{j+1}$
\end_inset

 is isomorphic to 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

.
 What we have to prove is that 
\begin_inset Formula $n(G,(G_{i}),S)$
\end_inset

 does not depend on the chosen filtration 
\begin_inset Formula $(G_{i})$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Note first that, if 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 is a subgroup of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

, a filtration 
\begin_inset Formula $(G_{i})$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 incudes a filtration 
\begin_inset Formula $(H_{i})$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 by putting 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{i}=G_{i}\cap H$
\end_inset

.
 Similarly, if 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 is a normal subgroup of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

, we obtain a filtration of 
\begin_inset Formula $G/N$
\end_inset

 by putting 
\begin_inset Formula $(G/N)_{i}=G_{i}/(G_{i}\cap N)=G_{i}N/N$
\end_inset

.
 The exact sequence 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd} 1 
\backslash
arrow[r] & N 
\backslash
arrow[r] & G 
\backslash
arrow[r] & G/N 
\backslash
arrow[r] & 1 
\backslash
end{tikzcd}
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
gives an exact sequence
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd} 1 
\backslash
arrow[r] & N_i / N_{i+1} 
\backslash
arrow[r] & G_i / G_{i+1} 
\backslash
arrow[r] & (G/N)_i / (G/N)_{i+1} 
\backslash
arrow[r] & 1 
\backslash
end{tikzcd}
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
i.e.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd} 1 
\backslash
arrow[r] & 
\backslash
mbox{gr}_i (N) 
\backslash
arrow[r] & 
\backslash
mbox{gr}_i (G) 
\backslash
arrow[r] &  
\backslash
mbox{gr}_i (G/N) 
\backslash
arrow[r] & 1 
\backslash
end{tikzcd}
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $(G_{i})$
\end_inset

 is a Jordan-Hlder filtration, all the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{gr}_{i}(G)$
\end_inset

 are simple; thus, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{gr}_{i}(N)$
\end_inset

 is either 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{gr}_{i}(G)$
\end_inset

.
 Let us partition 
\begin_inset Formula $I=\{1,\dots,n\}$
\end_inset

 into two sets:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
I_{1}=\{i\in I\mid\mbox{gr}_{i}(N)=\mbox{gr}_{i}(G)\}\quad\mbox{and}\quad I_{2}=\{i\in I\mid\mbox{gr}_{i}(N)=1\}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By reindexing 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{1}$
\end_inset

 (resp.
 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{2}$
\end_inset

) we obtain a Jordan-Hlder filtration of 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 (resp.
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $G/N$
\end_inset

) of length 
\begin_inset Formula $|I_{1}|$
\end_inset

 (resp.
 of length 
\begin_inset Formula $|I_{2}|$
\end_inset

); note that 
\begin_inset Formula $|I_{1}|+|I_{2}|=n$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

We now prove the theorem by induction on the length 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 of the filtration 
\begin_inset Formula $(G_{i})$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $n=0$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $G=1$
\end_inset

, and if 
\begin_inset Formula $n=1$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is simple and only one filtration is possible.
 Assume 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq2$
\end_inset

.
 Choose a normal subgroup 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 distinct from 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

.
 The sets 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{2}$
\end_inset

 defined above are non-empty, hence their number of elements is 
\begin_inset Formula $<n$
\end_inset

, and we can apply the induction hypothesis to 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $G/N$
\end_inset

; it shows that 
\begin_inset Formula $n(N,(N_{i})_{i\in I_{1}},S)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $n(G/N,((G/N)_{i})_{i\in I_{2}},S)$
\end_inset

 are independent of the filtrations since 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
n(G,(G)_{ii\in I},S)=n(N,(N_{i})_{i\in I_{2}},S)+n(G/N,((G/N)_{i})_{i\in I_{2}},S),
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
this implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $n(G,(G_{i})_{i\in I},S)$
\end_inset

 is independent of the choice of filtration, as wanted.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Illustration of proof for 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{4}=\langle r,s\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd} 
\backslash
langle s 
\backslash
rangle 
\backslash
arrow[r,dash, "C_1 "] 
\backslash
arrow[d,dash] & 
\backslash
langle s 
\backslash
rangle 
\backslash
arrow[r,dash, "C_1 "] 
\backslash
arrow[d,dash] & 
\backslash
langle s 
\backslash
rangle 
\backslash
arrow[r,dash, "C_2 "] 
\backslash
arrow[d,dash] & 
\backslash
langle 1 
\backslash
rangle 
\backslash
arrow[d,dash] 
\backslash

\backslash
 
\backslash
langle r , s 
\backslash
rangle 
\backslash
arrow[r,dash, "C_2 "] 
\backslash
arrow[d,dash] & 
\backslash
langle r^2 , s 
\backslash
rangle 
\backslash
arrow[r,dash, "C_2 "] 
\backslash
arrow[d,dash] & 
\backslash
langle s 
\backslash
rangle 
\backslash
arrow[r,dash, "C_2 "] 
\backslash
arrow[d,dash] & 
\backslash
langle 1 
\backslash
rangle 
\backslash
arrow[d,dash] 
\backslash

\backslash
 
\backslash
langle r 
\backslash
rangle 
\backslash
arrow[r,dash, "C_2 "] & 
\backslash
langle r^2 
\backslash
rangle 
\backslash
arrow[r,dash, "C_2 "] & 
\backslash
langle 1 
\backslash
rangle 
\backslash
arrow[r,dash, "C_1 "] & 
\backslash
langle 1 
\backslash
rangle 
\backslash
end{tikzcd}
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Group Actions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Definition of Group Action
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 be a group and let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be a set.
 An 
\begin_inset Formula $\textbf{action}$
\end_inset

 
\series bold
of
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 
\series bold
on
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is the choice, for each 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in G$
\end_inset

, of a permutation 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{g}\colon X\to X$
\end_inset

 such that the following two conditions hold:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

 is the identity element in 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{e}(x)=x$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We have 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{g_{1}}\circ\pi_{g_{2}}=\pi_{g_{1}g_{2}}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1},g_{2}\in G$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 In practice, one dispenses with the notation 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{g}$
\end_inset

 and writes 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{g}(x)$
\end_inset

 simply as 
\begin_inset Formula $g(x)$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $g\cdot x$
\end_inset

 or even just 
\begin_inset Formula $gx$
\end_inset

.
 This is 
\emph on
not
\emph default
 meant to be an actual multiplication of elements from two possibly different
 sets 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 It is just the notation for the effect permutation associated to 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 on the element 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 In this notation, the axioms for a group action take the following form:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $ex=x$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1}(g_{2}x)=(g_{1}g_{2})x$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1},g_{2}\in G$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The basic idea in any group action is that the elements of a group are viewed
 as permutations of a set in such a way that composition of the corresponding
 permutations matches multilpication in the original group.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Examples of Group Actions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Permutation Action
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{n}$
\end_inset

 act on 
\begin_inset Formula $X=\{1,2,\dots,n\}$
\end_inset

 in the usual way.
 Here 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{\sigma}(i)=\sigma(i)$
\end_inset

 in the usual notation.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Any group 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 acts on itself 
\begin_inset Formula $(X=G)$
\end_inset

 by left multilpication functions.
 That is, we set 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{g}\colon G\to G$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\pi_{g}(h)=gh
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $g,h\in G$
\end_inset

.
 Then the conditions for 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

 being a group action are satisfied since 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

 is the identity and multiplication in 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is associative.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The group 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{n}$
\end_inset

 acts on polynomials 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T_{1},\dots,T_{n})$
\end_inset

, by permuting variables:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(\sigma\cdot f)(T_{1},\dots,T_{n})=f(T_{\sigma(1)},\dots,T_{\sigma(n)}).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is a change of variables 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{i}\mapsto T_{\sigma(i)}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T_{1},\dots,T_{n})$
\end_inset

.
 For example, 
\begin_inset Formula $(12)(23)=(123)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{3}$
\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
(12)\cdot((23)\cdot(T_{2}+T_{3}^{2})) & =(12)\cdot(T_{3}+T_{2}^{2})\\
 & =T_{3}+T_{1}^{2}\\
 & =(123)\cdot(T_{2}+T_{3}^{2})
\end{align*}

\end_inset

giving the same result both ways.
 It's also obvious that 
\begin_inset Formula $(1)\cdot f=f$
\end_inset

.
 To check 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma\cdot(\sigma'\cdot f)=(\sigma\sigma')\cdot f$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma,\sigma'\in S_{n}$
\end_inset

, we compute
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
(\sigma\cdot(\sigma'\cdot f))(T_{1},\dots,T_{n}) & =(\sigma\cdot f)(T_{\sigma'(1)},\dots,T_{\sigma'(n)})\\
 & =f(T_{\sigma(\sigma'(1))},\dots,T_{\sigma(\sigma'(n))})\\
 & =f(T_{(\sigma\sigma')(1)},\dots,T_{(\sigma\sigma')(n)})\\
 & =((\sigma\sigma')\cdot f)(T_{1},\dots,T_{n})
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Lagranges study of this group action marked the first systematic use of
 symmetric groups in algebra.
 Lagrange wanted to understand why nobody had found an analogue of the quadratic
 formula for roots of a polynomial in degree greater than four.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Here is a tricky example, so pay atttenion.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{n}$
\end_inset

 act on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 by permuting coordinates: for 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma\in S_{n}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $v=(c_{1},\dots,c_{n})\in\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

, set 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma\cdot v=(c_{\sigma(1)},\dots,c_{\sigma(n)})$
\end_inset

.
 Is this a group action? No.
 The reason is because 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{\sigma(i)}$
\end_inset

 is treated as the 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

'th position, whereas in conrast to the previous example, 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{\sigma(i)}$
\end_inset

 is treated as the 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma(i)$
\end_inset

'th position.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Conjugation Action
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 be a group and let 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 be a normal subgroup.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 acts on 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 by conjugation: let 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in G$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in N$
\end_inset

.
 We set
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
x\cdot y & =xyx^{-1}.\label{eq:conjugationactionnormal}
\end{align}

\end_inset

To see that this is in fact an action, first note that 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:conjugationactionnormal})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 lands in 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 is normal in 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

.
 Next, let 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1},x_{2}\in G$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in N$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
x_{1}\cdot(x_{2}\cdot y) & =x_{1}\cdot(x_{2}yx_{2}^{-1})\\
 & =x_{1}(x_{2}yx_{2}^{-1})x_{1}^{-1}\\
 & =(x_{1}x_{2})y(x_{1}x_{2})^{-1}\\
 & =(x_{1}x_{2})\cdot y.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Also if 
\begin_inset Formula $e\in G$
\end_inset

 is the identity, then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
e\cdot y & =eye^{-1}\\
 & =y.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

It follows that 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:conjugationactionnormal})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 gives an action of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Orbit-Stabilizer Theorem
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An action of a group 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 on a set 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 gives rise to an equivalence relation on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 Namely, for 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in X$
\end_inset

 we say 
\begin_inset Formula $x\sim y$
\end_inset

 if there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in G$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $gx=y$
\end_inset

.
 One readily checks that this is indeed an equivalence relation.
 The equivalence classes are called 
\series bold

\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

-orbits
\series default
 (or more simply just 
\series bold
orbits
\series default
 if 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is understood).
 Let us make the following definitions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 be a group and suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 acts on a set 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 For each 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

, we define
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The 
\series bold
orbit of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset


\series default
, denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Orb}_{G}(x)$
\end_inset

, is the subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\text{Orb}_{G}(x)=\{gx\in X\mid g\in G\}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The 
\series bold
stabilizer of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset


\series default
, denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Stab}_{G}(x)$
\end_inset

, is the subgroup of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\text{Stab}_{G}(x)=\{g\in G\mid gx=x\}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{ex}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Verify that 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Stab}_{G}(x)$
\end_inset

 is a subgroup of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{ex}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Orbit-Stabilizer Theorem) Let 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 be a group and suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 acts on a set 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 Then for each 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
|\mathrm{Orb}_{G}(x)|=[G:\mathrm{Stab}_{G}(x)].
\]

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Define 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon G\to\text{Orb}_{G}(x)$
\end_inset

 be given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varphi(g)=gx
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in G$
\end_inset

.
 The map 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 induces a map 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\varphi}\colon G\slash\text{Stab}_{G}(x)\to\text{Orb}_{G}(x)$
\end_inset

, given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\overline{\varphi}(\overline{g})=gx
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{g}\in\text{Stab}_{G}(x)$
\end_inset

.
 We claim that 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\varphi}$
\end_inset

 is a bijection.
 Indeed, it is surjective since 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is surjective.
 To see that it is injective, suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\varphi}(\overline{g})=\overline{\varphi}(\overline{h})$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{g},\overline{h}\in G\slash\text{Stab}_{G}(x)$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $gx=hx$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $g^{-1}h\in\text{Stab}_{G}(x)$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\overline{g} & =\overline{gg^{-1}h}\\
 & =\overline{h}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

This implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\varphi}$
\end_inset

 is injective.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Stabilizers and Conjugate Subgroups
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 be a group and suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 acts on a set 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in G$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
g\text{Stab}_{G}(x)g^{-1}=\text{Stab}_{G}(g(x))
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $h\in\text{Stab}_{G}(x)$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
ghg^{-1}(g(x)) & =gh(g^{-1}g)(x)\\
 & =gh(x)\\
 & =g(x).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $g\text{Stab}_{G}(x)g^{-1}\subseteq\text{Stab}_{G}(g(x))$
\end_inset

.
 Converesely, if 
\begin_inset Formula $h\in\text{Stab}_{G}(g(x))$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $h=g(g^{-1}hg)g^{-1}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $g^{-1}hg\in\text{Stab}_{G}(x)$
\end_inset

 since
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
g^{-1}hg(x) & =g^{-1}h(g(x))\\
 & =g^{-1}(g(x))\\
 & =(g^{-1}g)(x)\\
 & =x.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $g\text{Stab}_{G}(x)g^{-1}\supseteq\text{Stab}_{G}(g(x))$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Fixed-Point Congruence
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The fixed-point congruence theorem is very useful when dealing with 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

-groups.
 To state this theorem, we first need the following definition.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 be a finite 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

-group and suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 acts on a finite set 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 We define
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{Fix}_{G}(X):=\{x\in X\mid g\cdot x=x\text{ for all }g\in G\}.
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 be a finite 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

-group and suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 acts on a finite set 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
|X|\equiv\mathrm{Fix}_{G}(X)\text{ mod }p.
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 After partitioning 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 into its 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

-orbit classes.
 We have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
|X|=|\text{Fix}_{G}(X)|+|\text{Orb}_{G}(x_{1})|+\cdots+|\text{Orb}_{G}(x_{n})|.\label{eq:fixedpoint}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1},\dots,x_{n}$
\end_inset

 are representatives whose 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

-orbit classes have size 
\begin_inset Formula $\geq2$
\end_inset

.
 By the orbit-stabilizer theorem, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Orb}_{G}(x_{i})=[G:\text{Stab}_{G}(x_{i})]$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i=1,\dots,n$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}\notin\text{Fix}_{G}(X)$
\end_inset

, we must have 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Stab}_{G}(x_{i})$
\end_inset

 is a 
\emph on
proper 
\emph default
subgroup of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, this implies 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 divides 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Orb}_{G}(x_{i})$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, we obtain our desired reults after reduce both sides of 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:fixedpoint})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 modulo 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 acts on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 is a subgroup of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

, then the following are equivalent:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 acts transtivitely on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 acts transitively on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $G=H$
\end_inset

Stab
\begin_inset Formula $_{x}$
\end_inset

 for every 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 is transitive, then clearly 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is transitive too.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in G$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $gx=hx$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $h\in H$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $h^{-1}g\in$
\end_inset

Stab
\begin_inset Formula $_{x}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $g=h\left(h^{-1}g\right)\in H$
\end_inset

Stab
\begin_inset Formula $_{x}$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $G=H$
\end_inset

Stab
\begin_inset Formula $_{x}$
\end_inset

.
 Conversely, given 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in X$
\end_inset

, choose 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in G$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $gx=y$
\end_inset

.
 Write 
\begin_inset Formula $g=hs$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $h\in H$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $s\in$
\end_inset

Stab
\begin_inset Formula $_{x}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $hx=y$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 acts transitively on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

If 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is a group that acts on 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 then the action defines an equivalence relation on 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula $a\sim b$
\end_inset

 if there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in G$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $ga=b$
\end_inset

.
 The equivalence class of 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in A$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{a}=\{ga\mid g\in G\}$
\end_inset

.
 We say 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{a}$
\end_inset

 is the 
\series bold
orbit 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 containing 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

.
 Recall 
\begin_inset Formula $|C_{a}|=|G:G_{a}|$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{a}=\{g\in G\mid ga=a\}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The action of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
transitive
\series default
 if there is exactly one orbit, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{a}=A$
\end_inset

 for any 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in A$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq2$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{n}$
\end_inset

 acts transitively on 
\begin_inset Formula $A=\{1,2,\dots,n\}$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma\cdot i=\sigma(i)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma\in S_{n}$
\end_inset

 and for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in\{1,2,\dots,n\}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 be a group and let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 be a nonempty set.
 Consider the trivial action of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 : 
\begin_inset Formula $ga=a$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in G$
\end_inset

 and for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in A$
\end_inset

.
 This action is transitive if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 has exactly one element since 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{a}=\{a\}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in A$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Groups Acting by Left Multiplication
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 be a group with identity 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

.
 Recall that 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 acts on itself by left multiplication by 
\begin_inset Formula $g\cdot h=gh$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $g,h\in G$
\end_inset

.
 The associated permutation representation 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi:G\to S_{G}$
\end_inset

 given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(g)=\sigma_{g}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{g}:G\to G$
\end_inset

 given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{g}(a)=ga$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in G$
\end_inset

.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{Ker}\varphi=\{g\in G\mid\sigma_{g}=1_{g}\}=\{g\in G\mid ga=a,\,\forall a\in G\}=\{1\}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Cayley) Every group is isomorphic to a subgroup of a group of permutations.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 acts on 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 by left multiplication.
 This gives a homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi:G\to S_{G}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{Ker}\varphi=\{1\}$
\end_inset

.
 By the first isomorphism theorem, 
\begin_inset Formula $G\cong G/\mbox{Ker}\varphi\cong\varphi(G)\leq S_{G}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 be a group, let 
\begin_inset Formula $H\leq G$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $A=\{aH\mid a\in G\}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 acts transitively on 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 by left multiplication: 
\begin_inset Formula $g\cdot aH=gaH$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in G$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $aH\in A$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{Ker}=\bigcap\limits _{x\in G}xHx^{-1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{Ker}\leq H$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $(1):$
\end_inset

 We have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
g_{1}\cdot(g_{2}\cdot aH) & =g_{1}\cdot(g_{2}a)H)\\
 & =g_{1}(g_{2}a)H\\
 & =(g_{1}g_{2})aH\\
 & =g_{1}g_{2}\cdot aH
\end{align*}

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1},g_{2}\in G$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $aH\in A$
\end_inset

.
 We also have 
\begin_inset Formula $1\cdot aH=aH$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $aH\in A$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore this is a group action.
 Now we check that the action is transitive.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $aH$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $bH$
\end_inset

 be two elements in 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $ba^{-1}\cdot aH=bH$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore this action is transitive.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $(2):$
\end_inset

 By definition, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{Ker}=\{g\in G\mid g\cdot xH=xH,\,\forall x\in G\}$
\end_inset

.
 This means 
\begin_inset Formula $g=xh_{x}x^{-1}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in G$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{x}\in H$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 be a group of finite order.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is the smallest prime dividing 
\begin_inset Formula $|G|$
\end_inset

, then any subgroup of index 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is normal.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $H\leq G$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $[G:H]=p$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $A=\{aH\mid a\in G\}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $|A|=p$
\end_inset

.
 We've just shown 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 acts on 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi:G\to S_{A}$
\end_inset

 be the permutation representation and let 
\begin_inset Formula $K=\mbox{Ker}\pi$
\end_inset

.
 We know that 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is a normal subgroup of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 and that 
\begin_inset Formula $K\leq H$
\end_inset

.
 We show that 
\begin_inset Formula $K=H$
\end_inset

.
 By the first isomorphism theorem, 
\begin_inset Formula $G/K\cong\pi(G)\leq S_{A}$
\end_inset

.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $|\pi(G)|$
\end_inset

 divides 
\begin_inset Formula $|S_{A}|=p!$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $|\pi(G)|=[G:K]$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $K\leq H\leq G$
\end_inset

 we have 
\begin_inset Formula $[G:K]=[G:H][H:K]=p[H:K]$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $[H:K]>1$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $[H:K]$
\end_inset

 divides 
\begin_inset Formula $(p-1)!$
\end_inset

, and this implies any prime dividing 
\begin_inset Formula $[H:K]<p$
\end_inset

.
 But 
\begin_inset Formula $[H:K]$
\end_inset

 divides 
\begin_inset Formula $|H|$
\end_inset

 which implies 
\begin_inset Formula $[H:K]$
\end_inset

 divides 
\begin_inset Formula $|G|$
\end_inset

.
 By hypothesis, any prime dividing 
\begin_inset Formula $[H:K]$
\end_inset

 is greater than or equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 Contradiction.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $[H:K]=1$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $H=K=\mbox{Ker}\pi\trianglelefteq G$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Groups Acting on Themselves by Conjugation and the Class Equation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 act on itself by conjugation, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $g\cdot a=gag^{-1}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $g,a\in G$
\end_inset

.
 The equivalence relation induced on 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is: 
\begin_inset Formula $a\sim b$
\end_inset

 if there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in G$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $b=gag^{-1}$
\end_inset

.
 In this case, 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 are 
\series bold
conjugate
\series default
.
 The orbit containing 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in G$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{a}=\{gag^{-1}\mid g\in G\}$
\end_inset

 and the stabilizer of 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{a}=\{g\in G\mid gag^{-1}=a\}=C_{G}(a)$
\end_inset

.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $|C_{a}|=[G:C_{G}(a)].$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{a}=\{a\}$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in Z(G)$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{a}=\{a\}$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $gag^{-1}=a$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in G$
\end_inset

.
 This implies 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in Z(G)$
\end_inset

.
 Conversely, if 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in Z(G)$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $gag^{-1}=a$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in G$
\end_inset

.
 This implies 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{a}=\{a\}$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (The Class Equation) Let 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 be a group.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1},\dots,g_{k}$
\end_inset

 be representatives of all distinct conjugacy classes not contained in 
\begin_inset Formula $Z(G)$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
|G|=|Z(G)|+\sum_{i=1}^{k}[G:C_{G}(g_{i})].
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $Z(G)=\{1=z_{1},z_{2},\dots,z_{\ell}\}$
\end_inset

.
 By the lemma, 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{z_{\ell}}=\{z_{\ell}\}$
\end_inset

.
 The distinct conjugacy classes of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 are 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
C_{z_{1}},\dots,C_{z_{\ell}},C_{g_{1}},\dots,C_{g_{k}}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
G=C_{z_{1}}\cup\cdots\cup C_{z_{\ell}}\cup C_{g_{1}}\cup\cdots\cup C_{g_{k}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
is a disjoint union of these conjugacy classes.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
|G| & =|C_{z_{1}}|\cup\cdots\cup|C_{z_{\ell}}|\cup|C_{g_{1}}|\cup\cdots\cup|C_{g_{k}}|\\
 & =|Z(G)|+\sum_{i=1}^{k}[G:C_{G}(g_{i})].
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 In 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{3}$
\end_inset

, the class equation says
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
|S_{3}| & =|Z(S_{3})|+[S_{3}:C_{S_{3}}((1,2))]+[S_{3}:C_{S_{3}}((1,2,3))]\\
 & =1+3+2
\end{align*}

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 be a prime and let 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 be a 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

-group.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $Z(G)\neq\{1\}.$
\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1},\dots,g_{k}$
\end_inset

 be representatives of all distinct conjugacy classes which are not contained
 in 
\begin_inset Formula $Z(G)$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
|G|=|Z(G)|+\sum_{i=1}^{k}[G:C_{G}(g_{i})].\label{eq:classequationpgroup}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
First note that 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{G}(g_{i})$
\end_inset

 is a proper subgroup of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{i}\notin Z(G)$
\end_inset

 for each 
\begin_inset Formula $i=1,\dots,k$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore, reducing both sides of 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:classequationpgroup})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 mod 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $|Z(G)|\equiv0\text{ mod }p$
\end_inset

, which implies the theorem.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{cor}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Any group 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 of order 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{2}$
\end_inset

 is abelian.
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{cor}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 By the previous theorem, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $|Z(G)|\in\{p,p^{2}\}$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $|Z(G)|=p^{2}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is abelian.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $|Z(G)|=p$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $|G\slash Z(G)|=p$
\end_inset

 , which implies 
\begin_inset Formula $G\slash Z(G)$
\end_inset

 is cyclic.
 This implies 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is abelian.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 be a group.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $H\trianglelefteq G$
\end_inset

 and if 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is a conjugacy class of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

, then either 
\begin_inset Formula $H\cap K=\emptyset$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $K\subseteq H$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $H\cap K=\emptyset$
\end_inset

 we're done.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $H\cap K\neq\emptyset$
\end_inset

 then there exists an 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $H\cap K$
\end_inset

.
 This implies 
\begin_inset Formula $K=C_{a}=\{gag^{-1}\mid g\in G\}\subseteq H$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 is normal in 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{cor}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $H\trianglelefteq G$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 is a union of conjugacy classes 
\begin_inset Formula $(H=\cup_{a\in H}C_{a})$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{cor}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We list all conjugacy classes and their sizes in 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{4}$
\end_inset

 in the table below
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Tabular
