\begin_layout Standard
Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $H\trianglelefteq S_{4}$
\end_inset

.
 By Lagrange's Theorem, 
\begin_inset Formula $|H|$
\end_inset

 divides 
\begin_inset Formula $|S_{4}|=2^{3}\cdot3$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $|H|=\{1,2,3,4,6,8,12,24\}$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $H\trianglelefteq S_{4}$
\end_inset

, it must be a union of conjugacy classes.
 This implies 
\begin_inset Formula $|H|=1+\ell_{1}+\cdots+\ell_{k}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell_{i}\in\{6,8,3,6\}$
\end_inset

.
 From this we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $|H|\in\{1,4,12,24\}$
\end_inset

.
 Clearly there are normal subgroups of 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{4}$
\end_inset

 with orders 
\begin_inset Formula $1,12,$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $24$
\end_inset

, namely the trivial group, 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{4}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{4}$
\end_inset

.
 There is also a normal subgroup of 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{4}$
\end_inset

 with size 
\begin_inset Formula $4$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula $V=\{(1),(1,2)(3,4),(1,3)(2,4),(1,4)(2,3)\}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Sylow's Theorem
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this section, let 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 be a prime and let 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 be a group of order 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{\alpha}m$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\ge0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p\not\mid m$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 be a prime.
 A 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

-
\series bold
group 
\series default
is a group of order 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{m}$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $m\geq0$
\end_inset

.
 A 
\series bold
Sylow 
\series default

\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

-
\series bold
subgroup 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is a subgroup 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $|P|=p^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

.
 We use the notation 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{Syl}_{p}(G)=\{P\leq G\mid|P|=p^{\alpha}\}$
\end_inset

 to denote the set of all Sylow 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

-subgroups of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 and we also use the notation 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{p}=|\mbox{Syl}_{p}(G)|$
\end_inset

 to denote the number of Sylow 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

-subgroups of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 be a prime and let 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 be a group of order 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{\alpha}m$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\ge0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p\not\mid m$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{Syl}_{p}(G)\neq\emptyset.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

-subgroup of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 and if 
\begin_inset Formula $P\in\mbox{Syl}_{p}(G)$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $Q\leq gPg^{-1}$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in G$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
For all 
\begin_inset Formula $P\in\mbox{Syl}_{p}(G)$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{p}\equiv1\mbox{ mod }p$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{p}\mid m$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{p}=[G:N_{G}(P)]$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{cor}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The following are equivalent.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $n_{p}=1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 is a characteristic subgroup of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $P\trianglelefteq G$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{cor}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We show that any group of order 
\begin_inset Formula $15$
\end_inset

 is cyclic.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 be a group of order 
\begin_inset Formula $15$
\end_inset

.
 We have 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{5}\mid3$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{5}\equiv1\mbox{ mod }5$
\end_inset

, thus 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{5}=1$
\end_inset

.
 Similarly 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{3}=1$
\end_inset

.
 This implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{Syl}_{3}(G)=\{P\}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $|P|=3$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, 
\begin_inset Formula $P=\langle x\rangle$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{ord}(x)=3$
\end_inset

.
 Similarly 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{Syl}_{5}(G)=\{Q\}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Q=\langle y\rangle$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{ord}(y)=5$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 are normal subgroups of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $P\cap Q=\{e\}$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $xy=y^{k}x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $xy=yx^{\ell}$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell$
\end_inset

.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $y^{k}x=yx^{\ell}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $y^{k-1}x^{1-\ell}=1$
\end_inset

, which implies 
\begin_inset Formula $k=\ell=1$
\end_inset

.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 commutes with 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 and this implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{ord}(xy)=\mbox{ord}(x)\mbox{ord}(y)=15$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

-subgroup of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 and if 
\begin_inset Formula $P\in\mbox{Syl}_{p}(G)$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $Q\cap N_{G}(P)=Q\cap P$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We show that any group of order 
\begin_inset Formula $105$
\end_inset

 is not simple.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 be a group such that 
\begin_inset Formula $|G|=105=3\cdot5\cdot7$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is simple.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{3},n_{5},n_{7}>1$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{p}\mid m$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{3}\in\{1,5,7,35\}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{5}\in\{1,3,7,21\}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{7}\in\{1,3,5,15\}$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{p}\equiv1\mbox{ mod }p$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{3}\in\{1,7\}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{5}\in\{1,21\}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{7}\in\{1,15\}$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{p}>1$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{3}=7$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{5}=21$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{7}=15$
\end_inset

.
 This is a contradiction though because this would imply there are 
\begin_inset Formula $2\cdot7$
\end_inset

 elements of order 
\begin_inset Formula $3$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $4\cdot21$
\end_inset

 elements of order 
\begin_inset Formula $5$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $6\cdot15$
\end_inset

 elements of order 
\begin_inset Formula $7$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $2\cdot7+4\cdot21+6\cdot15=188>105$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 be a group of order 
\begin_inset Formula $30=2\cdot3\cdot5$
\end_inset

.
 We show that 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 has a normal subgroup of order 
\begin_inset Formula $15$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{p}\mid m$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{p}\equiv1\mbox{ mod }p$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{2}\in\{1,3,5,15\}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{3}\in\{1,10\}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{5}\in\{1,6\}$
\end_inset

.
 We want to show that one of 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{3},n_{5}$
\end_inset

 has to be 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{3},n_{5}>1$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{3}=10$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{5}=6$
\end_inset

.
 This is a contradiction though since 
\begin_inset Formula $2\cdot10+4\cdot6=44>30$
\end_inset

.
 So either 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{3}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{5}$
\end_inset

 is equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

.
 Assume 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{3}=1$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 be the 
\begin_inset Formula $3$
\end_inset

-Sylow Subgroup and let 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 be a 
\begin_inset Formula $5$
\end_inset

-Sylow Subgroup.
 Then since 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 is normal, 
\begin_inset Formula $PQ$
\end_inset

 is a subgroup of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $|P\cap Q|=1$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $|PQ|=|P|\cdot|Q|$
\end_inset

.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $PQ$
\end_inset

 is a group of order 
\begin_inset Formula $15$
\end_inset

, hence it is cyclic.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{Syl}_{5}(PQ)=\{Q\}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 is a characteristic subgroup of 
\begin_inset Formula $PQ$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $PQ\trianglelefteq G$
\end_inset

 because 
\begin_inset Formula $[G:PQ]=2$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $Q\trianglelefteq G$
\end_inset

.
 The same idea works when 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{5}=1$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Sylows's Theorem Applications
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Recall, if 
\begin_inset Formula $|G|=15$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is cyclic.
 In particular, 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{5}=1$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $|G|=30$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{3}=n_{5}=1$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is a group of order 
\begin_inset Formula $6$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{3}=1$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is a group of order 
\begin_inset Formula $20$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{5}=1$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Any group of order 
\begin_inset Formula $12$
\end_inset

 has either 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{2}=1$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{3}=1$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 be a group of order 
\begin_inset Formula $12=3\cdot2^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{3}=1$
\end_inset

 then we are done.
 So assume 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{3}>1$
\end_inset

.
 Then by Sylow's Theorems, 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{3}=4$
\end_inset

.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{Syl}_{3}(G)=\{P_{1},P_{2},P_{3},P_{4}\}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $|P_{i}|=3$
\end_inset

.
 Each 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{i}$
\end_inset

 is cyclic of order 
\begin_inset Formula $3$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{i}\cap P_{j}=\{e\}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $i\neq j$
\end_inset

, so there are 
\begin_inset Formula $8$
\end_inset

 elements of order 
\begin_inset Formula $3$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

.
 Now 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 acts on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{Syl}_{3}(G)$
\end_inset

 by conjugation: 
\begin_inset Formula $g\cdot P_{i}=gP_{i}g^{-1}$
\end_inset

.
 This gives a homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi:G\to S_{4}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mbox{Ker}\varphi=\{g\in G\mid gP_{i}g^{-1}=P_{i},\quad1\leq i\leq4\}=\bigcap_{i=1,2,3,4}\mbox{N}_{G}(P_{i}).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
4 & =n_{3}\\
 & =[G:\mbox{N}_{G}(P_{i})]\\
 & =\frac{|G|}{\mbox{N}_{G}(P_{i})}\\
 & =\frac{12}{\mbox{N}_{G}(P_{i})}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{N}_{G}(P_{i})=3$
\end_inset

.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{i}\leq\mbox{N}_{G}(P_{i})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $|P_{i}|=|\mbox{N}_{G}(P_{i})|$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{i}=\mbox{N}_{G}(P_{i})$
\end_inset

.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mbox{Ker}\varphi==\bigcap_{i=1,2,3,4}P_{i}=\{e\}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then 
\begin_inset Formula $G\cong\varphi(G)\leq S_{4}$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 has 
\begin_inset Formula $8$
\end_inset

 elements of order 
\begin_inset Formula $3$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(G)$
\end_inset

 also has 
\begin_inset Formula $8$
\end_inset

 elements of order 
\begin_inset Formula $3$
\end_inset

.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $|\varphi(G)\cap A_{4}|\geq8$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(G)\cap A_{4}\leq\varphi(G)$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $|\varphi(G)\cap A_{4}|=12=\varphi(G)$
\end_inset

.
 So if 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{3}=4$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(G)\cong A_{4}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{2}(A_{4})=1$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is a group of order 
\begin_inset Formula $60$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{5}>1$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is simple.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 To obtain a contradiction, suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is a group of order 
\begin_inset Formula $60=2^{2}\cdot3\cdot5$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is not simple.
 By Sylow's Theorems, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{5}\in\{1,6\}$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is not simple, we must have 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{5}=6$
\end_inset

.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{Syl}_{6}(G)=\{P_{1},P_{2},P_{3},P_{4},P_{5},P_{6}\}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $|P_{i}|=5$
\end_inset

.
 Each 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{i}$
\end_inset

 is cyclic of order 
\begin_inset Formula $5$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{i}\cap P_{j}=\{e\}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $i\neq j$
\end_inset

, so there are 
\begin_inset Formula $24$
\end_inset

 elements of order 
\begin_inset Formula $5$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is not simple, there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $H\trianglelefteq G$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $H\neq1,G$
\end_inset

.
 Now 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
|H|\mid60\implies|H|\in\{2,3,4,5,6,10,12,15,20,30\}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $5\mid|H|$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 contains a subgroup of order 
\begin_inset Formula $5$
\end_inset

.
 Thus there is some 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{i}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{i}\leq H$
\end_inset

.
 For any other 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{j}\in\mbox{Syl}_{5}(G)$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{j}=gP_{i}g^{-1}$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in G$
\end_inset

.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{j}=gP_{i}g^{-1}\leq gHg^{-1}=H$
\end_inset

.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 contains all the Sylow 
\begin_inset Formula $5$
\end_inset

-subgroups of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $|H|\geq1+24=25$
\end_inset

, this implies 
\begin_inset Formula $|H|=30$
\end_inset

.
 But if 
\begin_inset Formula $|H|=30$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{5}(H)=1$
\end_inset

, which is a contradiction.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
|H|\in\{2,3,4,6,12\}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $|H|\in\{6,12\}$
\end_inset

, then there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $K\mbox{ char }H$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $K\in\mbox{Syl}_{3}(H)$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $K\in\mbox{Syl}_{2}(H)$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is characteristic in 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 is normal in 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is normal in 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

.
 So there is a normal subgroup 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $|K|\in\{2,3,4\}$
\end_inset

.
 So it suffices to assume
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
|H|\in\{2,3,4\}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
leads to a contradiction.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $|G/H|\in\{30,20,15\}$
\end_inset

.
 Now 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{5}(G/H)=1$
\end_inset

 implies there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $H\trianglelefteq T\trianglelefteq G$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $T/H\trianglelefteq G/H$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $|T/H|=5$
\end_inset

.
 So there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $T\trianglelefteq G$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $|T|/|H|=5$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $|T|=5\cdot|H|$
\end_inset

.
 But this leads to the first case where 
\begin_inset Formula $5\mid|T|$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 is normal.
 This leads to a contradiction.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{cor}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{5}$
\end_inset

 is simple in 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{5}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{cor}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We have 
\begin_inset Formula $|A_{5}|=60$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{5}>1$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle(1,2,3,4,5)\rangle\neq\langle(2,1,3,4,5)\rangle$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is a simple group of order 
\begin_inset Formula $60$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $G\cong A_{5}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{n}$
\end_inset

 is a simple group for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq5$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 be a group of order 
\begin_inset Formula $231=3\cdot7\cdot11$
\end_inset

.
 We will show 
\begin_inset Formula $Z(G)$
\end_inset

 contains a Sylow 
\begin_inset Formula $11$
\end_inset

-sybgroup and 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{7}=1$
\end_inset

.
 From the Sylow theorems, we obtain 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{11}=1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{7}=1$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 be the Sylow 11 -subgroup of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

.
 Consider the action of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 by conjugation 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi:G\to\mbox{Aut}(P)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(g)=\sigma_{g}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{g}(x)=gxg^{-1}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in P$
\end_inset

.
 The kernel of 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{G}(P)$
\end_inset

.
 By the Isomorphism theorems, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $G/C_{G}(P)\cong\varphi(G)\leq\mbox{Aut}(P)$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $|\mbox{Aut}(P)|=10$
\end_inset

, we must have 
\begin_inset Formula $|G/C_{G}(P)|\mid10$
\end_inset

.
 The only possibility is when 
\begin_inset Formula $|G/C_{G}(P)|=1$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{G}(P)=G$
\end_inset

.
 That is, 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 is contained in 
\begin_inset Formula $Z(G)$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 be a group of order 
\begin_inset Formula $105=3\cdot5\cdot7$
\end_inset

 and suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{3}=1$
\end_inset

.
 We will show 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is abelian.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 be the Sylow 
\begin_inset Formula $3$
\end_inset

-subgroup and consider the action of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 by conjugation.
 Again, we find that 
\begin_inset Formula $|G/C_{G}(P)|$
\end_inset

 divides 
\begin_inset Formula $|\mbox{Aut}(P)|=2$
\end_inset

.
 The only possibility is 
\begin_inset Formula $|G/C_{G}(P)|=1$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $G=C_{G}(P)$
\end_inset

.
  
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Direct Products of Abelian Groups
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{1},G_{2},\dots,G_{n}$
\end_inset

 be groups and let 
\begin_inset Formula $G=\{(a_{1},\dots,a_{n})\mid a_{i}\in G_{i},\,1\leq i\le n\}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is a group with multiplication defined by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(a_{1},\dots,a_{n})\cdot(b_{1},\dots,b_{n})=(a_{1}b_{1},\dots,a_{n}b_{n}).
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The multiplicaiton operation is clearly an associative binary operation.
 We also have an identity element 
\begin_inset Formula $(e_{1},\dots,e_{n})$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the identity element in 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 And the inverse of an element 
\begin_inset Formula $(a_{1},\dots,a_{n})\in G$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $(a_{1}^{-1},\dots,a_{n}^{-1})$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A group 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
finitely generated
\series default
 if 
\begin_inset Formula $G=\langle A\rangle$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $\emptyset\neq A\subset G$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $|A|<\infty$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
The Fundamental Theorem of Finitely Generated Abelian Groups
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 be a finitely generated abelian group.
 Then 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $G\cong\mathbb{Z}^{r}\times\mathbb{Z}_{n_{1}}\times\mathbb{Z}_{n_{2}}\cdots\times\mathbb{Z}_{n_{k}}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $r\geq0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{i}\geq2$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{i+1}\mid n_{i}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq i\le k-1$
\end_inset

.
 We say 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{i}$
\end_inset

 are the 
\series bold
invariant factors
\series default
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 is the 
\series bold
Betti number
\series default
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The decomposition in 
\begin_inset Formula $(1)$
\end_inset

 is unique i.e.
 if 
\begin_inset Formula $G\cong\mathbb{Z}^{\ell}\times\mathbb{Z}_{m_{1}}\times\mathbb{Z}_{m_{2}}\cdots\times\mathbb{Z}_{m_{t}}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell\geq0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{j}\geq2$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{j+1}\mid m_{j}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq j\leq t-1$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $r=\ell$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $k=t$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{i}=m_{i}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq i\leq k$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $|G|<\infty$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $r=0$
\end_inset

.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $G\cong\mathbb{Z}_{n_{1}}\times\mathbb{Z}_{n_{2}}\times\cdots\times\mathbb{Z}_{n_{k}}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{i}\geq2$
\end_inset

 and such that 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{i+1}\mid n_{i}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq i\leq k-1$
\end_inset

.
 In this case, 
\begin_inset Formula $|G|=n_{1}n_{2}\cdots n_{k}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is a finite abelian group, then every prime divisor of 
\begin_inset Formula $|G|$
\end_inset

 must divide 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 This is because 
\begin_inset Formula $p\mid n_{1}n_{2}\cdots n_{k}$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $p\mid n_{i}\mid n_{i-1}\mid\cdots\mid n_{2}\mid n_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We find (up to isomorphism) all abelian groups of order 
\begin_inset Formula $180$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 be a group of order 
\begin_inset Formula $180=2^{2}\cdot3^{2}\cdot5$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $G\cong\mathbb{Z}_{n_{1}}\times\mathbb{Z}_{n_{2}}\times\cdots\times\mathbb{Z}_{n_{k}}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{i}\geq2$
\end_inset

 and such that 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{i+1}\mid n_{i}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq i\leq k-1$
\end_inset

.
 So we have by the second remark, 
\begin_inset Formula $2,3,5\mid n_{1}$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{1}$
\end_inset

 equals 
\begin_inset Formula $2\cdot3\cdot5$
\end_inset

, or 
\begin_inset Formula $2^{2}\cdot3\cdot5$
\end_inset

, or 
\begin_inset Formula $2\cdot3^{2}\cdot5$
\end_inset

, or 
\begin_inset Formula $2^{2}\cdot3^{2}\cdot5$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

In the case 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{1}=2\cdot3\cdot5$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
n_{2}\mid n_{1}\qquad\mbox{and}\qquad n_{1}n_{2}\mid2^{2}\cdot3^{2}\cdot5\qquad\implies\qquad n_{2}\in\{2,3,2\cdot3\}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{2}=2$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{1}n_{2}=2^{2}\cdot3\cdot5<|G|$
\end_inset

.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{3}\mid n_{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{1}n_{2}n_{3}\mid180$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{3}=3$
\end_inset

 which is a contradiction.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{2}\neq2$
\end_inset

.
 Again we get a contradiction if we assume 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{2}=3$
\end_inset

.
 So for 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{1}=2\cdot3\cdot5$
\end_inset

, the only possibility is for 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{2}=2\cdot3$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{1}n_{2}=2^{2}\cdot3^{2}\cdot5$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{3}=1$
\end_inset

.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $G\cong\mathbb{Z}_{30}\times\mathbb{Z}_{6}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

In the case 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{2}=2^{2}\cdot3\cdot5$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
n_{2}\mid n_{1}\qquad\mbox{and}\qquad n_{1}n_{2}\mid2^{2}\cdot3^{2}\cdot5\qquad\implies\qquad n_{2}=3.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So 
\begin_inset Formula $G\cong\mathbb{Z}_{60}\times\mathbb{Z}_{3}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

In the case 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{1}=2\cdot3^{2}\cdot5$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
n_{2}\mid n_{1}\qquad\mbox{and}\qquad n_{1}n_{2}\mid2^{2}\cdot3^{2}\cdot5\qquad\implies\qquad n_{2}=2.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So 
\begin_inset Formula $G\cong\mathbb{Z}_{90}\times\mathbb{Z}_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

The last case to consider is 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{1}=180$
\end_inset

.
 In this case, 
\begin_inset Formula $G\cong\mathbb{Z}_{180}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 be a finite abelian group of order 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
 Write the prime factorization of 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $n=p_{1}^{e_{1}}\cdots p_{k}^{e_{k}}$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $G\cong A_{1}\times A_{2}\times\cdots\times A_{k}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $|A_{i}|=p_{i}^{e_{i}}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq i\le k$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $A\in\{A_{1},\dots,A_{k}\}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $|A|=p^{e}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $A\cong\mathbb{Z}_{p^{f_{1}}}\times\cdots\times\mathbb{Z}_{p^{f_{\ell}}}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1}\geq f_{2}\geq\cdots\geq f_{\ell}\geq1$
\end_inset

.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}^{f_{i}}$
\end_inset

 are called the 
\series bold
elementary divisors 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The decomposition of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is unique.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We find all abelian groups (up to isomorphism) of order 
\begin_inset Formula $8$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Tabular
