\begin_layout Subsection
Class Equation of a Group Action
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is a group and 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is a finite set.
 Suppose we are given a group action of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{0}$
\end_inset

 denote the set of those points in 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 that are fixed under the action of all elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $O_{1},O_{2,},\dots,O_{r}$
\end_inset

 be the orbits of size greater than one under this action.
 For each orbit 
\begin_inset Formula $O_{i}$
\end_inset

, let 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}$
\end_inset

 be an element of 
\begin_inset Formula $O_{i}$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{i}$
\end_inset

 denote the stabilizer of 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

.
 The class equation for this action is given as follows:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
|X|=|X_{0}|+\sum_{i=1}^{r}[G:G_{i}]
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This follows from Orbit-Stabilizer.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Group Cohomology
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Basic Terminology
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Throughout this subsection, let 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 be a group.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Group Rings
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The 
\series bold
group ring 
\series default

\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}[G]$
\end_inset

 corresponding to 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is defined as follows: the underlying set of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}[G]$
\end_inset

 is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbb{Z}[G]=\left\{ \sum_{g\in G}n_{g}g\mid n_{g}\in\mathbb{Z}\,\text{and }n_{g}=0\text{ for all but finitely many }g\in G\right\} .
\]

\end_inset

Addition in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}[G]$
\end_inset

 is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sum_{g\in G}m_{g}g+\sum_{g\in G}n_{g}g=\sum_{g\in G}(m_{g}+n_{g})g
\]

\end_inset

and multiplication in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}[G]$
\end_inset

 is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(\sum_{g\in G}m_{g}g\right)\left(\sum_{g\in G}n_{g}g\right)=\sum_{g\in G}\left(\sum_{h\in G}m_{h}n_{h^{-1}g}\right)g
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{g\in G}m_{g}g$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{g\in G}n_{g}g$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}[G]$
\end_inset

.
 To simplify notation, whenever we write 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{g\in G}n_{g}g$
\end_inset

, it will be understood that this is an element in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}[G]$
\end_inset

.
 It is straightforward to check that addition and multiplication defined
 above gives 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}[G]$
\end_inset

 the structure of a ring, with 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

 being the unit (where 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

 is the usual identity element in 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

).
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

-Modules
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset


\series bold
-module 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 
\series default
is just a 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}[G]$
\end_inset

-module in the usual sense.
 In particular, 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is abelian group (written additively) on which 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}[G]$
\end_inset

 acts by additive maps, so
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
(gh)a & =g(ha)\\
ea & =a\\
g(a+b) & =ga+gb
\end{align*}

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $g,h\in G$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in A$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 For each 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

, we define the following 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}[G]$
\end_inset

-modules: as a set, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbb{Z}[G^{n+1}]=\left\{ \sum_{g_{0},\dots,g_{n}\in G}n_{g_{0},\dots,g_{n}}(g_{0},\dots,g_{n})\mid n_{g_{0},\dots,g_{n}}\in\mathbb{Z}\,\text{and }n_{g_{0},\dots,g_{n}}=0\text{ for all but finitely many tuples }(g_{0},\dots,g_{n})\in G^{n}\right\} .
\]

\end_inset

Addition in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}[G^{n+1}]$
\end_inset

 is defined pointwise as in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}[G]$
\end_inset

 and scalar multiplication is uniquely determined by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
g(g_{0},\dots,g_{n})=(gg_{0},\dots,gg_{n})
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in G$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(g_{0},\dots,g_{n})\in G^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 We write 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}[[G]]$
\end_inset

 to be the graded module whose component in degree 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbb{Z}[[G]]_{n}=\mathbb{Z}[G^{n+1}]
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here, we view 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}[G]$
\end_inset

 as a trivially graded ring which sits in the degree 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 component of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}[[G]]$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbb{Z}[[G]]=\bigoplus_{n\geq0}\mathbb{Z}[G^{n+1}].
\]

\end_inset

We give 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}[[G]]$
\end_inset

 the structure of a 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}[G]$
\end_inset

-complex by defining the differential 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{d}\colon\mathbb{Z}[[G]]\to\mathbb{Z}[[G]]$
\end_inset

 by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{d}_{n+1}(g_{0},\dots,g_{n})=\sum_{i=0}^{n}(-1)^{i}(g_{0},\dots,\widehat{g}_{i},\dots,g_{n})
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(g_{0},\dots,g_{n})\in\mathbb{Z}[[G]]$
\end_inset

, and extending it 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}[G]$
\end_inset

-linearly.
 It is easy to check that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{d}$
\end_inset

 is graded of degree 
\begin_inset Formula $-1$
\end_inset

 and satisfies 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{d}^{2}=0$
\end_inset

, making it a differential.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Viewing 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}[G^{n+1}]$
\end_inset

 as a Free 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}[G]$
\end_inset

-Module
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By definition, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}[G^{n+1}]$
\end_inset

 is a free 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

-module with basis given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\{(g_{0},\dots,g_{n})\mid g_{0},\dots,g_{n}\in G\}.
\]

\end_inset

In fact, let us now show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}[G^{n+1}]$
\end_inset

 is a free 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}[G]$
\end_inset

-module, with basis 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\{(1,g_{1},\dots,g_{n})\mid g_{1},\dots,g_{n}\in G\}\label{eq:zgbasis}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 is the identity in 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}[G^{n}]$
\end_inset

 is a free 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}[G]$
\end_inset

-module with basis given by 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:zgbasis})
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 First note that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\sum_{g_{0},\dots,g_{n}\in G}n_{g_{0},\dots,g_{n}}(g_{0},\dots,g_{n}) & =\sum_{g_{0},\dots,g_{n}\in G}n_{g_{0},\dots,g_{n}}g_{0}(1,g_{0}^{-1}g_{1}\dots,g_{0}^{-1}g_{n})
\end{align*}

\end_inset

shows 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{span}_{\mathbb{Z}[G]}\{(1,g_{1},\dots,g_{n})\mid g_{1},\dots,g_{n}\in G\}=\mathbb{Z}[G^{n}].
\]

\end_inset

It remains to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\{(1,g_{1},\dots,g_{n})\mid g_{1},\dots,g_{n}\in G\}$
\end_inset

 is linearly independent over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}[G]$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sum_{i=1}^{k}\left(\sum_{g\in G}n_{g,i}g\right)(1,g_{1,i},\dots,g_{n,i})=0,
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{g\in G}n_{g,i}g\in\mathbb{Z}[G]$
\end_inset

 for each 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq i\leq k$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(1,g_{1,i},\dots,g_{n,i})\neq(1,g_{1,j},\dots,g_{n,j})$
\end_inset

 whenever 
\begin_inset Formula $i\neq j$
\end_inset

 (so 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{m,i}\neq g_{m,j}$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq m\leq n$
\end_inset

).
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
0 & =\sum_{i=1}^{k}\left(\sum_{g\in G}n_{g,i}g\right)(1,g_{1,i},\dots,g_{n,i})\\
 & =\sum_{i=1}^{k}\sum_{g\in G}n_{g,i}(g,gg_{1,i},\dots,gg_{n,i})\\
 & =\sum_{\substack{g\in G\\
1\leq i\leq k
}
}n_{g,i}(g,gg_{1,i},\dots,gg_{n,i})
\end{align*}

\end_inset

implies 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{g,i}=0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in G$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq i\leq k$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\{(g,gg_{1,i},\dots,gg_{n,i})\mid g\in G\text{ and }1\leq i\leq k\}
\]

\end_inset

is linearly independent over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

.
 Here we are using the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $(g,gg_{1,i},\dots,gg_{n,i})\neq(h,hg_{1,j},\dots,hg_{n,j})$
\end_inset

 whenever 
\begin_inset Formula $g\neq h$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $i\neq j$
\end_inset

.
 To see why this is the case, first note that if 
\begin_inset Formula $g\neq h$
\end_inset

, then clearly 
\begin_inset Formula $(g,gg_{1,i},\dots,gg_{n,i})\neq(h,hg_{1,j},\dots,hg_{n,j})$
\end_inset

 since they do not agree in the first component, so assume 
\begin_inset Formula $g=h$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $i\neq j$
\end_inset

, then there exists an 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq m\leq n$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{m,i}\neq g_{m,j}$
\end_inset

, in which case 
\begin_inset Formula $gg_{m,i}\neq gg_{m,j}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Differential on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}[[G]]$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We want to give 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}[[G]]$
\end_inset

 a 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}[G]$
\end_inset

-complex structure as follows.
 We define 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{d}\colon\mathbb{Z}[[G]]\to\mathbb{Z}[[G]]$
\end_inset

 in terms of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

-basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\{(g_{0},\dots,g_{n})\mid n\in\mathbb{N}\}$
\end_inset

 and then extend it 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

-linearly.
 We will then show that it is in fact 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}[G]$
\end_inset

-linear.
 The reason we define it on the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

-basis first is because it will be easy to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{d}^{2}=0$
\end_inset

.
 So for any 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

-basis element 
\begin_inset Formula $(g_{0},\dots,g_{n})$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}[[G]]$
\end_inset

, we set
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathrm{d}((g_{0},\dots,g_{n})) & =\sum_{i=0}^{n}(-1)^{i}(g_{0},\dots,\widehat{g}_{i},\dots,g_{n}).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

It is easy to check that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{d}^{2}=0$
\end_inset

 and is homogeneous of degree 
\begin_inset Formula $-1$
\end_inset

.
 Let us show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{d}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}[G]$
\end_inset

-linear.
 First note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{d}$
\end_inset

 is additive since it is 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

-linear, so we just need to show that is preserves 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}[G]$
\end_inset

-scalar multiplication.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{d}$
\end_inset

 is already additive, we just need ot check this on the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}[G]$
\end_inset

-basis elements, so let 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in G$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $(1,g_{1}\dots,g_{n})$
\end_inset

 be any 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}[G]$
\end_inset

-basis element.
 We have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathrm{d}\left(g(1,g_{1}\dots,g_{n})\right) & =\mathrm{d}(g,gg_{1}\dots,gg_{n})\\
 & =(gg_{1}\dots,gg_{n})+\sum_{i=1}^{n}(-1)^{i}(g,gg_{1},\dots,\widehat{gg_{i}},\dots,gg_{n})\\
 & =g\left((g_{1}\dots,g_{n})+\sum_{i=1}^{n}(-1)^{i}(1,g_{1},\dots,\widehat{g_{i}},\dots,g_{n})\right)\\
 & =g\mathrm{d}(1,g_{1}\dots,g_{n}).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{d}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}[G]$
\end_inset

-linear, and since already 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{d}^{2}=0$
\end_inset

 and is graded of degree 
\begin_inset Formula $-1$
\end_inset

, we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{d}$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}[G]$
\end_inset

-differential.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Free Resolution of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 Over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}[G]$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So far we've shown that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}[[G]]$
\end_inset

 can be given a nice 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}[G]$
\end_inset

-complex structure.
 We will now show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}[[G]]$
\end_inset

 can be the structure of a free resolution of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}[G]$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, we view 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 as a trivial 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}[G]$
\end_inset

-complex and we define a chain map 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon\colon\mathbb{Z}[[G]]\to\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 as follows: in homological degree 
\begin_inset Formula $i>0$
\end_inset

 we set 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{i}\colon\mathbb{Z}[G^{i+1}]\to0$
\end_inset

 to be the zero map, and in homological degree 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 we define 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{0}\colon\mathbb{Z}[G]\to\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varepsilon_{0}\left(\sum_{g\in G}n_{g}g\right)=\sum_{g\in G}n_{g}.
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{g\in G}n_{g}g\in\mathbb{Z}[G]$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

To show that the pair 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mathbb{Z}[[G]],\varepsilon)$
\end_inset

 really is a free resolution of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}[G]$
\end_inset

, we need to check that the augmented 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}[G]$
\end_inset

-complex 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}[[G]]_{\varepsilon}$
\end_inset

 is exact.
 Here, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}[[G]]_{\varepsilon}$
\end_inset

 is defined as follows: as a graded module, the homogeneous component in
 homological degree 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 is
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathbb{Z}[[G]]_{\varepsilon,i} & =\begin{cases}
\mathbb{Z}[[G]]_{i} & \text{if }i\geq0\\
\mathbb{Z} & \text{if }i=-1\\
0 & \text{if }i<-1
\end{cases}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

and the differential 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{d}_{\varepsilon}\colon\mathbb{Z}[[G]]_{\varepsilon}\to\mathbb{Z}[[G]]_{\varepsilon}$
\end_inset

 in homological degree 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 is defined by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{d}_{\varepsilon,i}=\begin{cases}
\mathrm{d}_{i} & \text{if }i>0\\
\varepsilon & \text{if }i=0\\
0 & \text{if }i<0
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset

It is easy to check that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}[[G]]_{\varepsilon}$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}[G]$
\end_inset

-complex.
 Now we will show that it is exact.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The complex 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}[[G]]_{\varepsilon}$
\end_inset

 is exact.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Define a 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

-graded homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{h}\colon\mathbb{Z}[[G]]_{\varepsilon}\to\mathbb{Z}[[G]]_{\varepsilon}$
\end_inset

 of degree 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 as follows: if 
\begin_inset Formula $i\geq1$
\end_inset

 we define 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{h}_{i-1}\colon\mathbb{Z}[G^{i}]\to\mathbb{Z}[G^{i+1}]$
\end_inset

 on the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

-basis by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathrm{h}_{i-1}(g_{1},\dots,g_{i}) & =(e,g_{1},\dots,g_{i})
\end{align*}

\end_inset

and extend 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

-linearly.
 In homological degree 
\begin_inset Formula $-1$
\end_inset

, we define 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{h}_{-1}\colon\mathbb{Z}\to\mathbb{Z}[G]$
\end_inset

 by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{h}_{-1}(n)=ne
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

.
 One check thats 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{h}\colon\mathbb{Z}[[G]]_{\varepsilon}\to\mathbb{Z}[[G]]_{\varepsilon}$
\end_inset

 is in fact a 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}[G]$
\end_inset

-graded homomorphism of degree 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 and furthermore satisfies
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{d}_{\varepsilon}\mathrm{h}+\mathrm{h}\mathrm{d}_{\varepsilon}=1.
\]

\end_inset

In particular, the identity map 
\begin_inset Formula $1\colon\mathbb{Z}[[G]]\to\mathbb{Z}[[G]]$
\end_inset

 is null homotopic.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Definition of Group Cohomology
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us now define cohomology groups.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
