\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Now let 
\begin_inset Formula $(E',\alpha',\beta')$
\end_inset

 be an extensions of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon(E,\alpha,\beta)\to(E',\alpha',\beta')$
\end_inset

 be an isomorphism.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 induces an isomorphism between the extensions 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(E,\alpha'\alpha^{-1},\gamma\beta')$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $E\slash\alpha(A)$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha(A)$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, since 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma\colon G\to E\slash\alpha(A)$
\end_inset

 and and 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha^{-1}\colon\alpha(A)\to A$
\end_inset

 are isomorphisms, we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha'\alpha^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is injective and 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma\beta'$
\end_inset

 is surjective, moreover 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{im}\,(\gamma\beta')\subseteq\ker(\alpha'\alpha^{-1})$
\end_inset

.
 It follows that
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd}  1 
\backslash
arrow[r] & 
\backslash
alpha(A) 
\backslash
arrow[r,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\backslash
alpha ' 
\backslash
alpha ^{-1} 
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

] & E 
\backslash
arrow[r,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\backslash
gamma 
\backslash
beta ' 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

] & G 
\backslash
arrow[r] & 1 
\backslash
end{tikzcd}
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
is a short exact sequence.
 Furthemore, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma\beta'\varphi=\gamma\beta=\pi$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha'\alpha^{-1}=\varphi\alpha\alpha^{-1}=\varphi\iota$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Conversely, let 
\begin_inset Formula $(E',\delta,\varepsilon)$
\end_inset

 be an extension of 
\begin_inset Formula $E\slash\alpha(A)$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha(A)$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi\colon E\to(E',\delta,\varepsilon)$
\end_inset

 be an isomorphism.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 induces an isomoprhism between the extensions 
\begin_inset Formula $(E,\alpha,\beta)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(E',\delta\alpha,\gamma^{-1}\varepsilon)$
\end_inset

.
 This construction is easily checked to be the inverse to the consturction
 above, and thus we have a bijection of isomorphism classes.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

The proposition above simplifies our notation a bit.
 Given an extension 
\begin_inset Formula $(E,\alpha,\beta)$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, we are often interested in the set 
\begin_inset Formula $[E,\alpha,\beta]$
\end_inset

 up to 
\emph on
bijection.

\emph default
 The proposition above gives us a canonical bijection between 
\begin_inset Formula $[E,\alpha,\beta]$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $[E]$
\end_inset

.
 Thus there is no harm if we identify 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha(A)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $E\slash\alpha(A)$
\end_inset

 respectively.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Sections
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(E,\alpha,\beta)$
\end_inset

 be an extension of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
A 
\series bold
right 
\series default

\begin_inset Formula $\textbf{section}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $(E,\alpha,\beta)$
\end_inset

 is a function 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\beta}\colon G\to E$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta\widetilde{\beta}=1_{G}$
\end_inset

.
 In other words, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\beta(\widetilde{\beta}(g))=g
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in G$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\beta}$
\end_inset

 is a homomorphism, then we say 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\beta}$
\end_inset

 is a 
\series bold
right splitting section 
\series default
and that it 
\series bold
splits
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $(E,\alpha,\beta)$
\end_inset

 
\series bold
to the right
\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
A 
\series bold
left 
\series default

\begin_inset Formula $\textbf{section}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $(E,\alpha,\beta)$
\end_inset

 is a function 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\alpha}\colon E\to A$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\alpha}\alpha=1_{A}$
\end_inset

.
 In other words, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\widetilde{\alpha}(\alpha(a))=a
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in A$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 is a homomorphism, then we say 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 is a 
\series bold
left splitting section 
\series default
and that it 
\series bold
splits
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $(E,\alpha,\beta)$
\end_inset

 
\series bold
to the left
\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Right Splitting Sections
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(E,\alpha,\beta)$
\end_inset

 be be an extension of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 Then there exists a right splitting section of 
\begin_inset Formula $(E,\alpha,\beta)$
\end_inset

 if and only if there exists a homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho\colon G\to\mathrm{Aut}(A)$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $(E,\alpha,\beta)\cong(A\rtimes_{\rho}G,\iota_{1},\pi_{2})$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 To keep notation clean we identify 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha(A)$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, we assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is a normal subgroup of 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 and that 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 is the inclusion map.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\beta}\colon G\to E$
\end_inset

 be a right splitting section of 
\begin_inset Formula $(E,\alpha,\beta)$
\end_inset

.
 Define 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho\colon G\to\mathrm{Aut}(A)$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho(g)=\mathrm{c}_{\widetilde{\beta}(g)}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in G$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{c}_{\widetilde{\beta}(g)}$
\end_inset

 is conjugation map given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{c}_{\widetilde{\beta}(g)}(a)=\widetilde{\beta}(g)a\widetilde{\beta}(g)^{-1}
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in A$
\end_inset

.
 Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{c}_{\widetilde{\beta}(g)}$
\end_inset

 lands in 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is a normal subgroup.
 Since conjugation and 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\beta}$
\end_inset

 are both homomorphisms, it follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 is a homomorphism.
 Now define 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon(E,\alpha,\beta)\to(A\rtimes G,\iota_{1},\pi_{2})$
\end_inset

 by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varphi(x)=(x\widetilde{\beta}\beta(x)^{-1},\beta(x))
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in E$
\end_inset

.
 Observe that 
\begin_inset Formula $x\widetilde{\beta}\beta(x)^{-1}$
\end_inset

 really does belong to 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 since
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\beta(x\widetilde{\beta}\beta(x)^{-1}) & =\beta(x)\beta\widetilde{\beta}\beta(x)^{-1}\\
 & =\beta(x)\beta(x)^{-1}\\
 & =e
\end{align*}

\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula $A=\ker\beta$
\end_inset

.
 Also 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is a group homomorphism.
 Indeed, let 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in E$
\end_inset

.
 Then we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\varphi(x)\varphi(y) & =(x\widetilde{\beta}\beta(x)^{-1},\beta(x))\cdot(y\widetilde{\beta}\beta(y)^{-1},\beta(y))\\
 & =(x\widetilde{\beta}\beta(x)^{-1}\mathrm{c}_{\widetilde{\beta}\beta(x)}(y\widetilde{\beta}\beta(y)^{-1}),\beta(x)\beta(y))\\
 & =(x\widetilde{\beta}\beta(x)^{-1}\widetilde{\beta}\beta(x)y\widetilde{\beta}\beta(y)^{-1}\widetilde{\beta}\beta(x)^{-1},\beta(xy))\\
 & =(xy\widetilde{\beta}\beta(y)^{-1}\widetilde{\beta}\beta(x)^{-1},\beta(xy))\\
 & =(xy\widetilde{\beta}\beta(xy)^{-1},\beta(xy))\\
 & =\varphi(xy).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

It is straightforward to check that the map 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi\colon A\rtimes G\to E$
\end_inset

, defined by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\psi(a,g) & =a\widetilde{\beta}(g)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in G$
\end_inset

, is the inverse to 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, this implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is an isomorphism.
 It is also straightforward to check that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is an isomorphism of extensions, that is, 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\alpha=\iota_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{2}\varphi=\beta$
\end_inset

.
 We leave the details as an exercise.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Left Splitting Sections
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(E,\alpha,\beta)$
\end_inset

 be be an extension of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 Then there exists a left splitting section of 
\begin_inset Formula $(E,\alpha,\beta)$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $(E,\alpha,\beta)\cong(A\times G,\iota_{1},\pi_{2})$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota_{1}\colon A\to A\times G$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{2}\colon A\times G$
\end_inset

 are defined by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\iota_{1}(a)=(a,e)\quad\text{and}\quad\pi_{2}(a,g)=g
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in G$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The proof is similar in nature to the one above.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Conjugation Action of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Z}(A)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(E,\alpha,\beta)$
\end_inset

 be a group extension of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 To simplify notation in what follows, assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is a normal subgroup of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 (so 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 is just the inclusion map).
 We define an action of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Z}(A)$
\end_inset

 as follows: for each element 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in G$
\end_inset

, we choose a lift 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{g}\in E$
\end_inset

 with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 (so 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta(e_{g})=g$
\end_inset

).
 Thus the map 
\begin_inset Formula $g\mapsto e_{g}$
\end_inset

 is a right splitting section of 
\begin_inset Formula $(E,\alpha,\beta)$
\end_inset

.
 Furthermore, every element in 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 can be expressed uniquely in the form 
\begin_inset Formula $ae_{g}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in G$
\end_inset

 both uniquely determine that element.
 In other words, if 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in E$
\end_inset

 are expressed as 
\begin_inset Formula $x=ae_{\beta(x)}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y=be_{\beta(y)}$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in A$
\end_inset

, Then 
\begin_inset Formula $x=y$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta(x)=\beta(y)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a=b$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Now, for each 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in G$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathrm{Z}(A)$
\end_inset

, we define
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
g\cdot x=e_{g}xe_{g}^{-1}.\label{eq:welldefinedconjactiononcent}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

In a moment, we will need to show that 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:welldefinedconjactiononcent})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is well-defined, but first let us note that 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{g}xe_{g}^{-1}\in\mathrm{Z}(A)$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in A$
\end_inset

.
 Then since 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is normal in 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{g}^{-1}ae_{g}=a_{g}$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{g}\in A$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
ae_{g}xe_{g}^{-1} & =e_{g}a_{g}xe_{g}^{-1}\\
 & =e_{g}xa_{g}e_{g}\\
 & =e_{g}xe_{g}a.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{g}xe_{g}^{-1}\in\mathrm{Z}(A)$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:welldefinedconjactiononcent})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 at least lands in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Z}(A)$
\end_inset

.
 Now let us show that it is well-defined.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $ae_{g}$
\end_inset

 be another lift of 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset


\series bold
, 
\series default
where 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in A$
\end_inset

.
 Then we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
ae_{g}x(ae_{g})^{-1} & =ae_{g}xe_{g}^{-1}a^{-1}\\
 & =e_{g}xe_{g}^{-1}aa^{-1}\\
 & =e_{g}xe_{g}^{-1},
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where the last equality follows since 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{g}xe_{g}^{-1}\in\mathrm{Z}(A)$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:welldefinedconjactiononcent})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is well-defined.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Finally, let us show that this map is a group action of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\mathrm{Z}}(A)$
\end_inset

.
 Clearly the identity element 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 fixes all of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Z}(A)$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $g,h\in G$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathrm{Z}(A)$
\end_inset

.
 Then there exists a unique 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{g,h}\in A$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
e_{g}e_{h}=a_{g,h}e_{gh}.
\]

\end_inset

Thus we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
g\cdot(h\cdot x) & =g\cdot e_{h}xe_{h}^{-1}\\
 & =e_{g}e_{h}xe_{h}^{-1}e_{g}^{-1}\\
 & =e_{g}e_{h}x(e_{g}e_{h})^{-1}\\
 & =a_{g,h}e_{gh}x(a_{g,h}e_{gh})^{-1}\\
 & =a_{g,h}e_{gh}xe_{gh}^{-1}a_{g,h}^{-1}\\
 & =e_{gh}xe_{gh}^{-1}\\
 & =gh\cdot x
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where the last equality follows from the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $gh\cdot x\in\mathrm{Z}(A)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
\begin_inset Formula $\text{H}^{2}(G,A)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we assume 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is abelian (so 
\begin_inset Formula $A=Z(A)$
\end_inset

) and suppose the section mapping 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{g}$
\end_inset

 was actually a group theoretic section, i.e.
 a set theoretic section that is also a homomorphism.
 Then we would have:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
e_{g}e_{h}=e_{gh}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In general this isn't necessarily true, but since 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

 is a homomorphism, we know that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
e_{g}e_{h}=\alpha_{g,h}e_{gh}
\]

\end_inset

for some unique 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{g,h}\in A$
\end_inset

.
 What can we say about 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{g,h}$
\end_inset

? Well since 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 is a group, the associativity law tells us that on the one hand, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
(e_{g}e_{h})e_{k} & =\alpha_{g,h}e_{gh}e_{k}\\
 & =\alpha_{g,h}\alpha_{gh,k}e_{ghk,}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and on the other hand, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
e_{g}(e_{h}e_{k}) & =e_{g}\alpha_{h,k}e_{hk}\\
 & =e_{g}\alpha_{h,k}e_{g}^{-1}e_{g}e_{hk}\\
 & =g\cdot\alpha_{h,k}\alpha_{g,hk}e_{ghk},
\end{align*}

\end_inset

and so equating the two sides gives us the 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

-cocycle condition:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
g\cdot\alpha_{h,k}\alpha_{g,hk}=\alpha_{g,h}\alpha_{gh,k}.
\]

\end_inset

Thus, we can think of 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 as a map 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha:G\times G\to A$
\end_inset

, denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $(g,h)\mapsto\alpha_{g,h}$
\end_inset

, which satisfies the 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

-cocycle condition 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta\alpha=0$
\end_inset

.
 If we had chosen a differenent section, say 
\begin_inset Formula $g\mapsto\beta_{g}e_{g}$
\end_inset

, then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\beta_{g}e_{g}\beta_{h}e_{h} & =\beta_{g}(g\cdot\beta_{h})e_{g}e_{h}\\
 & =\beta_{g}(g\cdot\beta_{h})\alpha_{g,h}e_{gh},
\end{align*}

\end_inset

or in other words
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
e_{g}e_{h}=(\delta\beta)_{g,h}\alpha_{g,h}e_{gh}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 An automorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi:E\to E$
\end_inset

 which induces the identity on 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and on 
\begin_inset Formula $E/A$
\end_inset

 is of the form 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
ae_{g}\mapsto a\beta_{g}e_{g}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 is a 1-cocycle.
 It is an inner automorphism if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 is a coboundary.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 induces the identity on 
\begin_inset Formula $E/A$
\end_inset

, it must map 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{g}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{g}e_{g}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{g}\in A$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 induces the identity on 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, we must have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varphi(ae_{g})=\varphi(a)\varphi(e_{g})=a\beta_{g}e_{g}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We need to check that 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 is a 1-cocycle, i.e.
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\beta_{gh}=\beta_{g}(g\cdot\beta_{h})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We compute 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(e_{gh})$
\end_inset

 in two ways.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varphi(e_{gh})=\beta_{gh}e_{gh}=\beta_{gh}\alpha_{g,h}e_{g}e_{h}
\]

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 be groups.
 An 
\begin_inset Formula $\textbf{extension}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is a group 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

, together with an exact sequence: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd}  1 
\backslash
arrow[r] & A 
\backslash
arrow[r] & E 
\backslash
arrow[r] & G 
\backslash
arrow[r] & 1 
\backslash
end{tikzcd}
\backslash
