\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 One field of order 
\begin_inset Formula $16=2^{4}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{2}[X]\slash\langle X^{4}+X+1\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 All elements satisfy 
\begin_inset Formula $t^{16}=t$
\end_inset

.
 The solutions to 
\begin_inset Formula $t^{2}=t$
\end_inset

 are the subfield 
\begin_inset Formula $\{0,1\}$
\end_inset

 of order 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

 and the solutions to 
\begin_inset Formula $t^{4}=t$
\end_inset

 are the subfield 
\begin_inset Formula $\{0,1,X^{2}+X,X^{2}+X+1\}$
\end_inset

 of order 
\begin_inset Formula $4$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Describing 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p}$
\end_inset

-Conjugates
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Two elements in a finite field are called 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p}$
\end_inset

-
\series bold
conjugate 
\series default
if they share the same minimal polynomial over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p}$
\end_inset

.
 We will show, after some lemmas about polynomials over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p}$
\end_inset

, that all 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p}$
\end_inset

-conjugates can be obtained from each other by successively taking 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

th powers.
 This is in contrast to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}[X]$
\end_inset

: all the roots of an irreducible polynomial in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}[X]$
\end_inset

 are not generally expressible in terms of a particular root, with 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{3}-2$
\end_inset

 being a typical example.
 (The field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}(\sqrt[3]{2})$
\end_inset

 contains only one root to this polynomial, not all 
\begin_inset Formula $3$
\end_inset

 roots.) 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Irreduciple Polynomial in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p}[X]$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{p^{n}}-X$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theoremirreduciblefinfieldpower}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(X)$
\end_inset

 be irreducible of degree 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p}[X]$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
In 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p}[X]$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(X)\mid(X^{p^{d}}-X)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
For 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq0$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(X)\mid(X^{p^{n}}-X)$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $d\mid n$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 This divisibility in 1 is the same as the congruence 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{p^{d}}\equiv X\mod\pi(X)$
\end_inset

, or equivalently the equation 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{X}^{p^{d}}=\overline{X}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p}[X]\slash(\pi(X))$
\end_inset

.
 Such an equation follows immediately from the Lemmas above, using the field
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p}[X]\slash(\pi(X))$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

To prove 
\begin_inset Formula $(\impliedby)$
\end_inset

 in 2, write 
\begin_inset Formula $n=kd$
\end_inset

.
 Starting with 
\begin_inset Formula $X\equiv X^{p^{d}}\,\mod\pi(X)$
\end_inset

 and applying the 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{d}$
\end_inset

th power to both sides 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 times, we obtain
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
X & \equiv X^{p^{d}}\mod\pi(X)\\
 & \equiv X^{p^{2d}}\mod\pi(X)\\
 & \vdots\\
 & \equiv X^{p^{kd}}\mod\pi(X)\\
 & =X^{p^{n}}\mod\pi(X).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(X)\mid(X^{p^{n}}-X)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p}[X]$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Now we prove 
\begin_inset Formula $(\implies)$
\end_inset

 in 2.
 We assume 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
X^{p^{n}}\equiv X\mod\pi(X)
\]

\end_inset

and we want to show 
\begin_inset Formula $d\mid n$
\end_inset

.
 Write 
\begin_inset Formula $n=dq+r$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq r<d$
\end_inset

.
 We will show 
\begin_inset Formula $r=0$
\end_inset

.
 Observe that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
X & \equiv X^{p^{n}}\mod\pi(X)\\
 & \equiv(X^{p^{dq}})^{p^{r}}\mod\pi(X)\\
 & \equiv X^{p^{r}}\mod\pi(X)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

This tells us that one particular element of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p}[X]\slash(\pi(X))$
\end_inset

, the class of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, is equal to its own 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{r}$
\end_inset

th power.
 More generally, for any 
\begin_inset Formula $f(X)\in\mathbb{F}_{p}[X]$
\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
f(X)^{p^{r}} & \equiv f(X^{p^{r}})\mod\pi(X)\\
 & \equiv f(X)\mod\pi(X).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Therefore in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p}[X]\slash(\pi(X))$
\end_inset

 the congruence class of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(X)$
\end_inset

 is equal to its own 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{r}$
\end_inset

th power.
 As 
\begin_inset Formula $f(X)$
\end_inset

 is a general polynomial in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p}[X]$
\end_inset

, we have proved every element of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p}[X]\slash(\pi(X))$
\end_inset

 is its own 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{r}$
\end_inset

th power (in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p}[X]\slash(\pi(X))$
\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Consider now the polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{p^{r}}-T$
\end_inset

.
 When 
\begin_inset Formula $r>0$
\end_inset

, this is a polynomial with degree 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{r}>1$
\end_inset

, and we have found 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{d}$
\end_inset

 different roots of this polynomial in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p}[X]\slash(\pi(X))$
\end_inset

 (namely, every element of this field is a root).
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{d}\leq p^{r}$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $d\leq r$
\end_inset

.
 But, recalling where 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 came from, 
\begin_inset Formula $r<d$
\end_inset

.
 This is a contradiction, so 
\begin_inset Formula $r=0$
\end_inset

.
 This proves 
\begin_inset Formula $d\mid n$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Roots of an Irreducible 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(X)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p}[X]$
\end_inset

 are all Powers of a Root of 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(X)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorempixcontainsallroots}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(X)$
\end_inset

 be irreducible in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p}[X]$
\end_inset

 with degree 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $F\supseteq\mathbb{F}_{p}$
\end_inset

 be a field which 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(X)$
\end_inset

 has a root, say 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(X)$
\end_inset

 has roots 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha,\alpha^{p},\alpha^{p^{2}},\dots,\alpha^{p^{d-1}}$
\end_inset

.
 These 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 roots are distinct; more precisely, when 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 are nonnegative, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha^{p^{i}}=\alpha^{p^{j}}$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $i\equiv j\mod d$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(X)^{p}=\pi(X^{p})$
\end_inset

, we see 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha^{p}$
\end_inset

 is also a root of 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(X)$
\end_inset

, and likewise, 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha^{p^{2}},\alpha^{p^{3}}$
\end_inset

, and so on by iteration.
 Once we reach 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha^{p^{d}}$
\end_inset

 we have cycled back to the start: 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha^{p^{d}}=\alpha$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Theorem~(
\backslash
ref{theoremirreduciblefinfieldpower})
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Now we will show for 
\begin_inset Formula $i,j\geq0$
\end_inset

 that 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha^{p^{i}}=\alpha^{p^{j}}$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $i\equiv j\mod d$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha^{p^{d}}=\alpha$
\end_inset

, the implication 
\begin_inset Formula $(\impliedby)$
\end_inset

 is straightforward.
 To argue in the other direction, we may suppose without loss of generality
 that 
\begin_inset Formula $i\leq j$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $j=i+k$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $k\geq0$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\alpha^{p^{i}}=\alpha^{p^{i+k}}=(\alpha^{p^{k}})^{p^{i}}.
\]

\end_inset

Applying 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Lemma~(
\backslash
ref{injectiveintdomainfin})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 to this equality 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 times, with 
\begin_inset Formula $A=F$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=\alpha^{p^{k}}$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 is a root of 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{p^{k}}-X$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(X)\mid(X^{p^{k}}-X)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p}[X]$
\end_inset

.
 We conclude 
\begin_inset Formula $d\mid k$
\end_inset

 by the previous Theorem.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(X)$
\end_inset

 has at most 
\begin_inset Formula $d=\deg\pi$
\end_inset

 roots in any field, 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Theorem~(
\backslash
ref{theorempixcontainsallroots})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 tells us 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha,\alpha^{p},\dots,\alpha^{p^{d-1}}$
\end_inset

 are a complete set of roots of 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(X)$
\end_inset

 and these roots are distinct.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{3}+X+1$
\end_inset

 is irreducible in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{2}[X]$
\end_inset

.
 In the field 
\begin_inset Formula $F=\mathbb{F}_{2}[X]\slash(X^{3}+X+1)$
\end_inset

, one root of the polynomial is 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{X}$
\end_inset

.
 The other roots are 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{X}^{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{X}^{4}$
\end_inset

.
 If we wish to write the third root without going beyond the second power
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{X}$
\end_inset

, note 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{4}\equiv X^{2}+X\mod X^{3}+X+1$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore, the roots of 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{3}+X+1$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 are 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{X},\overline{X}^{2}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{X}^{2}+\overline{X}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Galois Groups
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p^{n}}$
\end_inset

 is the splitting field over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p}$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{p^{n}}-X$
\end_inset

, which is separable, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p^{n}}\slash\mathbb{F}_{p}$
\end_inset

 is Galois.
 It is a fundamental feature that the Galois group is cyclic, with a canonical
 generator.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Gal}(\mathbb{F}_{p^{n}}\slash\mathbb{F})$
\end_inset

 is Cyclic with Canonical Generator
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

th power map 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{p}\colon t\mapsto t^{p}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p^{n}}$
\end_inset

 generates 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Gal}(\mathbb{F}_{p^{n}}\slash\mathbb{F}_{p})$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Any 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in\mathbb{F}_{p}$
\end_inset

 satisfies 
\begin_inset Formula $a^{p}=a$
\end_inset

, so the function 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{p}\colon\mathbb{F}_{p^{n}}\to\mathbb{F}_{p^{n}}$
\end_inset

 fixes 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p}$
\end_inset

 pointwise.
 Also 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{p}$
\end_inset

 is a field homomorphism and it is injective, so 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{p}$
\end_inset

 is surjective since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p^{n}}$
\end_inset

 is finite.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{p}\in\mathrm{Gal}(\mathbb{F}_{p^{n}}\slash\mathbb{F}_{p})$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

The size of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Gal}(\mathbb{F}_{p^{n}}\slash\mathbb{F}_{p})$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $[\mathbb{F}_{p^{n}}:\mathbb{F}_{p}]=n$
\end_inset

.
 We will show 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{p}$
\end_inset

 has order 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 in this group, so it generates the Galois group.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $r\geq1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in\mathbb{F}_{p^{n}}$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{p}^{r}(t)=t^{p^{r}}$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{p}^{r}$
\end_inset

 is the identity then 
\begin_inset Formula $t^{p^{r}}=t$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in\mathbb{F}_{p^{n}}$
\end_inset

, which can be rewritten as 
\begin_inset Formula $t^{p^{r}}-t=0$
\end_inset

.
 The polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{p^{r}}-X$
\end_inset

 has degree 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{r}$
\end_inset

 (since 
\begin_inset Formula $r\geq1$
\end_inset

), so it has at most 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{r}$
\end_inset

 roots in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p^{n}}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{n}\leq p^{r}$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $n\leq r$
\end_inset

.
 Hence 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{p}$
\end_inset

 has order at least 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Gal}(\mathbb{F}_{p^{n}}\slash\mathbb{F}_{p})$
\end_inset

, a group of order 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{p}$
\end_inset

 generates the Galois group: every element of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Gal}(\mathbb{F}_{p^{n}}\slash\mathbb{F}_{p})$
\end_inset

 is an iterate of 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{p}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Field Extensions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 be a fields.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $L\supseteq K$
\end_inset

, then we say 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 is a 
\series bold
field extension
\series default
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

.
 We denote such a field extension of 
\begin_inset Formula $L\slash K$
\end_inset

.
 A field 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is an 
\series bold
extension field 
\series default
of a field 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $F\subseteq K$
\end_inset

.
 We denote such a field extension by 
\begin_inset Formula $K\slash F$
\end_inset

.
 In this case, 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is an 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

-vector space.
 We denote the dimension of 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 as an 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

-vector space by 
\begin_inset Formula $[K:F]$
\end_inset

.
 Finally, if 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 is a field with
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
F\subseteq E\subseteq K,
\]

\end_inset

we say 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 is an 
\series bold
intermediate 
\series default
extension field.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{ch}\mathbb{Q}=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{ch}\mathbb{F}_{p}=p$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The characteristic of a field 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 is either 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 or a prime.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{ch}F=0$
\end_inset

 then we are done, so assume 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{ch}F=m$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 is not prime.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $m=ab$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b>1$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $m\cdot1_{F}=(a\cdot1_{F})(b\cdot1_{F})=0$
\end_inset

 implies either 
\begin_inset Formula $(a\cdot1_{F})=0$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $(b\cdot1_{F})=0$
\end_inset

.
 In either case, we get a contradiction since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{ch}F\leq a,b<m$
\end_inset

.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 is prime.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 be a field and define 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi:\mathbb{Z}\to F$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(n)=n\cdot1_{F}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is a ring homomorphism.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}/\mbox{Ker}\varphi\cong\varphi(\mathbb{Z})\subseteq F$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 is a PID, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{Ker}\varphi=m\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $m\geq0$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $p=\mbox{ch}F$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in m\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $m=1$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $m=p$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is prime.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $m=1$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(1)=0$
\end_inset

 which is a contradiction, so 
\begin_inset Formula $m=p$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{Ker}\varphi=p\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p}\cong\mathbb{Z}/p\mathbb{Z}\subseteq F$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{ch}F=0$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}\cong\varphi(\mathbb{Z})\subseteq F$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 contains an isomorphic copy of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

.
 In either case, we call this the 
\series bold
prime subfield 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Field Extension) Let 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 be fields.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 is a subfield of 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 then we say 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is a 
\series bold
field extension 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

, denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $F\subset K$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $K/F$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $F\subseteq K$
\end_inset

 is a field extension, then 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is a vector space over 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

.
 The 
\series bold
degree 
\series default
of the extension 
\begin_inset Formula $K/F$
\end_inset

, denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $[K:F]$
\end_inset

, is the dimension of 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 as an 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

-vector space.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $[\mathbb{R}:\mathbb{R}]=1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $[\mathbb{C}:\mathbb{R}]=2$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

If 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 is a field and 
\begin_inset Formula $p(x)\in F[x]$
\end_inset

 is an irreducible polynomial over 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

, can we find a field 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 containing 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 such that the equation 
\begin_inset Formula $p(x)=0$
\end_inset

 has a solution in 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

? Yes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 be a field and let 
\begin_inset Formula $p(x)\in F[x]$
\end_inset

 be an irreducible polynomial over 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

.
 Then there is a field 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 containing (an isomorphic copy of) 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $p(x)$
\end_inset

 has a root 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in K$
\end_inset

.
 Identifying 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 with this isomorphic copy which is contained in 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

, we'll regard 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 as a field extension of 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $p(x)$
\end_inset

 is irreducible in 
\begin_inset Formula $F[x]$
\end_inset

, which is a PID, 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle p(x)\rangle$
\end_inset

 is a maximal ideal in 
\begin_inset Formula $F[x]$
\end_inset

.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $K:=F[x]/\langle p(x)\rangle$
\end_inset

 is a field.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi:F[x]\to F[x]/\langle p(x)\rangle$
\end_inset

 be the canonical projection map given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(a(x))=\overline{a(x)}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi:=\pi_{_{\mid F}}$
\end_inset

 gives a ring homomorphism from 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $F[x]/\langle p(x)\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 is a field and since 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(1)\neq0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{Ker}\varphi=0$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is injective.
 Finally, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha:=\overline{x}$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
p(\alpha) & =p(\overline{x})\\
 & =\overline{p(x)}\\
 & =\overline{0}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 be a field, 
\begin_inset Formula $p(x)$
\end_inset

 be an irreducible polynomial over 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $K:=F[x]/\langle p(x)\rangle$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha:=\bar{x}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $n=\mbox{deg}p(x)$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\{1,\alpha,\dots,\alpha^{n-1}\}$
\end_inset

 is an 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

-basis of 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, 
\begin_inset Formula $[K:F]=n$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{g(x)}\in K$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 is a field, 
\begin_inset Formula $F[x]$
\end_inset

 is a Euclidean Domain, so there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $q(x),r(x)\in F[x]$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $g(x)=q(x)p(x)+r(x)$
\end_inset

 with either 
\begin_inset Formula $r(x)=0$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{deg}r(x)\leq n-1$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $r(x)=0$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{g(x)}=\bar{0}$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $r(x)\neq0$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $r(x)=c_{0}+c_{1}x+\cdots+c_{\ell}x^{\ell}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell\leq n-1$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\overline{g(x)} & =\overline{q(x)p(x)+r(x)}\\
 & =\overline{r(x)}\\
 & =\overline{c_{0}+c_{1}x+\cdots+c_{\ell}x^{\ell}}\\
 & =c_{0}+c_{1}\alpha+\cdots+c_{\ell}\alpha^{\ell}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $g(x)\in\mbox{Span}\{1,\alpha,\dots,\alpha^{n-1}\}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Next we check that 
\begin_inset Formula $\{1,\alpha,\dots,\alpha^{n-1}\}$
\end_inset

 is linearly independent over 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{0},b_{1},\dots,b_{n-1}\in F$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{0}+b_{1}\alpha+\cdots+b_{n-1}\alpha^{n-1}=\bar{0}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{0}+b_{1}x+\cdots+b_{n-1}x^{n-1}=p(x)q(x)$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $q(x)\in F[x]$
\end_inset

.
 But the degree of 
\begin_inset Formula $p(x)$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, so we must have 
\begin_inset Formula $q(x)=0$
\end_inset

, which implies 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{i}=0$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq i\leq n-1$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Algebraic Extensions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $L\slash K$
\end_inset

 be a field extension.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
An element 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in L$
\end_inset

 is said to be 
\series bold
algebraic 
\series default
over 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 if there exists a nonzero polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)\in K[T]$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\alpha)=0$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in L$
\end_inset

 is not algebraic, then we say it is 
\series bold
transcendental
\series default
 over 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We say 
\begin_inset Formula $L\slash K$
\end_inset

 is an 
\series bold
algebraic extension
\series default
 if every 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in L$
\end_inset

 is algebraic over 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

.
 We say 
\begin_inset Formula $L\slash K$
\end_inset

 is a 
\series bold
transcendental extension 
\series default
if there exists at least one 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in L$
\end_inset

 which is transcendental over 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We say 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
algebraically closed 
\series default
if every irreducible polynomial in 
\begin_inset Formula $L[X]$
\end_inset

 splits completely in 
\begin_inset Formula $L[X]$
\end_inset

.
 We say 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 is an 
\series bold
algebraic closure 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 is algebraically closed and 
\begin_inset Formula $L\slash K$
\end_inset

 is an algebraic extension.

\series bold
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The number 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

 is algebraic over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\pi)=0$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)=T-\pi$
\end_inset

.
 On the other hand, it is a nontrivial theorem that 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

 is transcendental over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The imaginary number 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 is algebraic over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $f(i)=0$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)=T^{2}+1$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $K/F$
\end_inset

 be a field extension.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in K$
\end_inset

 is algebraic over 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

, then there is a unique monic irreducible polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $p(x)\in F[x]$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $p(\alpha)=0$
\end_inset

.
 Moreover, if 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)\in F[x]$
\end_inset

 has 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 as a root, then 
\begin_inset Formula $p(x)\mid f(x)$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $p(x)\in F[x]$
\end_inset

 be a polynomial of minimal degree having 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 as a root.
 We can assume, without loss of generality, that 
\begin_inset Formula $p(x)$
\end_inset

 is monic.
 We show that 
\begin_inset Formula $p(x)$
\end_inset

 is irreducible in 
\begin_inset Formula $F[x]$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose not.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $p(x)=a(x)b(x)$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $a(x),b(x)\in F[x]$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq\mbox{deg}a(x)<\mbox{deg}p(x)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq\mbox{deg}b(x)<\mbox{deg}p(x)$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $0=p(\alpha)=a(\alpha)b(\alpha)$
\end_inset

 implies either 
\begin_inset Formula $a(\alpha)=0$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $b(\alpha)=0$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is a field.
 But this contradicts the minimality of the degree of 
\begin_inset Formula $p(x)$
\end_inset

.
 Next, suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)\in F[x]$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\alpha)=0$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $F[x]$
\end_inset

 is a Euclidean Domain, there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $q(x),r(x)\in F[x]$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=q(x)p(x)+r(x)$
\end_inset

 where either 
\begin_inset Formula $r(x)=0$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{deg}r(x)<\mbox{deg}p(x)$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $r(x)\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $r(\alpha)=f(\alpha)-q(\alpha)p(\alpha)=0$
\end_inset

.
 But this contradicts the minimality of the degree of 
\begin_inset Formula $p(x)$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Recall that if 
\begin_inset Formula $K/F$
\end_inset

 is a field extension, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 is algebraic over 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $F\subseteq F(\alpha)$
\end_inset

 is finite.
 In this case, the degree of the extension 
\begin_inset Formula $[F(\alpha):F]$
\end_inset

 is the degree of the minimal polynomial of 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $F\subseteq K\subseteq L$
\end_inset

 are field extensions, then 
\begin_inset Formula $[L:F]=[L:K][K:F]$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $[K:F]=\ell$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $[L:K]=m$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\alpha_{1},\dots,\alpha_{m}\}$
\end_inset

 be a basis of 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\beta_{1},\dots,\beta_{\ell}\}$
\end_inset

 be a basis of 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\alpha_{1}\beta_{1},\dots,\alpha_{m}\beta_{\ell}\}$
\end_inset

 is a basis for 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Recall that 
\begin_inset Formula $p(x)=x^{3}+3x-1$
\end_inset

 is irreducible over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $p(\pm1)\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 But there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in(0,1)$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $p(\alpha)=0$
\end_inset

.
 Let's show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{2}\notin\mathbb{Q}(\alpha)$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{2}\in\mathbb{Q}(\alpha)$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}\subseteq\mathbb{Q}(\sqrt{2})\subseteq\mathbb{Q}(\alpha)$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $3=[\mathbb{Q}(\alpha):\mathbb{Q}]=[\mathbb{Q}(\alpha):\mathbb{Q}(\sqrt{2})][\mathbb{Q}(\sqrt{2}):\mathbb{Q}]=[\mathbb{Q}(\alpha):\mathbb{Q}(\sqrt{2})]\cdot2$
\end_inset

 which is a contradiction.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $F\subseteq K$
\end_inset

 be a field extension and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{1},\dots,\alpha_{\ell}\in K$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
F(\alpha_{1},\dots,\alpha_{\ell})=F(\alpha_{1})(\alpha_{2},\dots,\alpha_{\ell})=\cdots=F(\alpha_{1})(\alpha_{2})\cdots(\alpha_{\ell}).
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $F\subseteq K$
\end_inset

 be a field extension.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{1},\dots,\alpha_{\ell}\in K$
\end_inset

 are all algebraic over 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $F\subseteq F(\alpha_{1},\dots,\alpha_{\ell})$
\end_inset

 is finite.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{i}=\mbox{deg}m_{\alpha_{i},F}$
\end_inset

.
 We have a sequence of field extensions
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
F\subseteq F(\alpha_{1})\subseteq F(\alpha_{1},\alpha_{2})\subseteq\cdots\subseteq F(\alpha_{1},\alpha_{2},\dots,\alpha_{\ell}).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
[F(\alpha_{1},\alpha_{2},\dots,\alpha_{\ell}):F] & =[F(\alpha_{1},\alpha_{2},\dots,\alpha_{\ell}):F(\alpha_{1})][F(\alpha_{1}):F]\\
 & =[F(\alpha_{1},\alpha_{2},\dots,\alpha_{\ell}):F(\alpha_{1},\alpha_{2})][F(\alpha_{1},\alpha_{2}):F(\alpha_{1})][F(\alpha_{1}):F]\\
 & =[F(\alpha_{1},\alpha_{2},\dots,\alpha_{\ell}):F(\alpha_{1},\alpha_{2},\dots\alpha_{\ell-1})]\cdots[F(\alpha_{1},\alpha_{2}):F(\alpha_{1})][F(\alpha_{1}):F]\\
 & \leq n_{\ell}\cdots n_{2}n_{1}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $F\subseteq K$
\end_inset

 be a field extension.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $F\subseteq K$
\end_inset

 is finite if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $K=F(\alpha_{1},\dots,\alpha_{\ell})$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Constructing Algebraic Closures
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 be a field.
 The purpose of this subsection is to construct an algebraic closure of
 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

.
 Let us first introduce some notation.
 For each 
\begin_inset Formula $k,n\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

 the 
\series bold

\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

th elementary symmetric polynomial in 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 variables 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{1},\dots,X_{n}$
\end_inset


\series default
, denoted 
\series bold

\begin_inset Formula $e_{k}(X_{1},\dots,X_{n})$
\end_inset


\series default
, is defined by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
e_{k}(X_{1},\dots,X_{n})=\begin{cases}
1 & \text{if }k=0\\
\sum_{1\leq i_{1}<\cdots<i_{k}\leq n}X_{i_{1}}\cdots X_{i_{k}} & \text{if }k\leq n\\
0 & \text{if }k>n
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For each nonconstant monic polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $f(X)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[X]$
\end_inset

, write
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(X)=X^{n_{f}}+c_{f,1}X^{n_{f}-1}+\cdots+c_{f,k}X^{n_{f}-k}+\cdots+c_{f,n_{f}}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{f}$
\end_inset

 is the degree of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{f,k}\in K$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq k\leq n_{f}$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{f,1},\dots,t_{f,n_{f}}$
\end_inset

 be independent variables.
 Throughout this section, whenever we write 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $t_{f,k}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, it is understood that 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is a nonconstant monic polynomial in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[X]$
\end_inset

 and that 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq k\leq n_{f}$
\end_inset

.
 For each nonconstant monic polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $f(X)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[X]$
\end_inset

, choose a splitting field of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(X)$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{f,1},\dots,\alpha_{f,n_{f}}$
\end_inset

 be the roots of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(X)$
\end_inset

 in this splitting field.
 Finally, let 
\begin_inset Formula $A=K[\{t_{f,k}\}]$
\end_inset

 be the polynomial ring generated over 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 by indepedent variables doubly indexed by every nonconstant monic 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in K[X]$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq k\leq n_{f}$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 be the ideal in 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 generated by the coefficients of all the difference polynomials
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(X)-\prod_{i=1}^{n_{f}}(X-t_{f,k})\in A[X].
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In other words, 
\begin_inset Formula $I=\langle\{u_{f,k}\}\rangle$
\end_inset

 where
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u_{f,k}:=c_{f,k}-(-1)^{k}e_{k}(t_{f,1},\dots,t_{f,n_{f}})
\]

\end_inset

for each nonconstant monic polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 and for each 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq k\leq n_{f}$
\end_inset

.
 Observe that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u_{f,k}(\alpha_{f,1},\dots,\alpha_{f,n_{f}})=0
\]

\end_inset

for all nonconstant monic polynomials 
\begin_inset Formula $f(X)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[X]$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, we can factor 
\begin_inset Formula $f(X)$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $K(\alpha_{f,1}\dots,\alpha_{f,n_{f}})$
\end_inset

 as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
(X-\alpha_{f,1})\cdots(X-\alpha_{f,n_{f}})-f(X)=X^{n_{f}}+c_{f,1}X^{n_{f}-1}+\cdots+c_{f,n_{f}}.\label{eq:factoraldjklfsd}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Expanding the righthand side of 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:factoraldjklfsd})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 and comparing coefficients gives us the desired result.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\backslash
label{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The ideal 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is proper.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Assume for a contradiction that 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is not proper, so 
\begin_inset Formula $1\in I$
\end_inset

.
 Then we can write 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 as a finite sum
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
1=\sum_{i=1}^{m}v_{i}u_{f_{i},k_{i}}\label{eq:bothsidesofalgejklsdfs}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{i}\in A$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq i\leq m$
\end_inset

.
 Evaluating 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{f_{i},k_{i}}=\alpha_{f_{i},k_{i}}$
\end_inset

 for each 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq i\leq m$
\end_inset

 to both sides of 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:bothsidesofalgejklsdfs})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 gives us 
\begin_inset Formula $1=0$
\end_inset

.
 This is a contradiction.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is a proper ideal, Zorn's Lemma guarantees that 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is contained in some maximal ideal 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 The quotient ring 
\begin_inset Formula $A\slash\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

 is a field and the natural composite homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $K\to A\to A\slash\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

 of rings lets us view the field 
\begin_inset Formula $A\slash\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

 as an extension of 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 since ring homomorphisms out of fields are always injective.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The field 
\begin_inset Formula $A\slash\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

 is an algebraic closure of 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 For each indeterminate 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{f,k}$
\end_inset

, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{t}_{f,k}$
\end_inset

 denote its coset in 
\begin_inset Formula $A\slash\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

.
 Observe that for each nonconstant monic polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $f(X)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[X]$
\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
f(X) & =X^{n_{f}}+\sum_{k=1}^{n_{f}}c_{f,k}X^{n_{f}-k}\\
 & \equiv X^{n_{f}}+\sum_{k=1}^{n_{f}}(-1)^{k}e_{k}(t_{f_{,},1},\dots,t_{f,n_{f}})X^{n_{f}-k}\,\,\mod\mathfrak{m}\\
 & =\prod_{k=1}^{n_{f}}(X-\overline{t}_{f,k}).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

since 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{f,1},\dots,u_{f,n_{f}}\in\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $f(X)$
\end_inset

 splits completely in 
\begin_inset Formula $(A\slash\mathfrak{m})[X]$
\end_inset

, and since 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{t}_{f,k}$
\end_inset

 is a root of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(X)$
\end_inset

, we see that each 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{t}_{f,k}$
\end_inset

 is algebraic over 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

.
 It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $A\slash\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

 is an algebraic extension field of 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $A\slash\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

 is generated by the 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{t}_{f,k}$
\end_inset

's (as 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is generated by the 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{f,k}$
\end_inset

's) and that every nonconstant monic in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[X]$
\end_inset

 splits completely.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

We will now show 
\begin_inset Formula $A\slash\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

 is algebraically closed, and thus it is an algebraic closure of 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

.
 Set 
\begin_inset Formula $F=A\slash\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

.
 It suffices to show every monic irreducible 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(X)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $F[X]$
\end_inset

 has a root in 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

.
 We have already seen that any nonconstant monic polynomial in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[X]$
\end_inset

 splits completely in 
\begin_inset Formula $F[X]$
\end_inset

, so let's show 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(X)$
\end_inset

 is a factor of some monic polynomial in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[X]$
\end_inset

.
 There is a root 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(X)$
\end_inset

 in some extension of 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 is algebraic over 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 is algebraic over 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 is algebraic over 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

.
 That implies some monic 
\begin_inset Formula $f(X)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[X]$
\end_inset

 has 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 as a root.
 The polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(X)$
\end_inset

 is the minimal polynomial of 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $F[X]$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(X)\mid f(X)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $F[X]$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $f(X)$
\end_inset

 splits completely in 
\begin_inset Formula $F[X]$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in F$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Uniqueness of Algebraic Closures
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Throughout this subsection, let 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 be a field and 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{k}\slash k$
\end_inset

 be a choice of an algebraic closure.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\backslash
label{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $L\slash k$
\end_inset

 be an algebraic extension and let 
\begin_inset Formula $L'\slash L$
\end_inset

 be another algebraic extension.
 There is a 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

-embedding 
\begin_inset Formula $i\colon L\hookrightarrow\overline{k}$
\end_inset

, and once 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 is picked there exists a 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

-embedding 
\begin_inset Formula $L'\hookrightarrow\overline{k}$
\end_inset

 extending 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Since an embedding 
\begin_inset Formula $i\colon L\hookrightarrow\overline{k}$
\end_inset

 realizes the algebraically closed 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{k}$
\end_inset

 as an algebraic extension of 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 (and hence as an algebraic closure of 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

), by renaming the base field as 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 it suffices to just prove the first part: any algebraic extension admits
 an embedding into a specified algebraic closure.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Define 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

 to be the set of pairs 
\begin_inset Formula $(k',i)$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $k'\subseteq L$
\end_inset

 is an intermediate extension over 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $i\colon k'\hookrightarrow\overline{k}$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

-embedding.
 Using the inclusion 
\begin_inset Formula $i_{0}\colon k\hookrightarrow\overline{k}$
\end_inset

 that comes along with the data of how 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{k}$
\end_inset

 is realized as an algebraic closure of 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

, we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $(k,i_{0})\in\Sigma$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

 is nonempty.
 We wish to apply Zorn's Lemma, where we define a partial ordering on 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

 by the condition that 
\begin_inset Formula $(k',i')\leq(k'',i'')$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $k'\subseteq k''$
\end_inset

 inside of 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $i''|_{k'}=i'$
\end_inset

.
 It is a simple exercise in gluing set maps to see that the hypothesis of
 Zorn's Lemma is satisfied, so there exists a maximal element 
\begin_inset Formula $(K,i)\in\Sigma$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

We just have to show 
\begin_inset Formula $K=L$
\end_inset

.
 Pick 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in L$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is algebraic over 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 (as it is algebraic over 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

).
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{x}\in K[T]$
\end_inset

 is the minimal polynomial of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $K(x)\cong K[T]\slash f_{x}$
\end_inset

.
 Using 
\begin_inset Formula $i\colon K\hookrightarrow\overline{k}$
\end_inset

 realizes 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{k}$
\end_inset

 as an algebraic closure of 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{x}\in K[T]$
\end_inset

 has a root in 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{k}$
\end_inset

.
 Pick such a root, say 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

, and then we define 
\begin_inset Formula $K[T]\to\overline{k}$
\end_inset

 by using 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 on the coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 and sending 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

.
 This map kills 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{x}$
\end_inset

, and hence factors through the quotient to define a map of fields 
\begin_inset Formula $K[T]\slash f_{x}\hookrightarrow\overline{k}$
\end_inset

 extending 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
 Composing this with the isomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $K(x)\cong K[T]\slash f_{x}$
\end_inset

 therefore defines an element 
\begin_inset Formula $(K(x),i')\in\Sigma$
\end_inset

 which dominates 
\begin_inset Formula $(K,i)$
\end_inset

.
 By maximality, this forces 
\begin_inset Formula $(K(x),i')=(K,i)$
\end_inset

, or in other words 
\begin_inset Formula $K(x)=K$
\end_inset

 as subfields of 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

.
 This holds for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in L$
\end_inset

 and says exactly 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in K$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $L=K$
\end_inset

, as desired.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{k}_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{k}_{2}$
\end_inset

 be two algebraic closures of 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

.
 Then there exists an isomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{k}_{1}\cong\overline{k}_{2}$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 By the lemma, applied to 
\begin_inset Formula $L=\overline{k}_{1}$
\end_inset

 (algebraic over 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

) and 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{k}=\overline{k}_{2}$
\end_inset

 (an algebraically closed field equipped with a structure of algebraic extension
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

), there exists a 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

-embedding 
\begin_inset Formula $i\colon\overline{k}_{1}\hookrightarrow\overline{k}_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{k}_{1}$
\end_inset

 is algebraic over 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{k}_{2}$
\end_inset

 is algebraically closed, it follows that the 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

-embedding 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 realizes 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{k}_{2}$
\end_inset

 as an algebraic extension of 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{k}_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 But an algebraically closed field (such as 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{k}_{1}$
\end_inset

) admits no non-trivial algebraic extensions, so the map 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 is forced to be an isomorphism.
 More concretely, any 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in\overline{k}_{2}$
\end_inset

 is a root of an irreducible monic 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in k[T]$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $f=\prod(T-r_{j})$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{k}_{1}[T]$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{k}_{1}$
\end_inset

 is algebraically closed, so applying 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 shows that 
\begin_inset Formula $i(r_{j})$
\end_inset

's exhaust the roots of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{k}_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, 
\begin_inset Formula $y=i(r_{j})$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

, so indeed 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 is surjective.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Beware that the isomorphism in the theorem is nearly always highly non-unique
 (it can be composed with any 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

-automorphism of 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{k}_{2}$
\end_inset

, of which there are many in general).
 Thus, one should 
\emph on
never 
\emph default
write 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{k}_{1}=\overline{k}_{2}$
\end_inset

; 
\emph on
always 
\emph default
keep track of the choice of isomorphism.
 In particular, always speak of 
\emph on
an 
\emph default
algebraic closure rather than 
\emph on
the 
\emph default
algebraic closure; there is no 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

preferred
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 algebraic closure except in cases when there are no non-trivial automorphisms
 over 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 (which happens for fields which have the property of being 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

separably closed
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Splitting Fields
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is a field and 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)\in K[T]$
\end_inset

 is nonconstant, there is a field extension 
\begin_inset Formula $K'\slash K$
\end_inset

 in which 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)$
\end_inset

 picks up a root, say 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)=(T-\alpha)g(T)$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $g(T)\in K'[T]$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\deg g=\deg f-1$
\end_inset

.
 By applying the same process to 
\begin_inset Formula $g(T)$
\end_inset

 and continuing in this way finitely many times, we reach an extension 
\begin_inset Formula $L\slash K$
\end_inset

 in which 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)$
\end_inset

 splits into linear factors: in 
\begin_inset Formula $L[T]$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(T)=c(T-\alpha_{1})\cdots(T-\alpha_{n}).
\]

\end_inset

We call the field 
\begin_inset Formula $K(\alpha_{1},\dots,\alpha_{n})$
\end_inset

 that is generated by the roots of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 a 
\series bold
splitting field of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset


\series default
.
 The idea is that in a splitting field we can find a full set of roots of
 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)$
\end_inset

 and 
\emph on
no smaller field extension of 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 
\emph default
has that property.
 Let's look at some examples.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The polynomials 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{2}+3T-2$
\end_inset

 does not split over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

, but it does split over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}(\sqrt{17})$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
T^{2}+3T-2=\left(T-\frac{-3+\sqrt{17}}{2}\right)\left(T-\frac{-3-\sqrt{17}}{2}\right).
\]

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}(\sqrt{17})$
\end_inset

 is the smallest field which contains the roots 
\begin_inset Formula $(-3+\sqrt{17})/2$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(-3-\sqrt{17})/2$
\end_inset

, it must be a splitting field for 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{2}+3T-2$
\end_inset

.
 The polynomial also splits over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

, but 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 is not a splitting field for 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{2}+3T-2$
\end_inset

 .
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A splitting field of 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{2}+1$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}(i,-i)=\mathbb{C}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A splitting field of 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{2}-2$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}(\sqrt{2})$
\end_inset

, since we pick up two roots 
\begin_inset Formula $\pm\sqrt{2}$
\end_inset

 in the field generated by just one of the roots.
 A splitting field of 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{2}-2$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{2}-2$
\end_inset

 splits into linear factors in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}[T]$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 In 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{C}[T]$
\end_inset

, a factorization of 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{4}-2$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $(T-\sqrt[4]{2})(T+\sqrt[4]{2})(T-i\sqrt[4]{2})(T+i\sqrt[4]{2})$
\end_inset

.
 A splitting field of 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{4}-2$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbb{Q}(\sqrt[4]{2},i\sqrt[4]{2})=\mathbb{Q}(\sqrt[4]{2},i).
\]

\end_inset

In the second description one of the field generators is not a root of the
 original polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{4}-2$
\end_inset

.
 This is a simpler way of writing the splitting field.
 A splitting field of 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{4}-2$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}(\sqrt[4]{2},i\sqrt[4]{2})=\mathbb{C}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

These examples illustrate that, as with irreducibility, the choice of base
 field is an important part of determining the splitting field.
 Over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{4}-2$
\end_inset

 has a splitting field that is an extension of degree 
\begin_inset Formula $8$
\end_inset

, while over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 the splitting field of the same polynomial is an extension (of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

!) of degree 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theoremsplittingfield}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 be a field and 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)$
\end_inset

 be nonconstant in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[T]$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $L'$
\end_inset

 are splitting fields of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $[L:K]=[L':K]$
\end_inset

, there is a field isomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $L\to L'$
\end_inset

 fixing all of 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

, and the number of such isomorphisms 
\begin_inset Formula $L\to L'$
\end_inset

 is at most 
\begin_inset Formula $[L:K]$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Every splitting field of 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{4}-2$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

 has degree 
\begin_inset Formula $8$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

 and is isomorphism to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}(\sqrt[4]{2},i)$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Every splitting field of 
\begin_inset Formula $(T^{2}-2)(T^{2}-3)$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

 has degree 
\begin_inset Formula $4$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

 and is isomorphic to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}(\sqrt{2},\sqrt{3})$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Homomorphisms on Polynomial Coefficients
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To prove 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Theorem~(
\backslash
ref{theoremsplittingfield})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 we will use an inductive argument involving homomorphisms between polynomial
 rings.
 Any field homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma\colon F\to F'$
\end_inset

 extends to a ring homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma\colon F[T]\to F'[T]$
\end_inset

 as follows: for 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)=\sum_{i=0}^{n}c_{i}T^{i}\in F[T]$
\end_inset

, set 
\begin_inset Formula $(\sigma f)(T)=\sum_{i=0}^{n}\sigma(c_{i})T^{i}\in F'[T]$
\end_inset

.
 We call this map 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

applying 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 to the coefficients.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 Writing 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)=c_{n}T^{n}+c_{n-1}T^{n-1}+\cdots+c_{1}T+c_{0}$
\end_inset

, with 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{i}\in F$
\end_inset

, for 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in F$
\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\sigma(f(\alpha)) & =\sigma(c_{n}\alpha^{n}+c_{n-1}\alpha^{n-1}+\cdots+c_{1}\alpha+c_{0})\\
 & =\sigma(c_{n})\sigma(\alpha)^{n}+\sigma(c_{n-1})\sigma(\alpha)^{n-1}+\cdots+\sigma(c_{1})\sigma(\alpha)+\sigma(c_{0})\\
 & =(\sigma f)(\sigma(\alpha)).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

In particular, if 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\alpha)=0$
\end_inset

, then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
(\sigma f)(\sigma(\alpha)) & =\sigma(f(\alpha))\\
 & =\sigma(0)\\
 & =0,
\end{align*}

\end_inset

so 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 sends any root of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 to a root of 
\begin_inset Formula $(\sigma f)(T)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $F'$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Proof of the Theorem
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Rather than prove 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Theorem~(
\backslash
ref{theoremsplittingfield})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 directly, we formula a more general theorem.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma\colon K\to K'$
\end_inset

 be an isomorphism of fields, 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)\in K[T]$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 be a splitting field of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $L'$
\end_inset

 be a splitting field of 
\begin_inset Formula $(\sigma f)(T)$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $K'$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $[L:K]=[L':K']$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 extends to an isomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $L\to L'$
\end_inset

 and the number of such extensions is at most 
\begin_inset Formula $[L:K]$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd} L 
\backslash
arrow[r,dashed] & L' 
\backslash

\backslash
 K  
\backslash
arrow[r,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\backslash
sigma 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

] 
\backslash
arrow[u,dash]  & K' 
\backslash
arrow[u,dash] 
\backslash
end{tikzcd}
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We argue by induction on 
\begin_inset Formula $[L:K]$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $[L:K]=1$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)$
\end_inset

 splits completely in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[T]$
\end_inset

 so 
\begin_inset Formula $(\sigma f)(T)$
\end_inset

 splits completely in 
\begin_inset Formula $K'[T]$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $L'=K'$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $[L':K']=1$
\end_inset

.
 The only extension of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 in this case is 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

, so the number of extensions of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 is at most 
\begin_inset Formula $1=[L:K]$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $[L:K]>1$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 is generated as a field over 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 by the roots of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)$
\end_inset

 has a root 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in L$
\end_inset

 that is not in 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

.
 Fix this 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 for the rest of the proof.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(T)$
\end_inset

 be the minimal polynomial of 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 is a root of 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(T)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(T)\mid f(T)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[T]$
\end_inset

.
 If there's an isomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\sigma}\colon L\to L'$
\end_inset

 extending 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\sigma}(\alpha)$
\end_inset

 is a root of 
\begin_inset Formula $(\sigma\pi)(T)$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
(\sigma\pi)(\widetilde{\sigma}(\alpha)) & =(\widetilde{\sigma}\pi)(\widetilde{\sigma}(\alpha))\\
 & =\widetilde{\sigma}(\pi(\alpha))\\
 & =\widetilde{\sigma}(0)\\
 & =0,
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where the first equality comes from 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(T)$
\end_inset

 having coefficients in 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 (so 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\sigma}=\sigma$
\end_inset

 on those coefficients).
 Therefore the values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\sigma}(\alpha)$
\end_inset

 - to be determined - must come from roots of 
\begin_inset Formula $(\sigma\pi)(T)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Now we show 
\begin_inset Formula $(\sigma\pi)(T)$
\end_inset

 has a root in 
\begin_inset Formula $L'$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma\colon K\to K'$
\end_inset

 is an isomorphism, applying 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 to coefficients is a ring isomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $K[T]\to K'[T]$
\end_inset

 (the inverse applies 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma^{-1}$
\end_inset

 to coefficients in 
\begin_inset Formula $K'[T]$
\end_inset

), so 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(T)\mid f(T)$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $(\sigma\pi)(T)\mid(\sigma f)(T)$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(T)$
\end_inset

 is monic irreducible, 
\begin_inset Formula $(\sigma\pi)(T)$
\end_inset

 is monic irreducible (ring isomorphisms preserve irreducibility).
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $(\sigma f)(T)$
\end_inset

 splits completely in 
\begin_inset Formula $L'[T]$
\end_inset

 by the definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $L'$
\end_inset

, its factor 
\begin_inset Formula $(\sigma\pi)(T)$
\end_inset

 splits completely in 
\begin_inset Formula $L'[T]$
\end_inset

.
 Pick a root 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha'\in L'$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $(\sigma\pi)(T)$
\end_inset

.
 Set 
\begin_inset Formula $d=\deg\pi(T)=\deg(\sigma\pi)(T)$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $d>1$
\end_inset

 (since 
\begin_inset Formula $d=[K(\alpha):K]>1$
\end_inset

).
 This information is in the diagram below, and there are at most 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 choices for 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha'$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $L'$
\end_inset

.
 The minimal polynomials of 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha'$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $K'$
\end_inset

 (resp.) are 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(T)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(\sigma\pi)(T)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd} L 
\backslash
arrow[r, dashed] & L' 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash

\backslash

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

K(
\backslash
alpha ) 
\backslash
arrow[r,dashed] 
\backslash
arrow[u,dash] & K' (
\backslash
alpha ') 
\backslash
arrow[u, dash] 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash

\backslash

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

K 
\backslash
arrow[u,dash,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

d
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

] 
\backslash
arrow[r,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\backslash
sigma 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

] & K' 
\backslash
arrow[u,dash,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

d
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

,swap]  
\backslash
end{tikzcd}
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

There is a 
\emph on
unique 
\emph default
extension of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma\colon K\to K'$
\end_inset

 to a field isomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $K(\alpha)\to K'(\alpha')$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\mapsto\alpha'$
\end_inset

.
 First we show uniqueness.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma'\colon K(\alpha)\to K'(\alpha')$
\end_inset

 extends 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma'(\alpha)=\alpha'$
\end_inset

 , then the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma'$
\end_inset

 is determined everywhere on 
\begin_inset Formula $K(\alpha)$
\end_inset

 because 
\begin_inset Formula $K(\alpha)=K[\alpha]$
\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\sigma'\left(\sum_{i=0}^{m}c_{i}\alpha^{i}\right) & =\sum_{i=0}^{m}\sigma'(c_{i})(\sigma'(\alpha))^{i}\\
 & =\sum_{i=0}^{m}\sigma(c_{i})\alpha'^{i}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

In other words, a 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

-polynomial in 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 goes to the corresponding 
\begin_inset Formula $K'$
\end_inset

-polynomial in 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha'$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 is applied to the coefficients.
 Thus there is at most one 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma'$
\end_inset

 extending 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma'(\alpha)=\alpha'$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

To prove 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma'$
\end_inset

 exists, we will build an isomorphism from 
\begin_inset Formula $K(\alpha)$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $K'(\alpha')$
\end_inset

 with the desired behavior on 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

.
 Any element of 
\begin_inset Formula $K(\alpha)$
\end_inset

 can be written as 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\alpha)$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)\in K[T]$
\end_inset

.
 It can be like this for more than one polynomial: perhaps 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\alpha)=g(\alpha)$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $g(T)\in K[T]$
\end_inset

.
 In that case 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)\equiv g(T)\text{ mod }\pi(T)$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)=g(T)+\pi(T)h(T)$
\end_inset

.
 Applying 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 to coefficients on both sides, which is a ring homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $K[T]\to K'[T]$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $(\sigma f)(T)=(\sigma g)(T)+(\sigma\pi)(T)(\sigma h)(T)$
\end_inset

, and setting 
\begin_inset Formula $T=\alpha'$
\end_inset

 kills off the second term, leaving us with 
\begin_inset Formula $(\sigma f)(\alpha')=(\sigma g)(\alpha')$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore it is 
\emph on
well-defined 
\emph default
to set 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma'\colon K(\alpha)\to K'(\alpha')$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\alpha)\mapsto(\sigma f)(\alpha')$
\end_inset

.
 This function is 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 and sends 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha'$
\end_inset

.
 Since applying 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 to coefficients is a ring homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $K[T]\to K'[T]$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma'$
\end_inset

 is a field homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $K(\alpha)\to K'(\alpha')$
\end_inset

.
 For example, if 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $K(\alpha)$
\end_inset

 are written as 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\alpha)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\alpha)$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $xy=f(\alpha)g(\alpha)=(fg)(\alpha)$
\end_inset

 (evaluation at 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 is multiplicative) so
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\sigma'(xy) & =\sigma(fg)(\alpha')\\
 & =((\sigma f)(\sigma g))(\alpha')\\
 & =(\sigma f)(\alpha')(\sigma g)(\alpha')\\
 & =\sigma'(x)\sigma'(y).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Using 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma^{-1}\colon K'\to K$
\end_inset

 to go the other way shows 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma'$
\end_inset

 is a field isomorphism.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Place 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma'$
\end_inset

 in the field diagram below
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd} L 
\backslash
arrow[r, dashed] & L' 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash

\backslash

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

K(
\backslash
alpha ) 
\backslash
arrow[r,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\backslash
sigma '
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

] 
\backslash
arrow[u,dash] & K' (
\backslash
alpha ') 
\backslash
arrow[u, dash] 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash

\backslash

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

K 
\backslash
arrow[u,dash,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

d
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

] 
\backslash
arrow[r,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\backslash
sigma 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

] & K' 
\backslash
arrow[u,dash,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

d
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

,swap]  
\backslash
end{tikzcd}
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Now we can finally induct on degrees of splitting fields.
 Take as new base fields 
\begin_inset Formula $K(\alpha)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $K'(\alpha')$
\end_inset

, which are isomorphic by 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma'$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 is a splitting field of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

, it's also a splitting field of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)$
\end_inset

 over the larger field 
\begin_inset Formula $K(\alpha)$
\end_inset

.
 Similarly 
\begin_inset Formula $L'$
\end_inset

 is a splitting field of 
\begin_inset Formula $(\sigma f)(T)$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $K'$
\end_inset

 and thus also over the larger field 
\begin_inset Formula $K'(\alpha')$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)$
\end_inset

 has its coefficients in 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma'=\sigma$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $(\sigma'f)(T)=(\sigma f)(T)$
\end_inset

.
 So the top square in the above diagram is like the square in the theorem
 itself, except the splitting field degrees dropped: since 
\begin_inset Formula $d>1$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
[L:K(\alpha)]=\frac{[L:K]}{d}<[L:K].
\]

\end_inset

By induction, 
\begin_inset Formula $[L:K(\alpha)]=[L':K'(\alpha')]$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma'$
\end_inset

 has an extension to a field isomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $L\to L'$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma'$
\end_inset

 extends 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 itself has an extension to an isomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $L\to L'$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
[L:K] & =[L:K(\alpha)]d\\
 & =[L':K'(\alpha')]d\\
 & =[L':K'].
\end{align*}

\end_inset

(If the proof started with 
\begin_inset Formula $K'=K$
\end_inset

, it would usually be false that 
\begin_inset Formula $K(\alpha)=K'(\alpha')$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Theorem~(
\backslash
ref{theoremsplittingfield})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is not directly accessible to our inductive proof.) 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

It remains to show 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 has at most 
\begin_inset Formula $[L:K]$
\end_inset

 extensions to an isomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $L\to L'$
\end_inset

.
 First we show every isomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\sigma}\colon L\to L'$
\end_inset

 extending 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 is the extension of some intermediate isomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma'$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $K(\alpha)$
\end_inset

 with a subfield of 
\begin_inset Formula $L'$
\end_inset

.
 From the start of the proof, 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\sigma}(\alpha)$
\end_inset

 must be a root of 
\begin_inset Formula $(\sigma\pi)(T)$
\end_inset

.
 Define 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha':=\widetilde{\sigma}(\alpha)$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\sigma}|_{K}=\sigma$
\end_inset

, the restriction 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\sigma}|_{K(\alpha)}$
\end_inset

 is a field homomorphism that is 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 and sends 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha'$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\sigma}|_{K(\alpha)}$
\end_inset

 is an isomorphism from 
\begin_inset Formula $K(\alpha)$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $K'(\widetilde{\sigma}(\alpha))=K'(\alpha')$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\sigma}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 is a lift of the intermediate field isomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma':=\widetilde{\sigma}|_{K(\alpha)}.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd} L 
\backslash
arrow[r, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\backslash
widetilde{
\backslash
sigma }
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

] & L' 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash

\backslash

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

K(
\backslash
alpha ) 
\backslash
arrow[r,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\backslash
sigma '
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

] 
\backslash
arrow[u,dash] & K' (
\backslash
alpha ') 
\backslash
arrow[u, dash] 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash

\backslash

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

K 
\backslash
arrow[u,dash,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

d
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

] 
\backslash
arrow[r,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\backslash
sigma 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

] & K' 
\backslash
arrow[u,dash,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

d
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

,swap]  
\backslash
end{tikzcd}
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

By induction on degrees of splitting fields, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma'$
\end_inset

 lifts to at most 
\begin_inset Formula $[L:K(\alpha)]$
\end_inset

 isomorphisms 
\begin_inset Formula $L\to L'$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma'$
\end_inset

 is determined by 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma'(\alpha)$
\end_inset

, which is a root of 
\begin_inset Formula $(\sigma\pi)(T)$
\end_inset

, the number of maps 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma'$
\end_inset

 is at most 
\begin_inset Formula $\deg(\sigma\pi)(T)=d$
\end_inset

.
 The number of isomorphisms 
\begin_inset Formula $L\to L'$
\end_inset

 that lift 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 is the number of homomorphisms 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma'\colon K(\alpha)\to L'$
\end_inset

 lifting 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 times the number of extensions of each 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma'$
\end_inset

 to an isomoprhism 
\begin_inset Formula $L\to L'$
\end_inset

, and that total is at most 
\begin_inset Formula $d[L:K(\alpha)]=[L:K]$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Separability
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defnseparability}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 be a field.
 We have the following definitions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)$
\end_inset

 be a nonzero polynomial over 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
We say 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
separable 
\series default
when it has distinct roots in a splitting field over 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

.
 That is, each root of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)$
\end_inset

 has multiplicity 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)$
\end_inset

 has a multiple root, then 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)$
\end_inset

 is called 
\series bold
inseparable
\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We say 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
purely inseparable 
\series default
if it has the form 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{p^{d}}-c$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $d\geq0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in K$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 be an algebraic number over 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
We say 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
separable over 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 
\series default
when its minimal polynomial over 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is separable.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If the minimal polynomial of 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 is inseperable over 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

, then we say 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
inseperable over 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset


\series default
.
 Note that if 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in L$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $L\slash K$
\end_inset

 is a field extension, then the minimal polynomial of 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 is simply 
\begin_inset Formula $T-\alpha$
\end_inset

, which is clearly separable.
 Thus we really do need the qualifier 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

over 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in this definition.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We say 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
purely inseperable 
\series default
if its minimal polynomial over 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is purely inseparable.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $L\slash K$
\end_inset

 be an algebraic field extension.
 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
We say 
\begin_inset Formula $L\slash K$
\end_inset

 is a 
\series bold
separable 
\series default
field extension if every 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in L$
\end_inset

 is separable over 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We say 
\begin_inset Formula $L\slash K$
\end_inset

 is an 
\series bold
inseparable 
\series default
field extension if there exists one 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in L$
\end_inset

 which is inseparable over 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We say 
\begin_inset Formula $L\slash K$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
purely inseparable 
\series default
if every 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in L$
\end_inset

 is purely inseperable.
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 In 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}[T]$
\end_inset

, the polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{2}-T$
\end_inset

 is separable since its roots are 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{3}-2$
\end_inset

 is separable since there are 
\begin_inset Formula $3$
\end_inset

 different cube roots of 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

 in the complex numbers.
 In 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{3}[T]$
\end_inset

 the polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{3}-2$
\end_inset

 is inseparable because
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
T^{3}-2=(T+1)^{3}
\]

\end_inset

in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{3}[T]$
\end_inset

, so it has a triple root.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Separable Polynomials
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Definition~(
\backslash
ref{defnseparability})
\end_layout

\end_inset

, checking a polynomial is separable requires building a splitting field
 to check the roots are distinct.
 It turns out however that there is a criterion for deciding a polynomial
 is separable (that is, having no multiple roots) without having to work
 in a splitting field.
 Indeed, we can use differentiation in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[T]$
\end_inset

 to describe the separability condition without leaving 
\begin_inset Formula $K[T]$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Criterion for Nonzero Polynomial to be Separable
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{firstcriterionseparability}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A nonzero polynomial in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[T]$
\end_inset

 is separable if and only if it is relatively prime to its derivative in
 
\begin_inset Formula $K[T]$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)$
\end_inset

 be a nonzero polynomial in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[T]$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)$
\end_inset

 is separable, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 be any root of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)$
\end_inset

 (in some extension of 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

).
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(T)=(T-\alpha)h(T)
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $h(T)\in K[T]$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $h(\alpha)\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 Since
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
f'(\alpha) & =h(\alpha)+(\alpha-\alpha)h'(\alpha)\\
 & =h(\alpha)\\
 & \neq0,
\end{align*}

\end_inset

we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 is not a root of 
\begin_inset Formula $f'(T)$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f'(T)$
\end_inset

 have no common roots, so they have no common factors in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[T]$
\end_inset

: they are relatively prime.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Now suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)$
\end_inset

 is not separable, so by definition it has a repeated root (in a splitting
 field over 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

).
 This root is also a root of 
\begin_inset Formula $f'(T)$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, when 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)=(T-\alpha)^{2}g(T)$
\end_inset

, the product rule shows
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f'(T)=(T-\alpha)^{2}g'(T)+2(T-\alpha)g(T),
\]

\end_inset

so 
\begin_inset Formula $f'(\alpha)=0$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f'(T)$
\end_inset

 have 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 as a common root, they are both divisible by the minimal polynomial of
 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[T]$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f'(T)$
\end_inset

 are not relatively prime in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[T]$
\end_inset

.
 Taking the contrapositive, if 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f'(T)$
\end_inset

 are relatively prime in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[T]$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)$
\end_inset

 has no repeated root so it is separable.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

When we are given a specific 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)$
\end_inset

, whether or not 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f'(T)$
\end_inset

 are relatively prime can be checked by Euclid's algorithm for polynomials.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 In 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{3}[T]$
\end_inset

, let 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)=T^{6}+T^{5}+T^{4}+2T^{3}+2T^{2}+T+2$
\end_inset

.
 Using Euclid's algorithm in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{3}[T]$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f'(T)$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
f(T) & =f'(T)(2T^{2}+T)+(2T^{2}+2)\\
f'(T) & =(2T^{2}+2)(T^{2}+2T+2),
\end{align*}

\end_inset

so 
\begin_inset Formula $(f(T),f'(T))=2T^{2}+2$
\end_inset

.
 The greatest common divisor is nonconstant, so 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)$
\end_inset

 is inseparable.
 In fact, 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)=(T^{2}+1)^{2}(T^{2}+T+2)$
\end_inset

.
 Notice we were able to detect that 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)$
\end_inset

 has a repeated root 
\emph on
before 
\emph default
we gave its factorization.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)=T^{n}-a$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in K^{\times}$
\end_inset

.
 The derivative of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $nT^{n-1}$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $n=0$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $f'(T)=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(f(T),f'(T))=f(T)$
\end_inset

 is nonconstant, so 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{n}-a$
\end_inset

 is inseparable.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $n\neq0$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $f'(T)\neq0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(T^{n}-a,nT^{n-1})=1$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 doesn't divide 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{n}-a$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{n}-a$
\end_inset

 is separable in over 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $n\neq0$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Criterion for Irreducible Polynomial to be Separable
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 For any field 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

, an irreducible polynomial over 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is separable if and only if its derivative if not 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, when 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 has characteristic 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 every irreducible over 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is separable and when 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 has characteristic 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, an irreducible over 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is separable if and only if it is not a polynomial in 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{p}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(T)$
\end_inset

 be irreducible over 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

.
 Separability is equivalent to 
\begin_inset Formula $(\pi(T),\pi'(T))=1$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Theorem~(
\backslash
ref{firstcriterionseparability})
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(T)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi'(T)$
\end_inset

 are not relatively prime, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(T)\mid\pi'(T)$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(T)$
\end_inset

 is irreducible.
 Taking the derivative drops degrees, so having 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi'(T)$
\end_inset

 be divisible by 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(T)$
\end_inset

 forces 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi'(T)=0$
\end_inset

.
 Conversely, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi'(T)=0$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $(\pi(T),\pi'(T))=\pi(T)$
\end_inset

 is nonconstant, so 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(T)$
\end_inset

 is inseparable by 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Theorem~(
\backslash
ref{firstcriterionseparability})
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Thus separability of 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(T)$
\end_inset

 is equivalent to 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi'(T)\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

When 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 has characteristic 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

, every irreducible over 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 has nonzero derivative since any nonconstant polynomial has nonzero derivative.
 So all irreducibles over 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 are separable.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Now suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 has characteristic 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 If there is an irreducible 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(T)$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 that is not separable, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi'(T)=0$
\end_inset

.
 Writing 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\pi(T)=T^{n}+c_{n-1}T^{n-1}+\cdots+c_{1}T+c_{0},
\]

\end_inset

the condition 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi'(T)=0$
\end_inset

 means 
\begin_inset Formula $ic_{i}=0$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq i\leq n$
\end_inset

.
 This implies 
\begin_inset Formula $p\mid i$
\end_inset

 whenever 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{i}\neq0$
\end_inset

, so the only nonzero terms in 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(T)$
\end_inset

 occur in degrees divisible by 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, 
\begin_inset Formula $n=\deg\pi$
\end_inset

 is a multiple of 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, say 
\begin_inset Formula $n=pm$
\end_inset

.
 Write each exponent of a nonzero term in 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(T)$
\end_inset

 as a multiple of 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\pi(T)=T^{pm}+c_{p(m-1)}T^{p(m-1)}+\cdots+c_{p}T^{p}+c_{0}=g(T^{p})
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $g(T)\in K[T]$
\end_inset

.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(T)\in K[T^{p}]$
\end_inset

.
 Conversely, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(T)=g(T^{p})$
\end_inset

 is a polynomial in 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{p}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi'(T)=g'(T^{p})pT^{p-1}=0$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(T)$
\end_inset

 is inseparable if it is irreducible in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[T]$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $K=\mathbb{F}_{3}(u)$
\end_inset

 be a rational function field over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{3}$
\end_inset

.
 The polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{7}+u^{2}T^{5}+u\in K[T]$
\end_inset

 is irreducible by Eisenstein's criterion.
 It is also separable since it is irreducible and its derivative 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{6}+2u^{2}T^{4}$
\end_inset

 is nonzero.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Multiplicities for Inseparable Irreducible Polynomials
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When a polynomial is inseparable, at least one of its roots has multiplicity
 greater than 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

.
 The multiplicities of all the roots need not agree.
 For example, 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{2}(X-1)^{3}=0$
\end_inset

 has 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 as a root with multiplicity 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 as a root with multiplicity 
\begin_inset Formula $3$
\end_inset

.
 This polynomial is reducible, so it is a dull example.
 When an inseparable polynomial is 
\emph on
irreducible
\emph default
, which can only happen in positive characteristic, it is natural to ask
 how the multiplicities of different roots are related to each other.
 In fact, the multiplicities are all the same:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(X)\in K[X]$
\end_inset

 be irreducible, where 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 has characteristic 
\begin_inset Formula $p>0$
\end_inset

.
 Write 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(X)=\widetilde{\pi}(X^{p^{m}})$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $m\geq0$
\end_inset

 is as large as possible.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\pi}(X)$
\end_inset

 is irreducible and separable in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[X]$
\end_inset

, and each root of 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(X)$
\end_inset

 has multiplicity 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{m}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\deg\pi=p^{m}\deg\widetilde{\pi}$
\end_inset

, there is a largest possible 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 that can be used.
 Writing 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(X)=\widetilde{\pi}(X^{p^{m}})$
\end_inset

, any nontrivial factorization of 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\pi}(X)$
\end_inset

 gives one for 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(X)$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\pi}(X)=f(X)g(X)$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(X)=f(X^{p^{m}})g(X^{p^{m}})$
\end_inset

), so 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\pi}(X)$
\end_inset

 is irreducible in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[X]$
\end_inset

.
 By the maximality of 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

, we se that 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\pi}(X)$
\end_inset

 is not a polynomial in 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{p}$
\end_inset

, which means its derivative is not 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

, so it must be separable.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Factor 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\pi}(X)$
\end_inset

 in a splitting field over 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

, say
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\widetilde{\pi}(X)=c(X-\alpha_{1})\cdots(X-\alpha_{d}),
\]

\end_inset

where the 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{i}$
\end_inset

's are distinct since 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\pi}(X)$
\end_inset

 is separable.
 Then observe that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\pi(X) & =\widetilde{\pi}(X)\\
 & =c(X^{p^{m}}-\alpha_{1})\cdots(X^{p^{m}}-\alpha_{d}),
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{i}=\gamma_{i}^{p^{m}}$
\end_inset

 in a large enough field.
 Since the 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

th power map is injective in characteristic 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, distinctness of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{i}$
\end_inset

's implies distinctness of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{i}$
\end_inset

's.
 Therefore
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\pi(X) & =c(X^{p^{m}}-\alpha_{1})\cdots(X^{p^{m}}-\alpha_{d})\\
 & =c(X^{p^{m}}-\gamma_{1}^{p^{m}})\cdots(X^{p^{m}}-\gamma_{d}^{p^{m}}),\\
 & =c(X-\gamma_{1})^{p^{m}}\cdots(X-\gamma_{d})^{p^{m}},
\end{align*}

\end_inset

which shows the roots of 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(X)$
\end_inset

 (the 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{i}$
\end_inset

's) are the 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{m}$
\end_inset

th roots of the roots of 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\pi}(X)$
\end_inset

 (the 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{i}$
\end_inset

's), and each root of 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(X)$
\end_inset

 has multiplicity 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{m}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Separable Extensions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $L\slash K$
\end_inset

 be a finite extension of fields with 
\begin_inset Formula $[L:K]=n$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma\colon K\to F$
\end_inset

 a field embedding.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
label{diagram}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd} L 
\backslash
arrow[dd, dash, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

n
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

,swap] 
\backslash
arrow[dr,dashed]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash

\backslash

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

& F 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash

\backslash

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

K 
\backslash
arrow[ur,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\backslash
sigma 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

, swap]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{tikzcd} 
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The number of extensions of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 to an embedding 
\begin_inset Formula $L\to F$
\end_inset

 is at most 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $L\slash K$
\end_inset

 is inseparable then the number of extensions of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 to an embedding 
\begin_inset Formula $L\to F$
\end_inset

 is less than 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $L\slash K$
\end_inset

 is separable then there is a field 
\begin_inset Formula $F'\supseteq F$
\end_inset

 such that the number of extensions of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 to an embedding 
\begin_inset Formula $L\to F'$
\end_inset

 is equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 1.
 We argue by induction on 
\begin_inset Formula $n=[L:K]$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $n=1$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $L=K$
\end_inset

 and the result is clear.
 Now suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $n>1$
\end_inset

.
 Pick 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in L$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\notin K$
\end_inset

.
 Our field diagram looks like the following.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
label{diagram}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd} L 
\backslash
arrow[d, dash]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash

\backslash

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

K(
\backslash
alpha ) & F 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash

\backslash

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

K 
\backslash
arrow[u,dash] 
\backslash
arrow[ur,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\backslash
sigma 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

, swap]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{tikzcd} 
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To bound the number of extensions of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 to an embedding of 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 into 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

, we first bound the number of extensions of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 to an embedding 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau\colon K(\alpha)\to F$
\end_inset

 and then bound the number of extensions of any such 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 to an embedding 
\begin_inset Formula $L\to F$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
label{diagram}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd} L 
\backslash
arrow[d, dash]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash

\backslash

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

K(
\backslash
alpha ) 
\backslash
arrow[r, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\backslash
tau 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

] & F 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash

\backslash

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

K 
\backslash
arrow[u,dash] 
\backslash
arrow[ur,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\backslash
sigma 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

, swap]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{tikzcd} 
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From the proof that two splitting fields of a polynomial are isomorphic,
 the number of 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

's extending 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 is the number of roots in 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $(\sigma\pi)(X)$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(X)$
\end_inset

 is the minimal polynomial of 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[X]$
\end_inset

.
 The number of these roots is 
\emph on
at most 
\emph default
the degree of 
\begin_inset Formula $(\sigma\pi)(X)$
\end_inset

, which equals 
\begin_inset Formula $\deg\pi=[K(\alpha):K]$
\end_inset

.
 This upper bound could be strict for two reasons: 
\begin_inset Formula $(\sigma\pi)(X)$
\end_inset

 might not split in 
\begin_inset Formula $F[X]$
\end_inset

 or it could split but be inseparable.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Once we have extended 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 to some 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $K(\alpha)$
\end_inset

, we count how many ways 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 extends to 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

.
 As in the proof that splitting fields are isomorphic, the trick is to consider
 
\begin_inset Formula $K(\alpha)$
\end_inset

 as the new base field, with 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 playing the role of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\notin K$
\end_inset

 we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
[L:K(\alpha)]<[L:K],
\]

\end_inset

so by induction on the field degree the number of extensions of 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau\colon K(\alpha)\to F$
\end_inset

 to an embedding of 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 into 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 is at most 
\begin_inset Formula $[L:K(\alpha)]$
\end_inset

.
 Multiplying the upper bounds on the number of extensions of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $K(\alpha)$
\end_inset

 and the number of further extensions up to 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

, the number of extensions of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 is at most
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
[L:K(\alpha)][K(\alpha):K]=[L:K],
\]

\end_inset

so by induction we're done.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
2.
 When 
\begin_inset Formula $L\slash K$
\end_inset

 is inseparable, some 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in L$
\end_inset

 is inseparable over 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

.
 Running through the first part of the proof of (1) with this 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

, its minimal polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(X)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[X]$
\end_inset

 is inseparable, so 
\begin_inset Formula $(\sigma\pi)(X)$
\end_inset

 is inseparable in 
\begin_inset Formula $F[X]$
\end_inset

.
 This inseparability forces the number of extensions of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $K(\alpha)$
\end_inset

 to be 
\emph on
less 
\emph default
than 
\begin_inset Formula $[K(\alpha):K]=\deg\pi$
\end_inset

.
 By (1), the number of extensions up to 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 of any field embedding 
\begin_inset Formula $K(\alpha)\to F$
\end_inset

 is at most 
\begin_inset Formula $[L:K(\alpha)]$
\end_inset

, so the number of extensions of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 is strictly less than
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
[L:K(\alpha)][K(\alpha):K]=[L:K].
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
3.
 Write 
\begin_inset Formula $L=K(\alpha_{1},\dots,\alpha_{r})$
\end_inset

 with each 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{i}$
\end_inset

 separable over 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

.
 We want to construct a field 
\begin_inset Formula $F'\supseteq F$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma\colon K\to F$
\end_inset

 has 
\begin_inset Formula $[L:K]$
\end_inset

 extensions to embeddings of 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 into 
\begin_inset Formula $F'$
\end_inset

.
 We will argue in a similar way to (1), but replacing 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 with some larger 
\begin_inset Formula $F'$
\end_inset

 will let the upper bound on the number of embeddings in the proof of (1)
 be reached.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Transitivity of Separable Extensions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $F\subseteq K\subseteq L$
\end_inset

 be an extension of fields and suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $L\slash F$
\end_inset

 is algebraic.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $L\slash F$
\end_inset

 is separable if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $L\slash K$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $K\slash F$
\end_inset

 are separable.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $L\slash F$
\end_inset

 is separable.
 Clearly 
\begin_inset Formula $K\slash F$
\end_inset

 is separable since 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is a subfield of 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 which contains 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

, so it remains to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $L\slash K$
\end_inset

 is separable.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in L$
\end_inset

, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{\alpha,K}(X)$
\end_inset

 be the minimal polynomial of 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{\alpha,F}(X)$
\end_inset

 be the minimal polynomial of 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{\alpha,K}\mid\pi_{\alpha,F}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[X]$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\pi_{\alpha,K}(X)g(X)=\pi_{\alpha,F}(X)\label{eq:diffbothsidesof}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $g(X)\in K[X]$
\end_inset

.
 Now differentiate both sides of 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:diffbothsidesof})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 and set 
\begin_inset Formula $X=\alpha$
\end_inset

 to get
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\pi_{\alpha,K}'(\alpha)g(\alpha)=\pi_{\alpha,F}'(\alpha).
\]

\end_inset

Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{\alpha,F}'(\alpha)\neq0$
\end_inset

 since otherwise this would imply 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{\alpha,F}\mid\pi_{\alpha,F}'$
\end_inset

 which would contradict separability of 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

.
 Similarly 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\alpha)\neq0$
\end_inset

 since otherwise this would imply 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{\alpha,K}\mid g$
\end_inset

 which would imply 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{\alpha,K}^{2}\mid\pi_{\alpha,F}$
\end_inset

 which would again contradict separability of 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Conversely, suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $L\slash K$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $K\slash F$
\end_inset

 are both separable.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in L$
\end_inset

, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{\alpha,K}(X)$
\end_inset

 be the minimal polynomial of 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{\alpha,F}(X)$
\end_inset

 be the minimal polynomial of 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in K$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 is separable over 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $K\slash F$
\end_inset

 is a separable extension, thus we may assume 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\notin K$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{\alpha,K}\mid\pi_{\alpha,F}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[X]$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\pi_{\alpha,K}(X)g_{1}(X)=\pi_{\alpha,F}(X)\label{eq:diffbothsidesof-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1}(X)\in K[X]$
\end_inset

.
 Now differentiate both sides of 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:diffbothsidesof})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 and set 
\begin_inset Formula $X=\alpha$
\end_inset

 to get
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\pi_{\alpha,K}'(\alpha)g_{1}(\alpha)=\pi_{\alpha,F}'(\alpha).
\]

\end_inset

Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{\alpha,K}'(\alpha)\neq0$
\end_inset

 since otherwise this would imply 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{\alpha,K}\mid\pi_{\alpha,K}'$
\end_inset

 which would contradict separability of 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1}(\alpha)=0$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{\alpha,K}\mid g$
\end_inset

 which would imply 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{\alpha,K}^{2}\mid\pi_{\alpha,F}$
\end_inset

 which would again contradict separability of 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in L$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{\alpha,K}(X)$
\end_inset

 be its minimal polynomial of 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{\alpha,F}(X)$
\end_inset

 be its minimal polynomial over 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in K$
\end_inset

, then the result is clear, so assume 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\notin K$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{\alpha,K}(\alpha)\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 We wish to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{\alpha,F}$
\end_inset

 is separable.
 Observe that 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{\alpha,K}\mid\pi_{\alpha,F}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $F[X]$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{\alpha,K}f=\pi_{\alpha,F}$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $f(X)\in F[X]$
\end_inset

.
 Also, note that since 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{\alpha,K}$
\end_inset

 is separable and irreducible, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\pi_{\alpha,F}'(X) & =\pi_{\alpha,K}'(X)f(X)+\pi_{\alpha,K}(X)f'(X)\\
 & =\pi_{\alpha,K}(X)f'(X)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $f'(\alpha)\neq0$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $\deg f'<\deg\pi_{\alpha,F}$
\end_inset

, therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{\alpha,F}'(\alpha)\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi'_{\alpha,F}(X)\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{\alpha,F}$
\end_inset

 is separable which implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 is separable.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Classification of Finite Separable Extensions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $L\slash K$
\end_inset

 be a finite extension and write 
\begin_inset Formula $L=K(\alpha_{1},\dots,\alpha_{r})$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $L\slash K$
\end_inset

 is separable if and only if each 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{i}$
\end_inset

 is separable over 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Primitive Element Theorem) Any finite separable extension of 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 has the form 
\begin_inset Formula $K(\gamma)$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

When 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 has characteristic 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

, all of its finite extensions are separable, so the primitive element theorem
 says any finite extension of 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 has the form 
\begin_inset Formula $K(\gamma)$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Trace and Norm
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Definition of Trace, Norm, and Characteristic Polynomial
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $L\slash K$
\end_inset

 be a finite field extension.
 We associate each element 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 the 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

-linear transformation 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{m}_{\alpha}\colon L\to L$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{m}_{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 is multiplication by 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

, that is,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{m}_{\alpha}(x)=\alpha x
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in L$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}=(e_{1},\dots,e_{n})$
\end_inset

 is an ordered 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

-basis of 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

.
 The matrix representation of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{m}_{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 with respect to the basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}$
\end_inset

 will be denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $[\mathrm{m}_{\alpha}]_{\mathbf{e}}$
\end_inset

.
 If the basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}$
\end_inset

 is clear from context, then will will simplify this notation to just 
\begin_inset Formula $[\mathrm{m}_{\alpha}]$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}'=(e_{1}',\dots,e_{n}')$
\end_inset

 is another ordered 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

-basis of 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 is a change of basis matrix from 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}'$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}'=\mathbf{e}C$
\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
[\mathrm{m}_{\alpha}]_{\mathbf{e}'}=C^{-1}[\mathrm{m}_{\alpha}]_{\mathbf{e}}C.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In particular, the trace and norm of the matrix represenation of 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 does not depend on the basis.
 Now let us define the trace and norm.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $L\slash K$
\end_inset

 be a finite field extension and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in L$
\end_inset

.
 We define the 
\series bold
trace function
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Tr}_{L\slash K}\colon L\to K$
\end_inset

 and 
\series bold
norm function
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{N}_{L\slash K}\colon L\to K$
\end_inset

 as follows: choose any ordered 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

-basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}=(e_{1},\dots,e_{n})$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 and for each 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in K$
\end_inset

 let 
\begin_inset Formula $[\mathrm{m}_{\alpha}]$
\end_inset

 be the matrix representation of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{m}_{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 with respect to this basis.
 Then we set
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{Tr}_{L\slash K}(\alpha)=\mathrm{tr}[\mathrm{m}_{\alpha}]\quad\text{and}\quad\mathrm{N}_{L\slash K}(\alpha)=\det[\mathrm{m}_{\alpha}]
\]

\end_inset

We also define the 
\series bold
characteristic polynomial 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 relative to the extension 
\begin_inset Formula $L\slash K$
\end_inset

 to be the polynomial
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\chi_{\alpha,L\slash K}(X)=\det(X\cdot I_{n}-[\mathrm{m}_{\alpha}])\in K[X],
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $n=[L:K]$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{exampletracenormcharex}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $K=\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $L=\mathbb{Q}(\gamma)$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 a root of 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{3}-X-1$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma^{3}=1+\gamma$
\end_inset

.
 Use the basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\{1,\gamma,\gamma^{2}\}$
\end_inset

.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=a+b\gamma+c\gamma^{3}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b,$
\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 rational, multiply 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $1,\gamma$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma^{2}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\alpha\cdot1 & =a+b\gamma+c\gamma^{2}\\
\alpha\cdot\gamma & =a\gamma+b\gamma^{2}+c\gamma^{3}=c+(a+c)\gamma+b\gamma^{2}\\
\alpha\cdot\gamma^{2} & =c\gamma+(a+c)\gamma^{2}+b\gamma^{3}=b+(b+c)\gamma+(a+c)\gamma^{2}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $[\mathrm{m}_{\alpha}]$
\end_inset

 equals
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{pmatrix}a & c & b\\
b & a+c & b+c\\
c & b & a+c
\end{pmatrix}.
\]

\end_inset

Thus we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathrm{Tr}_{L/K}(\alpha) & =3a+2c\\
\mathrm{N}_{L\slash K}(\alpha) & =a^{3}+2a^{2}c-ab^{2}-3abc+ac^{2}+b^{3}-bc^{2}+c^{3}\\
\chi_{\alpha,L\slash K}(X) & =X^{3}-(3a+2c)X^{2}+(b^{2}+3bc-c^{2}-4ac-3a^{2})X-(a^{3}+2a^{2}c-ab^{2}-3abc+ac^{2}+b^{3}-bc^{2}+c^{3})
\end{align*}

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

For any 
\begin_inset Formula $n\times n$
\end_inset

 square matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, its trace and determinant appear up to sign as coefficients in its characteris
tic polynomial:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\det(XI_{n}-A)=X^{n}-\mathrm{tr}(A)X^{n-1}+\cdots+(-1)^{n}\det A.
\]

\end_inset

Thus
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\chi_{\alpha,L\slash K}(X)=X^{n}-\mathrm{Tr}_{L\slash K}(\alpha)X^{n-1}+\cdots+(-1)^{n}\mathrm{N}_{L\slash K}(\alpha).
\]

\end_inset

This tells us the trace and norm of 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 are, up to sign, coefficients of the characteristic polynomial of 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

, which can been seen in 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Example~(
\backslash
ref{exampletracenormcharex})
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Unlike the minimal polynomial of 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

, whose degree 
\begin_inset Formula $[K(\alpha):K]$
\end_inset

 varies with 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

, the degree of 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi_{\alpha,L\slash K}(X)$
\end_inset

 is always 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, which is independent of the choice of 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Every 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 is a root of its own characteristic polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi_{\alpha,L\slash K}(X)$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 This is a consequence of the Cayley-Hamilton theorem in linear algebra.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Properties of Trace and Norm
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $L\slash K$
\end_inset

 be a finite field extension.
 The trace 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Tr}_{L\slash K}\colon L\to K$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

-linear and the norm 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{N}_{L\slash K}:L\to K$
\end_inset

 is multiplicative.
 Moreover, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{N}_{L\slash K}(L^{\times})\subseteq K^{\times}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha,\beta\in L$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in K$
\end_inset

.
 Choose any basis of 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

.
 Then we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathrm{Tr}_{L\slash K}(a\alpha+b\beta) & =\mathrm{tr}[\mathrm{m}_{a\alpha+b\beta}]\\
 & =\mathrm{tr}[a\mathrm{m}_{\alpha}+b\mathrm{m}_{\beta}]\\
 & =a\mathrm{tr}[\mathrm{m}_{\alpha}]+b\mathrm{tr}[\mathrm{m}_{\beta}]\\
 & =a\mathrm{Tr}_{L\slash K}(\alpha)+b\mathrm{Tr}_{L\slash K}(\beta).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Similarly we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathrm{N}_{L\slash K}(\alpha\beta) & =\det[m_{\alpha\beta}]\\
 & =\det[\mathrm{m}_{\alpha}\mathrm{m}_{\beta}]\\
 & =\det[\mathrm{m}_{\alpha}]\det[\mathrm{m}_{\beta}]\\
 & =\mathrm{N}_{L\slash K}(\alpha)\mathrm{N}_{L\slash K}(\beta).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Tr}_{L\slash K}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

-linear and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{N}_{L\slash K}$
\end_inset

 is multiplicative.
 For the last statement, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in L^{\times}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
1 & =\mathrm{N}_{L\slash K}(1)\\
 & =\mathrm{N}_{L\slash K}(\alpha\alpha^{-1})\\
 & =\mathrm{N}_{L\slash K}(\alpha)\mathrm{N}_{L\slash K}(\alpha^{-1}).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{N}_{L\slash K}(\alpha)\in K^{\times}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Trace and Norm For a Galois Extension
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $L\slash K$
\end_inset

 be a finite Galois extension with Galois group 
\begin_inset Formula $G=\mathrm{Gal}(L\slash K)$
\end_inset

.
 We can express characteristic polynomials, traces, and norms for the extension
 
\begin_inset Formula $L\slash K$
\end_inset

 in terms of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 When 
\begin_inset Formula $L\slash K$
\end_inset

 is a finite Galois extension with Galois group 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in L$
\end_inset

, then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\chi_{\alpha,L\slash K}(X)=\prod_{\sigma\in G}(X-\sigma(\alpha)).
\]

\end_inset

In particular,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{Tr}_{L\slash K}(\alpha)=\sum_{\sigma\in G}\sigma(\alpha),\quad\text{and}\quad\mathrm{N}_{L\slash K}(\alpha)=\prod_{\sigma\in G}\sigma(\alpha).
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{\alpha,K}(X)$
\end_inset

 be the minimal polynomial of 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi_{\alpha,L\slash K}(X)=\pi_{\alpha,K}(X)^{n/d}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $n=[L:K]$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $d=[K(\alpha):K]=\deg\pi_{\alpha,K}$
\end_inset

.
 From Galois theory,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\pi_{\alpha,K}(X)=\prod_{i=1}^{d}(X-\sigma_{i}(\alpha))
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{1}(\alpha),\dots,\sigma_{d}(\alpha)$
\end_inset

 are all the distinct values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma(\alpha)$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 runs over the Galois group.
 For each 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma\in G$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma(\alpha)=\sigma_{i}(\alpha)$
\end_inset

 for a unique 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 from 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

.
 Moreover, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma(\alpha)=\sigma_{i}(\alpha)$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma\in\sigma_{i}H$
\end_inset

, where
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
H=\{\tau\in G\mid\tau(\alpha)=\alpha\}=\mathrm{Gal}(L\slash K(\alpha)).
\]

\end_inset

Therefore as 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 runs over 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

, the number 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{i}(\alpha)$
\end_inset

 appears as 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma(\alpha)$
\end_inset

 whenever 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 is in the left coset 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{i}H$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{i}(\alpha)$
\end_inset

 occurs 
\begin_inset Formula $|H|$
\end_inset

 times, and
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
|H| & =[L:K(\alpha)]\\
 & =[L:K]/[K(\alpha):K]\\
 & =n/d.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Therefore
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\prod_{\sigma\in G}(X-\sigma(\alpha)) & =\prod_{i=1}^{d}(X-\sigma_{i}(\alpha))^{n/d}\\
 & =\left(\prod_{i=1}^{d}(X-\sigma_{i}(\alpha))\right)^{n/d}\\
 & =\pi_{\alpha,K}(X)^{n/d}\\
 & =\chi_{\alpha,L/K}(X).
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Perfect Fields
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Characteristic 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 fields have a very handy feature: every irreducible polynomial in characteristi
c 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 is separable.
 Fields in characteristic 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 may or may not have this feature.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A field 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is called 
\series bold
perfect 
\series default
if every irreducible polynomial in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[X]$
\end_inset

 is separable.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Part
Module Theory
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this document, we will study the theory of modules over a commutative
 ring
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
There is a theory of modules over a non-commutative ring, but we leave that
 topic to another document.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Basic Definitions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Definition of an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-Module
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be a commutative ring
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
For us, all rings have an identity element by definition.
 Note that some authors define rings to be associative 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

-algebras which do not necessarily have an identity element.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 An 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-
\begin_inset Formula $\textbf{module}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 consists of an abelian group on which 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 acts by additive maps: there is a scalar multiplication function 
\begin_inset Formula $R\times M\to M$
\end_inset

 denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $(a,m)\mapsto am$
\end_inset

 such that for all 
\begin_inset Formula $u,v\in M$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in R$
\end_inset

 we have
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $1u=u$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a(bu)=(ab)u$
\end_inset

.
  
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $a(u+v)=au+av$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(a+b)u=au+bu$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Throughout these notes, we often write 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

let 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

let 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 be an ideal in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 without specifying what 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is.
 In either case, it is understood that 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is a commutative ring.
 We will also say 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

let 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 be a module over 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 instead of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

let 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 Sometimes the base ring 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 isn't important to know and we will refer to 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 simply as a module rather than an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Consistency in Notation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When learning Mathematics, it's a good practice to write things down in
 an organized way.
 Doing so will help organize ideas and concepts in your mind, making it
 easier to work with them.
 For instance, we will typically use the capital letters 
\begin_inset Formula $R,S$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $A,B$
\end_inset

 to denote rings.
 Similarly, we will typically use the capital letters 
\begin_inset Formula $M,N$
\end_inset

 to denote modules.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module, then we will typically use lower case letters 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b,c$
\end_inset

 to denote elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 and use lower case letters 
\begin_inset Formula $u,v,w$
\end_inset

 to denote elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 Many authors use the lower case letters 
\begin_inset Formula $r,s$
\end_inset

 to denote elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 and use the lower case letter 
\begin_inset Formula $m,n$
\end_inset

 to denote elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 This is completely fine! Sometimes we will even use the lower case letters
 
\begin_inset Formula $r,s$
\end_inset

 to denote elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 In fact, if we are dealing with a ring 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 together with a ring 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, then we will try to use the lower case letters 
\begin_inset Formula $r,s$
\end_inset

 to denote elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 and the lower case letters 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b$
\end_inset

 to denote elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 However we will try to avoid using the lower case letters 
\begin_inset Formula $m,n$
\end_inset

 to denote elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 This is because we try to use lower case letters like 
\begin_inset Formula $i,j,k,l,m,n$
\end_inset

 as indices.
 For instance, we may write an element in 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\sum_{i=1}^{m}a_{i}u_{i}=a_{1}u_{1}+\cdots+a_{m}u_{m}.\label{eq:termsinfjdsklf}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where the 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{i}$
\end_inset

 are elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 and the 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{i}$
\end_inset

 are elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 The lower case 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 here is simply the number of terms in 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:termsinfjdsklf})
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Throughout this document, the reader will find many more examples of consistency
 in notation as in the case described above.
 Keep in mind however that this rule is not set in stone; we may violate
 it.
 The point however is that if you try to be as consistent as possible with
 your notation, it will make learning Mathematics much easier (and more
 fun!).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Examples of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-Modules
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be a ring and let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be a nonempty set.
 At the moment, the ring 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 and the set 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 have nothing to do with each other, however we'd like to turn 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 into an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module somehow.
 How can we do this? Well, the first step would be to give 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 the 
\series bold
structure of an abelian group
\series default
! In particular, we need define an addition map 
\begin_inset Formula $+\colon X\times X\to X$
\end_inset

 such that the pair 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,+)$
\end_inset

 forms an abelian group.
 In this case, we say addition 
\begin_inset Formula $+$
\end_inset

 
\series bold
gives 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 the structure of an abelian group
\series default
.
 Once 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is given the structure of an abelian group, the next thing we'd need to
 do is to define a scalar multiplication map 
\begin_inset Formula $\cdot\colon R\times X\to X$
\end_inset

 such that the triple 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,+,\cdot)$
\end_inset

 forms an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module.
 In this case, we say addition 
\begin_inset Formula $+$
\end_inset

 and multiplication 
\begin_inset Formula $\cdot$
\end_inset

 
\series bold
gives 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 the structure of an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module
\series default
.
 We often use this language when describing modules.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be a ring and let 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq1$
\end_inset

.
 Then the set 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{n}=\{(a_{1},\dots,a_{n})\mid a_{i}\in R\}$
\end_inset

 can be given the structure of an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module as follows: addition and scalar multiplication are defined by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(a_{1},\dots,a_{n})+(b_{1},\dots,b_{n}):=(a_{1}+b_{1},\dots,a_{n}+b_{n})\quad\text{and}\quad a(a_{1},\dots,a_{n}):=(aa_{1},\dots,aa_{n})
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $a\in R$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(a_{1},\dots,a_{n}),(b_{1},\dots,b_{n})\in R^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Check that addition and scalar multiplication defined in this way really
 does give 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{n}$
\end_inset

 an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module structure.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 One of the reasons why we study 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-modules is because they help us obtain information about the ring 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 itself.
 For instance, if 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is a principal ideal domain, then it turns out that every finitely generated
 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module is isomorphic to a direct sum of a free module plus a torsion module.
 The proof of this fact uses the in an essential way the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is a principal ideal domain.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Definition of an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-Linear Map
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 be 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-modules.
 A map 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon M\to N$
\end_inset

 is called an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset


\series bold
-linear map 
\series default
if for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $u,v$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varphi(au+bv)=a\varphi(u)+b\varphi(v).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-linear map 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon M\to N$
\end_inset

 is also called an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset


\series bold
-module homomorphism
\series default
.
 A bijective 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module homomorphism is called an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset


\series bold
-module
\series default
 
\series bold
isomorphism
\series default
.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon M\to N$
\end_inset

 is an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module isomorphism, then we say 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
isomorphic to
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

, and we denote this by 
\begin_inset Formula $M\cong N$
\end_inset

.
 The collection of all 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-modules and 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-linear maps forms a category
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
See the Appendix for an introduction to Category Theory.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 which we will denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{Mod}_{R}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(0)=\varphi(0+0)=\varphi(0)+\varphi(0)$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(0)=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

When the base ring 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is understood from context, we will sometimes drop 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-linear map
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and simply write 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

linear map
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 We also write 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon M\to N$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-linear map
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 without specifying what 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 is.
 In thise case, it is understood that 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is a commutative ring and that 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 are 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-modules.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Submodules, Kernels, and Quotient Modules
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon M\to N$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-linear map.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The 
\series bold
kernel 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

, denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $\ker\varphi$
\end_inset

, is defined to be the set
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\ker\varphi:=\{u\in M\mid\varphi(u)=0\}.
\]

\end_inset

In a moment, we will show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\ker\varphi$
\end_inset

 can be given the structure of an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The 
\series bold
image 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

, denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{im}\,\varphi$
\end_inset

, is defined to be the set
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{im}\,\varphi:=\{\varphi(u)\in N\mid u\in M\}.
\]

\end_inset

In a moment, we will show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{im}\,\varphi$
\end_inset

 can be given the structure of an an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is a subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is the inclusion map, then we say 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset


\series bold
-submodule
\series default
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

.
 In this case, we also define the 
\series bold
quotient 
\series default
of
\series bold
 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 
\series default
with respect to 
\series bold

\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset


\series default
, denoted
\series bold
 
\series default

\begin_inset Formula $N\slash M$
\end_inset

, to be the set
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
N\slash M=\{v+M\mid v\in N\}.
\]

\end_inset

That is, 
\begin_inset Formula $N\slash M$
\end_inset

 is the set of equivalence classes of elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{1},v_{2}\in N$
\end_inset

 are equivalent if 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{1}-v_{2}\in M$
\end_inset

.
 An equivalent class in 
\begin_inset Formula $N\slash M$
\end_inset

 is denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $v+M$
\end_inset

 or more simply by 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{v}$
\end_inset

.
 In this case, we call 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 a 
\series bold
representative 
\series default
of the equivalence class 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{v}$
\end_inset

.
 From basic group theory, we know that 
\begin_inset Formula $N\slash M$
\end_inset

 has the structure of an abelian group, where addition is defined by 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{v_{1}}+\overline{v_{2}}=\overline{v_{1}+v_{2}}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{v_{1}},\overline{v_{2}}\in N\slash M$
\end_inset

.
 In fact, 
\begin_inset Formula $N\slash M$
\end_inset

 has the structure of an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module, where scalar multiplication is defined by 
\begin_inset Formula $a\overline{v}=\overline{av}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in R$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{v}\in N\slash M$
\end_inset

.
 One checks that this is well-defined and together with addition defined
 above does indeed give 
\begin_inset Formula $N\slash M$
\end_inset

 the structure of an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The 
\series bold
cokernel 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

, denote 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{coker}\,\varphi$
\end_inset

, is defined to be the 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathrm{coker}\,\varphi=N\slash\mathrm{im}\,\varphi.\label{eq:definitionofcoker}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

In a moment, we will show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{im}\,\varphi$
\end_inset

 can be given the structure of an an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-submodule of 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

, so that definition 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:definitionofcoker})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 makes sense.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module and let 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 be a subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-submodule of 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is nonempty and 
\begin_inset Formula $au+bv\in M$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in R$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $u,v\in M$
\end_inset

.
 Equivalently, 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-submodule of 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is nonempty 
\begin_inset Formula $au+v\in M$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in R$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $u,v\in M$
\end_inset

.
 This is sometimes called the 
\series bold
submodule criterion test
\series default
.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 satisfies the submodule criterion test, then it is easy to check that we
 can give it the structure of an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module by using the 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module operations from 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon M\to N$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-linear map.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\ker\varphi$
\end_inset

 is a submodule of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{im}\,\varphi$
\end_inset

 is a submodule of 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let us first show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\ker\varphi$
\end_inset

 is a submodule of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 Observe that 
\begin_inset Formula $\ker\varphi$
\end_inset

 is nonempty since 
\begin_inset Formula $0\in\ker\varphi$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in R$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $u,v\in\ker\varphi$
\end_inset

.
 Then we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\varphi(au+v) & =a\varphi(u)+\varphi(v)\\
 & =a\cdot0+0\\
 & =0+0\\
 & =0.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $au+v\in\ker\varphi$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\ker\varphi$
\end_inset

 is a submodule of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Now we will show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{im}\,\varphi$
\end_inset

 is a submodule of 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

.
 Observe that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{im}\,\varphi$
\end_inset

 is nonempty since 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(0)\in\mathrm{im}\,\varphi$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in R$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(u),\varphi(v)\in\mathrm{im}\,\varphi$
\end_inset

.
 Then we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
a\varphi(u)+\varphi(v) & =\varphi(au)+\varphi(v)\\
 & =\varphi(au+v).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $a\varphi(u)+\varphi(v)\in\mathrm{im}\,\varphi$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{im}\,\varphi$
\end_inset

 is a submodule of 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Base Change
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Throughout this subsection, let 
\begin_inset Formula $f\colon R\to S$
\end_inset

 be a ring homomorphism.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Restriction of scalars functor
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 is an 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

-module, then we can restrict it to an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{R}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{R}$
\end_inset

 has the same underlying abelian group structure as 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 but with scalar multiplication given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a\cdot v=f(a)v
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in R$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $v\in N$
\end_inset

.
 This is called 
\series bold
restriction of scalars 
\series default
since in the case where 
\begin_inset Formula $R\subseteq S$
\end_inset

 we are just restricting the 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

-action to an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-action.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi\colon N\to N'$
\end_inset

 is an 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

-module linear map, then we define an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module linear map 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{R}\colon N_{R}\to N'_{R}$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\psi_{R}(v)=\psi(v)
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $v\in N_{R}$
\end_inset

.
 Let us check that 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{R}$
\end_inset

 is indeed an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-linear map.
 We just need to check that 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{R}$
\end_inset

 respects scalar multiplication since additivity is clear.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in R$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $v\in N_{R}$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\psi_{R}(a\cdot v) & =\psi_{R}(f(a)v)\\
 & =\psi(f(a)v)\\
 & =f(a)\psi(v)\\
 & =a\cdot\psi(v)\\
 & =a\cdot\psi_{R}(v).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{R}$
\end_inset

 is an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module linear map.
 It is easy to check that we obtain a functor
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
-_{R}\colon\mathbf{Mod}_{S}\to\mathbf{Mod}_{R}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Extension of scalars functor
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module, then we can extend it to an 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

-module 
\begin_inset Formula $S\otimes_{R}M$
\end_inset

 where scalar multiplication is defined by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a\cdot(b\otimes u)=ab\otimes u
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in S$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $u\in M$
\end_inset

.
 This is called 
\series bold
extension of scalars
\series default
 since in the case where 
\begin_inset Formula $R\subseteq S$
\end_inset

 we are just extending the 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-action to an 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

-action.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon M\to M'$
\end_inset

 is an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module linear map, then we define an 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

-module linear map 
\begin_inset Formula $1\otimes\varphi\colon S\otimes_{R}M\to S\otimes_{R}M$
\end_inset

 on elementary tensors 
\begin_inset Formula $a\otimes u\in S\otimes_{R}M$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(1\otimes\varphi)(a\otimes u)=a\otimes\varphi(u),
\]

\end_inset

and then extend this linearly everywhere else.
 We just need to check that 
\begin_inset Formula $1\otimes\varphi$
\end_inset

 respects scalar multiplication since additivity is clear.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in S$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $b\otimes u$
\end_inset

 be an elementary tensor in 
\begin_inset Formula $S\otimes_{R}M$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
(1\otimes\varphi)(a\cdot(b\otimes u)) & =(1\otimes\varphi)(ab\otimes u)\\
 & =ab\otimes\varphi(u)\\
 & =a\cdot(b\otimes\varphi(u))\\
 & =a\cdot((1\otimes\varphi)(b\otimes u)).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $1\otimes\varphi$
\end_inset

 is an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module linear map.
 It is easy to check that we obtain a functor
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
S\otimes_{R}-\colon\mathbf{Mod}_{R}\to\mathbf{Mod}_{S}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Restricting scalars and extending scalars form an adjoint pair
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The functors 
\begin_inset Formula $-_{R}\colon\mathbf{Mod}_{S}\to\mathbf{Mod}_{R}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $-\otimes_{R}S\colon\mathbf{Mod}_{R}\mapsto\mathbf{Mod}_{S}$
\end_inset

 are adjoint functors.
 In a formula
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{Hom}_{R}(M,N_{R})\cong\mathrm{Hom}_{S}(M\otimes_{R}S,N)
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-modules 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 and for all 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

-modules 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 be an ideal in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 Let us calculate 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Hom}_{R}(R\slash I,R\slash I)$
\end_inset

.
 We have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathrm{Hom}_{R}(R\slash I,R\slash I) & \cong\mathrm{Hom}_{R\slash I}((R\slash I)\otimes_{R}(R\slash I),R\slash I)\\
 & \cong\mathrm{Hom}_{R\slash I}(R\slash I,R\slash I)\\
 & \cong R\slash I.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Base Change
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There is another type of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module that can be viewed as an 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

-module.
 For simplicity, assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $R\subset S$
\end_inset

 is an extension of rings.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module and 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 is an 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

-module.
 Through restriction of scalars, we can view 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 as an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module.
 Thus we can consider 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Hom}_{R}(N,M)$
\end_inset

.
 In fact, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Hom}_{R}(N,M)$
\end_inset

 can be viewed as an 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

-module via the action
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
b\cdot\varphi(v)=\varphi(bv)
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $b\in S$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\in\mathrm{Hom}_{R}(N,M)$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $v\in N$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R\subset S$
\end_inset

 be a ring extension and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\in\mathrm{Hom}_{S}(N,N')$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi\in\mathrm{Hom}_{R}(M,M')$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $M,M'$
\end_inset

 are 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-modules and 
\begin_inset Formula $N,N'$
\end_inset

 are 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

-modules.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi^{*}\colon\mathrm{Hom}_{R}(N',M)\to\mathrm{Hom}_{R}(N,M)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{*}\colon\mathrm{Hom}_{R}(N,M)\to\mathrm{Hom}_{R}(N,M')$
\end_inset

 are 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

-module homomorphisms.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Translated Modules
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this section, we want to discuss how to translate an 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-module 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 by an element 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in M$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $M^{x}:=\left\{ y+x\mid y\in M\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 We define addition and scaling operations as follows.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 is an element in 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and, 
\begin_inset Formula $y+x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y'+x$
\end_inset

 are two elements in 
\begin_inset Formula $M^{x}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(y+x)\dot{+}(y'+x)=y+y'+x
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a\cdot(y+x)=a\cdot y+x.
\]

\end_inset

Addition 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{+}$
\end_inset

 makes 
\begin_inset Formula $M^{x}$
\end_inset

 into an abelian group with identity being 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, and one can check that all of the conditions for 
\begin_inset Formula $M^{x}$
\end_inset

 to be an 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-module are satisfied.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

We can generalize the above constrution as follows: Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi:M\to M^{\varphi}$
\end_inset

 be an isomorphism from 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 to some set 
\begin_inset Formula $M^{\varphi}$
\end_inset

.
 We define addition and scaling operations as follows: Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in M^{\varphi}$
\end_inset

.
 Then we define 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x\dot{+}y=\varphi\left(\varphi^{-1}(x)+\varphi^{-1}(y)\right)
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a\cdot x=\varphi\left(a\varphi^{-1}(x)\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Addition 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{+}$
\end_inset

 makes 
\begin_inset Formula $M^{\varphi}$
\end_inset

 into an abelian group with identity being 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(0)$
\end_inset

.
 For instance, we have associativity:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\left(x\dot{+}y\right)\dot{+}z & =\varphi\left(\varphi^{-1}(x)+\varphi^{-1}(y)\right)\dot{+}z\\
 & =\varphi\left(\varphi^{-1}\left(\varphi\left(\varphi^{-1}(x)+\varphi^{-1}(y)\right)\right)\dot{+}\varphi^{-1}\left(z\right)\right)\\
 & =\varphi\left(\left(\varphi^{-1}(x)+\varphi^{-1}(y)\right)\dot{+}\varphi^{-1}\left(z\right)\right)\\
 & =\varphi\left(\varphi^{-1}(x)+\left(\varphi^{-1}(y)\dot{+}\varphi^{-1}\left(z\right)\right)\right)\\
 & =\varphi\left(\varphi^{-1}(x)+\varphi\left(\varphi^{-1}\left(\varphi^{-1}(y)\dot{+}\varphi^{-1}\left(z\right)\right)\right)\right)\\
 & =x\dot{+}\varphi\left(\varphi^{-1}(y)+\varphi^{-1}(z)\right)\\
 & =x\dot{+}\left(y\dot{+}z\right).
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and we have commutativity: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
x\dot{+}y & =\varphi\left(\varphi^{-1}(x)+\varphi^{-1}(y)\right)\\
 & =\varphi\left(\varphi^{-1}(y)+\varphi^{-1}(x)\right)\\
 & =y\dot{+}x.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One can check that all of the conditions for 
\begin_inset Formula $M^{\varphi}$
\end_inset

 to be an 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-module are satisfied.
 For instance, suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in A$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in M^{\varphi}$
\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
a\cdot\left(x\dot{+}y\right) & =a\cdot\left(\varphi\left(\varphi^{-1}(x)+\varphi^{-1}(y)\right)\right)\\
 & =\varphi\left(a\left(\varphi^{-1}\left(\varphi\left(\varphi^{-1}(x)+\varphi^{-1}(y)\right)\right)\right)\right)\\
 & =\varphi\left(a\left(\varphi^{-1}(x)+\varphi^{-1}(y)\right)\right)\\
 & =\varphi\left(a\varphi^{-1}(x)+a\varphi^{-1}(y)\right)\\
 & =\varphi\left(\varphi^{-1}(a\cdot x)+\varphi^{-1}(a\cdot y)\right)\\
 & =a\cdot x\dot{+}a\cdot y.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
(a+b)\cdot x & =\varphi\left((a+b)\varphi^{-1}(x)\right)\\
 & =\varphi\left(a\varphi^{-1}(x)+b\varphi^{-1}(x)\right)\\
 & =\varphi\left(\varphi^{-1}(a\cdot x)+\varphi^{-1}(b\cdot x)\right)\\
 & =a\cdot x\dot{+}b\cdot x
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
(ab)\cdot x & =\varphi\left(ab\varphi^{-1}(x)\right)\\
 & =\varphi\left(a\varphi^{-1}\left(\varphi(b\varphi^{-1}(x))\right)\right)\\
 & =a\cdot(\varphi(b\varphi^{-1}(x)))\\
 & =a\cdot(b\cdot x)
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

The way we defined addition and 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-scaling on 
\begin_inset Formula $M^{\varphi}$
\end_inset

 makes 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 an 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-linear map.
 Indeed, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\varphi(ax+by) & =\varphi(\varphi^{-1}(\varphi(ax))+\varphi^{-1}(\varphi(by)))\\
 & =\varphi(ax)\dot{+}\varphi(by)\\
 & =\varphi(a\varphi^{-1}(\varphi(x)))\dot{+}\varphi(b\varphi^{-1}(\varphi(y)))\\
 & =a\cdot\varphi(x)\dot{+}b\cdot\varphi(y)
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in M$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Now suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $M^{\varphi}=M$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 be additive, that is, 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(x+y)=\varphi(x)+\varphi(y)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in M$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{+}$
\end_inset

 is the same 
\begin_inset Formula $+$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is additive and
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
x\dot{+}y & =\varphi(\varphi^{-1}(x)+\varphi^{-1}(y))\\
 & =\varphi(\varphi^{-1}(x+y))\\
 & =x+y
\end{align*}

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in M$
\end_inset

.
 On the other hand, we can still have a different scaling map, as long as
 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is not 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-linear.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Free Modules
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Generating Sets
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\{u_{\lambda}\}_{\lambda\in\Lambda}$
\end_inset

 be a collection of elements in 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 We say 
\begin_inset Formula $\{u_{\lambda}\}$
\end_inset

 
\series bold
generates 
\series default

\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 if for all 
\begin_inset Formula $u\in M$
\end_inset

 there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{\lambda_{1}},\dots u_{\lambda_{n}}\in\{u_{\lambda}\}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{\lambda_{1}},\dots,a_{\lambda_{n}}\in R$
\end_inset

 such that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u=a_{\lambda_{1}}u_{\lambda_{1}}+a_{\lambda_{2}}u_{\lambda_{2}}+\cdots+a_{\lambda_{n}}u_{\lambda_{n}}.
\]

\end_inset

If 
\begin_inset Formula $\{u_{\lambda}\}$
\end_inset

 generates 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, then we say 
\begin_inset Formula $\{u_{\lambda}\}$
\end_inset

 is a 
\series bold
generating set 
\series default
for 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 We say 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
finitely-generated 
\series default
if there exists a finite generating set for 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Free Modules
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module and let 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{1},\dots,u_{n}\in M$
\end_inset

.
 We say the set 
\begin_inset Formula $\{u_{1},\dots,u_{n}\}$
\end_inset

 is a 
\series bold
basis for 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 
\series default
if the following conditions hold:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
it generates 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 as an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module: for each 
\begin_inset Formula $u\in M$
\end_inset

 there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{1},\dots,a_{n}\in R$
\end_inset

 such that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u=a_{1}u_{1}+\cdots+a_{n}u_{n},
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
it is linearly independent: if 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{1},\dots,a_{n}\in R$
\end_inset

 such that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a_{1}u_{1}+\cdots+a_{n}u_{n}=0,
\]

\end_inset

then 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{i}=0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq i\leq n$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
More generally, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\{u_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

} be a collection of elements in 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 indexed over some (possibly infinite) set 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda$
\end_inset

.
 We say the set 
\begin_inset Formula $\{u_{\lambda}\}$
\end_inset

 is a 
\series bold
basis for 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 
\series default
if
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
it generates 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 as an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module: for each 
\begin_inset Formula $u\in M$
\end_inset

 there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{\lambda_{1}},\dots,u_{\lambda_{n}}\in\{u_{\lambda}\}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{\lambda_{1}},\dots,a_{\lambda_{n}}\in R$
\end_inset

 such that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u=a_{\lambda_{1}}u_{\lambda_{1}}+\cdots+a_{\lambda_{n}}u_{\lambda_{n}}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
every finite subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $\{u_{\lambda}\}$
\end_inset

 is linearly independent: if 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{\lambda_{1}},\dots,a_{\lambda_{n}}\in R$
\end_inset

 such that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a_{\lambda_{1}}u_{\lambda_{1}}+\cdots+a_{\lambda_{n}}u_{\lambda_{n}}=0,
\]

\end_inset

then 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{\lambda_{i}}=0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq i\leq n$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We say 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is a 
\series bold
free 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module 
\series default
if it has a basis.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{n}$
\end_inset

 is the 
\series bold
standard free 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module of rank 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset


\series default
.
 It has as basis the 
\series bold
standard basis elements 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{i}$
\end_inset

 
\series default
where 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the vector with 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 in the 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

th entry and 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 everywhere else.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is a nonzero ideal in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $R\slash I$
\end_inset

 is not a free 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module.
 Indeed, if 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 is a nonzero element in 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

, then for all 
\begin_inset Formula $s\in R$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $r\overline{s}=\overline{rs}=0$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $R\slash I$
\end_inset

.
 In other words, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\series bold
torsion
\series default

\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 makes linear independence fail for elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $R\slash I$
\end_inset

 when taking coefficients from 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Universal Mapping Property of Free 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-Modules
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Free modules are characterized by the following universal mapping property:
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 be a free 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module with basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\{e_{\lambda}\}$
\end_inset

 indexed over a set 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda$
\end_inset

.
 Then for all 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-modules 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 and for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\{u_{\lambda}\}\subseteq M$
\end_inset

 there exists a unique 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon F\to M$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(e_{\lambda})=u_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\in\Lambda$
\end_inset

.
 In terms of diagrams, this is pictured as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd} 
\backslash
{ e_{ 
\backslash
lambda } 
\backslash
} 
\backslash
arrow[r,hookrightarrow] 
\backslash
arrow[dr, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

e_{
\backslash
lambda } 
\backslash
mapsto u_{
\backslash
lambda } 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

,swap] & F 
\backslash
arrow[d, dashed, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\backslash
exists ! 
\backslash
varphi 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash

\backslash

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

& M   
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{tikzcd}
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using the universal mapping property of free 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-modules, let us prove the following theorem:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theoremuniversalmappingoffreemodules}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 are finite rank free 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-modules with basis 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{1},\dots,e_{n}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1},\dots,f_{n}$
\end_inset

 respectively, then 
\begin_inset Formula $F\cong G$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 By the universal mapping property of free 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-modules there exists a unique 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon F\to G$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(e_{i})=f_{i}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i=1,\dots,n$
\end_inset

.
 Similarly, there exists a unique 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi\colon G\to F$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi(f_{i})=e_{i}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i=1,\dots,n$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi\circ\varphi\colon F\to F$
\end_inset

 satisfies 
\begin_inset Formula $(\psi\circ\varphi)(e_{i})=e_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 But we also have 
\begin_inset Formula $1(e_{i})=e_{i}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i=1,\dots,n$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $1\colon F\to F$
\end_inset

 is the identity map.
 Therefore by uniqueness of the map in the universal mapping property of
 free 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-modules, we must have 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi\circ\varphi=1$
\end_inset

.
 A similar argument shows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\circ\psi=1$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{cor}
\backslash
label{cor}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 be a free 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module with basis 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{1},\dots,e_{n}\in F$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $F\cong R^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{cor}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Note that you can prove 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Theorem~(
\backslash
ref{theoremuniversalmappingoffreemodules})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 without the universal mapping property of free 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-modules, but the point is that you'd have to show well-definedness, linearity,
 etc...
 of the maps constructed.
 The point is that all of this is built into the universal mapping property
 of free 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-modules.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Representing 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module Homomorphisms By Matrices
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 be a 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module with basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta=\{\beta_{1},\dots,\beta_{m}\}$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 be a free 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module with basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma=\{\gamma_{1},\dots,\gamma_{n}\}$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $v\in F$
\end_inset

, then for each 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq i\leq m$
\end_inset

, there exists unique 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{i}\in R$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
v=\sum_{i=1}^{m}a_{i}\beta_{i}.
\]

\end_inset

Since the 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{i}$
\end_inset

 are uniquely determined, we are justified in making the following definition:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The 
\series bold
column representation of 
\series default

\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 
\series bold
with respect to the basis
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

, denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $[v]_{\beta}$
\end_inset

, is defined by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
[v]_{\beta}:=\begin{pmatrix}a_{1}\\
\vdots\\
a_{m}
\end{pmatrix}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{propcolumnislinear}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $[\cdot]_{\beta}\colon V\to R^{m}$
\end_inset

 be given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
[\cdot]_{\beta}(v)=[v]_{\beta}
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $v\in V$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $[\cdot]_{\beta}$
\end_inset

 is an isomorphism.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\backslash
label{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We first show that 
\begin_inset Formula $[\cdot]_{\beta}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-linear.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{1},v_{2}\in V$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{1},c_{2}\in R$
\end_inset

.
 Then for each 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq i\leq m$
\end_inset

, there exists unique 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{i1},a_{i2}\in R$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
v_{1}=\sum_{i=1}^{m}a_{i1}\beta_{i}\quad\text{and}\quad v_{2}=\sum_{i=1}^{m}a_{i2}\beta_{i}.
\]

\end_inset

 Therefore we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
a_{1}v_{1}+a_{2}v_{2} & =a_{1}\sum_{i=1}^{m}a_{i1}\beta_{i}+a_{2}\sum_{i=1}^{m}a_{i2}\beta_{i}\\
 & =\sum_{i=1}^{m}(a_{1}a_{i1}+a_{2}a_{i2})\beta_{i}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

This implies 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
[a_{1}v_{1}+a_{2}v_{2}]_{\beta} & =\begin{pmatrix}a_{1}a_{11}+a_{2}a_{12}\\
\vdots\\
a_{1}a_{m1}+a_{2}a_{m2}
\end{pmatrix}\\
 & =a_{1}\begin{pmatrix}a_{11}\\
\vdots\\
a_{m1}
\end{pmatrix}+a_{2}\begin{pmatrix}a_{12}\\
\vdots\\
a_{m2}
\end{pmatrix}\\
 & =a_{1}[v_{1}]_{\beta}+a_{2}[v_{2}]_{\beta}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $[\cdot]_{\beta}$
\end_inset

 is linear.
 To see that 
\begin_inset Formula $[\cdot]_{\beta}$
\end_inset

 is an isomorphism, note that 
\begin_inset Formula $[\beta_{i}]=e_{i}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the column vector in 
\begin_inset Formula $K^{n}$
\end_inset

 whose 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

-th entry is 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 and whose entry everywhere else is 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, 
\begin_inset Formula $[\cdot]_{\beta}$
\end_inset

 restricts to a bijection on basis sets
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
[\cdot]_{\beta}\colon\{\beta_{1},\dots,\beta_{m}\}\to\{e_{1},\dots,e_{n}\},
\]

\end_inset

and so it must be an isomorphism.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Matrix Representation of a Linear Map
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-linear map from 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

.
 Then for each 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq i\leq m$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq j\leq n$
\end_inset

, there exists unique elements 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{ji}\in R$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\varphi(\beta_{i})=\sum_{j=1}^{n}a_{ji}\gamma_{j}\label{eq:matrixrepeq}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq i\leq m$
\end_inset

.
 Since the 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{ji}$
\end_inset

 are uniquely determined, we are justified in making the following definition:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The 
\series bold
matrix representation of
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 
\series bold
with respect to the bases
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 
\series bold
and
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

, denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $[\varphi]_{\beta}^{\gamma}$
\end_inset

, is defined to be the 
\begin_inset Formula $n\times m$
\end_inset

 matrix
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
[\varphi]_{\beta}^{\gamma}:=\begin{pmatrix}a_{11} & \cdots & a_{1m}\\
\vdots & \ddots & \vdots\\
a_{n1} & \cdots & a_{nm}
\end{pmatrix}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{propcommutative}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 be a linear map from 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
[\varphi]_{\beta}^{\gamma}[v]_{\beta}=[\varphi(v)]_{\gamma}
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $v\in F$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 In terms of diagrams, this proposition says that the following diagram
 is commutative
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


