end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-module.
 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is called of 
\series bold
finite presentation
\series default
 or 
\series bold
finitely presented 
\series default
if there exists an 
\begin_inset Formula $n\times m$
\end_inset

-matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is isomorphic to the cokernel of the map 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi:A^{m}\to A^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 We call 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 a 
\series bold
presentation matrix 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 We write 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd}  A^m 
\backslash
arrow[r," 
\backslash
varphi "] & A^n 
\backslash
arrow[r] & M 
\backslash
arrow[r] & 0 
\backslash
end{tikzcd}
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
to denote a presentation of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Constructive module theory is concerned with modules of finite presentation,
 that is, with modules which can be given as the cokernel of some matrix.
 All operations with modules are then represented by operations with the
 corresponding presentation matrices.
 We shall see later on that every finitely generated module over a Noetherian
 ring is finitely presented.
 As polynomial rings and localizations thereof are Noetherian every finitely
 generated module over these rings is of finite presentation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A=\mathbb{Q}[x,y,z]$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 be the submodule of 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{2}$
\end_inset

 generated by the column vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $(xy,yz)^{t}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(xz,z^{2})^{t}$
\end_inset

.
 This means we have a map
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd}[column sep=huge, row sep=0.4, ampersand replacement=
\backslash
&] A^2 
\backslash
arrow{r}{ 
\backslash
begin{pmatrix} xy & xz 
\backslash

\backslash
 yz & z^2 
\backslash
end{pmatrix} } 
\backslash
& M 
\backslash

\backslash
 e_1 
\backslash
arrow[r,mapsto,shorten >=0.2cm,shorten <=0.2cm] 
\backslash
& xye_1 + yze_2 
\backslash

\backslash
 e_2 
\backslash
arrow[r,mapsto, shorten >=0.2cm,shorten <=0.2cm] 
\backslash
& xze_1 + z^2 e_2 
\backslash
end{tikzcd}
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To obtain a presentation of 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

, we need to compute the kernel of this map.
 The kernel is generated by the column vector 
\begin_inset Formula $(-z,y)^{t}$
\end_inset

.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $(-z,y)^{t}$
\end_inset

 is the presentation matrix of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd}[column sep=huge, row sep=0.4, ampersand replacement=
\backslash
&] A 
\backslash
arrow{r}{
\backslash
begin{pmatrix} -z 
\backslash

\backslash
 y 
\backslash
end{pmatrix} } 
\backslash
& A^2 
\backslash
arrow{r}{ 
\backslash
begin{pmatrix} xy & xz 
\backslash

\backslash
 yz & z^2 
\backslash
end{pmatrix} } 
\backslash
& M 
\backslash

\backslash
 e_1 
\backslash
arrow[r,mapsto,shorten >=0.2cm,shorten <=0.2cm] 
\backslash
& -ze_1 + ye_2 
\backslash

\backslash
 
\backslash
& e_1 
\backslash
arrow[r,mapsto,shorten >=0.2cm,shorten <=0.2cm] 
\backslash
& xye_1 + yze_2 
\backslash

\backslash
 
\backslash
& e_2 
\backslash
arrow[r,mapsto, shorten >=0.2cm,shorten <=0.2cm] 
\backslash
& xze_1 + z^2 e_2 
\backslash
end{tikzcd}
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\backslash
label{modulehomomorphism}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 be two 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-modules with presentations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd}  A^m 
\backslash
arrow[r," 
\backslash
varphi "] & A^n 
\backslash
arrow[r, " 
\backslash
pi "] & M 
\backslash
arrow[r] & 0 
\backslash
end{tikzcd} 
\backslash
quad 
\backslash
mbox{and} 
\backslash
quad 
\backslash
begin{tikzcd}  A^r 
\backslash
arrow[r," 
\backslash
psi "] & A^s 
\backslash
arrow[r, " 
\backslash
kappa "] & N 
\backslash
arrow[r] & 0.
 
\backslash
end{tikzcd} 
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda:M\to N$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-module homomorphism, then there exist 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-module homomorphisms 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha:A^{m}\to A^{r}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta:A^{n}\to A^{s}$
\end_inset

 such that the following diagram commutes: 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd}  A^m 
\backslash
arrow[r," 
\backslash
varphi "] 
\backslash
arrow[d, " 
\backslash
alpha "] & A^n 
\backslash
arrow[r, " 
\backslash
pi "] 
\backslash
arrow[d, " 
\backslash
beta "] & M 
\backslash
arrow[r] 
\backslash
arrow[d, " 
\backslash
lambda "] & 0 
\backslash

\backslash
  A^r 
\backslash
arrow[r," 
\backslash
psi "] & A^s 
\backslash
arrow[r, " 
\backslash
kappa "] & N 
\backslash
arrow[r] & 0.
 
\backslash
end{tikzcd} 
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 that is, 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta\circ\varphi=\psi\circ\alpha$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\circ\pi=\kappa\circ\beta$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta:A^{n}\to A^{s}$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-module homomorphism such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta(\mbox{Im}(\varphi))\subset\mbox{Im}(\psi).$
\end_inset

 Then there exist 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-module homomorphisms 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha:A^{m}\to A^{r}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda:M\to N$
\end_inset

 such that the corresponding diagram commutes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $(1):$
\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\{e_{1},\dots,e_{n}\}$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-basis for 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{n}$
\end_inset

 and choose 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}\in A^{s}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa(x_{i})=(\lambda\circ\pi)(e_{i})$
\end_inset

.
 We define 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta(\sum_{i=1}^{n}a_{i}e_{i})=\sum_{i=1}^{n}a_{i}x_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 Obviously 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 is an 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-module homomorphism and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\circ\pi=\kappa\circ\beta$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\{f_{1},\dots,f_{m}\}$
\end_inset

 be a basis of 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{m}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $(\kappa\circ\beta\circ\varphi)(f_{i})=(\lambda\circ\pi\circ\varphi)(f_{i})=0$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta(\varphi(f_{i}))\in\mbox{Ker}(\kappa)$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore, there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{i}\in A^{r}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi(y_{i})=(\beta\circ\varphi)(f_{i})$
\end_inset

.
 We define 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha(\sum_{i=1}^{n}b_{n}f_{i})=\sum_{i=1}^{n}b_{i}y_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 Again 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 is an 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-module homomorphism and 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi\circ\alpha=\beta\circ\varphi$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $(2):$
\end_inset

 Define 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda(m)=(\kappa\circ\beta)(\tilde{m})$
\end_inset

, for some 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{m}\in A^{n}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(\tilde{m})=m$
\end_inset

.
 To see that this definition does not depend on the choice of 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{m}$
\end_inset

, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{m}+\varphi(x)$
\end_inset

 be another lift where 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in A^{m}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $(\kappa\circ\beta)(\tilde{m}+\varphi(x))=(\kappa\circ\beta)(\tilde{m})+(\kappa\circ\beta\circ\varphi)(x)=(\kappa\circ\beta)(\tilde{m})$
\end_inset

.
 Obviously, 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 is an 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-module homomorphism satisfying 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\circ\pi=\kappa\circ\beta$
\end_inset

.
 We can define 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 as in 
\begin_inset Formula $(1)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Short Exact Sequences and Splitting Modules
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A sequence of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-modules and 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-linear maps
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd} L 
\backslash
arrow[r,"
\backslash
varphi "] & M 
\backslash
arrow[r,"
\backslash
psi "] & N 
\backslash
end{tikzcd}
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
is called 
\begin_inset Formula $\textbf{exact}$
\end_inset

 
\series bold
at
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{im}\,\varphi=\ker\psi$
\end_inset

.
 A 
\begin_inset Formula $\textbf{short exact sequence}$
\end_inset

 is a sequence of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-modules and 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-linear maps
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd} 0 
\backslash
arrow[r] & L 
\backslash
arrow[r,"
\backslash
varphi "] & M 
\backslash
arrow[r,"
\backslash
psi "] & N 
\backslash
arrow[r] & 0 
\backslash
end{tikzcd}
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
which is exact at 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Five Lemma
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Suppose the following diagram of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-modules and 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-linear maps is commutative with exact rows
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd}  M_1 
\backslash
arrow[r,"
\backslash
varphi _1 "] 
\backslash
arrow[d,"
\backslash
psi _1 "] & M_2 
\backslash
arrow[r,"
\backslash
varphi _2 "] 
\backslash
arrow[d,"
\backslash
psi _2 "] &  M_3 
\backslash
arrow[r,"
\backslash
varphi _3 "] 
\backslash
arrow[d,"
\backslash
psi _3 "] & M_4 
\backslash
arrow[r,"
\backslash
varphi _4 "] 
\backslash
arrow[d,"
\backslash
psi _4 "] & M_5 
\backslash
arrow[d,"
\backslash
psi _5 "]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash

\backslash

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

M_1 ' 
\backslash
arrow[r,"
\backslash
varphi _1 '"] & M_2 '
\backslash
arrow[r,"
\backslash
varphi _2 '"] &  M_3 '
\backslash
arrow[r,"
\backslash
varphi _3 '"] & M_4 ' 
\backslash
arrow[r,"
\backslash
varphi _4 '"] & M_5 '
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{tikzcd}
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{2},\psi_{4}$
\end_inset

 are surjective and 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{5}$
\end_inset

 is injective, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{3}$
\end_inset

 is surjective.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{2},\psi_{4}$
\end_inset

 are injective and 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{1}$
\end_inset

 is surjective, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{3}$
\end_inset

 is injective.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
1.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{2},\psi_{4}$
\end_inset

 are surjective and 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{5}$
\end_inset

 is injective and let 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{3}'\in M_{3}'$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{4}$
\end_inset

 is surjective, we may choose a 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{4}\in M_{4}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{4}(u_{4})=\varphi_{3}'(u_{3}')$
\end_inset

.
 Observe that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\psi_{5}\varphi_{4}(u_{4}) & =\varphi_{4}'\psi_{4}(u_{4})\\
 & =\varphi_{4}'\varphi_{3}'(u_{3}')\\
 & =0.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{4}(u_{4})=0$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{5}$
\end_inset

 is injective.
 Therefore we may choose a 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{3}\in M_{3}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{3}(u_{3})=u_{4}$
\end_inset

 (by exactness of the top row).
 Now observe that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\varphi_{3}'(u_{3}'-\psi_{3}(u_{3})) & =\varphi_{3}'(u_{3}')-\varphi_{3}'\psi_{3}(u_{3})\\
 & =\psi_{4}(u_{4})-\psi_{4}\varphi_{3}(u_{3})\\
 & =\psi_{4}(u_{4})-\psi_{4}(u_{4})\\
 & =0.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Therefore we may choose a 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{2}'\in M_{2}'$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{2}'(u_{2}')=u_{3}'-\psi_{3}(u_{3})$
\end_inset

 (by exactness of the bottom row).
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{2}$
\end_inset

 is surjective, we may choose a 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{2}\in M_{2}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{2}(u_{2})=u_{2}'$
\end_inset

.
 Finally we see that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\psi_{3}(\varphi_{2}(u_{2})+u_{3}) & =\psi_{3}\varphi_{2}(u_{2})+\psi_{3}(u_{3})\\
 & =\varphi_{2}'\psi_{2}(u_{2})+\psi_{3}(u_{3})\\
 & =\varphi_{2}'(u_{2}')+\psi_{3}(u_{3})\\
 & =u_{3}'-\psi_{3}(u_{3})+\psi_{3}(u_{3})\\
 & =u_{3}'.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{3}$
\end_inset

 is surjective.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
2.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{2},\psi_{4}$
\end_inset

 are injective and 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{1}$
\end_inset

 is surjective and let 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{3}\in\ker\psi_{3}$
\end_inset

.
 Observe that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\psi_{4}\varphi_{3}(u_{3}) & =\varphi_{3}'\psi_{3}(u_{3})\\
 & =\varphi_{3}'(0)\\
 & =0.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{3}(u_{3})=0$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{4}$
\end_inset

 is injective.
 Therefore we may choose a 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{2}\in M_{2}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{2}(u_{2})=u_{3}$
\end_inset

 (by exactness of the top row).
 Now observe that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\varphi_{2}'\psi_{2}(u_{2}) & =\psi_{3}\varphi_{2}(u_{2})\\
 & =\psi_{3}(u_{3})\\
 & =0.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Therefore we may choose a 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{1}'\in M_{1}'$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{1}'(u_{1}')=\psi_{2}(u_{2})$
\end_inset

 (by exactness of the bottom row).
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{1}$
\end_inset

 is surjective, we may choose a 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{1}\in M_{1}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{1}(u_{1})=u_{1}'$
\end_inset

.
 Now observe that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\psi_{2}\varphi_{1}(u_{1}) & =\varphi_{1}'\psi_{1}(u_{1})\\
 & =\varphi_{1}'(u_{1}')\\
 & =\psi_{2}(u_{2}).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{1}(u_{1})=u_{2}$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{2}$
\end_inset

 is injective.
 Therefore
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
u_{3} & =\varphi_{2}(u_{2})\\
 & =\varphi_{2}\varphi_{1}(u_{1})\\
 & =0,
\end{align*}

\end_inset

which implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\ker\psi_{3}=0$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{3}$
\end_inset

 is injective.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
