\begin_layout Standard
Moreover, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{1}$
\end_inset

 is injective, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\varphi_{1}}$
\end_inset

 is injective; and if 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{2}'$
\end_inset

 is surjective, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\varphi_{2}'}$
\end_inset

 is surjective.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Step 1: 
\series default
We first define the maps in question.
 Define 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\varphi_{1}}\colon\ker\psi_{1}\to\ker\psi_{2}$
\end_inset

 by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\widetilde{\varphi_{1}}(u_{1})=\varphi_{1}(u_{1})
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{1}\in\ker\psi_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\varphi_{1}}$
\end_inset

 lands in 
\begin_inset Formula $\ker\psi_{2}$
\end_inset

 by the commutativity of the diagram.
 Indeed,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\psi_{2}\widetilde{\varphi_{1}}(u_{1}) & =\psi_{2}\varphi_{1}(u_{1})\\
 & =\varphi_{1}'\psi_{1}(u_{1})\\
 & =\varphi_{1}'(0)\\
 & =0
\end{align*}

\end_inset

implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\varphi_{1}}(u_{1})\in\ker\psi_{2}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{1}\in\ker\psi_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 Also note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\varphi_{1}}$
\end_inset

 is an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module homomorphism since 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{1}$
\end_inset

 is an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module homomorphism.
 Similarly, we define 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\varphi_{2}}\colon\ker\psi_{2}\to\ker\psi_{3}$
\end_inset

 by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\widetilde{\varphi_{2}}(u_{2})=\varphi_{2}(u_{2})
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{2}\in\ker\psi_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Next we define 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial\colon\ker\psi_{3}\to\mathrm{coker}\,\psi_{1}$
\end_inset

 as follows: let 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{3}\in\ker\psi_{3}$
\end_inset

.
 Choose 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{2}\in M_{2}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{2}(u_{2})=u_{3}$
\end_inset

 (such an element exists because 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{2}$
\end_inset

 is surjective by exactness of the first row).
 By the commutativity of the diagram, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\varphi_{2}'\psi_{2}(u_{2}) & =\psi_{3}\varphi_{2}(u_{2})\\
 & =\psi_{3}(u_{3})\\
 & =0.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{2}(u_{2})\in\ker\varphi_{2}'$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore there exists a unique 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{1}'\in M_{1}'$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{1}'(u_{1}')=\psi_{2}(u_{2})$
\end_inset

 (by exactness of the second row).
 We set 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\partial(u_{3})=\overline{u_{1}'}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{u_{1}'}$
\end_inset

 is the coset in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{coker}\,\psi_{1}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{1}'$
\end_inset

 as a representative.
 We must check that 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial$
\end_inset

 defined in this is in fact a well-defined map.
 There was one choice that we made in our construction, namely the lift
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{3}$
\end_inset

 under 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{2}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 So let 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{2}$
\end_inset

 be another element in 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{2}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{2}(v_{2})=u_{3}$
\end_inset

.
 Denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{1}'$
\end_inset

 to be the unique element in 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{1}'$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{1}'(v_{1}')=\psi_{2}(v_{2})$
\end_inset

.
 We must show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{u_{1}'}=\overline{v_{1}'}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{coker}\,\psi_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 In other words, we must show that 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{1}'-u_{1}'\in\mathrm{im}\,\psi_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 Observe that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\varphi_{2}(v_{2}-u_{2}) & =\varphi_{2}(v_{2})-\varphi_{2}(u_{2})\\
 & =u_{3}-u_{3}\\
 & =0
\end{align*}

\end_inset

implies 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{2}-u_{2}\in\ker\varphi_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 It follows that there exists a unique element 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{1}\in M_{1}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{1}(u_{1})=v_{2}-u_{2}$
\end_inset

 (by exactness of the first row).
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\varphi_{1}'\psi_{1}(u_{1}) & =\psi_{2}\varphi_{1}(u_{1})\\
 & =\psi_{2}(v_{2}-u_{2})\\
 & =\psi_{2}(v_{2})-\psi_{2}(u_{2})\\
 & =\varphi_{1}'(v_{1}')-\varphi_{1}'(u_{1}')\\
 & =\varphi_{1}'(v_{1}'-u_{1}')
\end{align*}

\end_inset

implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{1}(u_{1})=v_{1}'-u_{1}'$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{1}'$
\end_inset

 is injective (by exactness of the second row).
 It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{1}'-u_{1}'\in\mathrm{im}\,\psi_{1}$
\end_inset

, and hence 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial$
\end_inset

 is well-defined.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Finally, we define 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\varphi_{1}'}\colon\mathrm{coker}\,\psi_{1}\to\mathrm{coker}\,\psi_{2}$
\end_inset

 by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\overline{\varphi_{1}'}(\overline{u_{1}'})=\overline{\varphi_{1}'(u_{1}')}
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{u_{1}'}\in\mathrm{coker}\,\psi_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 The map 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\varphi_{1}'}$
\end_inset

 is well-defined by the commutativity of the diagram.
 Indeed, let 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{1}'$
\end_inset

 be another representative of the coset 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{u_{1}'}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{coker}\,\psi_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 Choose 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{1}\in M_{1}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{1}'-u_{1}'=\psi_{1}(u_{1})$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\psi_{2}\varphi_{1}(u_{1}) & =\varphi_{1}'\psi_{1}(u_{1})\\
 & =\varphi_{1}'(v_{1}'-u_{1}')\\
 & =\varphi_{1}'(v_{1}')-\varphi_{1}'(u_{1}').
\end{align*}

\end_inset

It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{1}'(v_{1}')-\varphi_{1}'(u_{1}')\in\mathrm{im}\,\psi_{2}$
\end_inset

, and hence 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{1}'(v_{1}')$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{1}'(u_{1}')$
\end_inset

 represent the same coset in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{coker}\,\psi_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Similarly, we define 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\varphi_{2}'}\colon\mathrm{coker}\,\psi_{2}\to\mathrm{coker}\,\psi_{3}$
\end_inset

 by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\overline{\varphi_{2}'}(\overline{u_{2}'})=\overline{\varphi_{2}'(u_{2}')}
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{u_{2}'}\in\mathrm{coker}\,\psi_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Step 2: 
\series default
Now that we've defined the maps in question, we will now show that the sequence
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{snakelemma})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is exact as well as prove the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

moreover
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 part of the proposition.
 First we show exactness at 
\begin_inset Formula $\ker\psi_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Observe that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\widetilde{\varphi_{2}}\widetilde{\varphi_{1}}(u_{1}) & =\varphi_{2}\varphi_{1}(u_{1})\\
 & =0
\end{align*}

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{1}\in\ker\psi_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\ker\widetilde{\varphi_{2}}\supseteq\mathrm{im}\,\widetilde{\varphi_{1}}$
\end_inset

.
 Conversely, let 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{2}\in\ker\widetilde{\varphi_{2}}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{2}\in\ker\varphi_{2}\cap\ker\psi_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 By exactness of the top row in 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{snakelemmad})
\end_layout

\end_inset

, we may choose a 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{1}\in M_{1}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{1}(u_{1})=u_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Moreover, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\varphi_{1}'\psi_{1}(u_{1}) & =\psi_{2}\varphi_{1}(u_{1})\\
 & =\psi_{2}(u_{2})\\
 & =0
\end{align*}

\end_inset

implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{1}(u_{1})=0$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{1}'$
\end_inset

 is injective (by exactness of the bottom row in 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{snakelemmad})
\end_layout

\end_inset

).
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{1}\in\ker\psi_{1}$
\end_inset

, and so 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{2}\in\mathrm{im}\,\widetilde{\varphi_{1}}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\ker\widetilde{\varphi_{2}}\subseteq\mathrm{im}\,\widetilde{\varphi_{1}}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Next we show exactness at 
\begin_inset Formula $\ker\psi_{3}$
\end_inset

: let 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{3}\in\ker\partial$
\end_inset

.
 Choose 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{2}\in M_{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{1}'\in M_{1}'$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{2}(u_{2})=u_{3}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{1}'(u_{1}')=\psi_{2}(u_{2})$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
0 & =\partial(u_{3})\\
 & =\overline{u_{1}'}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

implies 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{1}'\in\mathrm{im}\,\psi_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 Choose 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{1}\in M_{1}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{1}(u_{1})=u_{1}'$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\psi_{2}(u_{2}-\varphi_{1}(u_{1})) & =\psi_{2}(u_{2})-\psi_{2}\varphi_{1}(u_{1})\\
 & =\psi_{2}(u_{2})-\varphi_{1}'\psi_{1}(u_{1})\\
 & =\psi_{2}(u_{2})-\varphi_{1}'(u_{1}')\\
 & =\psi_{2}(u_{2})-\psi_{2}(u_{2})\\
 & =0
\end{align*}

\end_inset

implies 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{2}-\varphi_{1}(u_{1})\in\ker\psi_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Furthermore, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\varphi_{2}(u_{2}-\varphi_{1}(u_{1})) & =\varphi_{2}(u_{2})-\varphi_{2}\varphi_{1}(u_{1})\\
 & =\varphi_{2}(u_{2})\\
 & =u_{3}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{3}\in\mathrm{im}\,\widetilde{\varphi_{2}}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\ker\partial\subseteq\mathrm{im}\,\widetilde{\varphi_{2}}$
\end_inset

.
 Convsersely, let 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{3}\in\mathrm{im}\,\widetilde{\varphi_{2}}$
\end_inset

.
 Choose 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{2}\in\ker\psi_{2}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{2}(u_{2})=u_{3}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $0\in M_{1}'$
\end_inset

 is the unique element in 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{1}'$
\end_inset

 which maps to 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{2}(u_{2})=0$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial(u_{3})=\overline{0}$
\end_inset

 which implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\ker\partial\supseteq\mathrm{im}\,\widetilde{\varphi_{2}}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Next we show exactness at 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{coker}\,\psi_{1}$
\end_inset

: let 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{u_{1}'}\in\ker\overline{\varphi_{1}'}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{1}'(u_{1}')=\psi_{2}(u_{2})$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{2}\in M_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Moreover,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\psi_{3}\varphi_{2}(u_{2}) & =\varphi_{2}'\psi_{2}(u_{2})\\
 & =\varphi_{2}'\varphi_{1}'(u_{1}')\\
 & =0
\end{align*}

\end_inset

implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{2}(u_{2})\in\ker\psi_{3}$
\end_inset

.
 Also we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial(\varphi_{2}(u_{2}))=\overline{u_{1}'}$
\end_inset

, and so 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{u_{1}'}\in\mathrm{im}\partial$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\ker\overline{\varphi}_{1}'\subseteq\mathrm{im}\partial$
\end_inset

.
 Conversely, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{u_{1}'}\in\mathrm{im}\partial$
\end_inset

.
 Choose 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{3}\in M_{3}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{2}\in M_{2}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{2}(u_{2})=u_{3}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{2}(u_{2})=\varphi_{1}'(u_{1}')$
\end_inset

.
 It follows that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\overline{\varphi_{1}'}(\overline{u_{1}'}) & =\overline{\varphi_{1}'(u_{1}')}\\
 & =\overline{\psi_{2}(u_{2})}\\
 & =\overline{0}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{coker}\,\psi_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\ker\overline{\varphi_{1}'}\supseteq\mathrm{im}\partial$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Next we check exactness at 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{coker}\,\psi_{2}$
\end_inset

: let 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{u_{2}'}\in\ker\overline{\varphi_{2}'}$
\end_inset

.
 Choose 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{3}\in M_{3}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{3}(u_{3})=\varphi_{2}'(u_{2}')$
\end_inset

 and choose 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{2}\in M_{2}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{2}(u_{2})=u_{3}$
\end_inset

.
 Since
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\varphi_{2}'(u_{2}'-\psi_{2}(u_{2})) & =\varphi_{2}'(u_{2}')-\varphi_{2}'\psi_{2}(u_{2})\\
 & =\varphi_{2}'(u_{2}')-\psi_{3}\varphi_{2}(u_{2})\\
 & =\varphi_{2}'(u_{2}')-\psi_{3}(u_{3})\\
 & =\varphi_{2}'(u_{2}')-\varphi_{2}'(u_{2}')\\
 & =0,
\end{align*}

\end_inset

it follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{2}'-\psi_{2}(u_{2})\in\ker\varphi_{2}'$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore there exists a unique 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{1}'\in M_{1}'$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{1}'(u_{1}')=u_{2}'-\psi_{2}(u_{2})$
\end_inset

 (by exactness of the bottom row in 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{snakelemmad})
\end_layout

\end_inset

).
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\overline{\varphi_{1}'}(\overline{u_{1}'}) & =\overline{\varphi_{1}'(u_{1}')}\\
 & =\overline{u_{2}'-\psi_{2}(u_{2})}\\
 & =\overline{u_{2}'}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{coker}\,\psi_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{u_{2}'}\in\mathrm{im}\,\overline{\varphi_{2}'}$
\end_inset

 and hence 
\begin_inset Formula $\ker\overline{\varphi_{2}'}\subseteq\mathrm{im}\,\overline{\varphi_{1}'}$
\end_inset

.
 Conversely, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{u_{2}'}\in\mathrm{im}\,\overline{\varphi_{2}'}$
\end_inset

.
 Choose 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{1}'\in M_{1}'$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{1}'(u_{1}')=u_{2}'$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
0 & =\varphi_{2}'\varphi_{1}'(u_{1}')\\
 & =\varphi_{2}'(u_{2}')
\end{align*}

\end_inset

implies 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{2}'\in\ker\varphi_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\varphi_{2}'}(\overline{u_{2}'})=\overline{0}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{coker}\,\psi_{3}$
\end_inset

, and it follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\ker\overline{\varphi_{2}'}\supseteq\mathrm{im}\,\overline{\varphi_{1}'}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Finally, we prove the moreover part of this proposition.
 Suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{1}$
\end_inset

 is injective.
 We want to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\varphi_{1}}$
\end_inset

 is injective.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{1}\in\ker\widetilde{\varphi_{1}}$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
0 & =\widetilde{\varphi_{1}}(u_{1})\\
 & =\varphi_{1}(u_{1})
\end{align*}

\end_inset

implies 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{1}=0$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{1}$
\end_inset

 is injective.
 It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\varphi_{1}}$
\end_inset

 is injective.
 Now suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{2}'$
\end_inset

 is surjective.
 We want to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\varphi_{2}'}$
\end_inset

 is surjective.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{u_{3}'}\in\mathrm{coker}\,\psi_{3}$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{2}'$
\end_inset

 is surjective, we may choose a 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{2}'\in M_{2}'$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{2}'(u_{2}')=u_{3}'$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\overline{\varphi_{2}'}(\overline{u_{2}'}) & =\overline{\varphi_{2}'(u_{2}')}\\
 & =\overline{u_{3}'}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\varphi_{2}'}$
\end_inset

 is surjective.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Split Short Exact Sequences
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module and let 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-submodule of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{equation}
\backslash
