\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{tikzcd}
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We first need to check that the restriction of 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\ker\psi$
\end_inset

 lands in 
\begin_inset Formula $\ker\iota_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $w\in\ker\psi$
\end_inset

.
 Then observe that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\iota_{1}\varphi(w) & =[\varphi(w),0]\\
 & =[0,-\psi(w)]\\
 & =[0,0],
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where we write 
\begin_inset Formula $[u,v]$
\end_inset

 for the equivalence class of 
\begin_inset Formula $(u,v)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $E+_{M}N$
\end_inset

.
 It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(w)\in\ker\iota_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus the map 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi|_{\ker\psi}\colon\ker\psi\to\ker\iota_{1}$
\end_inset

 makes sense.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Clearly, 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi|_{\ker\psi}$
\end_inset

 is an injective 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-linear map since 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is an injective 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-linear map.
 It remains to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi|_{\ker\psi}$
\end_inset

 is surjective.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $u\in\ker\iota_{1}$
\end_inset

 (so 
\begin_inset Formula $[u,0]=[0,0]$
\end_inset

).
 This implies that there exists a 
\begin_inset Formula $w\in M$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $u=\varphi(w)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi(w)=0$
\end_inset

.
 In other words, this implies the map 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi|_{\ker\psi}$
\end_inset

 is surjective.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Modules over a PID
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Annihilators and Torsion 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be an integral domain, let 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $u\in M$
\end_inset

.
 We define the 
\series bold
annihilator 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 to be
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
0:_{R}u=\{a\in R\mid au=0\}.
\]

\end_inset

We say 
\begin_inset Formula $0:_{R}u$
\end_inset

 is the set of all elements in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 which 
\series bold
kills 
\series default

\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $0:_{R}u\neq0$
\end_inset

, then we say 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 is a 
\series bold
torsion element 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 We denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{\mathrm{tor}}$
\end_inset

 to be the set of all torsion elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 We say 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
torsion-free 
\series default
if 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{\mathrm{tor}}=0$
\end_inset

, that is, the only torsion element of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

.
 We say 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
torsion 
\series default
if 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{\mathrm{tor}}=M$
\end_inset

, that is, every element in 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is a torsion element.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be an integral domain, let 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $u\in M$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $0:_{R}u$
\end_inset

 is an ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{\mathrm{tor}}$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-submodule of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We first show that 
\begin_inset Formula $0:_{R}u$
\end_inset

 is an ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 Observe that 
\begin_inset Formula $0\in0:_{R}u$
\end_inset

 which implies 
\begin_inset Formula $0:_{R}u$
\end_inset

 is nonempty.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in0:_{R}u$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in R$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
(ax+y)u & =axu+yu\\
 & =0+0\\
 & =0
\end{align*}

\end_inset

implies 
\begin_inset Formula $ax+y\in0:_{R}u$
\end_inset

.
 It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $0:_{R}u$
\end_inset

 is an ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Now we will show that 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{\mathrm{tor}}$
\end_inset

 is an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-submodule of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 Observe that 
\begin_inset Formula $0\in M_{\mathrm{tor}}$
\end_inset

 which implies 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{\mathrm{tor}}$
\end_inset

 is nonempty.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $u,v\in M_{\mathrm{tor}}$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in R$
\end_inset

.
 Choose 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in R\backslash\{0\}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $xu=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $yv=0$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $xy\neq0$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is an integral domain, and moreover we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
xy(au+v) & =xyau+xyv\\
 & =ya(xu)+x(yv)\\
 & =0+0\\
 & =0,
\end{align*}

\end_inset

which implies 
\begin_inset Formula $0:_{R}(au+v)\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $au+v\in M_{\mathrm{tor}}$
\end_inset

, which implies 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{\mathrm{tor}}$
\end_inset

 is an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-submodule of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be a PID, let 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 be a prime in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

, let 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $u\in M$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{k}u=0$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $k\geq0$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
0:_{R}u=\langle p^{i}\rangle
\]

\end_inset

for some 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq i\leq k$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Choose 
\begin_inset Formula $i\geq0$
\end_inset

 to be the smallest integer such that 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{i}u=0$
\end_inset

.
 We claim that 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle p^{i}\rangle=0:_{R}u$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{i}\in0:_{R}u$
\end_inset

, we certainly have 
\begin_inset Formula $0:_{R}u\supseteq\langle p^{i}\rangle.$
\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $0:_{R}u\supseteq\langle q^{j}\rangle$
\end_inset

 for some other prime 
\begin_inset Formula $q\neq p$
\end_inset

, then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
0:_{R}u & \supseteq\langle p^{i},q^{j}\rangle\\
 & =\langle1\rangle
\end{align*}

\end_inset

since 
\begin_inset Formula $\gcd(p^{i},q^{j})=1$
\end_inset

.
 In this case, 
\begin_inset Formula $i=0$
\end_inset

.
 Otherwise, 
\begin_inset Formula $i\neq0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $0:_{R}u=\langle p^{i}\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Embedding finitely generated torsion-free module in 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{d}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\backslash
label{lemmaembeddingtorsionfreeoverintdomain}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Every finitely generated torsion-free module 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 over an integral domain 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 can be embedded in a finite free 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module.
 More precisely, if 
\begin_inset Formula $M\neq0$
\end_inset

, then there is an embedding 
\begin_inset Formula $M\hookrightarrow R^{d}$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $d\geq1$
\end_inset

 such that the image of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 intersects the standard coordinate axis of 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{d}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 be the fraction field of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{1},\dots,u_{n}$
\end_inset

 be a generating set for 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 as an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module.
 We will show 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is an upper bounded on the size of any 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-linearly independent subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon R^{n}\to M$
\end_inset

 be the linear map given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varphi(e_{i})=u_{i}
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq i\leq n$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{1},\dots,v_{k}$
\end_inset

 be linearly independent in 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 Choose 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{v}_{1},\dots,\widetilde{v}_{k}\in R^{n}$
\end_inset

 such that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varphi(\widetilde{v}_{j})=v_{j}
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq j\leq k$
\end_inset

.
 We claim that 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\widetilde{v}_{1},\dots,\widetilde{v}_{k}\}$
\end_inset

 is linearly independent.
 Indeed, suppose
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
a_{1}\widetilde{v}_{1}+\cdots+a_{k}\widetilde{v}_{k}=0\label{eq:inverseimagelinearindislinearind}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

for some 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{1},\dots,a_{k}\in R$
\end_inset

.
 Then applying 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 to both sides of 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:inverseimagelinearindislinearind})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 gives us
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a_{1}v_{1}+\cdots+a_{k}v_{k}=0
\]

\end_inset

which implies 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{1}=\cdots=a_{k}=0$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $\{v_{1},\dots,v_{k}\}$
\end_inset

 is linearly independent.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\widetilde{v}_{1},\dots,\widetilde{v}_{k}\}$
\end_inset

 is linearly independent.
 In fact, we claim that 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\widetilde{v}_{1},\dots,\widetilde{v}_{k}\}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

-linearly independent in 
\begin_inset Formula $K^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, suppose
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
x_{1}\widetilde{v}_{1}+\cdots+x_{k}\widetilde{v}_{k}=0\label{eq:inverseimagelinearindislinenearind2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

for some 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}\dots,x_{k}\in K$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $d\in R$
\end_inset

 be the common denominator of 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1},\dots,x_{k}$
\end_inset

.
 Then multiplying 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 to both sides of 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:inverseimagelinearindislinenearind2})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 gives us
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(dx_{1})\widetilde{v}_{1}+\cdots+(dx_{k})\widetilde{v}_{k}=0
\]

\end_inset

which implies 
\begin_inset Formula $dx_{1}=\cdots=dx_{k}=0$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\widetilde{v}_{1},\dots,\widetilde{v}_{k}\}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-linearly independent.
 This further implies 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}=\cdots=x_{k}=0$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $d\neq0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is an integral domain.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\widetilde{v}_{1},\dots,\widetilde{v}_{k}\}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

-linearly independent in 
\begin_inset Formula $K^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Now it follows from linear algebra over fields that 
\begin_inset Formula $k\leq n$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

From the bound 
\begin_inset Formula $k\leq n$
\end_inset

, there is a linearly independent subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 with maximal size, say 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{1},\dots,w_{d}$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sum_{j=1}^{d}Rw_{j}\cong R^{d}.
\]

\end_inset

We will find a scalar multiple of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 inside of this.
 For any 
\begin_inset Formula $u\in M$
\end_inset

, the set 
\begin_inset Formula $\{u,w_{1},\dots,w_{d}\}$
\end_inset

 is linearly independent by maximality of 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

, so there is a nontrivial relation
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
au+\sum_{i=1}^{d}a_{i}w_{i}=0,
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $a,a_{1},\dots,a_{d}\in R$
\end_inset

, necessarily with 
\begin_inset Formula $a\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 Thus
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
au\in\sum_{j=1}^{d}Rw_{j}.
\]

\end_inset

In particular, for each 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq i\leq n$
\end_inset

, there exists a nonzero 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{i}\in R$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a_{i}u_{i}\in\sum_{j=1}^{d}Rw_{j}.
\]

\end_inset

Setting 
\begin_inset Formula $a=a_{1}\cdots a_{n}$
\end_inset

 and using the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is an integral domain and 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is torsion free, we see that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
au_{i}\in\sum_{j=1}^{d}Rw_{j}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $aM\subseteq\sum_{j=1}^{d}Rw_{j}$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is an integral domain, multiplying by 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 is an isomorphism of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $aM$
\end_inset

, so we have the sequence of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-linear maps
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
M & \to aM\\
 & \hookrightarrow\sum_{j=1}^{d}Rw_{j}\\
 & \to R^{d}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where the last map is an isomorphism.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Submodules of a finite free module over a PID
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theoremsubmodoffreeisfreewhenrispid}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 When 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is a PID, any submodule of a free 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module of rank 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is free of rank 
\begin_inset Formula $\leq n$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We may assume the free 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module is literally 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{n}$
\end_inset

 and will induct on 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
 The case where 
\begin_inset Formula $n=1$
\end_inset

 is true since 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is a PID: every 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-submodule of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is an ideal, hence of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $Ra$
\end_inset

 since all ideals in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 are principal, and 
\begin_inset Formula $Ra\cong R$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-modules when 
\begin_inset Formula $a\neq0$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is an integral domain.
 Say 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq1$
\end_inset

 and the theorem is proved for 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $M\subseteq R^{n+1}$
\end_inset

 be a submodule.
 We want to show 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is free of rank 
\begin_inset Formula $\leq n+1$
\end_inset

.
 View 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
M\subseteq R^{n+1}=R\oplus R^{n}
\]

\end_inset

and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi\colon R\oplus R^{n}\to R^{n}$
\end_inset

 be the projection to the second component of this direct sum.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
N=\pi(M)\subseteq R^{n}
\]

\end_inset

is free of rank 
\begin_inset Formula $\leq n$
\end_inset

 by the induction hypothesis.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

 maps 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 onto 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 is free (and hence projective), we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
M\cong N\oplus\ker\pi|_{M}
\]

\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula $\ker\pi|_{M}=M\cap(R\oplus0)$
\end_inset

.
 All submodules of 
\begin_inset Formula $R\oplus0\cong R$
\end_inset

 are free of rank 
\begin_inset Formula $\leq1$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $N\oplus\ker\pi|_{M}$
\end_inset

 is free of rank 
\begin_inset Formula $\leq n+1$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is as well.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Using Zorn's Lemma, one can show that 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Theorem~(
\backslash
ref{theoremsubmodoffreeisfreewhenrispid})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 holds for non-finitely generated free modules too: any submodule of a free
 module over a PID is free.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{cor}
\backslash
label{cor}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 When 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is a PID, every finitely generated torsion-free 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module is a finite free 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{cor}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 By 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Lemma~(
\backslash
ref{lemmaembeddingtorsionfreeoverintdomain})
\end_layout

\end_inset

, such a module embeds into a finite free 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module, so it is finite free too by 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Theorem~(
\backslash
ref{theoremsubmodoffreeisfreewhenrispid})
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{cor}
\backslash
label{cor}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be a PID.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $M,M',M''$
\end_inset

 be 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-modules such that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
M''\subseteq M'\subseteq M
\]

\end_inset

and such that 
\begin_inset Formula $M\cong R^{n}\cong M''$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $M'\cong R^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{cor}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is free of rank 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $M'$
\end_inset

 is a submodule, 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Theorem~(
\backslash
ref{theoremsubmodoffreeisfreewhenrispid})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 tells us that 
\begin_inset Formula $M'\cong A^{m}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $m\leq n$
\end_inset

.
 Using 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Theorem~(
\backslash
ref{theoremsubmodoffreeisfreewhenrispid})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 again on 
\begin_inset Formula $M''$
\end_inset

 as a submodule of 
\begin_inset Formula $M'$
\end_inset

, we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $M''\cong R^{k}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $k\leq m$
\end_inset

.
 By hypothesis, 
\begin_inset Formula $M''\cong R^{k}$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $k=n$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is commutative and hence 
\begin_inset Formula $m=n$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Finitely generated modules over PID is isomorphic to free + torsion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{cor}
\backslash
label{cor}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be a PID and let 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 be a finitely generated 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
M\cong F\oplus M_{\mathrm{tor}}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 is free.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{cor}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Observe that 
\begin_inset Formula $M\slash M_{\mathrm{tor}}$
\end_inset

 is torsion-free and finitely generated as an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module.
 Indeed, it is torsion-free since if 
\begin_inset Formula $au\in M_{\mathrm{tor}}$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $a\neq0$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $u\in M_{\mathrm{tor}}$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is an integral domain.
 It is finitely generated since it is the homomorphic image of a finitely
 generated module.
 Therefore by the previous theorem, 
\begin_inset Formula $M\slash M_{\mathrm{tor}}$
\end_inset

 is free.
 Therefore the short exact sequence
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
label{diagram}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd} 0 
\backslash
arrow[r] & M_{
\backslash
mathrm{tor}}  
\backslash
arrow[r] &   M 
\backslash
arrow[r] &  M
\backslash
slash M_{
\backslash
mathrm{tor}} 
\backslash
arrow[r] & 0 
\backslash
end{tikzcd} 
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
splits.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $M\cong F\oplus M_{\mathrm{tor}}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $F=M\slash M_{\mathrm{tor}}$
\end_inset

 is free.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be a PID and let 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 be a torsion 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module.
 For any prime 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

, set
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Gamma_{p}(M)=\bigcup_{k\geq0}(0:_{M}p^{k})=\{u\in M\mid p^{k}u=0\text{ for some }k\geq0\}.
\]

\end_inset

Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
M\cong\bigoplus_{p\text{ prime}}\Gamma_{p}(M).
\]

\end_inset

Furthermore, if 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is finitely-generated, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma_{p}(M)=0$
\end_inset

 for all but finitely many 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $0\neq a\in A$
\end_inset

.
 Then there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $0\neq r\in R$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $ra=0$
\end_inset

.
 Write
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
r=p_{1}^{b_{1}}\cdots p_{k}^{b_{k}}.
\]

\end_inset

Now observe that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
(p_{2}^{b_{2}}p_{3}^{b_{3}}\cdots p_{k}^{b_{k}})a & \in A_{p_{2}}\\
(p_{1}^{b_{2}}p_{3}^{b_{3}}\cdots p_{k}^{b_{k}})a & \in A_{p_{3}}\\
 & \vdots\\
(p_{1}^{b_{2}}p_{2}^{b_{3}}\cdots p_{k-1}^{b_{k-1}})a & \in A_{p_{k}}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

We claim that 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in A_{p_{1}}+A_{p_{2}}\cdots+A_{p_{k}}$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\gcd(p_{2}^{b_{2}}p_{3}^{b_{3}}\cdots p_{k}^{b_{k}},p_{1}^{b_{2}}p_{3}^{b_{3}}\cdots p_{k}^{b_{k}},\dots,p_{1}^{b_{2}}p_{2}^{b_{3}}\cdots p_{k-1}^{b_{k-1}})=1.
\]

\end_inset

Thus there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{1},r_{2},\dots,r_{k}$
\end_inset

 such that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sum r_{i}p_{1}^{b_{1}}\cdots\widehat{p_{i}^{b_{i}}}\cdots p_{k}^{b_{k}}=1.
\]

\end_inset

Therefore
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
a & =\sum r_{i}p_{1}^{b_{1}}\cdots\widehat{p_{i}^{b_{i}}}\cdots p_{k}^{b_{k}}a\\
 & \in A_{p_{1}}+A_{p_{2}}\cdots+A_{p_{k}}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

To see that the sum is direct, suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in A_{p}\cap\sum_{q\neq p}A_{q}$
\end_inset

.
 Choose 
\begin_inset Formula $k\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{k}a=0$
\end_inset

 and choose 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{q_{i}}\in A_{q_{i}}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{i}^{k_{i}}a=0$
\end_inset

 such that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a=a_{q_{1}}+\cdots+a_{q_{m}}.
\]

\end_inset

If 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=\prod_{i=1}^{m}q_{i}^{k_{i}}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{k}a=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha a=0$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\gcd(\alpha,p^{k})=1$
\end_inset

, we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 is killed by all of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $a=0$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $1\in R$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Aligned Bases
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There is a convenient way of picturing any submodule of a finite free module
 over a PID: bases can be chosen for the module and submodule that are aligned
 nicely, as follows.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be a PID, let 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 be a finite free 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $M'$
\end_inset

 be a submodule of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 A basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\{u_{1},\dots,u_{n}\}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 and a basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\{a_{1}u_{1},\dots,a_{m}u_{m}\}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $M'$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{i}\in R\backslash\{0\}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $m\leq n$
\end_inset

 is called a pair of 
\series bold
aligned 
\series default
bases.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Any finite free 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 of rank 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq1$
\end_inset

 and nonzero submodule 
\begin_inset Formula $M'$
\end_inset

 of rank 
\begin_inset Formula $m\leq n$
\end_inset

 admit a pair of aligned bases: there is a basis 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{1},\dots,u_{n}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 and nonzero 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{1},\dots,a_{m}\in R$
\end_inset

 such that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
M=\bigoplus_{i=1}^{n}Ru_{i}\quad\text{and}\quad M'=\bigoplus_{j=1}^{m}Ra_{j}u_{j}.
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Define 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 to be the set of ideals 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(M')$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon M\to R$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-linear.
 This includes nonzero ideals; for example, let 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 have 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\{e_{1},\dots,e_{n}\}$
\end_inset

.
 Choose any nonzero 
\begin_inset Formula $u'\in M'$
\end_inset

 and write 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u'=a_{1}e_{1}+\cdots+a_{n}e_{n}.
\]

\end_inset

Then since 
\begin_inset Formula $u'\neq0$
\end_inset

, we must have 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{i}\neq0$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

, and so 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{i}^{\star}(u')=a_{i}$
\end_inset

 is nonzero.
 Hence 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{i}^{\star}(M')\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Any nonzero ideal in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is contained in only finitely many ideals since 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is a PID, so 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 contains maximal members with respect to inclusion.
 Call one of these maximal members 
\begin_inset Formula $Ra_{1}$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{1}\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $Ra_{1}=\varphi_{1}(M')$
\end_inset

 for some linear map 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{1}\colon M\to R$
\end_inset

.
 There exists some 
\begin_inset Formula $v'\in M'$
\end_inset

 such that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a_{1}=\varphi_{1}(v').
\]

\end_inset

Eventually we are going to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{1}$
\end_inset

 takes the value 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

We claim that for any linear map 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon M\to R$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{1}\mid\varphi(v')$
\end_inset

.
 To show this, set 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(v')=a_{\varphi}\in R$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is a PID, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $Ra_{1}+Ra_{\varphi}=Rd$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $Ra_{1}\subseteq Rd$
\end_inset

.
 Then there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in R$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $d=xa_{1}+ya_{\varphi}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
d & =xa_{1}+ya_{\varphi}\\
 & =x\varphi_{1}(v')+y\varphi(v')\\
 & =(x\varphi_{1}+y\varphi)(v'),
\end{align*}

\end_inset

and so 
\begin_inset Formula $dR\subseteq(x\varphi_{1}+y\varphi)(M')\in S$
\end_inset

.
 Hence
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\varphi_{1}(M') & =Ra_{1}\\
 & \subseteq Rd\\
 & \subseteq(x\varphi_{1}+y\varphi)(M').
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $x\varphi_{1}+y\varphi$
\end_inset

 is a linear map 
\begin_inset Formula $M\to R$
\end_inset

, it belongs to 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

, so maximality of 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{1}(M')$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 implies
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\varphi_{1}(M') & =(x\varphi_{1}+y\varphi)(M')\\
 & =Rd.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Hence
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
Ra_{1} & =Rd\\
 & =Ra_{1}+Ra_{\varphi},
\end{align*}

\end_inset

which implies 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{\varphi}\in R$
\end_inset

, and so 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{1}\mid a_{\varphi}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

With the claim proved, we are ready to build aligned bases in 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $M'$
\end_inset

.
 Letting 
\begin_inset Formula $\{e_{1},\dots,e_{n}\}$
\end_inset

 be a basis for 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
v'=c_{1}e_{1}+\cdots+c_{n}e_{n}
\]

\end_inset

for some 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{i}\in R$
\end_inset

.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

th coordinate function for this basis is a linear map 
\begin_inset Formula $M\to R$
\end_inset

 taking the value 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{i}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $v'$
\end_inset

, and so 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{i}$
\end_inset

 is a multiple of 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{1}$
\end_inset

 by our claim.
 Writing 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{i}=a_{1}b_{i}$
\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
v' & =\sum_{i=1}^{n}c_{i}e_{i}\\
 & =\sum_{i=1}^{n}a_{1}b_{i}e_{i}\\
 & =a_{1}\left(b_{1}e_{1}+\cdots+b_{n}e_{n}\right)\\
 & =a_{1}v_{1},
\end{align*}

\end_inset

say.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
a_{1} & =\varphi_{1}(v')\\
 & =\varphi_{1}(a_{1}v_{1})\\
 & =a_{1}\varphi_{1}(v_{1}),
\end{align*}

\end_inset

and so 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{1}(v_{1})=1$
\end_inset

.
 We have found an element of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 at which 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{1}$
\end_inset

 takes the value 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

The module 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 can be written as 
\begin_inset Formula $Rv_{1}+\ker\varphi_{1}$
\end_inset

 since any 
\begin_inset Formula $v\in M$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
v=\varphi_{1}(v)v_{1}+(v-\varphi_{1}(v))v_{1}.
\]

\end_inset

Also 
\begin_inset Formula $Rv_{1}\cap\ker\varphi_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $M=Rv_{1}\oplus\ker\varphi_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is free of rank 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 its submodule 
\begin_inset Formula $\ker\varphi_{1}$
\end_inset

 is free and necessarily of rank 
\begin_inset Formula $n-1$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

How does 
\begin_inset Formula $M'$
\end_inset

 fit in this decomposition of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

? For any 
\begin_inset Formula $w\in M'$
\end_inset

 we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
w=\varphi_{1}(w)v_{1}+(w-\varphi_{1}(w)v_{1})
\]

\end_inset

and the first term is
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\varphi_{1}(w)v_{1} & \in\varphi_{1}(M')v_{1}\\
 & =(Ra_{1})v_{1}\\
 & =Ra_{1}v_{1}\\
 & =Rv'\\
 & \subseteq M',
\end{align*}

\end_inset

so 
\begin_inset Formula $w-\varphi_{1}(w)v_{1}\in M'$
\end_inset

 too.
 Therefore
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
M'=(M'\cap Rv_{1})\oplus(M'\cap\ker\varphi_{1}).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So 
\begin_inset Formula $M=Rv_{1}\oplus\ker\varphi_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $M'=Ra_{1}v_{1}\oplus(M'\cap\ker\varphi_{1})$
\end_inset

.
 The last equation tells us 
\begin_inset Formula $M'\cap\ker\varphi_{1}$
\end_inset

 is free of rank 
\begin_inset Formula $m-1$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $M'$
\end_inset

 is free of rank 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $m=1$
\end_inset

 then we're done.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $m>1$
\end_inset

, then we can describe how 
\begin_inset Formula $M'\cap\ker\varphi_{1}$
\end_inset

 sits in 
\begin_inset Formula $\ker\varphi_{1}$
\end_inset

 by induction on the rank: we have a basis 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{2},\dots,v_{n}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\ker\varphi_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{2},\dots,a_{m}\in R\backslash\{0\}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{2}v_{2},\dots,a_{m}v_{m}$
\end_inset

 is a basis of 
\begin_inset Formula $M'\cap\ker\varphi_{1}$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Tensor Products
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Definition of Tensor Products via UMP
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 be 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-modules.
 The 
\series bold
tensor product 
\series default

\begin_inset Formula $M\otimes_{R}N$
\end_inset

 is an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module equipped with a bilinear map 
\begin_inset Formula $\otimes\colon M\times N\to M\otimes_{R}N$
\end_inset

 such that for each bilinear map 
\begin_inset Formula $B\colon M\times N\to P$
\end_inset

 there is a unique linear map 
\begin_inset Formula $L\colon M\otimes_{R}N\to P$
\end_inset

 making the following diagram commute.
\end_layout

