\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(2
\begin_inset Formula $\implies$
\end_inset

3): Suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $E'$
\end_inset

 is an injective 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-module such that 
\begin_inset Formula $M\subset E'\subset E$
\end_inset

.
 Then the map 
\begin_inset Formula $E'\subset E$
\end_inset

 splits, so 
\begin_inset Formula $E=E'\oplus N$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-module 
\begin_inset Formula $N\subset E$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $M\subset E'$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $M'\cap N=0$
\end_inset

.
 This implies 
\begin_inset Formula $N=0$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 is essential over 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(3
\begin_inset Formula $\implies$
\end_inset

1): From the proof of 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Lemma~(
\backslash
ref{lemmamaximalessentialextension})
\end_layout

\end_inset

, it follows that there is a maximal essential extension 
\begin_inset Formula $E'$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 contained in 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

.
 By (1
\begin_inset Formula $\implies$
\end_inset

2), we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $E'$
\end_inset

 is injective.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 was a minimal injective module containing 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $E=E'$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
