\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A 
\series bold
syzygy 
\series default
between 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 elements 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1},\dots,f_{k}$
\end_inset

 of an 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-module 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

-tuple 
\begin_inset Formula $(g_{1},\dots,g_{k})\in A^{k}$
\end_inset

 satisfying 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sum_{i=1}^{k}g_{i}f_{i}=0.
\]

\end_inset

The set of syzygies between 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1},\dots,f_{k}$
\end_inset

 is a submodule of 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{k}$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, it is the kernel of the ring homomorphism
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varphi:F_{1}:=\bigoplus_{i=1}^{k}Ae_{i}\to M,\quad e_{i}\mapsto f_{i},
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\{e_{1},\dots,e_{k}\}$
\end_inset

 denotes the canonical basis of 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{k}$
\end_inset

.
 The map 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 surjects onto the 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-module 
\begin_inset Formula $I:=\langle f_{1},\dots,f_{k}\rangle_{A}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mbox{syz}(I):=\mbox{syz}(f_{1},\dots,f_{k}):=\mbox{Ker}(\varphi)
\]

\end_inset

is called the 
\series bold
module of syzygies 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 with respect to the generators 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1},\dots,f_{k}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example1}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A=K[x,y,z,w]$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
f_{1} & =xz-y^{2}\\
f_{2} & =yw-z^{2}\\
f_{3} & =xw-yz.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

There are three 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

trivial
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 syzygies of 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1},f_{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{3}$
\end_inset

, which are given by the 
\begin_inset Formula $3$
\end_inset

-tuples
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
m_{1} & =(f_{2},-f_{1},0),\\
m_{2} & =(f_{3},0,-f_{1}),\\
m_{3} & =(0,f_{3},-f_{2}),
\end{align*}

\end_inset

but 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{syz}(f_{1},f_{2},f_{3})$
\end_inset

 is not generated by them.
 A generating set for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{syz}(f_{1},f_{2},f_{3})$
\end_inset

 is given by the 
\begin_inset Formula $3$
\end_inset

-tuples
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
n_{1} & =(w,y,-z)\\
n_{2} & =(z,x,-y),
\end{align*}

\end_inset

 Note that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
f_{1} & =yn_{1}-zn_{2},\\
f_{2} & =xn_{1}-yn_{2},\\
f_{3} & =-zn_{1}+wn_{2}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem1}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 be a Noetherian local ring.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $I=\langle f_{1},\dots,f_{k}\rangle=\langle g_{1},\dots,g_{s}\rangle\subset A^{r}$
\end_inset

, then it is not necessarily true that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{syz}(f_{1},\dots,f_{k})\cong\mbox{syz}(g_{1},\dots,g_{s})$
\end_inset

.
 So why are we justified in writing 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{syz}(I)$
\end_inset

.
 The reason is because the modules 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{syz}(f_{1},\dots,f_{k})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{syz}(g_{1},\dots,g_{s})$
\end_inset

 are 
\series bold
projectively equivalent
\series default
.
 This means that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{syz}(f_{1},\dots,f_{k})\oplus A^{m}\cong A^{n}\oplus\mbox{syz}(g_{1},\dots,g_{s})$
\end_inset

 for some free 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-modules 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{m}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 To prove this, we first need a lemma.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\backslash
label{lemma1}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Schanuel's Lemma) Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 be a Noetherian ring and 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 a finitely generated 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-module.
 Moreover, assume that the following sequences are exact 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd} 0 
\backslash
arrow[r] & K_1 
\backslash
arrow[r] & A^{n_1 } 
\backslash
arrow[r,"
\backslash
pi _1 "] & M 
\backslash
arrow[r] & 0 
\backslash
end{tikzcd}
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd} 0 
\backslash
arrow[r] & K_2 
\backslash
arrow[r] & A^{n_2 } 
\backslash
arrow[r,"
\backslash
pi _2 "] & M 
\backslash
arrow[r] & 0
\backslash
end{tikzcd}
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{1}\oplus A^{n_{2}}\cong K_{2}\oplus A^{n_{1}}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Consider the 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-module homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi\colon A^{n_{1}}\oplus A^{n_{2}}\to M$
\end_inset

, given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(a,b)=\pi_{1}(a)+\pi_{2}(b)$
\end_inset

.
 We will show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{Ker}(\pi)\cong A^{n_{1}}\oplus K_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 A similar proof will show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{Ker}(\pi)\cong K_{1}\oplus A^{n_{2}}$
\end_inset

, and hence 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A^{n_{1}}\oplus K_{2}\cong\mbox{Ker}(\pi)\cong K_{1}\oplus A^{n_{2}}.
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{1},\dots,e_{n_{1}}$
\end_inset

 be a basis for 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{n_{1}}$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1},\dots,f_{n_{2}}$
\end_inset

 be a basis for 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{n_{2}}$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{2}$
\end_inset

 is surjective, there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{ij}\in A$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\pi_{1}(e_{i})=\sum_{j=1}^{n_{2}}a_{ij}\pi_{2}(f_{j}).
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i=1,\dots,n_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 Choose such 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{ij}$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon A^{n_{1}}\to A^{n_{2}}$
\end_inset

 be the unique 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-module homomorphism such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varphi(e_{i})=\sum_{j=1}^{n_{2}}a_{ij}f_{j}
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i=1,\dots,n_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{2}\circ\varphi=\pi_{1}$
\end_inset

 and the set 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
F:=\{(x,-\varphi(x))\mid x\in A^{n_{1}}\}
\]

\end_inset

is an 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-module which is isomorphic to 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{n_{1}}$
\end_inset

.
 Viewing 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{2}$
\end_inset

 as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
K_{2}=\{(0,y)\mid y\in K_{2}\},
\]

\end_inset

we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $F\cap K_{2}=\{(0,0)\}$
\end_inset

, so the sum 
\begin_inset Formula $F+K_{2}$
\end_inset

 is a direct sum 
\begin_inset Formula $F\oplus K_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Now suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $(x,y)\in\mbox{Ker}(\pi)$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
0 & =\pi_{1}(x)+\pi_{2}(y)\\
 & =(\pi_{2}\circ\varphi)(x)+\pi_{2}(y)\\
 & =\pi_{2}(\varphi(x))+\pi_{2}(y)\\
 & =\pi_{2}(\varphi(x)+y),
\end{align*}

\end_inset

implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(x)+y\in\mbox{Ker}(\pi_{2})$
\end_inset

.
 Moreover, we can write
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(x,y)=(x,-\varphi(x))+(0,\varphi(x)+y)\in F\oplus K_{2}\cong A^{n_{1}}\oplus K_{2}.
\]

\end_inset

Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{Ker}(\pi)\subseteq M\oplus K_{2}\cong A^{n_{1}}\oplus K_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Conversely, suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $(x,-\varphi(x))+(0,y)\in M\oplus K_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Applying 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $(x,-\varphi(x))+(0,y)$
\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\pi((x,-\varphi(x))+(0,y)) & =\pi((x,y-\varphi(x))\\
 & =\pi_{1}(x)+\pi_{2}(y)-\pi_{2}(\varphi(x))\\
 & =\pi_{1}(x)-\pi_{1}(x)\\
 & =0.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Therefore, 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{n_{1}}\oplus K_{2}\cong M\oplus K_{2}\subseteq\mbox{Ker}(\pi)$
\end_inset

.
 We conclude that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{Ker}(\pi)\cong A^{n_{1}}\oplus K_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{cor}
\backslash
label{cor1}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 be a Noetherian ring and 
\begin_inset Formula $M=\langle f_{1},\dots,f_{k}\rangle=\langle g_{1},\dots,g_{s}\rangle\subset A^{r}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{syz}(f_{1},\dots,f_{k})\oplus A^{s}\cong A^{r}\oplus\mbox{syz}(g_{1},\dots,g_{s})$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{cor}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Schanuel's Lemma
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\backslash
label{lemma1}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Schanuel's Lemma) Let 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd} 0 
\backslash
arrow[r] & K 
\backslash
arrow[r, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\backslash
iota 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

] & P 
\backslash
arrow[r,"
\backslash
pi "] & M 
\backslash
arrow[r] & 0 
\backslash
end{tikzcd}
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset

and
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd} 0 
\backslash
arrow[r] & K' 
\backslash
arrow[r, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\backslash
iota '
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

] & P ' 
\backslash
arrow[r,"
\backslash
pi '"] & M 
\backslash
arrow[r] & 0 
\backslash
end{tikzcd}
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
be two short exact sequences of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-modules where 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $P'$
\end_inset

 are projective 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-modules.
 Then there is an isomorphism
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
K\oplus P'\cong K'\oplus P.
\]

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Consider the diagram with exact rows
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd} 0 
\backslash
arrow[r] & K 
\backslash
arrow[r, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\backslash
iota 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

] 
\backslash
arrow[d,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\backslash
alpha
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

,dashed ] & P 
\backslash
arrow[r,"
\backslash
pi "] 
\backslash
arrow[d,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\backslash
beta
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

,dashed ] & M 
\backslash
arrow[r] 
\backslash
arrow[d,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

1_M 
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

] & 0
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash

\backslash

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

0 
\backslash
arrow[r] & K' 
\backslash
arrow[r, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\backslash
iota '
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

] & P ' 
\backslash
arrow[r,"
\backslash
pi '"] & M 
\backslash
arrow[r] & 0
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{tikzcd}
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 is projective, there is a map 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta\colon P\to P'$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi'\beta=\pi$
\end_inset

; that it, the right square in the diagram commutes.
 A diagram chase shows that there is a map 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\colon K\to K'$
\end_inset

 making the other square commute.
 This commutative diagram with exact rows gives an exact sequence
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
0\to K\xrightarrow{\theta}P\oplus K'\xrightarrow{\psi}P'\to0
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta\colon x\mapsto(\iota x,\alpha x)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi\colon(u,x')\mapsto\beta u-\iota'x'$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in K$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $u\in P$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $x'\in K'$
\end_inset

.
 Exactness of this sequence is a straightforward calculation.
 This sequence splits because 
\begin_inset Formula $P'$
\end_inset

 is projective.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Associated Primes and Primary Decomposition
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Radicals and Colon Ideals 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Radical of an Ideal
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defradical}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 be a ring and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{a}$
\end_inset

 be an ideal in 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $\textbf{radical}$
\end_inset

 
\series bold
of
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{a}$
\end_inset

, denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{\mathfrak{a}}$
\end_inset

, is defined to be the ideal
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sqrt{\mathfrak{a}}:=\{a\in A\mid a^{n}\in I\mbox{ for some }n\in\mathbb{N}\}.
\]

\end_inset

We call 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{\langle0\rangle}$
\end_inset

 the 
\series bold
nilradical of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset


\series default
.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 be a ring and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{a}$
\end_inset

 be an ideal in 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sqrt{\mathfrak{a}}=\bigcap_{\substack{\mathfrak{p}\supset\mathfrak{a}\\
\text{prime}
}
}\mathfrak{p}.
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We claim that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}\supset\mathfrak{a}$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}\supset\sqrt{\mathfrak{a}}$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, if 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\sqrt{\mathfrak{a}}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{n}\in\mathfrak{a}\subset\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

.
 But this implies 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 is prime.
 Thus, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sqrt{\mathfrak{a}}\subset\bigcap_{\substack{\mathfrak{p}\supset\mathfrak{a}\\
\text{prime}
}
}\mathfrak{p}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the reverse inclusion, we may assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{a}=0$
\end_inset

 by passing to the quotient 
\begin_inset Formula $A\slash\mathfrak{a}$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\bigcap\limits _{\text{prime}}\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 but 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{n}\neq0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq0$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $A[x^{-1}]$
\end_inset

 is nonzero and hence contains a prime ideal 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{q}$
\end_inset

.
 The preimage of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{q}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 under the natural inclusion 
\begin_inset Formula $A\to A[x^{-1}]$
\end_inset

 is a prime ideal which doesn't contain 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 This is a contradiction.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 be a ring and let 
\begin_inset Formula $I,J$
\end_inset

 be ideals in 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{I}$
\end_inset

 is an ideal.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $I\subset J$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{I}\subset\sqrt{J}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{I\cap J}=\sqrt{I}\cap\sqrt{J}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{I+J}=\sqrt{\sqrt{I}+\sqrt{J}}.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in\sqrt{I}$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{n},y^{m}\in I$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $n,m\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
(ax+y)^{n+m}=\sum_{i=0}^{n+m}(ax)^{n+m-i}y^{i}.\label{eq:radicalequation-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Each term in 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:radicalequation-1})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 belongs to 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $(ax+y)^{n+m}$
\end_inset

 belongs to 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $ax+y$
\end_inset

 belongs to 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{I}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in\sqrt{I}$
\end_inset

, then for some 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $a^{n}\in I\subset J$
\end_inset

, thus 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in\sqrt{J}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in\sqrt{I\cap J}$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $a^{n}\in I\cap J$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $a^{n}\in I\cap J\subset I$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a^{n}\in I\cap J\subset J$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in\sqrt{I}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in\sqrt{J}$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{I\cap J}\subset\sqrt{I}\cap\sqrt{J}$
\end_inset

.
 For the reverse inclusion, suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in\sqrt{I}\cap\sqrt{J}$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $a^{n}\in I$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a^{m}\in J$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $n,m\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $a^{\max(m,n)}\in I\cap J$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in\sqrt{I\cap J}$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{I\cap J}\supset\sqrt{I}\cap\sqrt{J}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The inclusion 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{I+J}\subset\sqrt{\sqrt{I}+\sqrt{J}}$
\end_inset

 follows from the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $I+J\subset\sqrt{I}+\sqrt{J}$
\end_inset

.
 For the reverse inclusion, suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in\sqrt{\sqrt{I}+\sqrt{J}}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $a^{n}=b+c$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $b^{m}\in I$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $c^{k}\in J$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $n,m,k\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $(a^{n})^{(m+k)}\in I+J$
\end_inset

, and it follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in\sqrt{I+J}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{I+J}\supset\sqrt{\sqrt{I}+\sqrt{J}}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Note that we do not necessarily have 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{\bigcap_{\lambda\in\Lambda}I_{\lambda}}=\bigcap_{\lambda\in\Lambda}\sqrt{I_{\lambda}}$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, consider 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{n}=\langle T^{n}\rangle$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[T]$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\sqrt{\bigcap_{n=1}^{\infty}\langle T^{n}\rangle} & =\sqrt{0}\\
 & =0\\
 & \neq\langle T\rangle.\\
 & =\bigcap_{n=1}^{\infty}\langle T\rangle\\
 & =\bigcap_{n=1}^{\infty}\sqrt{\langle T^{n}\rangle}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Colon Ideal
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 be a ring and let 
\begin_inset Formula $I,J$
\end_inset

 be ideals in 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $\textbf{colon ideal}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $I:J$
\end_inset

 is defined as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
I:J=\{a\in A\mid aJ\subseteq I\}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Given 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in A$
\end_inset

, we use the shorthand notation 
\begin_inset Formula $I:a$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $I:\langle a\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 be a ring, 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in A$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 be a nonzerodivisor in 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $I,J$
\end_inset

 be ideals in 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $(I\cap J):a=(I:a)\cap(J:a)$
\end_inset

,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $I:\langle a,b\rangle=(I:a)\cap(I:b)$
\end_inset

,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $I:d=\frac{1}{d}(I\cap\langle d\rangle)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill 
\backslash
break
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in(I\cap J):a$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $ax\in I\cap J.$
\end_inset

 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $I\cap J\subset I$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $I\cap J\subset J$
\end_inset

, this implies 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in I:a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in J:a$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $(I\cap J):f\subset(I:f)\cap(J:f)$
\end_inset

.
 Now suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in(I:a)\cap(J:a)$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $ax\in I$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $ax\in J$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in(I\cap J):a$
\end_inset

, which means 
\begin_inset Formula $(I\cap J):f\supset(I:f)\cap(J:f)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in A$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $x\langle a,b\rangle\subset I$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $xa\in I$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $xb\in I$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Omitted.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\backslash
label{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 be a ring and 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{1},I_{2},I_{3}$
\end_inset

 be ideals in 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $(I_{1}\cap I_{2}):I_{3}=(I_{1}:I_{3})\cap(I_{2}:I_{3})$
\end_inset

, in particular 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{1}:I_{3}=(I_{1}\cap I_{2}):I_{3}$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{3}\subset I_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $(I_{1}:I_{2}):I_{3}=I_{1}:(I_{2}I_{3})$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{1}$
\end_inset

 is prime and 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{2}\not\subset I_{1}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{1}:I_{2}^{j}=I_{1}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $j\geq1$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{1}=\bigcap_{i=1}^{r}\mathfrak{p}_{i}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}_{i}$
\end_inset

 prime, then 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{1}:I_{2}^{\infty}=I_{1}:I_{2}=\bigcap_{I_{2}\not\subset\mathfrak{p}_{i}}\mathfrak{p}_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Is an easy exercise
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $I_{1}\subset I_{1}:I_{2}^{j}$
\end_inset

 is clear.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $gI_{2}^{j}\subset I_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{2}\not\subset I_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{1}$
\end_inset

 is radical, 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{2}^{j}\not\subset I_{1}$
\end_inset

 and we can find an 
\begin_inset Formula $h\in I_{2}^{j}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $h\notin I_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $gh\in I_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{1}$
\end_inset

 is prime, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in I_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Primary Ideals
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 be a ring and let 
\begin_inset Formula $Q\subset A$
\end_inset

 be an ideal.
 We say 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 is a 
\series bold
primary ideal 
\series default
if for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in A$
\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
ab\in Q\text{ and }a\notin Q\text{ implies }b^{n}\in Q\text{ for some }n\in\mathbb{N}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{radicalprimary}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 be a ring and let 
\begin_inset Formula $Q\subset A$
\end_inset

 be a primary ideal.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{Q}$
\end_inset

 is a prime ideal.
 Moreover, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{Q}$
\end_inset

 is the smallest prime ideal containing 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $ab\in\sqrt{Q}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a\notin\sqrt{Q}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $(ab)^{m}=a^{m}b^{m}\in Q$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $m\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $a^{m}\notin Q$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 is primary, 
\begin_inset Formula $(b^{m})^{n}=b^{mn}\in Q$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

.
 This implies 
\begin_inset Formula $b\in\sqrt{Q}$
\end_inset

.
 This shows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{Q}$
\end_inset

 is a prime ideal.
 To see that it is the smallest prime ideal, suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}\subset A$
\end_inset

 is a prime ideal such that 
\begin_inset Formula $Q\subset\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 and suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in\sqrt{Q}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $a^{n}\in Q\subset\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 is a prime ideal, this implies 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{Q}\subset\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The converse to 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Proposition~(
\backslash
ref{radicalprimary})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is false, that is, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{a}\subset A$
\end_inset

 is an ideal such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{\mathfrak{a}}$
\end_inset

 is prime, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{a}$
\end_inset

 is not necessarily primary.
 Indeed, let 
\begin_inset Formula $A=K[x,y]$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{a}=\langle x^{2},xy\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{\mathfrak{a}}=\langle x\rangle$
\end_inset

 is prime, but 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{a}$
\end_inset

 is not primary.
 We have 
\begin_inset Formula $xy\in\mathfrak{a}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x\notin\mathfrak{a}$
\end_inset

, but no power of 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 belongs to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{a}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 be a ring and let 
\begin_inset Formula $Q\subset A$
\end_inset

 be a primary ideal.
 We denote 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}:=\sqrt{Q}$
\end_inset

 and say 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset


\series bold
-primary
\series default
.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Intersection of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

-Primary Ideals is Primary
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{primaryintersection}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 be a ring and let 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{1},Q_{2}\subset A$
\end_inset

 be 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

-primary ideals.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{1}\cap Q_{2}$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

-primary ideal.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $ab\in Q_{1}\cap Q_{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a\notin Q_{1}\cap Q_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Then either 
\begin_inset Formula $a\notin Q_{1}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $a\notin Q_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Without loss of generality, assume 
\begin_inset Formula $a\notin Q_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $b^{n}\in Q_{2}$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{Q_{2}}=\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $b\in P$
\end_inset

.
 But since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}=\sqrt{Q_{1}}$
\end_inset

, we also have 
\begin_inset Formula $b^{m}\in Q_{1}$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $m\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $b^{\gcd(m,n)}\in Q_{1}\cap Q_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Notice that we used the fact that these are 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

-primary ideals.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{1}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}_{1}$
\end_inset

-primary and 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{2}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}_{2}$
\end_inset

-primary, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}_{2}$
\end_inset

 are different primes, then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sqrt{Q_{1}\cap Q_{2}}=\sqrt{Q_{1}}\cap\sqrt{Q_{2}}=\mathfrak{p}_{1}\cap\mathfrak{p}_{2},
\]

\end_inset

which is not a prime ideal.
 Hence 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{1}\cap Q_{2}$
\end_inset

 is not primary.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

-primary ideals and colon properties
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 be a ring, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}\subset A$
\end_inset

 be a prime ideal, and 
\begin_inset Formula $Q\subset A$
\end_inset

 be a 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

-primary ideal.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $x\notin Q$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $Q:x$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

-primary.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $x\notin\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $Q:x=Q$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in Q$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $Q:x=A$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $ab\in Q:x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a\notin Q:x$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $abx\in Q$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $ax\notin Q$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $b^{n}\in Q$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

, since 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 is primary.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $b\in Q:x$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $b^{n}x\in Q$
\end_inset

.
 To see that 
\begin_inset Formula $Q:x$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

-primary, we simply note that 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in Q:x$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $ax\in Q$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $a^{n}\in Q$
\end_inset

.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $Q\subset Q:x\subset\sqrt{Q}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We certainly have 
\begin_inset Formula $Q\subset Q:x$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $ax\in Q$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in Q$
\end_inset

.
 For the reverse inclusion, suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in Q:x$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $ax\in Q$
\end_inset

.
 Assume 
\begin_inset Formula $a\notin Q$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 is a primary ideal, then 
\begin_inset Formula $ax\in Q$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a\notin Q$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{n}\in Q$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

.
 But this implies 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

, which is a contradiction.
 Hence 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in Q$
\end_inset

, and thus, 
\begin_inset Formula $Q:x\subset Q$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in A$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $ax\in Q$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in Q$
\end_inset

.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $A\subset Q:x$
\end_inset

.
 The reverse inclusion is obvious.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

th Symbolic Power
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 be a ring and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{q}$
\end_inset

 be a prime ideal in 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 The 
\series bold

\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

th symbolic power of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{q}$
\end_inset


\series default
, denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{q}^{(n)}$
\end_inset

, is defined to be the ideal
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathfrak{q}^{(n)}=\mathfrak{q}^{n}A_{\mathfrak{q}}\cap A=\left\{ a\in A\mid as\in\mathfrak{q}^{n}\text{ for some }s\in A\backslash\mathfrak{q}\right\} .
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 be a ring and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{q}$
\end_inset

 be a prime ideal in 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{q}^{(n)}$
\end_inset

 is the smallest 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{q}$
\end_inset

-primary ideal which contains 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{q}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 It is clear that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{q}^{n}\subset\mathfrak{q}^{(n)}$
\end_inset

.
 Let us show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{q}^{(n)}$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{q}$
\end_inset

-primary ideal.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $ab\in\mathfrak{q}^{(n)}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a\notin\mathfrak{q}^{(n)}$
\end_inset

.
 Choose 
\begin_inset Formula $s\in A\backslash\mathfrak{q}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $abs\in\mathfrak{q}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in\mathfrak{q}^{(n)}$
\end_inset

, we must not have 
\begin_inset Formula $bs\in A\backslash\mathfrak{q}$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, this implies 
\begin_inset Formula $b\in\mathfrak{q}$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $A\backslash\mathfrak{q}$
\end_inset

 is multiplicatively closed.
 But then 
\begin_inset Formula $b^{n}\in\mathfrak{q}^{n}\subset\mathfrak{q}^{(n)}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{q}^{(n)}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{q}$
\end_inset

-primary.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Now we will show that it is the smallest 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{q}$
\end_inset

-primary ideal which contains 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{q}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 be any 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{q}$
\end_inset

-primary ideal which contains 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{q}^{n}$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in\mathfrak{q}^{(n)}$
\end_inset

.
 Choose 
\begin_inset Formula $s\in A\backslash\mathfrak{q}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $as\in\mathfrak{q}^{n}\subset Q$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $A\backslash\mathfrak{q}$
\end_inset

 is multiplicatively closed and since 
\begin_inset Formula $Q\cap A\backslash\mathfrak{q}=\emptyset$
\end_inset

, we must have 
\begin_inset Formula $s^{m}\notin Q$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $m\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

.
 This implies 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in Q$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 is primary.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{q}^{(n)}\subset Q$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Primary Decomposition
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In a Noetherian ring, any ideal can be written as a finite intersection
 of primary ideals (called the 
\begin_inset Formula $\textbf{primary decomposition}$
\end_inset

).
 Before we go over the proof, we need a definition and a lemma.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 be a ring and let 
\begin_inset Formula $I\subset A$
\end_inset

 be an ideal.
 We say 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
irreducible 
\series default
if given two ideals 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{1},I_{2}\subset A$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $I=I_{1}\cap I_{2}$
\end_inset

, then either 
\begin_inset Formula $I=I_{1}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $I=I_{2}$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\backslash
label{irreducibleimpliesprimary}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 be a Noetherian ring and let 
\begin_inset Formula $I\subset A$
\end_inset

 be an irreducible ideal.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is primary.
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $ab\in I$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $a\notin I$
\end_inset

.
 There is a chain of ideals:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
I\subset I:b\subset I:b^{2}\subset\cdots
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By the Noetherian condition we must have 
\begin_inset Formula $I:b^{n}=I:b^{n+1}$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

.
 Assume 
\begin_inset Formula $b^{n}\notin I$
\end_inset

.
 We will show 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle I,b^{n}\rangle\cap\langle I,a\rangle=I$
\end_inset

, which is a contradiction since 
\begin_inset Formula $b^{n},a\notin I$
\end_inset

.
 To show this, we only need to show 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle b^{n}\rangle\cap\langle a\rangle\subset I$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\langle b^{n}\rangle\cap\langle a\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\langle a\rangle$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $x=ay$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\langle b^{n}\rangle$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $x=b^{n}z$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
bx=b^{n+1}z=bay\in I
\]

\end_inset

implies 
\begin_inset Formula $z\in I:b^{n+1}=I:b^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $x=zb^{n}\in I$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 be a Noetherian ring and let 
\begin_inset Formula $I\subset A$
\end_inset

 be an ideal.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 can be expressed as a finite intersection of primary ideals.
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 First, we show that 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 can be expressed as a finite intersection of irreducible ideals.
 Assume, on the contrary, that 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 cannot be expressed as a finite intersection of irreducible ideals.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 be the set of all ideals which cannot be expressed as a finite intersection
 of irreducible ideals.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is nonempty since 
\begin_inset Formula $I\in S$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is noetherian, 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 has a maximal element 
\begin_inset Formula $J$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $J\in S$
\end_inset

, it must be reducible, so we can write 
\begin_inset Formula $J=J_{1}\cap J_{2}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $J\subsetneq J_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $J\subsetneq J_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $J$
\end_inset

 is maximal, we can express 
\begin_inset Formula $J_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $J_{2}$
\end_inset

 as a finite intersection of irreducible ideals, and hence we can express
 
\begin_inset Formula $J$
\end_inset

 as a finite intersection of irreducible ideals, which is a contradiction.
 Now apply 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Lemma~
\backslash
ref{irreducibleimpliesprimary}
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 It is interesting to compare this proof with the proof given in my Algebraic
 Number Theory notes on why every ideal in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{K}$
\end_inset

 contains a product of primes.
 In both cases, we needed a maximal element; one based on the index of an
 ideal in the ring of integers, and one based containment.
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A primary decomposition 
\begin_inset Formula $I=\bigcap\limits _{i=1}^{n}Q_{i}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\textbf{irredundant}$
\end_inset

 if for each 
\begin_inset Formula $j\in\{1,\dots,n\}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\bigcap_{i\neq j}Q_{i}\neq I.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 So there are no 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

extraneous
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 factors
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Given an irredundant primary decomposition 
\begin_inset Formula $I=\bigcap\limits _{i=1}^{n}Q_{i}$
\end_inset

, if 
\begin_inset Formula $i\neq j$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}_{i}\neq\mathfrak{p}_{j}$
\end_inset

.
 The reason is because if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}_{i}=\mathfrak{p}_{j}$
\end_inset

, then by 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Proposition~
\backslash
ref{primaryintersection}
\end_layout

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $Q=Q_{i}\cap Q_{j}$
\end_inset

 is a smaller primary ideal which contains 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

, and hence the primary decomposition for 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 can be replaced by removing 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{j}$
\end_inset

 and replacing them with 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

, which means 
\begin_inset Formula $I=\bigcap\limits _{i=1}^{n}Q_{i}$
\end_inset

 is not irredundant.
 So we get a picture that looks like this: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The set of 
\begin_inset Formula $\textbf{associated primes}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

, denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $Ass(I)$
\end_inset

, is defined as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Ass(I)=\{P\subset R\mid P\mbox{ prime, }P=I:f\mbox{ for some }f\in R\}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given an irredundant primary decomposition 
\begin_inset Formula $I=\bigcap\limits _{i=1}^{n}Q_{i}$
\end_inset

, we claim 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{i}\in Ass(I)$
\end_inset

: For any 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

, we can find 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{j}\notin Q_{j}$
\end_inset

 but which is in all the other 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{i}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $i\neq j$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
I:f_{j}=\left(\bigcap\limits _{i=1}^{n}Q_{i}\right):f_{j}=\bigcap\limits _{i=1}^{n}(Q_{i}:f_{j})=Q_{j}:f_{j}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus, 
\begin_inset Formula $I:f_{j}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{j}$
\end_inset

-primary.
 In particular 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{I:f_{j}}=\sqrt{Q_{j}:f_{j}}=P_{j}$
\end_inset

.
 Also, if 
\begin_inset Formula $P=I:f$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in R$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P\supset Q_{1}\cap Q_{2}\cap\cdots\cap Q_{n}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 is a prime ideal, 
\begin_inset Formula $P\supset Q_{k}$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq k\leq n$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $P\supset P_{k}$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{k}$
\end_inset

 is the smallest prime ideal which contains 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{k}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 An associated prime 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{i}$
\end_inset

 which does not properly contain any other associated prime 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{j}$
\end_inset

 is called a 
\begin_inset Formula $\textbf{minimal}$
\end_inset

 associated prime.
 The non-minimal associated primes are called 
\begin_inset Formula $\textbf{embedded}$
\end_inset

 associated primes.
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $I=\langle x^{2},xy\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 Clearly 
\begin_inset Formula $I=\langle x^{2},y\rangle\cap\langle x\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


