\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\backslash
label{lemma1}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Splitting tool) Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 be a ring, 
\begin_inset Formula $I\subset A$
\end_inset

 an ideal, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $I:a=I:a^{2}$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in A$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $I=(I:a)\cap\langle I,a\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Since both 
\begin_inset Formula $I:a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle I,a\rangle$
\end_inset

 contain 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $I\subset(I:a)\cap\langle I,a\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 For the reverse inclusion, let 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in(I:a)\cap\langle I,a\rangle$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $f=g+xa$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in I$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $af=ag+xa^{2}\in I$
\end_inset

 and, therefore, 
\begin_inset Formula $xa^{2}\in I$
\end_inset

.
 That is, 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in I:a^{2}=I:a$
\end_inset

 which implies 
\begin_inset Formula $xa\in I$
\end_inset

 and, consequently, 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in I$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example1}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $I=\langle xy^{2},y^{3}\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $I:x=\langle y^{2}\rangle=I:x^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore, 
\begin_inset Formula $I=\langle y^{2}\rangle\cap\langle x,y^{3}\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example2}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $I=\langle wx,wy,wz,vx,vy,vz,ux,uy,uz,y^{3}-x^{2}\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $I:w=\langle x,y,z\rangle=I:w^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $I=\langle x,y,z\rangle\cap I_{1}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{1}=\langle w,vx,vy,vz,ux,uy,uz,y^{3}-x^{2}\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{1}:v=\langle w,x,y,z\rangle=I_{1}:v^{2}$
\end_inset

, and so 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{1}=\langle w,x,y,z\rangle\cap I_{2}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{2}=\langle w,v,ux,uy,uz,y^{3}-x^{2}\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 Finally, 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{2}:u=\langle w,v,x,y,z\rangle=I_{2}:u^{2}$
\end_inset

, and so 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{2}=\langle w,v,x,y,z\rangle\cap\langle w,v,u,y^{3}-x^{2}\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $I=\langle x,y,z\rangle\cap\langle w,x,y,z\rangle\cap\langle w,v,x,y,z\rangle\cap\langle w,v,u,y^{3}-x^{2}\rangle=\langle x,y,z\rangle\cap\langle w,v,u,y^{3}-x^{2}\rangle$
\end_inset

.
  
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{exampletwistedcubic}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A=K[x,y,z,w]$
\end_inset

.
 The twisted cubic is the set-theoretic intersection of 
\begin_inset Formula $xz-y^{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $z(yw-z^{2})-w(xw-yz)$
\end_inset

, but it is not a sheme-theoretic or ideal-theoretic complete intersection.
 To get a sense of why this is, we compute a primary decomposition of 
\begin_inset Formula $I=\langle xz-y^{2},z(yw-z^{2})-w(xw-yz)\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 Using Singular, we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

-primary where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}=\langle xz-y^{2},yw-z^{2},xw-yz\rangle$
\end_inset

, and thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{I}=\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{V}(I)=\mathbf{V}(\mathfrak{p})$
\end_inset

.
 On the other hand, 
\begin_inset Formula $I\subsetneq\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn1}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 be a Noetherian ring and let 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 be an ideal in 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The set of 
\series bold
associated primes 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

, denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{Ass}(I)$
\end_inset

, is defined as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mbox{Ass}(I)=\{\mathfrak{p}\subset A\mid\mathfrak{p}\mbox{ is prime and }\mathfrak{p}=I:a\mbox{ for some }a\in A\}.
\]

\end_inset

Elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{Ass}\left(\langle0\rangle\right)$
\end_inset

 are also called 
\series bold
associated primes 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p},\mathfrak{q}\in\mbox{Ass}(I)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{q}\subset\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 is called an 
\series bold
embedded prime ideal 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

.
 We define 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{Ass}(I,\mathfrak{p}):=\{\mathfrak{q}\mid\mathfrak{q}\in\mbox{Ass}(I)\mbox{ and }\mathfrak{q}\subset\mathfrak{p}\}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is called 
\series bold
equidimensional 
\series default
or 
\series bold
pure dimensional 
\series default
if all associated primes of 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 have the same dimension.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is a 
\series bold
primary ideal 
\series default
if, for any 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in A$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $ab\in I$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $a\notin I$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $b\in\sqrt{I}$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 be a prime ideal.
 Then a primary ideal 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is called 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

-primary if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}=\sqrt{I}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
A 
\series bold
primary decomposition 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

, that is, a decomposition 
\begin_inset Formula $I=Q_{1}\cap\cdots\cap Q_{s}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{i}$
\end_inset

 primary ideals, is called 
\series bold
irredundant 
\series default
if no 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{i}$
\end_inset

 can be omitted in the decomposition and if 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{Q_{i}}\neq\sqrt{Q}_{j}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i\neq j$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Examples
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A=K[x,y]$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $I=\langle x^{2},xy\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 Then a primary decomposition of 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $I=I_{1}\cap I_{2}$
\end_inset

, where
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
I_{1} & =\langle x^{2},y\rangle & \sqrt{I_{1}} & =\langle x,y\rangle\\
I_{2} & =\langle x\rangle & \sqrt{I_{2}} & =\langle x\rangle
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A=K[x,y,u,v]$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $I=\langle xu,xv,yu,yv\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 Then a primary decomposition of 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $I=I_{1}\cap I_{2}$
\end_inset

, where
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
I_{1} & =\langle x,y\rangle & \sqrt{I_{1}} & =\langle x,y\rangle\\
I_{2} & =\langle u,v\rangle & \sqrt{I_{2}} & =\langle u,v\rangle
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A=K[x,y,u,v]$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $I=\langle xu,yv,xv+yu\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 Then a primary decomposition of 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $I=I_{1}\cap I_{2}\cap I_{3}$
\end_inset

, where
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
I_{1} & =\langle x,y\rangle & \sqrt{I_{1}} & =\langle x,y\rangle\\
I_{2} & =\langle u,v\rangle & \sqrt{I_{2}} & =\langle u,v\rangle\\
I_{3} & =\langle x^{2},xy,xu,yu+xv,y^{2},yv,u^{2},uv,v^{2}\rangle & \sqrt{I_{3}} & =\langle x,y,u,v\rangle
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A=K[x,y,u,v]$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $I=\langle xu+yv,xv+yu\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 Then a primary decomposition of 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $I=I_{1}\cap I_{2}\cap I_{3}\cap I_{4}$
\end_inset

, where=
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
I_{1} & =\langle x,y\rangle & \sqrt{I_{1}} & =\langle x,y\rangle\\
I_{2} & =\langle u,v\rangle & \sqrt{I_{2}} & =\langle u,v\rangle\\
I_{3} & =\langle x+y,u-v\rangle & \sqrt{I_{3}} & =\langle x+y,u-v\rangle\\
I_{4} & =\langle x-y,u+v\rangle & \sqrt{I_{4}} & =\langle x-y,u+v\rangle
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R=K[x,y]$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $I=\langle x^{2}-xy,xy^{2}-xy\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 Using Singular, we calculate
\end_layout

