\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
What happened here is that we now have 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle x-1,y-1\rangle_{\mathfrak{m}}=R_{\mathfrak{m}}$
\end_inset

, since both 
\begin_inset Formula $x-1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y-1$
\end_inset

 are units.
 Thus it is becomes an irrelevant factor.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Associated Primes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be a ring, 
\series bold

\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}\subset R$
\end_inset

 
\series default
a prime ideal, and 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module.
 We say 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 is an 
\series bold
associated prime of
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}=0:u$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $u\in M$
\end_inset

.
 The set of all associated primes of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is written 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Ass}(M)$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 be a Noetherian ring and let 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 be a finitely generated 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-module.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Ass}(M)$
\end_inset

 is a finite, nonempty set of primes, each containing 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Ann}(M)$
\end_inset

.
 The set 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Ass}(M)$
\end_inset

 includes all primes minimal among primes containing 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Ann}(M)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The union of associated primes of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 consists of 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 and the set of zerodivisors on 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The formation of the set 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Ass}(M)$
\end_inset

 commutes with localization at an arbitrary multiplicately closed set, in
 the sense that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\text{Ass}_{S^{-1}A}(S^{-1}M)=\{S^{-1}\mathfrak{p}\mid\mathfrak{p}\in\text{Ass}(M)\text{ and }\mathfrak{p}\cap S=\emptyset\}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\backslash
label{primeavoidance}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Prime Avoidance) If 
\begin_inset Formula $I\subseteq\bigcup_{i=1}^{n}\mathfrak{p}_{i}$
\end_inset

, with 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}_{i}$
\end_inset

 prime, then 
\begin_inset Formula $I\subseteq\mathfrak{p}_{i}$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We prove the contrapositive: 
\begin_inset Formula $I\not\subseteq\mathfrak{p}_{i}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $I\not\subseteq\bigcup_{i=1}^{n}\mathfrak{p}_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 Induct on 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, the base case is trivial.
 We now suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $I\not\subseteq\mathfrak{p}_{i}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $I\subseteq\bigcup_{i=1}^{n}\mathfrak{p}_{i}$
\end_inset

, and arrive at a contradiction.
 From our inductive hypothesis, for each 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $I\not\subseteq\bigcup_{j\neq i}\mathfrak{p}_{j}$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, for each 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 there is an 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}$
\end_inset

 which is in 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 but is not in 
\begin_inset Formula $\bigcup_{j\neq i}\mathfrak{p}_{j}$
\end_inset

.
 Notice that if 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}\notin\mathfrak{p}_{i}$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}\notin\bigcup_{j=1}^{n}\mathfrak{p}_{j}$
\end_inset

, and we have an immediate contradiction.
 So suppose for every 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 that 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}\in\mathfrak{p}_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 Consider the element
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x=\sum_{i=1}^{n}x_{1}\cdots\hat{x}_{i}\cdots x_{n}.
\]

\end_inset

By construction, 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in I$
\end_inset

.
 We claim that 
\begin_inset Formula $x\notin\bigcup_{i=1}^{n}\mathfrak{p}_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 To see this, observe that 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}\cdots\hat{x}_{i}\cdots x_{n}\notin\mathfrak{p}_{i}$
\end_inset

, because for each index 
\begin_inset Formula $k\neq i$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{k}$
\end_inset

 is not in 
\begin_inset Formula $\bigcup_{j\neq k}\mathfrak{p}_{j}$
\end_inset

, so in particular is not in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}_{i}$
\end_inset

 is prime, this proves that 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}\cdots\hat{x}_{i}\cdots x_{n}\notin\mathfrak{p}_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 But every other monomial of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}_{i}$
\end_inset

, since every other monomial contains 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 This shows that 
\begin_inset Formula $x\notin\mathfrak{p}_{i}$
\end_inset

 for any 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

, hence 
\begin_inset Formula $x\notin\bigcup_{j=1}^{n}\mathfrak{p}_{j}$
\end_inset

, a contradiction.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Finitely generated modules over Noetherian rings are distinguished for two
 reasons: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Every zerodivisor of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is contained in an associated prime ideal: Let 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 be a nonzerodivisor of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 This means there is a nonzero 
\begin_inset Formula $m\in M$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $xm=0$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 belongs to the ideal 
\begin_inset Formula $0:m=\{a\in A\mid am=0\}$
\end_inset

.
 In a Noetherian ring, we have primary decomposition.
 So
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x\in0:m=Q_{1}\cap Q_{2}\cap\cdots\cap Q_{k}\subseteq\mathfrak{p}_{1}\cap\mathfrak{p}_{2}\cap\cdots\cap\mathfrak{p}_{k}
\]

\end_inset

where each 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}_{i}=(0:m):d_{i}=0:d_{i}m$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{i}\in A$
\end_inset

.
 That is, each 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}_{i}$
\end_inset

 is an associated prime ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The number of associated prime ideals of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is finite.
 So if 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is an ideal which consists of zero-divisors of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
I\subseteq\bigcup\limits _{\mathfrak{p}\in\mbox{Ass}(M)}\mathfrak{p}.
\]

\end_inset

and by the 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Lemma~(
\backslash
ref{primeavoidance})
\end_layout

\end_inset

, we must have 
\begin_inset Formula $I\subseteq\mathfrak{p}_{i}$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
 Writing 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}_{i}=0:m_{i}$
\end_inset

, the assignment 
\begin_inset Formula $1\mapsto m_{i}$
\end_inset

 induces a non-zero homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi:A/I\to M$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A=K[x,y]$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $M=K[x,y]/\langle xy\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Ass}(M)=\left\{ \langle x\rangle,\langle y\rangle\right\} $
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Supp}(M)=\mathbf{V}\left(\langle xy\rangle\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Clearly 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Supp}(M)$
\end_inset

 is much bigger than 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Ass}(M)$
\end_inset

.
 For example, 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle x-a,y\rangle\in\text{Supp}(M)$
\end_inset

 but 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle x-a,y\rangle\notin\text{Ass}(M)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in K$
\end_inset

.
 Consider the filtration
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
0=M_{0}\subset M_{1}\subset M_{2}\subset M_{3}=M,
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{1}=\langle x\rangle/\langle xy\rangle$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{2}=\langle x,y\rangle/\langle xy\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 The factors of this filtration are 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
M_{3}/M_{2} & \cong K[x,y]/\langle x,y\rangle,\\
M_{2}/M_{1} & \cong K[x,y]/\langle x\rangle,\\
M_{1}/M_{0} & \cong K[x,y]/\langle y\rangle.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
0\to M'\xrightarrow{\varphi}M\xrightarrow{\psi}M''\to0
\]

\end_inset

be a short exact sequence of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-modules.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{Ass}(M')\subset\mathrm{Ass}(M)\subset\mathrm{Ass}(M')\cup\mathrm{Ass}(M'')
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We first show 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Ass}(M')\subset\mathrm{Ass}(M)$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}\in\mathrm{Ass}(M')$
\end_inset

.
 Choose 
\begin_inset Formula $u'\in M'$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}=0:u'$
\end_inset

.
 We claim that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}=0:\varphi(u')$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, if 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

, then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
a\varphi(u') & =\varphi(au')\\
 & =\varphi(0)\\
 & =0
\end{align*}

\end_inset

implies 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in0:\varphi(u')$
\end_inset

 and hence 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}\subset0:\varphi(u')$
\end_inset

.
 Conversely, if 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in0:\varphi(u')$
\end_inset

, then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
0 & =a\varphi(u')\\
 & =\varphi(au')
\end{align*}

\end_inset

implies 
\begin_inset Formula $au'=0$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is injective, which implies 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}=0:u'$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}\supset0:\varphi(u')$
\end_inset

, and so 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}\in\mathrm{Ass}(M)$
\end_inset

.
 This implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Ass}(M')\subset\mathrm{Ass}(M)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

We now show 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Ass}(M)\subset\mathrm{Ass}(M')\cup\mathrm{Ass}(M'')$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}\in\mathrm{Ass}(M)$
\end_inset

.
 Choose 
\begin_inset Formula $u\in M$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}=0:u$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Case 1: 
\series default
Assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $Ru\cap M'\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 Choose an a nonzero element in 
\begin_inset Formula $Ru\cap M'$
\end_inset

, say 
\begin_inset Formula $au$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in R$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $au\neq0$
\end_inset

, we must have 
\begin_inset Formula $a\notin\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $0:u=\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
0:au & =(0:u):a\\
 & =\mathfrak{p}:a\\
 & =\mathfrak{p},
\end{align*}

\end_inset

which implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}\in\text{Ass}(M')$
\end_inset

, hence 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Ass}(M)\subset\mathrm{Ass}(M')$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Case 2: 
\series default
Assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $Ru\cap M'=0$
\end_inset

.
 We claim that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}=0:\psi(u)$
\end_inset

.
 First note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}\subset0:\psi(u)$
\end_inset

 follows from the argument above, so it suffices to show 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}\supset0:\psi(u)$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in0:\psi(u)$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
0 & =a\psi(u)\\
 & =\psi(au)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

implies 
\begin_inset Formula $au\in\mathrm{ker}\,\psi=M'$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $Ru\cap M'=0$
\end_inset

, this implies 
\begin_inset Formula $au=0$
\end_inset

, and consequently 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

.
 It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}\supset0:\psi(u)$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be a Noetherian ring and let 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 be a finitely-generated 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module.
 Then there exists a finite filtration
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
0=M_{0}\subset M_{1}\subset\cdots\subset M_{k}=M
\]

\end_inset

such that the successive quotients 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{i+1}\slash M_{i}$
\end_inset

 are isomorphic to various 
\begin_inset Formula $R\slash\mathfrak{p}_{i}$
\end_inset

 with the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}_{i}\subset R$
\end_inset

 prime.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $M'\subset M$
\end_inset

 be maximal among submodules for which such a filtration (ending with 
\begin_inset Formula $M'$
\end_inset

) exists.
 We would like to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $M'=M$
\end_inset

.
 Now 
\begin_inset Formula $M'$
\end_inset

 is well-defined since 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 has such a filtration and 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is Noetherian.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

There is a filtration
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
0=M_{0}\subset M_{1}\subset\cdots\subset M_{l}=M'\subset M
\]

\end_inset

where the successive quotients, 
\emph on
except 
\emph default
possibly the last 
\begin_inset Formula $M\slash M'$
\end_inset

, are of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $R\slash\mathfrak{p}_{i}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}_{i}$
\end_inset

 prime.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $M'=M$
\end_inset

, we are done.
 Otherwise, consider the quotient 
\begin_inset Formula $M\slash M'\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 There is an associated prime of 
\begin_inset Formula $M\slash M'$
\end_inset

.
 So there is a prime 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 which is the annihilator of 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in M\slash M'$
\end_inset

.
 This means that there is an injection
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
R\slash\mathfrak{p}\hookrightarrow M\slash M'.
\]

\end_inset

Now, take 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{l+1}$
\end_inset

 as the inverse image in 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $R\slash\mathfrak{p}\subset M\slash M'$
\end_inset

.
 Then we can consider the finite filtration
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
0=M_{0}\subset M_{1}\subset\cdots\subset M_{l+1},
\]

\end_inset

all of whose successive quotients are of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $R\slash\mathfrak{p}_{i}$
\end_inset

; this is because 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{l+1}\slash M_{l}=M_{l+1}\slash M'$
\end_inset

 is of this form by construction.
 We have thus extended this filtration one step further, a contradiction
 since 
\begin_inset Formula $M'$
\end_inset

 was assumed to be maximal.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Depth
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Prime Avoidance
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\backslash
label{primeavoidance}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Prime Avoidance) If 
\begin_inset Formula $I\subseteq\bigcup_{i=1}^{n}\mathfrak{p}_{i}$
\end_inset

, with 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}_{i}$
\end_inset

 prime, then 
\begin_inset Formula $I\subseteq\mathfrak{p}_{i}$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We prove the contrapositive: 
\begin_inset Formula $I\not\subseteq\mathfrak{p}_{i}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $I\not\subseteq\bigcup_{i=1}^{n}\mathfrak{p}_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 Induct on 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, the base case is trivial.
 We now suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $I\not\subseteq\mathfrak{p}_{i}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $I\subseteq\bigcup_{i=1}^{n}\mathfrak{p}_{i}$
\end_inset

, and arrive at a contradiction.
 From our inductive hypothesis, for each 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $I\not\subseteq\bigcup_{j\neq i}\mathfrak{p}_{j}$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, for each 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 there is an 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}$
\end_inset

 which is in 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 but is not in 
\begin_inset Formula $\bigcup_{j\neq i}\mathfrak{p}_{j}$
\end_inset

.
 Notice that if 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}\notin\mathfrak{p}_{i}$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}\notin\bigcup_{j=1}^{n}\mathfrak{p}_{j}$
\end_inset

, and we have an immediate contradiction.
 So suppose for every 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 that 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}\in\mathfrak{p}_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 Consider the element
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x=\sum_{i=1}^{n}x_{1}\cdots\hat{x}_{i}\cdots x_{n}.
\]

\end_inset

By construction, 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in I$
\end_inset

.
 We claim that 
\begin_inset Formula $x\notin\bigcup_{i=1}^{n}\mathfrak{p}_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 To see this, observe that 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}\cdots\hat{x}_{i}\cdots x_{n}\notin\mathfrak{p}_{i}$
\end_inset

, because for each index 
\begin_inset Formula $k\neq i$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{k}$
\end_inset

 is not in 
\begin_inset Formula $\bigcup_{j\neq k}\mathfrak{p}_{j}$
\end_inset

, so in particular is not in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}_{i}$
\end_inset

 is prime, this proves that 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}\cdots\hat{x}_{i}\cdots x_{n}\notin\mathfrak{p}_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 But every other monomial of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}_{i}$
\end_inset

, since every other monomial contains 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 This shows that 
\begin_inset Formula $x\notin\mathfrak{p}_{i}$
\end_inset

 for any 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

, hence 
\begin_inset Formula $x\notin\bigcup_{j=1}^{n}\mathfrak{p}_{j}$
\end_inset

, a contradiction.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Support
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module.
 The 
\series bold
support 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is the set
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{Supp}\,M=\{\mathfrak{p}\in\mathrm{Spec}\,R\mid M_{\mathfrak{p}}\neq0\}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\backslash
label{support}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module.
 Then we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{Supp}\,M\subseteq\mathrm{V}(\mathrm{Ann}\,M).
\]

\end_inset

If moreover, 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is finitely-generated, then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{Supp}\,M\supseteq\mathrm{V}(\mathrm{Ann}\,M).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}\in\mathrm{Supp}\,M$
\end_inset

 and assume for a contradiciton that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}\notin\mathrm{V}(\mathrm{Ann}\,M)$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}\not\supseteq\mathrm{Ann}\,M$
\end_inset

.
 Choose 
\begin_inset Formula $s\in\mathrm{Ann}\,M$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $x\notin\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{\mathfrak{p}}=0$
\end_inset

 since given any 
\begin_inset Formula $u/t\in M_{\mathfrak{p}}$
\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\frac{u}{t} & =\frac{su}{st}\\
 & =\frac{0}{st}\\
 & =0.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

This is a contradiction as 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}\in\mathrm{Supp}\,M$
\end_inset

 which means 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{\mathfrak{p}}\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}\in\mathrm{V}(\mathrm{Ann}\,M)$
\end_inset

 and since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 is arbitrary, this implies 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{Supp}\,M\subseteq\mathrm{V}(\mathrm{Ann}\,M).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we prove the second part of the lemma: suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is finitely-generated, say by 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{1},\dots,u_{n}\in M$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}\in\mathrm{V}(\mathrm{Ann}\,M)$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}\supseteq\mathrm{Ann}\,M$
\end_inset

.
 Assume for a contradiction that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}\notin\mathrm{Supp}\,M$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{\mathfrak{p}}=0$
\end_inset

.
 Choose 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{i}\in R\backslash\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{i}u_{i}=0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq i\leq n$
\end_inset

 and denote 
\begin_inset Formula $s=s_{1}s_{2}\cdots s_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $s\in R\backslash\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $s\in\mathrm{Ann}\,M$
\end_inset

 since
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
su_{i} & =s_{1}s_{2}\cdots s_{n}u_{i}\\
 & =s_{1}\cdots s_{i-1}s_{i+1}\cdots s_{n}(s_{i}u_{i})\\
 & =s_{1}\cdots s_{i-1}s_{i+1}\cdots s_{n}\cdot0\\
 & =0
\end{align*}

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq i\leq n$
\end_inset

.
 This contradicts the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}\supseteq\mathrm{Ann}\,M$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}\in\mathrm{Supp}\,M$
\end_inset

 and since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 is arbitary, this implies
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{Supp}\,M\supseteq\mathrm{V}(\mathrm{Ann}\,M).
\]

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Depth
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finite modules over Noetherian rings are distinguished for two reasons:
 First, every zerodivisor of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is contained in an associated prime ideal.
 Indeed, let 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 be a zerodivisor of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 This means there is a nonzero 
\begin_inset Formula $u\in M$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $xu=0$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 belongs to the ideal 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
0:_{R}u=\{a\in R\mid au=0\}.
\]

\end_inset

In a Noetherian ring, we have primary decomposition.
 So
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
x & \in0:_{R}u\\
 & =Q_{1}\cap\cdots\cap Q_{m}\\
 & \subseteq\mathfrak{p}_{1}\cap\cdots\cap\mathfrak{p}_{m},
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathfrak{p}_{i} & =(0:_{R}u):d_{i}\\
 & =0:_{R}d_{i}u.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

for some 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{i}\in R$
\end_inset

.
 That is, each 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}_{i}$
\end_inset

 is an associated prime ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Secondly, the number of associated prime ideals of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is finite.
 So if 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is an ideal which consists of zerodivisors of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
I\subseteq\bigcup\limits _{\mathfrak{p}\in\mbox{Ass}(M)}\mathfrak{p}.
\]

\end_inset

and by the 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Lemma~(
\backslash
ref{primeavoidance})
\end_layout

\end_inset

, we must have 
\begin_inset Formula $I\subseteq\mathfrak{p}_{i}$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
 Writing 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}_{i}=0:_{R}u_{i}$
\end_inset

, the assignment 
\begin_inset Formula $1\mapsto u_{i}$
\end_inset

 induces a nonzero homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon R\slash I\to M$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{annreg}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 be 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-modules.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Ann}\,M$
\end_inset

 contains an 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

-regular element, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Hom}_{R}(M,N)=0.$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Conversely, if 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is Noetherian, and 
\begin_inset Formula $M,N$
\end_inset

 are finite, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Hom}_{R}(M,N)=0$
\end_inset

 implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Ann}\,M$
\end_inset

 contains an 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

-regular element.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 1.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Ann}\,M$
\end_inset

 contains an 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

-regular element.
 Choose 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathrm{Ann}\,M$
\end_inset

 to be such an element and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\in\mathrm{Hom}_{R}(M,N)$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
x\varphi(u) & =\varphi(xu)\\
 & =\varphi(0)\\
 & =0
\end{align*}

\end_inset

implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(u)=0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $u\in M$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
2.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is Noetherian, 
\begin_inset Formula $M,N$
\end_inset

 are finite, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Hom}_{R}(M,N)=0$
\end_inset

.
 Assume for a contradiction that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Ann}\,M$
\end_inset

 consists of zerodivisors of 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

.
 Then by the remarks above, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Ann}\,M\subset\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 for some associated prime ideal 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

.
 By 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Lemma~(
\backslash
ref{support})
\end_layout

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}\in\mathrm{Supp}\,M$
\end_inset

; so 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{\mathfrak{p}}\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 In fact, Nakayama's Lemma tells us that 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{\mathfrak{p}}\slash\mathfrak{p}M_{\mathfrak{p}}\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{\mathfrak{p}}/\mathfrak{p}M_{\mathfrak{p}}$
\end_inset

 is just a direct sum of copies of 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{\mathfrak{p}}/\mathfrak{p}R_{\mathfrak{p}}$
\end_inset

, one has an epimorphism
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
M_{\mathfrak{p}}\to M_{\mathfrak{p}}/\mathfrak{p}M_{\mathfrak{p}}\to R_{\mathfrak{p}}/\mathfrak{p}R_{\mathfrak{p}}.
\]

\end_inset

Now observe that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}R_{\mathfrak{p}}\in\mathrm{Ass}\,N_{\mathfrak{p}}$
\end_inset

, and thus we can compose this epimorphism with a nonzero homomorphism to
 obtain a nonzero homomorphism,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
M_{\mathfrak{p}}\to R_{\mathfrak{p}}/\mathfrak{p}R_{\mathfrak{p}}\to N_{\mathfrak{p}}.
\]

\end_inset

Thus
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
0 & \neq\mathrm{Hom}_{R_{\mathfrak{p}}}(M_{\mathfrak{p}},N_{\mathfrak{p}})\\
 & =\mathrm{Hom}_{R}(M,N)_{\mathfrak{p}},
\end{align*}

\end_inset

which is a contradiction.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A=\mathbb{Q}[x,y]$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $N=\mathbb{Q}[x,y]/\langle x\rangle$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $M=\mathbb{Q}[x,y]/\langle x^{2},yx\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 Clearly there exists a nonzero morphism from 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 For example, 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{tikzcd} N 
\backslash
arrow[r, "
\backslash
cdot x "] & M 
\backslash
end{tikzcd}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is a homomorphism from 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 However, we want to construct a homomorphism from 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 using the techniques of 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Proposition~(
\backslash
ref{annreg})
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Set 
\begin_inset Formula $I:=\mbox{Ann}(N)=\langle x\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 There are two associated primes of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, namely 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}:=\langle x,y\rangle$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{q}:=\langle x\rangle$
\end_inset

, both contain 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $0:\overline{x}=\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $0:\overline{y}=\mathfrak{q}$
\end_inset

.
 We have 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{\mathfrak{q}}\cong\mathbb{Q}(y)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{\mathfrak{p}}\cong\mathbb{Q}[y]_{\langle y\rangle}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{\mathfrak{q}}/\mathfrak{q}A_{\mathfrak{q}}\cong\mathbb{Q}(y),$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{\mathfrak{p}}/\mathfrak{p}A_{\mathfrak{p}}\cong\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

.
 The morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{\mathfrak{p}}\to M_{\mathfrak{p}}$
\end_inset

 is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $f/g\mapsto xf/g$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $f,g\in\mathbb{Q}[y]$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g(0)\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 The morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{\mathfrak{q}}\to M_{\mathfrak{q}}$
\end_inset

 is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $f/g\mapsto yf/g$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $f,g\in\mathbb{Q}(y)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\backslash
label{exthom}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 be 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-modules and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}=x_{1},\dots,x_{n}$
\end_inset

 be a weak 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

-sequence contained in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Ann}\,M$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{Hom}_{R}(M,N\slash\mathbf{x}N)\cong\mathrm{Ext}_{R}^{n}(M,N).
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We use induction on 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, starting form the vacuous case 
\begin_inset Formula $n=0$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq1$
\end_inset

, and set 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}'=x_{1},\dots,x_{n-1}$
\end_inset

.
 Then the induction hypothesis implies that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{Ext}_{R}^{n-1}(M,N)\cong\mathrm{Hom}_{R}(M,N\slash\mathbf{x}'N).
\]

\end_inset

As 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $(N\slash\mathbf{x}'N)$
\end_inset

-regular, we must have 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Ext}_{R}^{n-1}(M,N\slash\mathbf{x}'N)=0$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Prop~(
\backslash
ref{annreg})
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Therefore the exact sequence 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd} 0 
\backslash
arrow[r] & N/ 
\backslash
mathbf{x}' N 
\backslash
arrow[r, "
\backslash
cdot x_n "] & N/ 
\backslash
mathbf{x} ' N 
\backslash
arrow[r] & N/ 
\backslash
mathbf{x} N 
\backslash
arrow[r] & 0 
\backslash
end{tikzcd}
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
yields an exact sequence 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd} 0 
\backslash
arrow[r] & 
\backslash
mathrm{Ext}_R ^{n-1} (M, N/ 
\backslash
mathbf{x} N ) 
\backslash
arrow[r] & 
\backslash
mathrm{Ext}_R ^n (M, N / 
\backslash
mathbf{x}' N) 
\backslash
arrow[r, "
\backslash
overline {x} _n "] & 
\backslash
mathrm{Ext}_R  ^n (M, N / 
\backslash
mathbf{x}' N) 
\backslash
end{tikzcd}
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The map 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is multiplication by 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n}$
\end_inset

 inherited from 
\begin_inset Formula $M/\mathbf{x}'M$
\end_inset

: That is, after choosing an injective resolution of 
\begin_inset Formula $M/\mathbf{x}'M$
\end_inset

 with modules labeled 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{i}$
\end_inset

 and morphisms labeled 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{i}:I_{i}\to I_{i+1}$
\end_inset

, then an element in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{Ext}_{A}^{n}(N,M/\mathbf{x}'M)$
\end_inset

 is represented by a map 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{n}:N\to I_{n}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{n}\circ\psi_{n}=0$
\end_inset

.
 Then the map 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 sends the representative 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{n}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{Ext}_{A}^{n}(N,M/\mathbf{x}'M)$
\end_inset

 to the representative 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n}\psi_{n}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{Ext}_{A}^{n}(N,M/\mathbf{x}'M)$
\end_inset

, but
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
(x_{n}\psi_{n})(n) & =x_{n}\psi_{n}(n)\\
 & =\psi_{n}(x_{n}n)\\
 & =\psi_{n}(0)\\
 & =0,
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in N$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is the zero map.
 Hence 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 is an isomorphism.
 It's now easy to show that we get the sequence of isomorphism:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mbox{Hom}_{A}(N,M/\mathbf{x}M)\cong\mbox{Ext}_{A}^{0}(N,M/\mathbf{x}M)\cong\mbox{Ext}_{A}^{1}(N,M/\mathbf{x}'M)\cong\cdots\cong\mbox{Ext}_{A}^{n}(N,M)
\]

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 be a Noetherian ring, 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 an ideal, 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 a finite 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-module with 
\begin_inset Formula $M\neq IM$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}=x_{1},\dots,x_{n}$
\end_inset

 a maximal 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

-sequence in 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

.
 From 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Prop~(
\backslash
ref{annreg})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Lemma~(
\backslash
ref{exthom})
\end_layout

\end_inset

, we have, since 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 contains an 
\begin_inset Formula $M/\langle x_{1},\dots,x_{i-1}\rangle M$
\end_inset

-regular element for 
\begin_inset Formula $i=1,\dots,n$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mbox{Ext}_{A}^{i-1}(A/I,M)\cong\mbox{Hom}_{A}(A/I,M/\langle x_{1},\dots,x_{i-1}\rangle M)\neq0.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have therefore proved
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{rees}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Rees).
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 be a Noetherian ring, 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 be a finite 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-module, and 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 an ideal such that 
\begin_inset Formula $IM\neq M$
\end_inset

.
 Then all maximal 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

-sequences in 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 have the same length 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
n=\mbox{min}\{i\mid\mbox{Ext}_{A}^{i}(A/I,M)\neq0\}.
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 be a ring, 
\begin_inset Formula $I\subset A$
\end_inset

 and ideal and 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 an 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-module.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $M\neq IM$
\end_inset

, then the maximal length 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 of an 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

-sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{1},\dots,a_{n}\in I$
\end_inset

 is called the 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

-
\series bold
depth 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 and denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{depth}(I,M)$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $M=IM$
\end_inset

 then the 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

-depth of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is by convention 
\begin_inset Formula $\infty$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $(A,\mathfrak{m})$
\end_inset

 is a local ring, then the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

-depth of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is simply called the 
\series bold
depth 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, that is, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{depth}(M):=\mbox{depth}(\mathfrak{m},M)$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 be a field and 
\begin_inset Formula $K[x_{1},\dots,x_{n}]$
\end_inset

 the polynomial ring.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mbox{depth}(\langle x_{1},\dots,x_{n}\rangle,K[x_{1},\dots,x_{n}])\geq n,
\]

\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1},\dots,x_{n}$
\end_inset

 is an 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle x_{1},\dots,x_{n}\rangle$
\end_inset

-sequence (and we shall see later that it is 
\begin_inset Formula $=n$
\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 be a ring, 
\begin_inset Formula $I\subset A$
\end_inset

 an ideal and 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 an 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-module.
 Then the 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

-depth of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 if and only if every element of 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is a zerodivisor for 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 Hence, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{depth}(I,M)=0$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is contained in some associated prime ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, for a local ring 
\begin_inset Formula $(A,\mathfrak{m})$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{depth}(\mathfrak{m},A/\mathfrak{m})=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Recall that if 
\begin_inset Formula $M=IM$
\end_inset

, then we set the 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

-depth of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 to be 
\begin_inset Formula $\infty$
\end_inset

.
 This is consistent with 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Theorem~(
\backslash
ref{rees})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 because 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{depth}(I,M)=\infty$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{Ext}_{A}^{i}(A/I,M)=0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
 For if 
\begin_inset Formula $IM=M$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{supp}(M)\cap\mbox{supp}(A/I)=\{\mathfrak{p}\mid\mathfrak{p}\supset I\mbox{ and }M_{\mathfrak{p}}\neq0\}=\emptyset$
\end_inset

, by Nakayama's lemma, hence 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mbox{supp}(\mbox{Ext}_{A}^{i}(A/I,M)\subset\mbox{supp}(M)\cap\mbox{supp}(A/I)=\emptyset;
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
conversely, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{Ext}_{A}^{i}(A/I,M)=0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Theorem~(
\backslash
ref{rees})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 gives 
\begin_inset Formula $IM=M$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 be a Noetherian ring, 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 and ideal in 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, and 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
label{1}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd} 0 
\backslash
arrow[r] & U 
\backslash
arrow[r] & M 
\backslash
arrow[r] & N 
\backslash
arrow[r] & 0 
\backslash
end{tikzcd}
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
an exact sequence of finite 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-modules.
 Then
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{depth}(I,M)\geq\mbox{min}\{\mbox{depth}(I,U),\mbox{depth}(I,N)\}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{depth}(I,U)\geq\mbox{min}\{\mbox{depth}(I,M),\mbox{depth}(I,N)+1\}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{depth}(I,N)\geq\mbox{min}\{\mbox{depth}(I,U)-1,\mbox{depth}(I,M)\}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $k=\mbox{depth}(I,U)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $m=\mbox{depth}(I,M)$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $n=\mbox{depth}(I,N)$
\end_inset

.
 The given exact sequence induces a long exact sequence
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd} & 
\backslash
cdots 
\backslash
arrow[r] 
\backslash
arrow[d, phantom, ""{coordinate, name=Z}] & Ext^{i-1} _A (A/I 
\backslash
text{,} N) 
\backslash
